export const PSYCH_SOC_QUIZZES = [
  {
    id:'ps01', cat:'Psych/Soc', title:'Social Psychology & Cognition', diff:'Medium',
    qs:[
      { q:`Which of the following best describes the fundamental attribution error?`, ch:[`Overestimating situational factors when explaining others' behavior`,`Overestimating dispositional factors and underestimating situational factors when explaining others' behavior`,`Attributing one's own failures to personal character`,`Consistently attributing success to luck`], ans:1, exp:`The fundamental attribution error (FAE) is the tendency to over-attribute others' behavior to internal (dispositional) factors (e.g., personality, character) while underestimating situational influences. When explaining our own behavior, we tend to do the opposite (actor-observer bias), focusing more on situational factors. The FAE is stronger in individualistic cultures.` },
      { q:`Cognitive dissonance, as described by Leon Festinger, refers to:`, ch:[`Holding two compatible beliefs simultaneously`,`The discomfort experienced when holding two contradictory beliefs, or when behavior contradicts beliefs, motivating attitude change`,`Selective attention to information that confirms existing beliefs`,`The tendency to mimic others' behaviors and attitudes`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive dissonance (Festinger, 1957): tension arising from inconsistency between two cognitions (beliefs, attitudes, or behaviors). To reduce dissonance, people change one of the cognitions, add new cognitions (rationalization), or trivialize the contradiction. Classic experiment: people paid $1 (vs. $20) to lie showed more attitude change because they had less external justification and had to find internal reasons to resolve dissonance.` },
      { q:`Conformity in the Asch line experiments was primarily driven by:`, ch:[`Informational social influence (believing others are correct)`,`Normative social influence (desire to fit in and avoid social disapproval) and informational social influence`,`Obedience to authority figures`,`Cognitive dissonance`], ans:1, exp:`Asch (1951): subjects conformed ~37% of the time when confederates gave obviously wrong answers. Two types of social influence: (1) Informational: conforming because you believe others have better information (more common in ambiguous situations). (2) Normative: conforming to avoid rejection/gain approval. Asch's setting had clear answers, so normative influence dominated. Conformity was reduced when even one other person disagreed (social support).` },
      { q:`According to Milgram's obedience experiments, which factor MOST reduced obedience?`, ch:[`When the experimenter wore a white lab coat`,`Physical proximity of the victim (learner) and increased distance from the authority figure`,`When the study was conducted at Yale University`,`Presence of other obedient participants`], ans:1, exp:`Milgram (1963): ~65% of participants delivered maximum (450 V) shocks when ordered by an authority. Obedience dropped dramatically when: (1) the learner was in the same room (touch proximity); (2) the experimenter gave orders by phone; (3) the study was conducted off-campus (prestige reduced); (4) other "teachers" refused (peer rebellion). Obedience increased with: institutional authority, physical proximity to authority, distance from victim.` },
      { q:`The bystander effect is best explained by which two psychological processes?`, ch:[`Deindividuation and social loafing`,`Diffusion of responsibility and pluralistic ignorance`,`Groupthink and social facilitation`,`Social comparison and in-group bias`], ans:1, exp:`Bystander effect (Darley & Latan├®, 1968): as the number of bystanders increases, the probability that any one person will help decreases. Two mechanisms: (1) Diffusion of responsibility ŌĆö each bystander feels less personally responsible. (2) Pluralistic ignorance ŌĆö bystanders look to each other, and if no one acts, each assumes others have determined no emergency exists. Practical implication: in emergencies, single out a specific person to request help.` },
      { q:`Social facilitation refers to:`, ch:[`Decreased performance in the presence of others when the task is complex`,`Improved performance on well-learned/simple tasks in the presence of others, and impaired performance on novel/difficult tasks in the presence of others`,`Helping behavior in group settings`,`Reduced effort when working in groups`], ans:1, exp:`Social facilitation (Zajonc, 1965): presence of others increases arousal ŌåÆ enhances dominant (most practiced) response. On easy/well-learned tasks, dominant response = correct response ŌåÆ performance improves. On difficult/novel tasks, dominant response = error ŌåÆ performance impairs. Real-world: athletes may perform better with an audience on practiced skills but worse when learning new techniques. Social loafing: in contrast, when individual contributions are hidden in a group, people exert less effort.` },
      { q:`Groupthink is characterized by:`, ch:[`Healthy debate and critical evaluation within a cohesive group`,`Deterioration of mental efficiency, reality testing, and moral judgment due to group pressures for uniformity and harmony ŌĆö leads to poor decision-making`,`Increased creativity due to brainstorming in groups`,`Lower conformity in small, cohesive groups`], ans:1, exp:`Groupthink (Janis, 1972): occurs in highly cohesive groups with strong directive leaders, isolated from outside opinions, under high stress. Symptoms: illusion of invulnerability, collective rationalization, belief in group's morality, stereotyped views of out-groups, self-censorship, illusion of unanimity, direct pressure on dissenters. Historical examples: Bay of Pigs, Challenger disaster. Prevention: encourage dissent, use devil's advocate, bring in outside experts, leader withholds opinion initially.` },
      { q:`In Festinger's social comparison theory, people tend to compare themselves to:`, ch:[`Those significantly better off than themselves (upward comparison) only`,`Similar others to evaluate their own abilities and opinions, especially when objective standards are unavailable`,`Those who are much worse off to feel better about themselves`,`Authority figures exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Social comparison theory (Festinger, 1954): people evaluate their own abilities and opinions by comparing themselves to others when objective measures are unavailable. Preferentially compare with similar others (appropriate benchmark). Upward comparison (to superior): can inspire improvement or create envy/anxiety. Downward comparison (to inferior): boosts self-esteem. Relevance: important in social media context, where constant upward comparisons can harm mental health.` },
      { q:`The self-serving bias refers to:`, ch:[`Attributing others' successes to luck`,`Attributing personal successes to internal factors (ability, effort) and failures to external factors (bad luck, task difficulty)`,`Overestimating one's own consistency across situations`,`Underestimating one's own abilities in social settings`], ans:1, exp:`Self-serving bias: protects and enhances self-esteem. Success ŌåÆ internal attribution (I worked hard, I am talented). Failure ŌåÆ external attribution (the test was unfair, circumstances were against me). Contrast with depressive realism: depressed individuals show a more realistic attribution pattern (reduced self-serving bias). Also related to: in-group favoritism (attributing in-group successes to ability, failures to bad luck, and out-group the opposite).` },
      { q:`The halo effect in psychology refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency to be more obedient to attractive authority figures`,`The cognitive bias in which one positive (or negative) trait influences the overall perception of a person in other unrelated domains`,`Improved memory for emotionally positive events`,`The tendency to seek information confirming initial impressions`], ans:0, exp:`Halo effect (Thorndike, 1920): one salient positive characteristic (attractiveness, warmth, confidence) biases ratings of other unrelated traits (intelligence, competence, honesty). Negative halo = horn effect. Applications: physically attractive individuals are perceived as more competent and honest (and receive lighter criminal sentences). Impacts hiring, teaching evaluations, and product marketing. Confirmation bias: different phenomenon ŌĆö tendency to search for and favor information that confirms prior beliefs.` },
      { q:`Stereotype threat, as described by Steele and Aronson (1995), refers to:`, ch:[`The increase in performance when positive stereotypes are primed`,`The risk of confirming a negative stereotype about one's social group, which impairs performance through anxiety and cognitive burden`,`The tendency of minorities to internalize stereotypes about their groups`,`Reduced motivation in the absence of social comparisons`], ans:1, exp:`Stereotype threat: awareness that one might confirm a negative stereotype about one's group creates psychological pressure ŌåÆ cognitive load, anxiety ŌåÆ impairs performance (especially on cognitively demanding tasks). Original study: Black students underperformed on GRE-like tests when race was made salient, but performed equally to White students when framing did not prime race-related stereotypes. Implications: explains gap scores without invoking genetic differences; reduced by interventions that affirm identity or reframe the test.` },
      { q:`Deindividuation in crowds and groups leads to:`, ch:[`Increased personal responsibility and prosocial behavior`,`Reduced self-awareness and personal accountability ŌåÆ increased impulsive, antisocial, or uninhibited behavior that individuals would not typically perform alone`,`Better coordination and productivity in groups`,`Increased conformity to individual norms`], ans:1, exp:`Deindividuation (Zimbardo, 1969): loss of individual identity in groups ŌåÆ reduced self-monitoring ŌåÆ behavior guided more by situational norms. Conditions: anonymity (masks, uniforms), arousal, group cohesion, reduced individuality cues. Examples: mob violence, online harassment (anonymity), carnival behavior. However, deindividuation can also increase pro-group behavior (positive norms). Zimbardo's prison study illustrated how situational factors (role, deindividuation) can override individual disposition.` },
      { q:`The just-world hypothesis (Lerner) suggests that people:`, ch:[`Believe the world is inherently unfair and unpredictable`,`Believe that people get what they deserve (and deserve what they get) ŌĆö leading to victim blaming as a way to maintain the belief that the world is fair and predictable`,`Are motivated to help victims because of empathy`,`Attribute misfortune to chance factors`], ans:1, exp:`Just-world hypothesis: people need to believe the world is fair and orderly. When confronted with victims of injustice (rape, poverty, illness), people restore the just-world belief by blaming the victim (she was asking for it, he made poor choices) rather than acknowledging random misfortune. Serves a defensive function: if victims are responsible for their fate, then I am safe if I behave differently. Reduces empathy for victims and interferes with social change. Replicates cross-culturally but is more prevalent in cultures emphasizing meritocracy.` },
      { q:`Attitude formation through classical conditioning was demonstrated by studies showing:`, ch:[`People change attitudes through cognitive elaboration of arguments`,`Attitudes toward neutral stimuli can be formed by repeatedly pairing them with stimuli that already elicit positive or negative responses (evaluative conditioning)`,`Attitudes are primarily determined by genetic factors`,`Attitudes only change through personal experience`], ans:1, exp:`Evaluative conditioning: neutral stimulus (NS) repeatedly paired with positive/negative unconditioned stimulus (US) ŌåÆ NS acquires positive/negative valence. Example: advertisement repeatedly pairs a neutral product with attractive/happy people ŌåÆ positive attitude toward product. This occurs even without awareness. Operant conditioning also shapes attitudes (rewards/punishments for expressing certain attitudes). Mere exposure effect (Zajonc): repeated exposure to a stimulus alone (without pairing) increases positive attitude toward it.` },
      { q:`In social psychology, the concept of 'social norms' refers to:`, ch:[`Legal rules enforced by government authorities`,`Unwritten rules and expectations about acceptable behavior in a given social group or situation ŌĆö violation results in social sanctions`,`Biologically determined behavioral patterns`,`Individual preferences for social interaction`], ans:1, exp:`Social norms: shared standards for behavior within a group. Types: (1) Descriptive norms (what most people do); (2) Injunctive norms (what people approve or disapprove of). Norms vary by culture, context, and group. Violation: social sanctions ranging from mild disapproval to ostracism. Norm enforcement: through internalization (people adopt norm as their own value) or compliance (external pressure). Norms influence health behavior (e.g., social norms marketing: correcting misperceptions about peers' drinking levels reduces alcohol use).` },
    ]
  },
  {
    id:'ps02', cat:'Psych/Soc', title:'Development, Learning & Memory', diff:'Medium',
    qs:[
      { q:`According to Piaget's theory, during the formal operational stage (approximately 12+ years), children develop:`, ch:[`Object permanence and sensorimotor schemas`,`Abstract reasoning, hypothetical-deductive thinking, and the ability to think systematically about all logical possibilities`,`Symbolic thought and language, but remain egocentric`,`Conservation and reversibility of concrete objects only`], ans:1, exp:`Piaget's stages: Sensorimotor (0ŌĆō2): object permanence develops. Preoperational (2ŌĆō7): symbolic thought, language, but egocentric (unable to take another's perspective); lacks conservation. Concrete operational (7ŌĆō12): conservation, reversibility, classification; thinking bound to concrete reality. Formal operational (12+): abstract reasoning, hypothetical thinking, systematic problem-solving, metacognition. Criticism: underestimates children's capabilities; development may be more continuous than stage-like; cultural context matters.` },
      { q:`Vygotsky's zone of proximal development (ZPD) refers to:`, ch:[`The cognitive tasks a child can perform independently`,`The gap between what a learner can do independently and what they can achieve with guidance from a more capable peer or adult (scaffolding)`,`The developmental period of maximum cognitive plasticity`,`The difference in cognitive abilities between gifted and average students`], ans:1, exp:`ZPD (Vygotsky): the distance between actual developmental level (independent performance) and potential developmental level (with expert assistance). Scaffolding: temporary support provided by teacher/peer that is gradually withdrawn as the learner becomes more capable. Vygotsky emphasized social/cultural context in cognitive development (contrast with Piaget's more individual-focused approach). Private speech: children talking to themselves guides problem-solving, eventually internalized as inner speech.` },
      { q:`In classical conditioning, the process of extinction occurs when:`, ch:[`A conditioned stimulus is repeatedly paired with a new unconditioned stimulus`,`The conditioned stimulus is repeatedly presented without the unconditioned stimulus, causing the conditioned response to gradually weaken and disappear`,`A second neutral stimulus becomes conditioned through association with the first conditioned stimulus`,`The organism generalizes the conditioned response to similar stimuli`], ans:1, exp:`Extinction: CR diminishes when CS is presented repeatedly without US. Not true unlearning ŌĆö the original association is suppressed. Spontaneous recovery: after rest, the extinguished CR returns weakly (evidence that extinction = new inhibitory learning). Renewal effect: extinguished CR returns in new context (CS-only extinction occurred in specific context). This has clinical implications: exposure therapy for phobias must account for renewal ŌĆö generalizing extinction across multiple contexts improves outcomes.` },
      { q:`The partial reinforcement extinction effect (PREE) refers to:`, ch:[`Faster extinction when reinforcement is continuous`,`Greater resistance to extinction for behaviors reinforced on partial schedules compared to those continuously reinforced ŌĆö the variable ratio schedule shows the greatest resistance`,`The extinction of behavior after punishment`,`Faster learning under partial reinforcement`], ans:1, exp:`PREE: partially reinforced behaviors are more resistant to extinction than continuously reinforced ones. Because partial reinforcement already involves non-reinforcement during acquisition, the organism cannot easily distinguish extinction (no reinforcement) from the partial schedule. Variable ratio (VR) schedule: produces highest and most consistent response rates; most resistant to extinction (slot machine principle). Fixed ratio (FR): produces post-reinforcement pause. Variable interval (VI): produces steady, moderate rates. Fixed interval (FI): scalloped pattern, increases near reinforcement time.` },
      { q:`Long-term potentiation (LTP) is important for memory formation because:`, ch:[`It decreases synaptic strength in unused circuits`,`It produces lasting increases in synaptic efficacy between neurons, dependent on NMDA receptor activation and AMPA receptor trafficking ŌĆö widely regarded as a cellular mechanism of learning and memory`,`It involves protein degradation in dendritic spines`,`It is a process restricted to the hippocampus`], ans:1, exp:`LTP: persistent strengthening of synaptic transmission following high-frequency stimulation. Mechanisms: NMDA receptor (requires concurrent pre- and postsynaptic activity = associative, Hebbian) ŌåÆ Ca2+ influx ŌåÆ CaMKII activation ŌåÆ AMPA receptor phosphorylation and trafficking to synapse ŌåÆ increased synaptic efficacy. Late-phase LTP: requires protein synthesis (PKA, CREB ŌåÆ gene expression ŌåÆ new synaptic proteins). Erasing LTP = long-term depression (LTD). Hippocampal LTP critical for declarative memory; amygdala LTP for emotional memory.` },
      { q:`Episodic memory differs from semantic memory in that episodic memory:`, ch:[`Contains general world knowledge and facts`,`Is the autobiographical memory system for personally experienced events with context (time, place, associated emotions)`,`Requires no conscious recall`,`Is not affected by hippocampal damage`], ans:1, exp:`Tulving's memory taxonomy: Episodic memory: personally experienced events with spatio-temporal context (autonoetic consciousness ŌĆö sense of mental time travel). Semantic memory: general world knowledge, facts, concepts, without personal context (noetic consciousness). Both are explicit (declarative) memories requiring conscious recollection and are hippocampus-dependent. Anterograde amnesia (e.g., HM): inability to form new episodic and semantic memories after hippocampal damage; procedural memory preserved. Semantic dementia: frontotemporal lobe damage ŌåÆ semantic memory loss with preserved episodic memory.` },
      { q:`According to Erikson's psychosocial theory, the primary developmental task of adolescence is:`, ch:[`Trust vs. mistrust`,`Identity vs. role confusion ŌĆö exploring and committing to a coherent sense of self, values, and future role in society`,`Intimacy vs. isolation`,`Generativity vs. stagnation`], ans:1, exp:`Erikson's 8 stages: Trust vs. mistrust (0ŌĆō1, feeding/care); Autonomy vs. shame (1ŌĆō3, toilet training); Initiative vs. guilt (3ŌĆō6, play); Industry vs. inferiority (6ŌĆō12, school); Identity vs. role confusion (12ŌĆō20, adolescence); Intimacy vs. isolation (20ŌĆō40, young adult); Generativity vs. stagnation (40ŌĆō65, middle age); Integrity vs. despair (65+, late life). Marcia's identity statuses (expansion): identity diffusion, foreclosure, moratorium, achievement.` },
      { q:`The serial position effect in memory recall refers to:`, ch:[`Better recall of items in the middle of a list`,`Better recall of items at the beginning (primacy effect) and end (recency effect) of a list, with poorest recall for items in the middle`,`Improved recall with visual vs. auditory presentation`,`The relationship between emotional intensity and memory vividness`], ans:1, exp:`Serial position effect: primacy effect = better recall of early items (encoded into long-term memory through rehearsal). Recency effect = better recall of most recent items (still in working memory/short-term memory). Middle items: least well recalled. Recency effect is abolished with delay before recall or interpolated tasks (working memory cleared). Primacy effect is diminished by fast presentation (less rehearsal time). Implications: in presentations/lists, first and last positions are most memorable.` },
      { q:`Learned helplessness (Seligman) occurs when:`, ch:[`An animal learns to avoid punishment through trial-and-error`,`An organism exposed to inescapable, uncontrollable stressors learns that its actions have no effect on outcomes ŌåÆ passivity, depression, and failure to escape even when escape becomes possible`,`A person becomes overly dependent on external rewards`,`Classical conditioning generalizes to new stimuli`], ans:1, exp:`Learned helplessness (Seligman, 1967): dogs exposed to inescapable shock later failed to escape when escape became possible. Translated to humans: depression model ŌĆö uncontrollable negative events ŌåÆ belief that outcomes are independent of one's actions ŌåÆ motivational, cognitive, and emotional deficits. Reformulated (Abramson et al., 1978): attributional style matters ŌĆö internal, stable, global attributions for failure ŌåÆ more severe helplessness/depression. Basis for cognitive theories of depression and CBT.` },
      { q:`In Kohlberg's theory of moral development, post-conventional morality is characterized by:`, ch:[`Obedience to rules to avoid punishment`,`Following rules because they are the law and social order must be maintained`,`Moral reasoning based on universal ethical principles and individual rights, which may supersede unjust laws`,`Acting to gain approval from others`], ans:2, exp:`Kohlberg's stages: Pre-conventional: Stage 1 (punishment avoidance, obedience); Stage 2 (instrumental/exchange ŌĆö 'what's in it for me'). Conventional: Stage 3 (good boy/girl ŌĆö approval from others); Stage 4 (law and order ŌĆö authority, rules). Post-conventional: Stage 5 (social contract ŌĆö laws should maximize welfare, can be changed democratically); Stage 6 (universal ethical principles ŌĆö Kant's categorical imperative, civil disobedience justified). Gilligan's critique: Kohlberg's model biased toward justice over care orientation (more typical of females).` },
      { q:`Harlow's rhesus monkey studies demonstrated that attachment is primarily driven by:`, ch:[`Feeding and nutritional dependency (cupboard love theory)`,`Contact comfort ŌĆö infant monkeys preferred the cloth mother over the wire mother even when only the wire mother provided food`,`Visual stimulation from the mother's face`,`Operant conditioning through maternal reinforcement`], ans:1, exp:`Harlow (1958): infant monkeys raised with surrogate mothers ŌĆö one wire (provided milk), one cloth (no milk, but comfortable). Infants spent most time clinging to cloth mother, especially when frightened (ran to cloth for comfort). Challenged the behaviorist/drive-reduction view that attachment = feeding relationship. Established that contact comfort is a primary need. Bowlby later developed attachment theory emphasizing evolutionary basis and secure base. Ainsworth's Strange Situation: secure, anxious-avoidant, anxious-ambivalent/resistant, disorganized attachment patterns.` },
      { q:`The mirror neuron system is proposed to play a role in:`, ch:[`Visual processing in the occipital cortex only`,`Imitation, understanding others' actions and intentions, and empathy ŌĆö these neurons fire both when an animal performs an action and when it observes the same action performed by another`,`Motor command generation in the cerebellum`,`Encoding of procedural memories in the basal ganglia`], ans:1, exp:`Mirror neurons (Rizzolatti et al., 1992): first discovered in macaque premotor cortex (F5). Activated by both performing and observing goal-directed actions. Proposed roles: action understanding, imitation learning, theory of mind, empathy, language evolution. In humans: evidence from fMRI, EEG, TMS showing analogous systems in inferior frontal gyrus (Broca's area) and inferior parietal lobule. Controversy: whether human 'mirror neurons' exist as discrete cell type (vs. learned associative connections). Linked speculatively to autism (broken mirror hypothesis ŌĆö largely unconfirmed).` },
      { q:`Operant conditioning differs from classical conditioning in that:`, ch:[`Operant conditioning involves involuntary, reflexive responses`,`In operant conditioning, behavior is modified by its consequences (reinforcers and punishers), while classical conditioning involves pairing a neutral stimulus with an unconditioned stimulus to elicit a reflexive response`,`Classical conditioning requires conscious awareness and active participation`,`Both forms are neurobiologically identical`], ans:1, exp:`Classical (Pavlovian): stimulus-stimulus learning; involves involuntary/reflexive responses; organism is passive. US ŌåÆ UR; CS paired with US ŌåÆ CS ŌåÆ CR. Operant (Skinnerian/instrumental): response-consequence learning; involves voluntary behaviors; organism acts on environment. Reinforcement (positive/negative) increases behavior; punishment (positive/negative) decreases behavior. Key differences: type of response (reflexive vs. voluntary), role of organism (passive vs. active), what is learned (S-S association vs. S-R-outcome). Both involve extinction and generalization.` },
      { q:`Piaget's concept of conservation refers to:`, ch:[`Understanding that objects continue to exist when out of sight`,`Understanding that certain properties of objects (quantity, number, volume) remain constant despite changes in their physical appearance`,`The ability to mentally reverse operations`,`The ability to classify objects according to multiple attributes simultaneously`], ans:1, exp:`Conservation (Piaget): develops in concrete operational stage (~7ŌĆō12). Classic task: two equal rows of coins ŌåÆ spread one row out ŌåÆ child in preoperational stage says the spread row has 'more' coins (perceptual centration on length). Conservation of volume, mass, number develop at different ages. Preoperational thought: centration (focus on one aspect), irreversibility (cannot mentally undo actions), egocentrism (cannot take another's viewpoint). Criticism: children may fail due to demand characteristics of the task, not lack of understanding.` },
      { q:`According to Bandura's social learning theory, observational learning requires:`, ch:[`Direct reinforcement of the observed behavior`,`Attention, retention, reproduction, and motivation (incentive/reinforcement) ŌĆö the learner observes a model and the consequences of the model's behavior, then reproduces the behavior based on vicarious reinforcement`,`Emotional conditioning to the observed behavior`,`Multiple repetitions with corrective feedback`], ans:1, exp:`Bandura's social learning theory / social cognitive theory: learning can occur without direct reinforcement through observation. Key processes: (1) Attention ŌĆö must notice and perceive model's behavior; (2) Retention ŌĆö must encode and remember behavior; (3) Reproduction ŌĆö must have physical ability to reproduce behavior; (4) Motivation ŌĆö must be motivated to perform behavior (intrinsic, direct, or vicarious reinforcement). Bobo doll experiments: children who observed aggressive model reproduced aggression even without direct reinforcement. Self-efficacy: belief in one's ability to perform ŌĆö central concept in Bandura's later work.` },
    ]
  },
  {
    id:'ps03', cat:'Psych/Soc', title:'Sociology & Research Methods', diff:'Medium',
    qs:[
      { q:`A Type I error in hypothesis testing refers to:`, ch:[`Failing to reject a false null hypothesis`,`Rejecting a true null hypothesis (false positive) ŌĆö the probability of a Type I error equals the significance level (╬▒)`,`Incorrectly calculating the effect size`,`Failing to achieve adequate statistical power`], ans:1, exp:`Type I error (╬▒): rejecting HŌéĆ when HŌéĆ is actually true. Type II error (╬▓): failing to reject HŌéĆ when it is actually false. Power = 1 ŌłÆ ╬▓ = probability of correctly rejecting a false HŌéĆ. Relationship: decreasing ╬▒ (more stringent threshold, e.g., 0.05 ŌåÆ 0.01) reduces Type I error rate but increases Type II error rate (and reduces power). Increasing sample size increases power. The p-value represents the probability of obtaining results at least as extreme as observed, given HŌéĆ is true ŌĆö it does not represent the probability that HŌéĆ is true.` },
      { q:`In Durkheim's theory, anomie refers to:`, ch:[`The integration of individuals into society through shared moral bonds`,`A condition of normlessness or weakening of social norms, often occurring during rapid social change, leading to increased deviant behavior and suicide risk`,`The collective conscience binding society together`,`Social stratification based on class differences`], ans:1, exp:`Anomie (Durkheim, 1897): disruption of social regulation ŌĆö norms are unclear or absent. Leads to anomic suicide (due to deregulation). Merton extended anomie: structural strain ŌĆö gap between culturally valued goals (wealth) and legitimate means to achieve them ŌåÆ strain ŌåÆ deviance. Modes of adaptation: conformity, innovation (crime), ritualism, retreatism, rebellion. Durkheim's suicide types: egoistic (low integration), altruistic (high integration), anomic (low regulation), fatalistic (high regulation).` },
      { q:`The difference between correlation and causation is best illustrated by:`, ch:[`Two variables that always change together must have a causal relationship`,`A statistically significant correlation between ice cream sales and drowning deaths does not mean ice cream causes drowning ŌĆö both are caused by hot weather (confounding variable)`,`Experimental studies never establish causation`,`Causation can always be inferred if the correlation is strong (r > 0.8)`], ans:1, exp:`Correlation ŌēĀ causation. A positive or negative correlation indicates that variables change together but does not identify the direction of causation or rule out confounders. For causation: (1) temporal precedence (cause precedes effect); (2) covariation; (3) elimination of plausible alternative explanations. Only randomized controlled experiments (random assignment controls confounders) can establish causation in most contexts. Natural experiments, longitudinal designs, and statistical controls help rule out confounders in observational studies.` },
      { q:`Social stratification refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency for social groups to become smaller over time`,`A hierarchical system of ranking groups in society based on wealth, power, and prestige ŌĆö determines differential access to resources and opportunities`,`The process by which individuals move between social classes`,`The equal distribution of resources in a society`], ans:1, exp:`Social stratification: structured inequality; every society has some form. Dimensions (Weber): class (economic), status (prestige/honor), party/power (political influence). Systems: caste (ascribed, closed ŌĆö India, historical feudalism); class (achieved, more open in principle ŌĆö modern capitalist societies). Consequences: differential life chances (health, education, mortality), social mobility (intergenerational/intragenerational), and reproduction of inequality through socialization and institutions. Functionalist view (Davis & Moore): stratification is functional ŌĆö rewards important positions. Conflict view (Marx): stratification serves the interests of the ruling class.` },
      { q:`Which research design provides the strongest evidence for establishing causality?`, ch:[`Case study`,`Cross-sectional survey`,`Randomized controlled experiment with random assignment of participants to conditions`,`Prospective longitudinal cohort study`], ans:2, exp:`Randomized controlled experiment (RCT): random assignment distributes confounders equally between groups ŌåÆ can establish causality. Limitations: ethical constraints, artificiality, demand characteristics. Longitudinal cohort study: follows participants over time ŌåÆ can establish temporal precedence, but not true experimental control. Cross-sectional: snapshot in time, no temporal data. Case study: rich qualitative data, but no control group, cannot generalize. In medical research, RCT is gold standard for establishing treatment efficacy. Natural experiments and quasi-experiments approximate this when randomization is not feasible.` },
      { q:`According to Goffman's concept of dramaturgy, social interaction is:`, ch:[`Governed primarily by unconscious biological drives`,`Analogous to a theatrical performance ŌĆö individuals manage impressions ('impression management') using a 'front stage' (public presentation) and 'back stage' (private behavior)`,`Determined entirely by social class and economic factors`,`Random and unpredictable`], ans:1, exp:`Goffman (1959, 'The Presentation of Self in Everyday Life'): dramaturgical model. Front stage: public, performed self; props, costumes (clothing), setting, manner. Back stage: relaxed, true self; preparation for front-stage performance. Impression management: strategic presentation of self to influence others' perceptions. Stigma management: individuals with stigmatized identities employ strategies to manage information and interactions. Goffman also analyzed total institutions (prisons, hospitals) ŌĆö stripping of individual identity.` },
      { q:`The concept of 'sick role' as described by Parsons includes all of the following EXCEPT:`, ch:[`The sick individual is exempt from normal social responsibilities`,`The sick individual must seek and cooperate with medical care`,`The sick individual is held morally responsible for their illness`,`The sick role is a temporary, deviant state requiring exit through recovery`], ans:2, exp:`Parsons' sick role (1951): four components. Rights: (1) exempt from normal duties; (2) not blamed/held responsible. Obligations: (3) must want to get well; (4) must seek competent help and cooperate. Criticisms: (1) assumes all sickness is temporary and treatable; (2) ignores chronic illness, disability; (3) ignores patient agency; (4) power differential; (5) doesn't account for variation across cultures. The sick person is NOT held morally responsible ŌĆö this is a right of the sick role. However, some conditions (STIs, obesity, smoking-related illness) face social stigma that violates this right.` },
      { q:`In sociological terms, a 'reference group' is:`, ch:[`A randomly selected group used as control in a study`,`A social group against which individuals compare themselves to evaluate their own status, behaviors, and attitudes`,`A group to which an individual belongs but does not identify with`,`The demographic group from which a representative sample is drawn`], ans:1, exp:`Reference group (Hyman, 1942): a group used as a standard for self-evaluation and attitude formation. Does not require membership (non-membership reference groups can be aspirational or comparative). Types: (1) Comparative ŌĆö provides a standard for comparison; (2) Normative ŌĆö provides norms and values for behavior. Relative deprivation: feeling deprived relative to one's reference group (not in absolute terms) ŌåÆ dissatisfaction, social unrest. In-group: group one belongs to. Out-group: groups one does not belong to.` },
      { q:`Internal validity in a research study refers to:`, ch:[`The degree to which results can be generalized to other populations`,`The degree to which the study accurately measures what it intends to measure and that changes in the dependent variable are attributable to the independent variable rather than confounders`,`The consistency of measurement across time`,`The clarity and precision of operational definitions`], ans:1, exp:`Internal validity: the extent to which a study's design allows causal inferences ŌĆö that IV caused changes in DV, not confounders. Threats: selection bias, history effects (external events), maturation, attrition, regression to the mean, testing effects, instrumentation. External validity: generalizability to other populations/contexts. Construct validity: whether the operational definitions accurately represent theoretical constructs. Ecological validity: whether the study settings reflect real-world conditions. RCTs maximize internal validity through random assignment.` },
      { q:`Operationalization of a variable in research refers to:`, ch:[`The statistical analysis plan for the study`,`The process of precisely defining a variable by specifying the procedures or criteria used to measure it ŌĆö converting an abstract concept into a measurable observation`,`The random assignment of participants to conditions`,`The ethical approval process`], ans:1, exp:`Operationalization: translating abstract constructs into concrete, measurable definitions. Example: 'stress' could be operationalized as cortisol level, self-report scale score, or heart rate variability. Good operationalization requires: validity (measures what it claims to measure), reliability (consistent across time and raters), and practicality. Conceptual definition: abstract theoretical meaning. Operational definition: specific measurement procedure. Construct validity: do the operational measures capture the theoretical construct?` },
      { q:`The Hawthorne effect refers to:`, ch:[`Increased aggression in overcrowded environments`,`The phenomenon in which people modify their behavior because they know they are being observed ŌĆö initially identified in factory productivity studies`,`The tendency to perform better in front of an audience`,`The effect of lighting conditions on workplace productivity`], ans:1, exp:`Hawthorne effect: identified at Western Electric's Hawthorne Works in 1920sŌĆō1930s (Mayo). Workers in the study showed improved productivity regardless of which variable was changed ŌĆö attributed to awareness of being observed and feeling valued. The original data have been disputed (not purely artifactual), but the concept remains influential. Implication for research: participants may change behavior when observed ŌåÆ biases results. Control strategies: unobtrusive observation, control groups, habituation periods. Relevance in clinical trials: patient behavior may change just due to participation, independent of treatment.` },
      { q:`A prospective cohort study differs from a retrospective cohort study in that:`, ch:[`Prospective studies are shorter in duration`,`Prospective studies follow participants forward in time from exposure to outcome, while retrospective studies look backward at already-collected data or use existing records to reconstruct exposure and outcome history`,`Retrospective studies use larger sample sizes`,`Prospective studies do not need control groups`], ans:1, exp:`Prospective cohort: follow up from now into the future ŌåÆ can directly measure exposure, control confounders, establish temporal sequence, measure multiple outcomes. Time-consuming, expensive, loss to follow-up. Example: Framingham Heart Study. Retrospective cohort: use existing records to reconstruct cohort ŌĆö faster, cheaper, but limited to variables recorded, potential recall/record bias. Case-control study: begins with outcome, looks back for exposure ŌĆö efficient for rare diseases, but susceptible to recall bias and selection bias in control selection. RCT vs. cohort: RCT has random assignment (controls confounding); cohort does not.` },
      { q:`In sociological research, ethnography involves:`, ch:[`Analyzing large datasets of demographic information`,`Immersive, in-depth qualitative study of a culture or social group through participant observation, fieldwork, and interviews to understand social life from the insider perspective`,`Randomized surveys of large population samples`,`Controlled laboratory experiments of group behavior`], ans:1, exp:`Ethnography: qualitative methodology originating in anthropology. Researcher immerses in the setting ŌĆö observing, participating, interviewing. Goal: thick description (Geertz) ŌĆö understanding cultural practices from the actor's perspective (emic view). Strengths: rich, contextual data; discovers unexpected patterns. Weaknesses: time-intensive; small non-representative samples; researcher bias (reflexivity required); ethical challenges. Examples: Goffman's asylum studies, Duneier's 'Sidewalk'. Grounded theory (Glaser & Strauss): theory emerges inductively from ethnographic data rather than testing pre-existing hypotheses.` },
      { q:`Social capital, as conceptualized by Putnam, refers to:`, ch:[`The total financial assets of a social class`,`The networks of relationships, norms of reciprocity, and trust among individuals and groups that facilitate collective action and resource access`,`Cultural knowledge and education that confers social status`,`The hereditary transfer of social advantages`], ans:1, exp:`Social capital (Putnam): trust, norms, and networks facilitating cooperation. Bonding social capital: strong ties within homogeneous groups (family, close friends) ŌĆö provides emotional support, resources within group. Bridging social capital: weak ties across diverse groups ŌĆö provides access to new information, opportunities, broader resources. Bourdieu's capital types: economic (financial), cultural (education, habits, tastes ŌĆö habitus), social (networks), symbolic (prestige). Bourdieu viewed social capital as reproducing class inequality. Social capital linked to health outcomes ŌĆö social isolation increases mortality risk.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps04`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Sensation & Perception Basics`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The process of converting physical stimuli (e.g., light, sound) into neural signals is called:`, ch:[`Perception`,`Transduction`,`Accommodation`,`Adaptation`], ans:1, exp:`Transduction: converting physical energy (photons, sound waves, pressure, chemicals) into electrochemical signals. Photoreceptors (rods/cones): light ŌåÆ hyperpolarization. Hair cells (cochlea): mechanical vibration ŌåÆ depolarization. Taste buds: chemical ŌåÆ depolarization. Transduction is part of sensation; perception is the interpretation of those signals in the brain (top-down processing involved).` },
      { q:`Absolute threshold is defined as:`, ch:[`The minimum change in stimulus intensity detectable 50% of the time`,`The minimum stimulus intensity detectable 50% of the time`,`The point at which a stimulus becomes painful`,`The maximum intensity detectable by a sense organ`], ans:1, exp:`Absolute threshold: the minimum stimulus intensity required for detection 50% of the time (not a fixed level ŌĆö it varies with attention, fatigue, noise, etc.). Difference threshold (just noticeable difference/JND): minimum detectable change in stimulus intensity ŌĆö follows Weber's Law: ╬öI/I = k (constant). Signal detection theory replaces simple threshold concept: separates sensitivity (d') from response bias (criterion ╬▓).` },
      { q:`According to the trichromatic (Young-Helmholtz) theory of color vision, color perception relies on:`, ch:[`One type of photoreceptor with different sensitivities`,`Three types of cones with peak sensitivities to short (blue), medium (green), and long (red) wavelengths; relative activation pattern encodes color`,`Opponent-process coding from the start`,`A single hue dimension`], ans:1, exp:`Trichromatic theory (Young, Helmholtz): three cone types (S, M, L ŌĆö short/medium/long wavelength). Color = ratio of activation. Explains color mixing (additive), colorblindness (missing or abnormal cone type: most common = red-green = L or M cone defect, X-linked). Opponent-process theory (Hering): pairs (red-green, blue-yellow, black-white) ŌĆö explains afterimages and color constancy. Both theories operate at different levels: trichromatic at photoreceptor level; opponent-process at ganglion/lateral geniculate level.` },
      { q:`Sensory adaptation refers to:`, ch:[`Increased sensitivity to a persistent stimulus over time`,`Decreased sensitivity to a constant, unchanging stimulus over time ŌĆö allows the nervous system to focus on new stimuli`,`The process of perceiving stimuli below the absolute threshold`,`The organization of sensory information into meaningful patterns`], ans:1, exp:`Sensory adaptation: prolonged exposure to a constant stimulus ŌåÆ reduced neural firing ŌåÆ diminished perception. Examples: perfume smell fades after minutes; skin pressure from clothing unnoticed; eyes adjust to constant dim light. Not all systems adapt equally: pain adapts slowly (evolutionary advantage); visual system does not adapt away from sharp borders (eye microsaccades prevent receptor bleaching). Adaptation ŌēĀ habituation (habituation is a learned behavioral response reduction).` },
      { q:`The gestalt principle of figure-ground refers to:`, ch:[`Perceiving similar objects as belonging together`,`The tendency to perceive one part of a visual scene as the object of focus (figure) and the rest as background (ground)`,`Perceiving incomplete figures as complete`,`Organizing stimuli into groups based on proximity`], ans:1, exp:`Gestalt principles of perceptual organization: figure-ground (foreground vs. background parsing), proximity (nearby elements grouped), similarity (like elements grouped), continuity (smooth contours grouped), closure (incomplete figures perceived as complete), common fate (objects moving together grouped), pr├żgnanz/good form (simplest interpretation chosen). Rubin's vase: classic figure-ground ambiguity. These principles reflect the brain's tendency to organize sensory input into coherent objects.` },
      { q:`The phi phenomenon, described by Wertheimer, refers to:`, ch:[`Perceiving depth from binocular disparity`,`The perception of movement created by a series of static images displayed in rapid succession (apparent motion)`,`The tendency to fill in gaps in incomplete figures`,`Misperceiving size due to background contrast`], ans:1, exp:`Phi phenomenon: rapid sequential presentation of stationary stimuli creates illusion of motion. Basis for cinema and animation. Stroboscopic motion (apparent motion): lights flashing alternately appear to move. Wertheimer (1912): demonstration was key evidence for Gestalt psychology ŌĆö the perception (motion) is more than the sum of its parts (individual still images). Beta movement: variant in which an object appears to jump from one position to another.` },
      { q:`Which cue provides depth perception using one eye (monocular cue)?`, ch:[`Retinal disparity`,`Convergence`,`Linear perspective ŌĆö parallel lines appear to converge at a vanishing point, signaling depth`,`Stereopsis`], ans:2, exp:`Monocular depth cues (one eye): linear perspective (parallel lines converge), interposition/occlusion (nearer objects block distant ones), relative size (farther objects appear smaller), texture gradient (fine texture signals distance), shading, motion parallax (near objects move faster across retina during head movement), aerial perspective (distant objects appear hazy). Binocular depth cues (two eyes): retinal disparity (each eye has slightly different image; basis for stereopsis), convergence (eye muscles turn inward for near objects). Stereopsis: the perceptual depth from retinal disparity; used in 3D movies.` },
      { q:`The McGurk effect demonstrates that:`, ch:[`Hearing is the dominant sense for speech perception`,`Speech perception is multimodal ŌĆö visual lip-reading information automatically integrates with auditory input; watching someone say 'ga' while hearing 'ba' produces the perception of 'da'`,`The brain processes speech purely through auditory cortex`,`Lip-reading does not influence speech perception in normal hearing`], ans:1, exp:`McGurk effect (McGurk & MacDonald, 1976): auditory syllable 'ba' + visual lip movements for 'ga' ŌåÆ perceived as 'da'. Demonstrates that visual speech information (articulatory gestures) automatically and obligatorily integrates with auditory information. Cannot be suppressed by knowing about the illusion. Neurological basis: multisensory integration in superior temporal sulcus (STS). Clinically: understanding of multisensory integration helps explain lip-reading benefits for hearing-impaired.` },
      { q:`Gate control theory (Melzack and Wall) of pain proposes that:`, ch:[`All pain signals travel directly and unmodified to the brain`,`Pain perception can be modulated at the spinal cord level ŌĆö large-diameter (A╬▓) fiber stimulation activates inhibitory interneurons in the dorsal horn that close the 'gate,' reducing transmission of pain signals from small-diameter (A╬┤, C) nociceptive fibers`,`Pain receptors adapt rapidly like other sensory receptors`,`The perception of pain is purely psychological`], ans:1, exp:`Gate control theory (1965): spinal cord dorsal horn (substantia gelatinosa) = 'gate.' A╬▓ fibers (touch/pressure, large diameter, fast) + A╬┤/C fibers (pain, small diameter) both converge. Large-fiber input activates inhibitory interneuron ŌåÆ reduces transmission cell firing ŌåÆ closes gate (reduces pain). Small-fiber input inhibits inhibitory interneuron ŌåÆ opens gate (increases pain). Descending modulation: brain can also close the gate (stress-induced analgesia, opioids). Clinical application: TENS (transcutaneous electrical nerve stimulation) activates A╬▓ fibers ŌåÆ closes gate.` },
      { q:`Which perceptual phenomenon explains why the moon appears larger on the horizon than when overhead?`, ch:[`Increased light refraction at the horizon`,`The moon illusion ŌĆö due to monocular depth cues (interposition, texture gradient) on the horizon making the horizon moon seem farther away ŌåÆ brain applies size constancy ŌåÆ perceives it as larger`,`The moon actually is closer to Earth when near the horizon`,`Atmospheric magnification of the moon's image`], ans:1, exp:`Moon illusion: the moon subtends the same visual angle (~0.5┬░) whether at horizon or zenith, but appears ~1.3ŌĆō1.5├Ś larger at the horizon. Explanations: relative size cues (buildings, trees provide reference ŌåÆ horizon moon perceived as farther ŌåÆ brain upscales apparent size = Emmert's Law version); flattened sky dome perception. The illusion disappears when viewed through a tube (removes context). Ames room: another illusion using depth misperception to distort apparent size.` },
      { q:`Signal detection theory (SDT) improved upon threshold theory by:`, ch:[`Eliminating the concept of noise in perception`,`Separating a person's sensory sensitivity (d-prime) from their decision criterion (╬▓) ŌĆö accounting for the fact that detecting a signal depends both on its strength and the perceiver's willingness to say 'yes'`,`Measuring absolute thresholds more precisely`,`Showing that thresholds are fixed biological constants`], ans:1, exp:`SDT: any detection situation involves a signal distribution and noise distribution. d' (d-prime): distance between means of signal and noise distributions = sensitivity (independent of criterion). Criterion (╬▓): decision threshold, influenced by payoffs, costs, base rates ŌĆö reflects response bias. Hits, misses, false alarms, correct rejections form the response matrix. ROC curve: trade-off between hit rate and false alarm rate as criterion changes. Applications: radiology (reading X-rays), eyewitness identification, clinical diagnosis ŌĆö optimal criterion setting depends on relative costs of miss vs. false alarm.` },
      { q:`Priming in cognitive psychology refers to:`, ch:[`Generating a response to stimuli presented below the absolute threshold`,`A prior stimulus (prime) facilitates faster or altered processing of a subsequent related stimulus (target) by activating associated mental representations`,`The conscious strategy of relating new information to existing knowledge`,`Retrieval of emotional memories from the amygdala`], ans:1, exp:`Priming: implicit memory phenomenon. Semantic priming: seeing 'doctor' primes faster recognition of 'nurse' (spreading activation in semantic networks). Perceptual priming: prior exposure to a word/image facilitates later perceptual identification ŌĆö implicit, not requiring conscious recall. Repetition priming: prior exposure to a stimulus improves subsequent processing. Priming does not require conscious awareness. Basis: connectionist models ŌĆö nodes in semantic network become pre-activated. Applications: marketing, eyewitness questioning (leading questions prime specific answer schemas).` },
      { q:`Top-down processing in perception involves:`, ch:[`Building perception purely from raw sensory data upward`,`Using prior knowledge, expectations, context, and concepts to interpret incoming sensory information ŌĆö expectations literally shape what we perceive`,`Processing that occurs below the level of consciousness`,`The neurological pathway from primary sensory cortex to association areas`], ans:1, exp:`Top-down (conceptually-driven): higher cognitive processes (expectations, context, goals, knowledge) influence sensory processing. Example: reading degraded text when context provides word prediction; seeing faces in clouds; phonemic restoration effect (missing phoneme 'heard' due to word context). Bottom-up (data-driven): stimulus-driven, builds from elementary features. Real perception: dynamic interplay. Predictive coding (Bayesian brain): brain constantly generates predictions about incoming sensory data; only prediction errors propagate upward. Context effects, experience, and attention are key top-down influences.` },
      { q:`Selective attention refers to:`, ch:[`The ability to attend to multiple streams of information simultaneously`,`The ability to focus cognitive resources on a specific stimulus or task while filtering out irrelevant information`,`Switching attention rapidly between two tasks`,`A decline in attention over time due to fatigue`], ans:1, exp:`Selective attention: the 'cocktail party effect' ŌĆö ability to tune in to one voice among many. Dichotic listening studies: Cherry (1953) ŌĆö information in the unattended ear (except one's own name) is not processed semantically. Broadbent's filter model (early selection); Deutsch-Norman model (late selection). Attenuation model (Treisman): attended channel is processed fully; unattended channels attenuated but not blocked ŌĆö explains why highly significant signals (one's name) break through. Neural correlates: prefrontal cortex (attentional control), parietal cortex (spatial attention).` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps05`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Sleep, Dreams & Consciousness`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`During REM (rapid eye movement) sleep, which of the following is TRUE?`, ch:[`Muscle tone is high`,`The brain is least active during REM sleep`,`Vivid dreaming occurs; the brain shows high-frequency, low-amplitude EEG activity similar to wakefulness; skeletal muscles are paralyzed (REM atonia)`,`Heart rate and breathing are at their slowest`], ans:2, exp:`REM sleep: irregular, low-amplitude, high-frequency EEG (desynchronized) ŌĆö paradoxical sleep. REM atonia: active inhibition of motor neurons (except eye muscles and diaphragm) by the brainstem ŌĆö prevents acting out dreams. Most vivid, narrative dreaming occurs. Heart rate, respiration, and blood pressure are irregular and variable. PGO (ponto-geniculo-occipital) waves. Penile erection/clitoral engorgement occur. REM rebounds after deprivation. Functions proposed: emotional memory consolidation, synaptic pruning, creativity.` },
      { q:`NREM Stage 3 sleep (slow-wave sleep) is characterized by:`, ch:[`High-frequency beta waves`,`Theta waves with sleep spindles and K-complexes`,`High-amplitude, low-frequency delta waves (0.5ŌĆō4 Hz) comprising >20% of the epoch`,`Alpha waves and relaxed wakefulness`], ans:2, exp:`Sleep stages by EEG: Awake (alert): beta (>13 Hz). Awake (relaxed/eyes closed): alpha (8ŌĆō12 Hz). NREM Stage 1: theta (4ŌĆō8 Hz); hypnic jerks. NREM Stage 2: theta + sleep spindles (12ŌĆō15 Hz bursts) + K-complexes. NREM Stage 3 (deep/slow-wave sleep, SWS): delta (0.5ŌĆō4 Hz, >20% of epoch). REM: mixed-frequency, low amplitude. Functions of SWS: physical restoration (GH secretion), declarative memory consolidation. SWS decreases with age. Parasomnias in SWS: sleepwalking, night terrors, confusional arousals.` },
      { q:`The suprachiasmatic nucleus (SCN) of the hypothalamus regulates:`, ch:[`Appetite and satiety`,`The circadian rhythm (approximately 24-hour biological clock), synchronized to the light-dark cycle via retinal input`,`Short-term memory consolidation`,`Pain modulation`], ans:1, exp:`SCN: master circadian pacemaker in the anterior hypothalamus. Receives photic input from intrinsically photosensitive retinal ganglion cells (ipRGCs containing melanopsin) via the retinohypothalamic tract. Molecular clock: CLOCK/BMAL1 ŌåÆ transcription of Per/Cry ŌåÆ PER/CRY proteins ŌåÆ negative feedback. SCN ŌåÆ pineal gland ŌåÆ melatonin (suppressed by light; released in darkness). Jet lag, shift work, and some mood disorders involve circadian misalignment. SCN lesions ŌåÆ loss of circadian rhythms.` },
      { q:`The activation-synthesis theory of dreams (Hobson and McCarley) proposes that:`, ch:[`Dreams are the fulfillment of unconscious wishes`,`Dreams result from the brain (cortex) attempting to synthesize meaning from random neural signals generated by the brainstem during REM sleep`,`Dreams are conscious planning for future events`,`All dreaming is meaningless neural noise`], ans:1, exp:`Activation-synthesis (1977): PGO waves from pons + brainstem ŌåÆ randomly activate sensory and motor areas ŌåÆ forebrain (cortex) synthesizes this random input into narratives = dreams. Dreams may be meaningful because the cortex applies personal schemas to random input, but not because they reflect specific unconscious wishes. Contrast: Freudian wish-fulfillment theory ŌĆö dreams represent disguised fulfillment of repressed wishes; manifest content (remembered dream) vs. latent content (hidden meaning). Modern view: dreams likely serve memory consolidation and emotional processing functions.` },
      { q:`Sleep deprivation primarily impairs which cognitive functions first?`, ch:[`Long-term memory retrieval`,`Sustained attention, working memory, executive function, and reaction time ŌĆö these are most sensitive to sleep loss`,`Motor skills and procedural learning`,`Semantic memory and vocabulary`], ans:1, exp:`Sleep deprivation effects: acute total: impaired sustained attention, reaction time, working memory, executive function (prefrontal cortex is most sensitive), impulse control, emotional regulation. Microsleeps (brief uncontrolled sleep episodes of 1ŌĆō10 seconds) occur. Psychomotor vigilance task (PVT): gold standard for sleep deprivation effects. Chronic partial sleep restriction (< 6 h/night): accumulates 'sleep debt'; subjective sleepiness adapts (does not reflect objective impairment) ŌåÆ people don't perceive how impaired they are. Motor skills and long-term memory are less acutely affected but are impaired with severe deprivation.` },
      { q:`Narcolepsy is associated with a deficiency of:`, ch:[`Serotonin in the raphe nuclei`,`Hypocretin (orexin) ŌĆö produced by lateral hypothalamic neurons; deficiency leads to fragmented sleep-wake regulation, cataplexy (sudden muscle weakness triggered by emotion), sleep paralysis, and hypnagogic hallucinations`,`GABA in the thalamus`,`Melatonin from the pineal gland`], ans:1, exp:`Narcolepsy type 1 (with cataplexy): HLA-DQB1*06:02 ŌĆö autoimmune destruction of ~70,000 hypocretin neurons in lateral hypothalamus. Hypocretin (orexin) promotes wakefulness and stabilizes sleep-wake states. Symptoms: excessive daytime sleepiness (EDS), cataplexy (sudden bilateral muscle atonia triggered by laughter, surprise ŌåÆ REM atonia intruding into wakefulness), sleep paralysis (unable to move on awakening or falling asleep), hypnagogic hallucinations (vivid hallucinations at sleep onset = dreaming while transitioning). Treatment: modafinil/sodium oxybate (wakefulness), SSRIs (cataplexy), venlafaxine.` },
      { q:`Meditation and mindfulness practices alter consciousness by:`, ch:[`Inducing NREM Stage 3 deep sleep states`,`Inducing relaxed, present-focused awareness associated with increased alpha and theta EEG activity, decreased default mode network (DMN) activity, and reduced mind-wandering`,`Eliminating all sensory awareness`,`Activating fight-or-flight sympathetic responses`], ans:1, exp:`Mindfulness: paying non-judgmental attention to the present moment. EEG: increased alpha (8ŌĆō12 Hz) and theta (4ŌĆō8 Hz) activity. fMRI: reduced activity in default mode network (DMN = medial PFC, posterior cingulate, precuneus ŌĆö active during mind-wandering and self-referential thought). Structural changes with long-term practice: increased cortical thickness in prefrontal regions and insula. Health effects: reduced stress (lower cortisol), improved attention, reduced anxiety/depression. Distinct from hypnosis (narrowed, focused attention with increased suggestibility) and REM/NREM sleep.` },
      { q:`Psychoactive substances that mimic endogenous neurotransmitters act by:`, ch:[`Irreversibly destroying receptors`,`Binding to the same receptors as endogenous neurotransmitters ŌĆö agonists activate the receptor; antagonists block it. Examples: opioids mimic endorphins; benzodiazepines enhance GABA; LSD acts on serotonin receptors`,`Enhancing immune system function`,`Only affecting the peripheral nervous system`], ans:1, exp:`Drug-receptor interactions: Agonist: binds receptor ŌåÆ activates it ŌåÆ mimics neurotransmitter (morphine at ╬╝-opioid receptor; nicotine at nAChR). Partial agonist: binds and activates but with lower efficacy (buprenorphine at ╬╝-opioid). Antagonist: binds receptor but does not activate; blocks agonist access (naloxone at ╬╝-opioid; haloperidol at D2). Inverse agonist: binds receptor and causes opposite effect to agonist. Tolerance: receptor downregulation or desensitization with chronic exposure. Dependence: physical adaptation; withdrawal on discontinuation.` },
      { q:`Which sleep disorder is characterized by cessation of breathing during sleep due to upper airway obstruction?`, ch:[`Insomnia`,`Restless legs syndrome`,`Obstructive sleep apnea (OSA) ŌĆö repeated upper airway collapse ŌåÆ apneic episodes ŌåÆ hypoxemia, arousals, fragmented sleep, excessive daytime sleepiness, and cardiovascular risk`,`Rapid eye movement sleep behavior disorder`], ans:2, exp:`OSA: most common sleep-related breathing disorder. Risk factors: obesity (especially central), male sex, age, alcohol/sedatives, anatomical factors (retrognathia, tonsillar hypertrophy). Polysomnography (PSG): gold standard; AHI (apnea-hypopnea index) Ōēź 5/hr = OSA; Ōēź 30 = severe. Complications: hypertension, coronary artery disease, heart failure, stroke, T2DM, depression. Treatment: CPAP (continuous positive airway pressure) first-line for moderate-severe OSA. REM sleep behavior disorder: act out dreams (REM atonia fails); associated with synucleinopathies (Parkinson, DLB, MSA).` },
      { q:`The default mode network (DMN) in the brain is most active during:`, ch:[`Focused, goal-directed cognitive tasks`,`Rest, daydreaming, mind-wandering, and self-referential thinking ŌĆö the DMN deactivates during externally directed attention`,`Deep NREM sleep`,`Sensory processing of new stimuli`], ans:1, exp:`DMN: medial prefrontal cortex, posterior cingulate cortex/precuneus, angular gyrus, medial temporal lobe. Active during: rest (task-free), mind-wandering, autobiographical memory retrieval, future planning (mental time travel), mentalizing/theory of mind. Deactivates during externally focused tasks. DMN dysfunction: implicated in depression (rumination), Alzheimer disease (amyloid preferentially accumulates in DMN hubs), ADHD (failure to suppress DMN during tasks). Functional connectivity (resting-state fMRI): brain network characterized by correlated spontaneous activity.` },
      { q:`Hypnosis is best characterized as:`, ch:[`A state of unconsciousness`,`A state of heightened suggestibility and focused attention, associated with dissociation from awareness; used therapeutically for pain, anxiety, and behavior change; individual differences in hypnotizability are stable traits`,`A form of deep NREM sleep`,`A dissociative disorder induced by external suggestion`], ans:1, exp:`Hypnosis: debate between state (special altered state of consciousness, resembles dissociation) and non-state (social role-playing, expectancy, imagination) theories. EEG during hypnosis: increased theta and alpha waves; decreased gamma. Highly hypnotizable individuals: better at focusing attention, richer mental imagery, more absorption-prone. Therapeutic uses: pain management (procedural, childbirth), IBS, smoking cessation, phobias (evidence modest for most). Hypnotic analgesia: fMRI shows reduced activity in anterior cingulate (attentional aspect of pain) but not somatosensory cortex.` },
      { q:`The reticular activating system (RAS) is primarily responsible for:`, ch:[`Motor coordination and balance`,`Arousal and wakefulness maintenance ŌĆö a network in the brainstem (reticular formation) that regulates consciousness; damage ŌåÆ coma`,`Visual processing in the occipital cortex`,`Short-term memory encoding in the hippocampus`], ans:1, exp:`Reticular activating system (ascending arousal system): brainstem reticular formation + specific modulatory nuclei. Key neurotransmitters: norepinephrine (locus coeruleus), serotonin (dorsal raphe), histamine (tuberomammillary nucleus), acetylcholine (basal forebrain + pedunculopontine tegmental nucleus), orexin/hypocretin (lateral hypothalamus). All project to thalamus and cortex ŌåÆ tonic cortical arousal. Damage ŌåÆ reduced consciousness (persistent vegetative state, coma). Benzodiazepines/anesthetics enhance GABA ŌåÆ reduce RAS activity ŌåÆ sedation.` },
      { q:`Sleep architecture changes across the normal night in that:`, ch:[`REM periods become shorter across the night`,`Slow-wave sleep (SWS) is concentrated in the first third of the night while REM sleep is concentrated in the last third`,`NREM Stage 2 only occurs at sleep onset`,`Sleep cycles last about 20 minutes each`], ans:1, exp:`Sleep cycle: ~90 minutes. First half of night: long SWS (Stage 3) episodes, short REM periods. Second half of night: little SWS, long REM periods. Full night: 4ŌĆō5 complete cycles. Total: adults ~20ŌĆō25% REM, ~15ŌĆō20% SWS. With age: SWS dramatically decreases; REM percentage relatively preserved; more awakenings. Infants: 50% REM (possibly important for brain development). Microsleep and brief awakenings (not usually remembered) are normal.` },
      { q:`Dissociative disorders involve:`, ch:[`Perceptual distortions of external stimuli`,`A disruption in the normal integration of consciousness, memory, identity, emotion, perception, behavior, or sense of self ŌĆö includes dissociative amnesia, dissociative identity disorder, and depersonalization/derealization`,`A primary psychotic break from reality`,`Motor disturbances without psychological cause`], ans:1, exp:`Dissociative disorders: on a spectrum with normal dissociation (daydreaming, highway hypnosis). Dissociative amnesia: memory loss for personal information or traumatic events. Dissociative identity disorder (DID): two or more distinct personality states (alters); typically associated with severe early trauma. Depersonalization/derealization disorder: persistent feeling of being detached from one's mind/body (depersonalization) or surroundings (derealization). Pathological dissociation: defense mechanism against overwhelming trauma. Treatment: psychotherapy (trauma-focused), not antipsychotics.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps06`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Stress & Coping`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The general adaptation syndrome (GAS) described by Hans Selye consists of which three stages?`, ch:[`Fight, flight, freeze`,`Alarm, resistance, exhaustion`,`Anticipation, response, recovery`,`Arousal, adaptation, suppression`], ans:1, exp:`GAS (Selye, 1936): (1) Alarm reaction: HPA axis + sympathetic nervous system activated ŌåÆ cortisol + epinephrine/norepinephrine ŌåÆ fight-or-flight response. (2) Resistance: body adapts to the ongoing stressor; physiological arousal decreases toward normal but remains elevated; resources depleted over time. (3) Exhaustion: prolonged stress depletes resources ŌåÆ breakdown of physiological defenses ŌåÆ increased illness vulnerability. Selye coined the term 'stress' in its modern biological sense. Stressor types: acute (challenge) vs. chronic (ongoing); physiological vs. psychological.` },
      { q:`Cortisol is released during the stress response primarily from:`, ch:[`The thyroid gland`,`The adrenal cortex ŌĆö stimulated by ACTH from the anterior pituitary, which is stimulated by CRH from the hypothalamus (HPA axis)`,`The adrenal medulla`,`The hippocampus`], ans:1, exp:`HPA axis: hypothalamus ŌåÆ CRH (corticotropin-releasing hormone) ŌåÆ anterior pituitary ŌåÆ ACTH (adrenocorticotropic hormone) ŌåÆ adrenal cortex ŌåÆ cortisol. Cortisol: glucocorticoid; increases blood glucose (gluconeogenesis), anti-inflammatory (initially), immunosuppressive. Negative feedback: cortisol ŌåÆ hypothalamus + pituitary (inhibits further CRH/ACTH release). Hippocampus has many glucocorticoid receptors ŌåÆ critical for feedback; chronic stress ŌåÆ hippocampal atrophy. Adrenal medulla: releases epinephrine + norepinephrine (catecholamines) via sympathetic nerve stimulation ŌåÆ rapid fight-or-flight.` },
      { q:`Problem-focused coping strategies involve:`, ch:[`Seeking emotional support from others`,`Directly addressing the source of stress ŌĆö solving the problem, seeking information, planning, changing the stressful situation`,`Reappraising the stressor as less threatening`,`Avoiding or denying the stressor`], ans:1, exp:`Lazarus & Folkman transactional model: stress = appraisal of threat exceeding available coping resources. Two coping strategies: Problem-focused: addresses the stressor directly ŌĆö information seeking, problem-solving, planning, changing behavior. Emotion-focused: manages the emotional response ŌĆö social support seeking, cognitive reappraisal, mindfulness, venting, wishful thinking. Adaptive in contexts where problem can be solved; emotion-focused more adaptive when situation is uncontrollable. Reappraisal: cognitively reframing the stressor as less threatening or more manageable ŌĆö most adaptive emotion-focused strategy.` },
      { q:`Perceived control over a stressor tends to:`, ch:[`Increase physiological stress responses`,`Reduce the psychological and physiological impact of a stressor ŌĆö even the belief that one could control a stressor reduces distress`,`Have no effect on stress response magnitude`,`Only affect subjective distress, not physiological indicators`], ans:1, exp:`Perceived control: Seligman's learned helplessness ŌĆö lack of control produces worst outcomes. Glass & Singer (1972): participants exposed to loud noise could tolerate it better when they had a button to stop it, even if they never pressed it. Type A personality vs. Type B: Type A (time urgency, competitiveness, hostility) associated with increased cardiovascular risk, partly through reduced perceived control and chronic sympathetic arousal. Mastery: belief in one's ability to control outcomes ŌĆö protective against depression, anxiety, and poor health.` },
      { q:`The social support buffering hypothesis proposes that:`, ch:[`Social support always reduces stress`,`Social support reduces the harmful effects of stressors by providing resources (emotional, informational, tangible) that help people appraise and cope with stress ŌĆö it buffers the relationship between stress and illness`,`Social support increases stress by adding social obligations`,`Only tangible support (money, services) has health benefits`], ans:1, exp:`Social support: main effect model ŌĆö support is beneficial regardless of stress level. Buffering model ŌĆö support specifically protects under high stress. Types: (1) Emotional (empathy, listening); (2) Informational (advice, guidance); (3) Instrumental/tangible (money, services); (4) Appraisal (feedback for self-evaluation). Social isolation is a major health risk factor (comparable to smoking). Social support ŌåÆ reduced HPA axis reactivity, better immune function, faster recovery, lower mortality. Social support can also be harmful: social control (pressure), excessive advice, undermining autonomy.` },
      { q:`Post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD) involves which of the following symptom clusters?`, ch:[`Only flashbacks and nightmares`,`Re-experiencing (intrusive memories, nightmares, flashbacks), avoidance (avoiding reminders), negative alterations in cognitions and mood, and hyperarousal (startle, hypervigilance, sleep disturbance)`,`Depression and panic attacks only`,`Dissociative episodes without re-experiencing`], ans:1, exp:`PTSD (DSM-5): follows exposure to actual or threatened death, serious injury, or sexual violence. Four symptom clusters: B (re-experiencing: intrusive memories, nightmares, flashbacks, psychological/physiological reactivity to cues); C (avoidance: thoughts, feelings, external reminders); D (negative alterations: anhedonia, guilt, blame, amnesia, estrangement); E (hyperarousal: sleep disturbance, irritability, hypervigilance, exaggerated startle). Minimum duration: 1 month. Neurobiology: amygdala hyperactivation, reduced hippocampal volume, impaired medial PFC inhibition of amygdala. Treatment: trauma-focused CBT, EMDR, SSRIs.` },
      { q:`Which neurotransmitter system is the primary target of anti-anxiety medications (benzodiazepines)?`, ch:[`Dopaminergic system`,`GABAergic system ŌĆö benzodiazepines bind GABAA receptors and enhance the effect of GABA (by increasing frequency of ClŌłÆ channel opening), increasing inhibitory transmission`,`Noradrenergic system`,`Serotonergic system`], ans:1, exp:`GABAA receptor: ligand-gated ClŌłÆ channel. GABA binds ŌåÆ channel opens ŌåÆ ClŌłÆ influx ŌåÆ hyperpolarization ŌåÆ decreased neuronal excitability. Benzodiazepines: bind benzodiazepine site (on ╬│-subunit) ŌåÆ allosteric modulator ŌåÆ increases frequency of channel opening (GABA must still be present ŌĆö they are positive allosteric modulators). Barbiturates: increase duration of channel opening; at high doses, open channel directly (more dangerous, narrow therapeutic index). Z-drugs (zolpidem, zaleplon): GABAA agonists at ╬▒1 subunit ŌåÆ sedation with less anxiolytic/muscle relaxant effect. BZD risks: tolerance, dependence, withdrawal seizures, amnesia, falls in elderly.` },
      { q:`The tend-and-befriend response to stress, described by Taylor et al., is more common in:`, ch:[`Males, due to higher testosterone levels`,`Females ŌĆö under stress, many women are more likely to seek social support and nurture others (oxytocin + estrogen enhance this response), whereas the classic fight-or-flight model was predominantly based on male research`,`Children, not adults`,`Individuals with Type A personality`], ans:1, exp:`Taylor et al. (2000): challenged the universality of fight-or-flight. In females, stress activates both sympathetic (fight-or-flight) AND tends-and-befriends. Oxytocin: released by HPA + stress; oxytocin effects amplified by estrogen, attenuated by testosterone. 'Tending': nurturing offspring. 'Befriending': affiliating with social groups. Adaptive advantage: caregiving without abandonment in threat situations. Males show it too but less prominently. Research historically used male subjects ŌåÆ biased understanding of stress responses.` },
      { q:`Eustress differs from distress in that:`, ch:[`Eustress activates the HPA axis while distress does not`,`Eustress refers to positive, beneficial stress that enhances performance and motivation (e.g., athletic competition, anticipation of a positive event), while distress refers to negative, harmful stress that impairs function`,`Eustress only occurs in children`,`Eustress and distress are physiologically identical`], ans:1, exp:`Selye's distinction: eustress (positive) ŌĆö manageable challenge, motivating, promotes growth. Distress (negative) ŌĆö overwhelming, harmful. Physiologically both activate stress response (cortisol, epinephrine), but psychological appraisal and controllability differ. Yerkes-Dodson inverted-U law: performance is optimal at moderate arousal ŌĆö too little arousal ŌåÆ boredom/underperformance; too much arousal ŌåÆ anxiety/impaired performance. Optimal arousal level varies with task complexity (higher optimal arousal for simple tasks, lower for complex tasks).` },
      { q:`Hardiness as a personality trait involves:`, ch:[`Avoidance of challenging situations`,`Commitment (finding meaning in life), control (belief in ability to influence events), and challenge (viewing change as an opportunity) ŌĆö associated with better health outcomes under stress`,`Emotional suppression`,`Pessimistic explanatory style`], ans:1, exp:`Hardiness (Kobasa, 1979): personality characteristic that buffers stress. Three C's: (1) Commitment: engagement with life, work, relationships ŌĆö meaning and purpose. (2) Control: internal locus of control ŌĆö belief that one influences events. (3) Challenge: stress seen as opportunity for growth rather than threat. Hardy individuals appraise stressors as less threatening ŌåÆ less HPA activation ŌåÆ better health. Resilience: broader construct ŌĆö ability to bounce back from adversity (involving hardiness, social support, coping skills). Optimism: related protective factor; associated with better immune function and longevity.` },
      { q:`Chronic stress contributes to cardiovascular disease primarily through which mechanism?`, ch:[`Vagal tone increasing heart rate`,`Sustained sympathetic activation and HPA axis activity ŌåÆ elevated cortisol and catecholamines ŌåÆ hypertension, endothelial dysfunction, increased atherosclerosis, platelet aggregation, arrhythmia risk`,`Increased parasympathetic activity`,`Reduced cardiac output only`], ans:1, exp:`Stress-CVD link: chronic sympathetic activation ŌåÆ sustained hypertension (vascular resistance increases). Cortisol: increases blood glucose, promotes central adiposity, increases LDL, decreases HDL. Catecholamines + cortisol: promote inflammation (cytokines), endothelial dysfunction (reduced NO), increased blood coagulation/platelet aggregation. Acute triggers: emotional stress can trigger MI (Takotsubo/broken heart syndrome; exercise-induced ischemia). Allostatic load: cumulative physiological wear from chronic stress across multiple systems (cortisol, BP, glucose, inflammatory markers, BMI). Lower SES: greater allostatic load.` },
      { q:`Immunosuppression from chronic psychological stress occurs because:`, ch:[`Stress increases NK cell activity`,`Glucocorticoids (cortisol) suppress immune function ŌĆö reducing lymphocyte proliferation, NK cell activity, antibody production, and pro-inflammatory cytokine secretion`,`Psychological stress only affects the CNS, not immune function`,`Stress increases IgE production`], ans:1, exp:`Psychoneuroimmunology (PNI): bidirectional communication between brain and immune system via HPA axis (cortisol), autonomic nervous system, and cytokines. Cortisol: potent anti-inflammatory/immunosuppressive. Acute stress: can be briefly immunoenhancing (redistributes lymphocytes to skin/mucosa). Chronic stress: sustained cortisol ŌåÆ T-cell suppression, reduced NK cell cytotoxicity, poorer antibody responses to vaccines, slower wound healing, increased susceptibility to infections. Cohen's common cold study (1991): higher stress ŌåÆ greater susceptibility to rhinovirus. Inflammation: paradoxically, chronic stress also produces low-grade chronic inflammation via NF-╬║B pathway (glucocorticoid resistance).` },
      { q:`Biofeedback is a technique in which:`, ch:[`Patients learn to control drug responses`,`Patients are given real-time physiological feedback (e.g., heart rate, skin conductance, brain waves) and learn to consciously regulate these normally involuntary functions to reduce stress or treat disorders`,`Patients practice relaxation in absence of any feedback`,`The therapist directly alters the patient's physiological responses`], ans:1, exp:`Biofeedback: uses monitoring equipment ŌåÆ displays physiological variable ŌåÆ patient learns to control it through relaxation, breathing, or mental strategies. Types: EMG (muscle tension), thermal (skin temperature), GSR/EDA (galvanic skin response), heart rate variability (HRV), EEG (neurofeedback). Applications: tension headache, migraine (thermal), chronic pain, hypertension, ADHD (neurofeedback), anxiety. Evidence: moderate for headache/migraine (Level A recommendation). Mechanism: operant conditioning of autonomic function via interoception. HRV biofeedback: paced breathing at resonance frequency (~0.1 Hz) ŌåÆ increases vagal tone.` },
      { q:`The fight-or-flight response is mediated by:`, ch:[`The parasympathetic nervous system`,`The sympathetic nervous system and adrenal medulla ŌĆö triggering cardiovascular, respiratory, and metabolic changes that prepare the organism for confrontation or escape`,`The hypothalamic-pituitary-thyroid (HPT) axis`,`Only the limbic system with no peripheral involvement`], ans:1, exp:`Fight-or-flight (Cannon): amygdala ŌåÆ hypothalamus ŌåÆ SNS ŌåÆ adrenal medulla ŌåÆ epinephrine (80%) + norepinephrine (20%). Effects: increased HR, BP, respiratory rate, bronchodilation, increased blood glucose (glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis), pupil dilation, blood redistributed from digestive organs to muscles. Parasympathetic (rest-and-digest): opposite ŌĆö decreased HR, increased GI motility, pupil constriction, glandular secretions. Acute response is adaptive but chronic activation ŌåÆ disease (metabolic syndrome, HTN, atherosclerosis). Freeze response: a third response to inescapable threat; mediated by dorsal vagal complex (Porges' polyvagal theory).` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps07`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Emotion Theories`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The James-Lange theory of emotion proposes that:`, ch:[`Emotions are universal biological responses`,`Emotions follow from the perception of physiological changes ŌĆö we feel afraid because we notice our heart racing, not the other way around`,`Emotions and physiological arousal occur simultaneously`,`Emotions are purely cognitive evaluations without bodily involvement`], ans:1, exp:`James-Lange (simultaneous but independent proposals, ~1884): stimulus ŌåÆ physiological response ŌåÆ emotion. We do not tremble because we are afraid; we are afraid because we tremble. Cannon-Bard critique: (1) visceral changes are too slow and non-specific; (2) cutting visceral input does not eliminate emotion. Schachter-Singer two-factor theory: arousal + cognitive label = emotion. Cognitive appraisal theories (Lazarus): emotions follow appraisal of events for personal relevance, not purely physiological states.` },
      { q:`The Cannon-Bard theory of emotion proposes that:`, ch:[`Emotional experience precedes physiological responses`,`The thalamus simultaneously relays emotional stimuli to both the cortex (for conscious emotional experience) and the hypothalamus (for physiological response) ŌĆö so emotion and arousal occur at the same time independently`,`Emotions are learned associations`,`Physiological feedback determines emotional quality`], ans:1, exp:`Cannon-Bard: challenged James-Lange by showing: (1) visceral organs respond similarly across different emotions; (2) visceral changes too slow; (3) animals with visceral denervation still show emotions. Thalamus splits the signal: cortex receives ŌåÆ conscious emotion; hypothalamus/ANS ŌåÆ physiological response; these occur simultaneously but independently. Modern view: amygdala (not just thalamus) processes emotional stimuli rapidly. LeDoux: two pathways for fear ŌĆö low road (thalamus ŌåÆ amygdala, fast, imprecise) and high road (thalamus ŌåÆ cortex ŌåÆ amygdala, slower, more detailed).` },
      { q:`Schachter and Singer's two-factor theory of emotion states that:`, ch:[`Emotions are purely determined by cognitive appraisal`,`Emotions require two components: physiological arousal AND a cognitive label; the label is determined by context and attribution of arousal`,`Physiological changes always occur after emotional experience`,`Emotions are hard-wired and do not involve cognition`], ans:1, exp:`Two-factor theory (1962): Misattribution of arousal experiment ŌĆö participants injected with epinephrine (physiological arousal); those told nothing about drug effects attributed arousal to a stooge's behavior (euphoric or angry) ŌåÆ felt that emotion. Those told about drug effects did not. Implies: undifferentiated arousal + situational attribution = specific emotion. Real-world application: excitation transfer ŌĆö arousal from one source (exercise) can be misattributed to another (romantic partner) ŌåÆ intensifying emotion. Capilano Bridge experiment (Dutton & Aron, 1974).` },
      { q:`Basic emotions, as described by Paul Ekman, are characterized by:`, ch:[`Being culturally specific and learned`,`Being universal across cultures, having distinct facial expressions, physiological signatures, and evolutionary bases; they include happiness, sadness, fear, anger, surprise, and disgust`,`Only including positive emotional states`,`Being absent in non-human primates`], ans:1, exp:`Ekman's basic emotions: happiness, sadness, fear, anger, surprise, disgust (and contempt). Evidence: cross-cultural recognition of facial expressions even in isolated cultures. Facial action coding system (FACS): categorizes facial movements. Micro-expressions: brief, involuntary muscle movements revealing concealed emotions. Challenge (social constructionist view): Russell, Barrett ŌĆö emotion categories are culturally constructed; facial expressions are not universally decoded. Plutchik's wheel: 8 primary emotions in opposing pairs; combinations produce secondary emotions.` },
      { q:`The amygdala plays a central role in which emotional process?`, ch:[`Long-term declarative memory encoding`,`Fear conditioning and emotional memory consolidation ŌĆö the amygdala processes threat-related stimuli, triggers fear responses, and enhances memory storage of emotionally significant events via modulation of hippocampal consolidation`,`Regulation of complex social emotions like pride`,`Motor planning for emotional expressions`], ans:1, exp:`Amygdala (almond-shaped, medial temporal lobe): basolateral complex (BLA) = sensory input; central nucleus = output (to hypothalamus, brainstem ŌåÆ fear responses). Fear conditioning: CS paired with US (shock) ŌåÆ conditioned fear response; requires lateral amygdala. Bilateral amygdala lesion (Urbach-Wiethe disease): impairs fear conditioning, impairs recognition of fearful faces, reduces conditioned fear response. Emotional memory enhancement: amygdala activates during high-arousal events ŌåÆ norepinephrine ŌåÆ modulates hippocampal consolidation ŌåÆ flashbulb memories. Also involved in: reward processing, social cognition, anxiety disorders.` },
      { q:`Emotional regulation refers to:`, ch:[`Expressing emotions openly without restraint`,`The processes by which individuals influence which emotions they have, when they have them, and how they experience and express them ŌĆö includes reappraisal, suppression, distraction, and acceptance`,`The absence of emotional response to stimuli`,`Memorizing facts about emotions`], ans:1, exp:`Emotion regulation strategies: Antecedent-focused (before response): situation selection (avoid triggering situations), situation modification, attentional deployment (distraction, rumination), cognitive reappraisal (reframing the meaning ŌåÆ most adaptive). Response-focused: expressive suppression (hide emotions ŌåÆ reduces expression but not experience; increases physiological arousal ŌåÆ less adaptive). Acceptance (mindfulness-based): observe emotions without judgment ŌåÆ reduces emotional reactivity. Neural: prefrontal cortex (dlPFC, vmPFC) ŌåÆ regulates amygdala activity. PFC hypoactivity + amygdala hyperactivity ŌåÆ dysregulation (depression, PTSD, BPD).` },
      { q:`Positive psychology focuses on:`, ch:[`Diagnosing and treating mental illness`,`Studying and promoting human strengths, well-being, positive emotions, resilience, and flourishing ŌĆö rather than focusing solely on pathology`,`Studying the neural basis of happiness`,`Positive reinforcement in behavior therapy only`], ans:1, exp:`Positive psychology (Seligman & Csikszentmihalyi, 2000): PERMA model: Positive emotions, Engagement (flow), Relationships, Meaning, Accomplishment. Broaden-and-build theory (Fredrickson): positive emotions broaden thought-action repertoires and build durable personal resources (cognitive, social, psychological). Flourishing: combination of positive affect, purpose, engagement, relationships, competence, autonomy. Hedonic well-being: pleasure/positive affect. Eudaimonic well-being: meaning and actualization. Flow (Csikszentmihalyi): optimal experience when challenge matches skill.` },
      { q:`According to the Lazarus cognitive appraisal theory, emotions arise from:`, ch:[`Hardwired subcortical responses`,`The person's appraisal (evaluation) of an event's significance for their well-being ŌĆö primary appraisal (is it relevant? threatening?); secondary appraisal (do I have resources to cope?)`,`Biological homeostatic drives`,`Social comparison with others`], ans:1, exp:`Lazarus: emotion = product of cognitive appraisal. Primary appraisal: is this relevant to my goals? Is it harmful, threatening, or challenging? Secondary appraisal: can I cope? What are my options? Reappraisal: change meaning ŌåÆ change emotion. Core relational themes: each emotion corresponds to a specific appraisal pattern (e.g., anger = blame of another for wrong done to self; guilt = blame of self; fear = danger + uncertainty). Controversy: Zajonc's affect primacy ŌĆö emotional reactions can precede cognition. LeDoux's low road: amygdala can generate fear without cortical evaluation.` },
      { q:`Display rules in emotion research refer to:`, ch:[`The rules governing verbal communication of emotions`,`Culturally specific norms that govern the appropriate expression of emotions in social situations ŌĆö they determine when, how, and to whom emotions are displayed, and can lead to masking, amplifying, or neutralizing expression`,`The rules of facial anatomy for producing expressions`,`Innate constraints on infant emotional expression`], ans:1, exp:`Display rules (Ekman & Friesen): socially learned norms for emotional expression. Types of modifications: intensification (amplify expression beyond true feeling), deintensification (reduce expression), masking (replace with different expression ŌĆö smile when feeling angry), neutralization (show no expression). Cultural differences: Western individualist cultures allow more open emotional expression; collectivist cultures have stronger display rules (especially for negative emotions in public). Demonstrate: people in different cultures show similar emotional facial expressions in private but differ in public display.` },
      { q:`The facial feedback hypothesis proposes that:`, ch:[`Facial expressions are always accurate indicators of internal states`,`The physical act of making a facial expression can influence the subjective emotional experience ŌĆö forcing a smile can induce more positive affect`,`Emotions are always expressed first in the face before being felt`,`Botox injections have no effect on emotional experience`], ans:1, exp:`Facial feedback: James-Lange-derived idea. Strack et al. (1988): participants holding a pen with teeth (inducing smile muscles) rated cartoons as funnier than those holding it with lips (preventing smile). Influential but controversial: Wagenmakers (2016) replication failure. Meta-analysis (Coles et al., 2022): small but significant effect. Botox (paralyzes corrugator/zygomatic muscles) ŌåÆ reduces facial feedback ŌåÆ attenuates emotional experience (slower emotion recognition, reduced emotional reactivity). Embodied cognition: bodily states more broadly influence cognition and emotion.` },
      { q:`Which brain structure is most associated with the subjective experience and integration of emotional information?`, ch:[`Cerebellum`,`The anterior cingulate cortex (ACC) and medial prefrontal cortex integrate emotional processing ŌĆö the insula processes interoceptive (body) signals relevant to emotion; the orbitofrontal cortex is key for emotional decision-making`,`Primary visual cortex`,`Hippocampus alone`], ans:1, exp:`Emotion brain network: amygdala (threat, fear conditioning), insula (interoception, disgust, social pain), anterior cingulate cortex (conflict monitoring, pain affect, emotion regulation), medial PFC/vmPFC (emotional decision-making, value representation, fear extinction), OFC (reward/punishment valuation), hippocampus (emotional memory context). Damasio's somatic marker hypothesis: vmOFC damage ŌåÆ impaired emotional decision-making (can't use gut feelings as guides), seen in gambling task (Iowa Gambling Task). Limbic system: historically defined ŌĆö hippocampus, amygdala, cingulate cortex, septal nuclei, hypothalamus.` },
      { q:`Cultural differences in emotional experience are best described by which finding?`, ch:[`Emotions are experienced identically across all cultures`,`While basic emotional responses (fear, happiness, sadness) may be universal, the frequency, intensity, triggers, and acceptable expressions of emotions are strongly shaped by cultural norms and language`,`Emotions are entirely culturally constructed with no universal component`,`Western cultures experience more intense emotions than Eastern cultures`], ans:1, exp:`Cross-cultural emotional research: basic emotions/universal facial expressions (Ekman) ŌĆö recognized across cultures including preliterate ones. However: (1) Display rules differ (East Asian cultures more suppressive of negative expressions in public); (2) Some emotion concepts are culture-specific (Japanese 'amae' = pleasant dependence; German 'schadenfreude' = pleasure from others' misfortune); (3) Intensity and frequency of emotional experiences vary; (4) Language shapes emotional categories (Whorfian hypothesis). Barret's constructed emotion theory: all emotions are built from core affect (valence ├Ś arousal) + cultural/conceptual knowledge.` },
      { q:`The broaden-and-build theory of positive emotions (Fredrickson) proposes that positive emotions:`, ch:[`Narrow attention to help focus on survival threats`,`Broaden the momentary thought-action repertoire and over time build enduring personal resources (physical, intellectual, social, psychological)`,`Are neurologically identical to negative emotions`,`Only serve social communication functions`], ans:1, exp:`Broaden-and-build: positive emotions (joy, love, interest, awe) ŌåÆ broadened attention, cognition, behavioral tendencies ŌåÆ enhanced creativity, learning, relationship building. Over time: builds durable resources. Undoing effect: positive emotions speed recovery from cardiovascular arousal caused by negative emotions. Positivity ratio (Losada): controversial specific ratio proposal (3:1) has been challenged; the general concept that positive emotions are beneficial remains supported. Applications: organizational psychology (flourishing workplaces), resilience building, broaden-and-build cycle (positive emotions ŌåÆ resources ŌåÆ more positive emotions).` },
      { q:`Alexithymia refers to:`, ch:[`Extreme emotional sensitivity`,`Difficulty identifying and describing one's own emotional states ŌĆö associated with somatic complaints, impaired social functioning, and some mental health conditions`,`Inability to express emotions facially`,`Hypersensitivity to others' emotions`], ans:1, exp:`Alexithymia (Sifneos, 1972): 'without words for feelings.' Characteristics: difficulty identifying feelings, difficulty describing feelings to others, externally-oriented cognitive style (focus on external events, not internal states), poor fantasy/imagination. Occurs on a spectrum; ~10% of general population. Associated with: somatic symptom disorders, eating disorders, substance use disorders, autism spectrum disorder (partially overlapping, not identical). Neural correlates: reduced insular activity; impaired interoception. Toronto Alexithymia Scale (TAS-20): most used measure.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps08`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Motivation ŌĆö Maslow & Self-Determination Theory`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`According to Maslow's hierarchy of needs, which level must be fulfilled before safety needs?`, ch:[`Esteem needs`,`Physiological needs (food, water, shelter, warmth, sleep) ŌĆö the most basic level that must be at least partially met before higher needs become motivating`,`Belongingness needs`,`Self-actualization`], ans:1, exp:`Maslow's hierarchy (1943): Physiological ŌåÆ Safety ŌåÆ Belongingness/Love ŌåÆ Esteem ŌåÆ Self-actualization. Deficiency needs (D-needs): physiological, safety, love, esteem ŌĆö must be satisfied to avoid discomfort. Growth needs (B-needs): self-actualization, and later (1969) transcendence. Maslow's theory lacks strong empirical support for strict hierarchy; cross-cultural application is questioned. However, it remains influential in management (McGregor's Theory Y) and educational psychology.` },
      { q:`Self-actualization, at the peak of Maslow's hierarchy, refers to:`, ch:[`Social acceptance and belonging`,`Realizing one's full potential, seeking personal growth, peak experiences, and becoming the most one can be`,`Achieving financial security`,`Meeting all basic physiological needs`], ans:1, exp:`Self-actualization (Maslow): being all one can be; full realization of potential. Characteristics of self-actualized people: problem-focused, comfortable with uncertainty, autonomous, fresh appreciation of life, peak experiences (transcendent moments of joy/connection), deep empathy, strong ethics. Peak experience: profound moments of happiness, often mystical. Maslow estimated only ~1% of people reach this level. Related concept: Carl Rogers' fully functioning person; Csikszentmihalyi's flow.` },
      { q:`Self-determination theory (Deci and Ryan) identifies which three basic psychological needs?`, ch:[`Achievement, affiliation, and power`,`Autonomy (feeling of choice and volition), competence (feeling of effectiveness), and relatedness (feeling of connection to others)`,`Safety, love, and esteem`,`Hunger, thirst, and sex`], ans:1, exp:`SDT (Deci & Ryan): basic psychological needs are universal: (1) Autonomy: acting from self-endorsed values/interests (not necessarily independence). (2) Competence: feeling effective in interacting with the environment. (3) Relatedness: feeling connected and cared for by others. When all three are satisfied: intrinsic motivation, well-being, vitality. When thwarted: amotivation, ill-being, controlled motivation. SDT applied in education, healthcare, workplace, and parenting. Intrinsic motivation: doing something for its inherent interest. Extrinsic motivation: for separable outcomes (rewards, punishments).` },
      { q:`Intrinsic motivation is undermined by:`, ch:[`Positive feedback and praise`,`External rewards for an already intrinsically motivating activity (overjustification effect) ŌĆö the individual now attributes their behavior to the external reward rather than internal interest, reducing intrinsic motivation`,`Providing autonomy in task completion`,`Experiencing competence in the task`], ans:1, exp:`Overjustification effect (Lepper, Greene, Nisbett, 1973): children who expected a reward for drawing (intrinsically motivating) ŌåÆ showed less interest in drawing later vs. children who received unexpected reward or no reward. Cognitive evaluation theory (CET, sub-theory of SDT): external events affect intrinsic motivation by affecting perceived autonomy and competence. Controlling rewards ŌåÆ undermine intrinsic motivation. Informational rewards (positive feedback, praise for competence) ŌåÆ can enhance intrinsic motivation. Autonomy-supportive contexts ŌåÆ preserve intrinsic motivation.` },
      { q:`According to McClelland, need for achievement (nAch) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Desire for power and control over others`,`A strong desire to accomplish difficult tasks, set challenging standards, and outperform others or previous performance ŌĆö associated with entrepreneurship and work motivation`,`Desire for close interpersonal relationships`,`Need for safety and security`], ans:1, exp:`McClelland's three needs (Acquired Needs Theory): nAch (achievement): set difficult goals, competitive, seek feedback. nAff (affiliation): need for close relationships, approval, avoiding conflict. nPow (power): influence over others ŌĆö personalized power (self-aggrandizement) vs. socialized power (benefiting others/organization). nAch high: prefer moderate risks (where skill makes a difference), want regular feedback, avoid both easy and impossible tasks. Research: entrepreneurs high in nAch. TAT (Thematic Apperception Test): used to measure these needs through story analysis.` },
      { q:`Drive reduction theory (Hull) proposes that motivation arises from:`, ch:[`Cognitive goals and expectations`,`Physiological needs create drives (arousal states), and behavior is motivated to reduce these drives and restore homeostasis`,`Social comparison with peers`,`Internal standards of excellence`], ans:1, exp:`Hull's drive reduction theory (1943): biological need ŌåÆ drive (psychological tension/arousal) ŌåÆ behavior to reduce drive ŌåÆ homeostasis restored ŌåÆ drive reduced. Primary drives: hunger, thirst, sex, sleep (biological). Secondary drives: learned (e.g., money reduces primary drives). Limitation: doesn't explain curiosity-driven behavior, sensation-seeking, or working toward distant goals. Arousal theory: optimal arousal level (not drive reduction) motivates; too little/too much ŌåÆ seek to increase/decrease arousal. Berlyne's curiosity: novel stimuli increase arousal ŌåÆ explore ŌåÆ reduce arousal.` },
      { q:`Extrinsic motivation involves:`, ch:[`Doing something for the inherent satisfaction of the activity`,`Doing something for a separable outcome (reward, avoidance of punishment, social recognition) ŌĆö external to the activity itself`,`Unconscious motivational forces`,`Homeostatic drives`], ans:1, exp:`Extrinsic motivation spectrum (SDT's self-determination continuum): External regulation (pure reward/punishment, least self-determined) ŌåÆ Introjected regulation (internalized external pressure, shame/guilt/pride) ŌåÆ Identified regulation (consciously valued, personally important) ŌåÆ Integrated regulation (fully assimilated into self-concept, most autonomous form of extrinsic motivation) ŌåÆ Intrinsic motivation (inherently interesting/enjoyable). As internalization increases ŌåÆ more autonomous, more volitional, better outcomes. Not all extrinsic motivation is equally undermining of well-being.` },
      { q:`Optimal arousal theory suggests that:`, ch:[`Humans always prefer the lowest possible arousal state`,`People are motivated to maintain an optimal level of arousal ŌĆö neither too low (boring) nor too high (overwhelming); optimal level varies by task and individual`,`Only physiological drives motivate behavior`,`All people have the same optimal arousal level`], ans:1, exp:`Yerkes-Dodson law: performance is best at moderate arousal. Optimal arousal: sensation-seeking (Zuckerman) ŌĆö individuals differ in their need for stimulation. High sensation seekers prefer novelty, risk, intense experiences. Arousal and performance: easy tasks ŌåÆ higher arousal optimal; complex tasks ŌåÆ lower arousal optimal. Boredom: under-arousal ŌåÆ seek stimulation (curiosity, exploration). Anxiety: over-arousal ŌåÆ impair performance (test anxiety, choking under pressure). Applications: sports psychology (psych-up for simple skills; calm down for complex skills).` },
      { q:`The concept of flow (Csikszentmihalyi) refers to:`, ch:[`A state of drowsiness and reduced alertness`,`An optimal psychological state of complete absorption, effortless focus, and intrinsic motivation that occurs when skill level matches the challenge level of the task`,`Emotional flooding in response to stress`,`Rapid thought patterns in mania`], ans:1, exp:`Flow: nine dimensions ŌĆö challenge-skill balance (key condition), clear goals, unambiguous feedback, concentration, sense of control, loss of self-consciousness, transformation of time, merging of action and awareness, intrinsically rewarding (autotelic). Conditions: clear goals, immediate feedback, balance between challenge and skill. If skill > challenge ŌåÆ boredom. If challenge > skill ŌåÆ anxiety/worry. Flow promotes well-being, engagement, and performance. Applications: education, sports (zone), video game design, workplace design. Flow state: associated with transient hypofrontality (reduced prefrontal self-monitoring).` },
      { q:`Homeostasis as a motivational concept means:`, ch:[`Achieving self-actualization`,`The body's tendency to maintain internal equilibrium ŌĆö deviations from set points (blood glucose, temperature, fluid balance) create drives that motivate restorative behavior`,`Seeking novel stimuli`,`Social belonging`], ans:1, exp:`Homeostasis: regulated variables maintained near set points by negative feedback. Hunger: blood glucose drops + gastric emptying + ghrelin ŌåÆ lateral hypothalamus (hunger center) activated ŌåÆ eat ŌåÆ blood glucose rises ŌåÆ satiety signals (CCK, GLP-1, leptin) ŌåÆ ventromedial hypothalamus (satiety center) ŌåÆ stop eating. Thirst: plasma osmolarity Ōåæ ŌåÆ supraoptic/paraventricular nuclei ŌåÆ vasopressin (ADH) + thirst sensation ŌåÆ drink. Temperature: hypothalamus preoptic area. Allostasis: broader concept ŌĆö predicting physiological needs and preparing in advance (not just reacting). Glucostatic theory: Mayer ŌĆö blood glucose levels regulate hunger.` },
      { q:`Need for cognition refers to:`, ch:[`Intelligence quotient`,`An individual's tendency to engage in and enjoy effortful thinking and mental challenge ŌĆö high need for cognition ŌåÆ more elaborative information processing`,`Need for clear, structured information`,`Reliance on cognitive heuristics to simplify decisions`], ans:1, exp:`Need for cognition (Cacioppo & Petty): individual difference in the tendency to engage in and enjoy thinking. High NFC: elaborate processing of messages (central route in ELM ŌĆö elaboration likelihood model), form attitudes based on argument quality. Low NFC: peripheral route ŌĆö influenced by heuristics (source attractiveness, number of arguments). High NFC correlates with: openness to experience, lower prejudice (more nuanced thinking), better academic achievement, more accurate decision-making. ELM: Petty & Cacioppo ŌĆö when motivation and ability are high ŌåÆ central route; when low ŌåÆ peripheral route.` },
      { q:`Which of the following best illustrates extrinsic motivation that has been integrated (most self-determined form of extrinsic motivation)?`, ch:[`Running every morning to avoid shame from peers`,`A medical student studying biochemistry late at night because they genuinely understand it aligns with their values and identity as a future physician, even though studying itself is not intrinsically enjoyable`,`Playing video games for fun`,`Receiving a bonus for meeting sales targets`], ans:1, exp:`SDT's self-determination continuum: integrated regulation ŌĆö the person has fully assimilated the reason for the behavior; it is consistent with their values and identity, though the behavior itself may not be inherently enjoyable. Key: the motivation is self-endorsed and coherent with the self (vs. introjected = pressure from internalized external demands; vs. identified = consciously valued but not yet fully integrated). Integrated is the most autonomous form of extrinsic motivation ŌĆö associated with highest well-being among extrinsic types. Practical implication: fostering integrated (not just identified) regulation in students/patients leads to better adherence.` },
      { q:`Terror management theory (Greenberg, Solomon, Pyszczynski) proposes that:`, ch:[`Terror attacks cause lasting personality changes`,`Awareness of one's own mortality creates existential terror managed through cultural worldviews and self-esteem ŌĆö bolstering worldviews and the symbolic self when mortality is salient (mortality salience paradigm)`,`Extreme emotions undermine health`,`Death anxiety only affects elderly individuals`], ans:1, exp:`Terror management theory (TMT): based on Becker's 'Denial of Death.' Awareness of mortality is uniquely threatening for humans. Management mechanisms: (1) Cultural worldview defense (symbolic immortality through culture, religion, nation); (2) Self-esteem as anxiety buffer (being a valued member of a meaningful world). Mortality salience experiments: reminding participants of death ŌåÆ increased worldview defense (harsher judgments of moral transgressors, increased nationalism, increased hostility toward out-groups). Applied to: nationalism, tribalism, xenophobia, religion.` },
      { q:`Incentive theory of motivation holds that:`, ch:[`All motivated behavior reduces internal deficits`,`External stimuli (incentives) have motivating properties ŌĆö organisms are pulled toward attractive stimuli (positive incentives) and away from aversive ones (negative incentives), not only pushed by internal drives`,`Motivation only arises from unconscious processes`,`Motivation is fixed and cannot be influenced by learning`], ans:1, exp:`Incentive theory: external goals and stimuli motivate behavior (contrast with drive-reduction theory which focuses on internal states). Positive incentives: food, money, sex, social approval ŌĆö pull toward approach. Negative incentives: pain, punishment ŌĆö push toward avoidance. Incentive value changes with deprivation state (food is more motivating when hungry). Integration with drive: Hull-Spence multiplicative model ŌĆö Drive ├Ś Incentive motivation ├Ś Habit strength = performance. Reward prediction errors: dopamine signals unexpected rewards (not rewards themselves) in nucleus accumbens ŌĆö key to incentive motivation and addiction.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps09`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Big Five Personality & Personality Theories`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The Big Five (OCEAN) personality dimensions are:`, ch:[`Openness, Caution, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism`,`Openness to experience, Conscientiousness, Extraversion, Agreeableness, Neuroticism`,`Optimism, Creativity, Empathy, Assertiveness, Negative affect`,`Openness, Competitiveness, Extroversion, Achievement, Neuroticism`], ans:1, exp:`Big Five (Five-Factor Model, McCrae & Costa): OCEAN. Openness: intellectual curiosity, creativity, aesthetic sensitivity. Conscientiousness: organization, self-discipline, goal-directedness. Extraversion: sociability, assertiveness, positive affect. Agreeableness: cooperation, trust, empathy. Neuroticism: emotional instability, anxiety, moodiness. Cross-culturally robust; heritable (~50%). Predicts: health behavior (conscientiousness ŌåÆ longevity), job performance (conscientiousness), academic achievement (conscientiousness + openness), mental health (neuroticism ŌåÆ mood disorders).` },
      { q:`According to Freud's psychoanalytic theory, the ego operates according to:`, ch:[`The pleasure principle`,`The reality principle ŌĆö mediates between the id (pleasure principle, unconscious drives) and superego (moral demands), postponing immediate gratification to achieve satisfaction in socially acceptable ways`,`The moral principle`,`The primary process`], ans:1, exp:`Freud's structural model: Id (unconscious, instinctual drives ŌĆö sex, aggression; primary process thinking ŌĆö wishful/fantasy); Ego (mediates id + superego + reality; secondary process thinking ŌĆö logical, reality-based); Superego (internalized moral standards, conscience and ego ideal; develops ~5ŌĆō6 y.o. from Oedipus complex resolution). Defense mechanisms: unconscious strategies to manage id-superego conflict (repression, displacement, rationalization, projection, sublimation, reaction formation, denial). Topographic model: unconscious, preconscious, conscious.` },
      { q:`Carl Jung's concept of the collective unconscious refers to:`, ch:[`Shared social norms learned through culture`,`A deeper layer of the unconscious shared by all humans, containing archetypes (universal, inherited images and patterns ŌĆö shadow, anima/animus, self, persona)`,`Repressed personal memories from childhood`,`The combined unconscious material of all individuals in a society`], ans:1, exp:`Jung: broke with Freud on nature of unconscious. Personal unconscious: repressed personal experiences. Collective unconscious: universal, inherited; contains archetypes ŌĆö recurring images/symbols found across cultures and history. Key archetypes: persona (social mask), shadow (dark, repressed aspects of self), anima/animus (feminine side of male/masculine side of female), self (integration of all aspects). Individuation: psychological development toward wholeness and integration of all aspects. Myers-Briggs Type Indicator (MBTI) inspired by Jungian types (introversion/extraversion, sensing/intuiting, thinking/feeling, judging/perceiving).` },
      { q:`Which personality theory emphasizes the role of unconscious defense mechanisms in personality functioning?`, ch:[`Humanistic theory (Rogers, Maslow)`,`Psychoanalytic theory (Freud) ŌĆö unconscious conflicts between id, ego, and superego are managed through defense mechanisms that shape personality and behavior`,`Social cognitive theory (Bandura)`,`Trait theory (Big Five)`], ans:1, exp:`Defense mechanisms (Freud, expanded by Anna Freud): unconscious psychological strategies. Mature defenses: sublimation (channeling impulses into socially acceptable activities), humor, suppression. Neurotic defenses: repression (blocking unacceptable thoughts from consciousness), displacement (redirecting emotions to a safer target), rationalization (logical justifications), intellectualization. Immature defenses: projection (attributing own unacceptable feelings to others), denial, splitting (BPD ŌĆö all good or all bad). Psychodynamic therapy: making unconscious conflicts conscious; free association; dream analysis; transference.` },
      { q:`Locus of control (Rotter) refers to the degree to which:`, ch:[`One believes in personal freedom`,`Individuals believe they have control over events that affect them (internal) vs. believe outcomes are controlled by luck, fate, or powerful others (external)`,`External rewards control behavior`,`Social pressure controls individual actions`], ans:1, exp:`Locus of control: Internal: attribute outcomes to own ability, effort, behavior ŌåÆ more proactive, better health behaviors, academic achievement, less depression. External: attribute to luck, fate, powerful others ŌåÆ more passive, higher health risk, less adaptive. Related to: self-efficacy (Bandura) ŌĆö specific belief in one's ability to perform specific behaviors. Learned helplessness = extreme external locus + no agency. Implications: interventions that increase perceived control can improve health outcomes (e.g., nursing home studies ŌĆö giving residents choices increased well-being and reduced mortality).` },
      { q:`Which approach to personality emphasizes that people's behavior is determined by their perception of the situation and their personal constructs?`, ch:[`Psychoanalytic approach`,`Cognitive social learning theory / Personal construct theory (Kelly) ŌĆö individuals develop mental models (personal constructs) to anticipate and interpret events; behavior depends on cognitive interpretation of situations`,`Biological/trait approach`,`Humanistic approach`], ans:1, exp:`George Kelly's personal construct theory: people are 'scientists' who develop hypotheses (personal constructs) about the world; constructs are bipolar dimensions (e.g., kind-cruel). Repertory Grid Test: measures personal constructs. Bandura's social cognitive theory: reciprocal determinism ŌĆö behavior, person (cognitions, expectations), and environment mutually influence each other. CAPS (Cognitive-Affective Processing System, Mischel & Shoda): behavior varies across situations in consistent 'if-then' profiles determined by five cognitive-affective units.` },
      { q:`Carl Rogers' client-centered therapy holds that therapeutic change is facilitated by:`, ch:[`Interpreting unconscious content`,`Unconditional positive regard, empathy, and congruence (genuineness) from the therapist ŌĆö creating a safe therapeutic environment in which clients can reconnect with their authentic selves`,`Behavior modification through reinforcement`,`Direct advice and guidance from the therapist`], ans:1, exp:`Rogers' necessary and sufficient conditions for therapeutic change: (1) Psychological contact (therapeutic relationship exists). (2) Incongruence in client (gap between ideal self and real self). (3) Therapist congruence/genuineness (authentic presence). (4) Unconditional positive regard (non-judgmental acceptance). (5) Empathic understanding (accurately sensing client's inner world). (6) Client perceives these (conditions 3ŌĆō5). Humanistic view: people have an actualizing tendency; therapy removes barriers. Non-directive: therapist reflects, clarifies, doesn't interpret or direct. Q-sort methodology: research tool for measuring self-concept change in therapy.` },
      { q:`The fundamental premise of person-situation debate in personality psychology is:`, ch:[`Traits are always stronger than situations in predicting behavior`,`Mischel argued that situations are more powerful than traits in determining behavior; Epstein and others later resolved the debate by showing that traits predict behavior well when aggregated across situations`,`Personality traits do not exist`,`Situations have no effect on behavior`], ans:1, exp:`Mischel (1968) 'Personality and Assessment': cross-situational consistency of behavior is low (correlations rarely exceed 0.3 ŌĆö 'personality coefficient'). Situationism: behavior is largely determined by context. Resolution: aggregation (averaging behavior across many situations increases predictability); interactionism (personality ├Ś situation interactions); if-then profiles (Mischel & Shoda CAPS model). Fleeson (2001): within-person variability is as large as between-person; traits represent density distributions of behaviors. Modern consensus: both traits and situations matter; effects are interactive.` },
      { q:`The Minnesota Multiphasic Personality Inventory (MMPI) is an example of which type of personality assessment?`, ch:[`Projective test`,`Self-report inventory (objective test) ŌĆö a structured questionnaire with defined response options (True/False) whose scores are compared to normative samples to detect psychopathology and personality traits`,`Neuropsychological battery`,`Observer rating scale`], ans:1, exp:`MMPI-2/MMPI-2-RF: most widely used objective personality and psychopathology assessment. Scales: clinical scales (hypochondriasis, depression, hysteria, psychopathic deviate, masculinity-femininity, paranoia, psychasthenia, schizophrenia, hypomania, social introversion) + validity scales (L, F, K, VRIN, TRIN ŌĆö detecting invalid responding). Projective tests: Rorschach (inkblot ŌĆö ambiguous stimuli elicit projections of unconscious material); TAT (tell a story about ambiguous pictures). Semi-structured interviews: SCID (structured clinical interview for DSM). Observer ratings: informant reports; behavioral observation scales.` },
      { q:`Which of the following best describes the concept of reciprocal determinism (Bandura)?`, ch:[`The idea that genes and environment interact multiplicatively`,`The idea that behavior, personal factors (cognitions, emotions, expectations), and environmental factors all mutually influence each other in a bidirectional manner`,`The principle that punishment and reward are equally effective`,`The notion that social reinforcement determines all behavior`], ans:1, exp:`Reciprocal determinism: triadic relationship ŌĆö Person (cognitions, expectations, self-efficacy) Ōåö Behavior Ōåö Environment. Each influences the others. Example: high self-efficacy (person) ŌåÆ approach behavior (behavior) ŌåÆ success experience (environment) ŌåÆ increased self-efficacy (person). Contrast with: unidirectional behaviorism (environment ŌåÆ behavior) and unidirectional psychoanalysis (internal drives ŌåÆ behavior). CAPS model extends this to situational cues activating cognitive-affective units ŌåÆ behavior. Social cognitive theory: emphasizes observational learning, self-regulation, and self-efficacy as key determinants of personality.` },
      { q:`Temperament, in developmental psychology, refers to:`, ch:[`Learned personality characteristics acquired through socialization`,`Early-emerging, biologically-based individual differences in reactivity and self-regulation that are relatively stable across time and context`,`The Big Five personality traits expressed in childhood`,`Attachment style to primary caregivers`], ans:1, exp:`Temperament (Thomas & Chess): 9 dimensions; three types: Easy (~40%), Difficult (~10%), Slow to warm up (~15%). Kagan: behavioral inhibition (fearful/shy) vs. uninhibited. Rothbart: effortful control (regulatory dimension), surgency/extraversion, negative affect. Heritable (~50%), present from early infancy, influenced by biology (limbic system reactivity, HPA axis, dopamine system). Goodness of fit: match between child's temperament and parenting style ŌåÆ outcome. Influences development of: attachment (partly), psychopathology risk (behavioral inhibition ŌåÆ anxiety), later personality.` },
      { q:`Defense mechanism 'sublimation' involves:`, ch:[`Attributing one's own unacceptable feelings to others`,`Redirecting unconscious impulses into socially acceptable, constructive activities ŌĆö e.g., channeling aggression into competitive sports or creative art`,`Denying the existence of threatening information`,`Returning to behaviors from an earlier developmental stage`], ans:1, exp:`Anna Freud classified defense mechanisms: Mature: sublimation (redirect impulses productively), humor, altruism, suppression (conscious delay of impulse). Neurotic: repression, displacement (impulse ŌåÆ safer target), rationalization, reaction formation (express opposite of true feeling), intellectualization. Immature: regression (return to earlier behavior), projection, denial, splitting, acting out, projective identification. Sublimation: most mature ŌĆö transforms unacceptable impulses into socially valued behaviors. Example: aggressive impulse ŌåÆ become a surgeon, competitive athlete, or defense attorney.` },
      { q:`According to the trait approach to personality, traits are:`, ch:[`Situational labels for specific behaviors`,`Stable, enduring dispositions that predispose individuals to behave consistently across situations and over time`,`Entirely culturally determined`,`Observable behaviors, not internal states`], ans:1, exp:`Trait theory: personality = stable internal characteristics (traits) that cause consistent behavior patterns. Allport: cardinal traits (dominate personality), central traits (characteristics most people notice), secondary traits (situation-specific). Cattell: 16PF (factor analysis ŌåÆ 16 source traits). Eysenck: PEN model (Psychoticism, Extraversion, Neuroticism). Big Five: most empirically supported structure. Biological basis: Eysenck ŌĆö introversion = higher arousal in ascending reticular activating system; Gray ŌĆö BIS (behavioral inhibition system) for anxiety; BAS (behavioral activation system) for reward-seeking. Traits predict behavior at aggregate level, not single instance.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps10`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`DSM Overview & Psychological Disorders`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The DSM-5 (Diagnostic and Statistical Manual of Mental Disorders) uses a categorical diagnostic system that requires:`, ch:[`A single biomarker for diagnosis`,`A symptom threshold ŌĆö a specified number of symptoms from defined criteria lists must be present for a minimum duration and cause clinically significant impairment or distress`,`Dimensional scoring only`,`Physician judgment without specific criteria`], ans:1, exp:`DSM-5 classification: categorical (disorder present or absent) with some dimensional elements (severity specifiers). Diagnosis requires: (1) specific number of symptoms from criteria; (2) minimum duration; (3) clinically significant distress or functional impairment; (4) symptoms not better explained by another disorder, medical condition, or substance. Multiaxial system of DSM-IV (Axes IŌĆōV) eliminated in DSM-5. ICD-11 (WHO): international counterpart; DSM and ICD are largely harmonized. Limitations of categorical approach: high comorbidity, arbitrary thresholds, heterogeneity within diagnoses ŌåÆ pushes toward dimensional approaches (e.g., Research Domain Criteria/RDoC).` },
      { q:`Major depressive disorder (MDD) requires the presence of which core symptom?`, ch:[`Psychosis`,`Depressed mood OR loss of interest/pleasure (anhedonia) ŌĆö at least one of these two must be present, along with Ōēź4 additional symptoms from the criteria, lasting at least 2 weeks`,`Sleep disturbance only`,`Decreased appetite only`], ans:1, exp:`MDD DSM-5 criteria: Ōēź5 symptoms during a 2-week period (at least one of: depressed mood OR anhedonia): depressed mood, anhedonia, weight/appetite changes, sleep changes (insomnia/hypersomnia), psychomotor changes, fatigue, worthlessness/guilt, concentration difficulty, suicidal ideation. Excludes grief, bipolar disorder, medical cause. Specifiers: with psychotic features, with anxious distress, with melancholic features, peripartum onset, seasonal pattern. Neurobiology: monoamine deficiency (serotonin, norepinephrine, dopamine) ŌĆö basis for antidepressants; HPA hyperactivation; neurogenesis deficit (hippocampus).` },
      { q:`Schizophrenia is diagnosed when which symptom is present for at least one month?`, ch:[`Persistent low mood`,`At least one of: delusions, hallucinations, or disorganized speech ŌĆö these positive symptoms are most specific; negative symptoms and disorganized behavior also contribute`,`Social withdrawal only`,`Sleep disturbance and disorganized thought`], ans:1, exp:`DSM-5 schizophrenia: Ōēź2 symptoms for Ōēź1 month (at least one must be from positive symptoms: delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech): may also include disorganized/catatonic behavior, negative symptoms. Prodromal symptoms: 6-month total duration required (may be attenuated). Positive symptoms: delusions (fixed false beliefs), hallucinations (auditory most common in schizophrenia, typically command or commentary), disorganized speech (loose associations, word salad), disorganized behavior. Negative symptoms: flat affect, alogia (poverty of speech), avolition, anhedonia, asociality. Neurobiology: dopamine hypothesis (D2 hypersensitivity in mesolimbic pathway); glutamate (NMDA hypofunction).` },
      { q:`Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Discrete episodes of intense fear with somatic symptoms`,`Persistent, excessive worry about multiple areas of life that is difficult to control, lasting Ōēź6 months, with symptoms such as restlessness, fatigue, concentration difficulty, irritability, muscle tension, and sleep disturbance`,`Anxiety only in specific social situations`,`Fear triggered by a specific object or situation`], ans:1, exp:`GAD: worry is the core feature ŌĆö not tied to specific triggers, anticipatory, difficult to control. Prevalence: ~5ŌĆō6% lifetime; 2:1 female:male. Comorbidity: high with depression, other anxiety disorders. Neurobiology: amygdala hyperreactivity, reduced GABAergic inhibition, HPA dysregulation. Treatment: CBT (most evidence), SSRIs/SNRIs, buspirone (GABAergic + serotonergic), benzodiazepines (short-term only ŌĆö dependence risk). Panic disorder: characterized by recurrent unexpected panic attacks + worry about future attacks. Specific phobia: marked fear of specific objects/situations. Social anxiety disorder: fear of social scrutiny.` },
      { q:`The distinction between bipolar I and bipolar II disorder is:`, ch:[`Bipolar I requires hospitalization for diagnosis`,`Bipolar I requires at least one manic episode (severe, Ōēź7 days or hospitalization-requiring); bipolar II requires at least one hypomanic episode + major depressive episode, with NO history of full mania`,`Bipolar II has more severe depression`,`Bipolar I does not include depressive episodes`], ans:1, exp:`Bipolar I: Ōēź1 manic episode (3ŌĆō7 days; DIGFAST: Distractibility, Impulsivity/Irresponsibility, Grandiosity, Flight of ideas, Activity increase/Agitation, Sleep decreased, Talkativeness/pressure of speech); may or may not have depression. Bipolar II: hypomania (4 days, less severe, no hospitalization, no psychosis) + major depression. Cyclothymia: 2+ years of hypomania and depression not meeting full criteria. Mixed features: depression with manic symptoms or vice versa. Management: mood stabilizers (lithium, valproate, lamotrigine), atypical antipsychotics. Misdiagnosis: bipolar often misdiagnosed as MDD (antidepressants alone can trigger mania).` },
      { q:`Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) involves:`, ch:[`Intrusive thoughts without behavioral responses`,`Obsessions (persistent, intrusive, unwanted thoughts/images/urges causing distress) AND compulsions (repetitive behaviors or mental acts performed to reduce obsession-related distress) ŌĆö compulsions are not enjoyable and are recognized as excessive`,`Compulsions that are enjoyable and ego-syntonic`,`Delusions about contamination`], ans:1, exp:`OCD: obsessions are ego-dystonic (person recognizes them as irrational/intrusive). Compulsions temporarily relieve distress but reinforce obsessions long-term (negative reinforcement). Common themes: contamination/cleaning, symmetry/ordering, harm/checking, forbidden thoughts (sexual, religious). Neurobiology: cortico-striato-thalamo-cortical (CSTC) circuit hyperactivity, particularly OFC and caudate. Serotonin involvement. Treatment: ERP (exposure and response prevention ŌĆö gold standard), SSRIs (high doses often needed), clomipramine. OCD spectrum: body dysmorphic disorder, hoarding disorder, hair-pulling (trichotillomania), skin-picking (excoriation).` },
      { q:`ADHD (Attention-Deficit/Hyperactivity Disorder) is diagnosed based on:`, ch:[`A blood test or neuroimaging finding`,`Persistent pattern of inattention and/or hyperactivity-impulsivity that impairs functioning in Ōēź2 settings, with symptoms present before age 12, in excess of what is expected for developmental level`,`Teacher report only`,`Parent consent only`], ans:1, exp:`ADHD DSM-5: three presentations ŌĆö predominantly inattentive, predominantly hyperactive-impulsive, combined. Inattentive symptoms (9 possible, need Ōēź6 for Ōēź17 y.o. or Ōēź5): careless mistakes, sustaining attention, not listening, following through, organizing, losing things, distraction, forgetfulness. Hyperactive-impulsive: fidgeting, leaving seat, running about, can't play quietly, always on the go, talks excessively, blurts out, can't wait turn, interrupts. Age 12 onset; 2+ settings (home, school); functional impairment. Neurobiology: dopamine/norepinephrine in prefrontal circuits; reduced volume of prefrontal cortex, caudate, cerebellum. Treatment: stimulants (methylphenidate, amphetamine) first-line; atomoxetine (NRI); behavioral interventions.` },
      { q:`Autism spectrum disorder (ASD) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Intellectual disability only`,`Persistent deficits in social communication and social interaction, plus restricted/repetitive behaviors, interests, or activities ŌĆö present from early developmental period with functional impact`,`Psychosis and delusions`,`ADHD exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`ASD DSM-5: Domain A: social communication/interaction deficits (social-emotional reciprocity; nonverbal communication; developing/maintaining relationships). Domain B: restricted, repetitive behaviors (stereotyped motor movements, insistence on sameness/rituals, highly restricted interests, hyper/hypo-reactivity to sensory input). Severity levels 1ŌĆō3 (requires support ŌåÆ very substantial support). Onset: symptoms present in early childhood (may not fully manifest until social demands exceed capacities). Prevalence: ~1 in 36 children (CDC 2023); male:female ~4:1. Genetic basis: highly heritable (~80%), multiple genes. No single cause; vaccines do not cause ASD (debunked). ABA (applied behavior analysis): behavioral intervention with evidence.` },
      { q:`Personality disorders in DSM-5 are characterized by:`, ch:[`Episodic symptoms that come and go`,`An enduring pattern of inner experience and behavior that deviates markedly from cultural expectations, is pervasive and inflexible, leads to distress or functional impairment, and is stable over time with onset in adolescence/early adulthood`,`Only occurring secondary to Axis I disorders`,`Being fully treatable with medication alone`], ans:1, exp:`DSM-5 Cluster A (odd/eccentric): paranoid, schizoid, schizotypal. Cluster B (dramatic/emotional): antisocial, borderline (BPD), histrionic, narcissistic. Cluster C (anxious/fearful): avoidant, dependent, obsessive-compulsive personality disorder (OCPD). BPD: marked by impulsivity, unstable relationships/identity/affect, fear of abandonment, self-harm. Antisocial PD: pattern of disregard for others' rights, deceit, lack of remorse. OCPD vs. OCD: OCPD is ego-syntonic (person sees traits as appropriate) and lacks true obsessions/compulsions. Treatment: DBT for BPD; various psychotherapies; medications for comorbid symptoms.` },
      { q:`The diathesis-stress model of psychopathology proposes that:`, ch:[`All mental disorders are caused by stress alone`,`Mental disorders result from the interaction between a diathesis (biological, genetic, psychological vulnerability) and environmental stress ŌĆö neither alone is sufficient`,`Genetic factors fully determine mental illness`,`Stress does not contribute to genetically-based disorders`], ans:1, exp:`Diathesis-stress: diathesis (predisposition) + stressor = disorder. Individual with high genetic risk may not develop disorder without significant stress; individual with high stress may not develop disorder without vulnerability. Examples: schizophrenia (genetic loading + cannabis use, childhood trauma, urban environment ŌåÆ onset); MDD (5-HTTLPR polymorphism + adverse life events ŌåÆ depression). Extensions: differential susceptibility hypothesis (Belsky) ŌĆö high sensitivity individuals are more affected by both adverse AND beneficial environments (orchid and dandelion children). Gene-environment interaction and gene-environment correlation complicate simple diathesis-stress models.` },
      { q:`Somatic symptom disorder (formerly somatization disorder) involves:`, ch:[`Intentional feigning of symptoms for external gain (malingering)`,`One or more somatic symptoms that are distressing or disruptive to daily life, with excessive thoughts, feelings, or behaviors related to them ŌĆö symptoms are real (not faked) but persistent focus on them is disproportionate`,`A single unexplained medical symptom`,`Delusions about bodily disease`], ans:1, exp:`Somatic symptom disorder (DSM-5): one or more somatic symptoms + excessive health-related thoughts, feelings, or behaviors. Symptoms may or may not have a known medical cause ŌĆö it is the excessive response to them that is pathological. Replaces somatization disorder, hypochondriasis, and related categories from DSM-IV. Illness anxiety disorder (health anxiety): preoccupation with having/acquiring a serious illness with few/no somatic symptoms. Conversion disorder (functional neurological symptom disorder): neurological-type symptoms (paralysis, blindness, non-epileptic seizures) inconsistent with known neurological disease; La belle indiff├®rence (limited concern about symptoms) not reliable.` },
      { q:`Eating disorders are characterized by which core psychopathology?`, ch:[`Purely physiological appetite dysfunction`,`Disturbed eating behavior AND marked distress about or impairment due to the disturbance ŌĆö anorexia nervosa involves restriction and body image disturbance; bulimia involves binge-purge cycles; binge eating disorder involves recurrent binges without compensatory behaviors`,`Only occur in females with low self-esteem`,`Are always caused by family dysfunction`], ans:1, exp:`Eating disorders: Anorexia nervosa: restriction ŌåÆ significantly low weight; intense fear of weight gain; body image disturbance. Types: restricting vs. binge-purge type. Highest mortality of any psychiatric disorder. Medical complications: cardiac arrhythmia (long QT, hypokalemia), bone loss, anemia, lanugo. Bulimia nervosa: recurrent binge eating + compensatory behaviors (purging, fasting, exercise); self-worth linked to shape/weight. Complications: enamel erosion, Russell's sign, esophageal tears. BED: binge without compensation; associated with obesity. ARFID: avoidant/restrictive food intake disorder (not driven by body image). Biopsychosocial etiology; serotonin system involved; genetics important.` },
      { q:`Substance use disorder (DSM-5) is diagnosed when substance use causes:`, ch:[`Any substance use`,`A problematic pattern causing significant impairment or distress ŌĆö manifested by Ōēź2 of 11 criteria in a 12-month period, including impaired control, social impairment, risky use, and pharmacological criteria (tolerance, withdrawal)`,`Physical dependence alone`,`A single episode of substance intoxication`], ans:1, exp:`DSM-5 SUD criteria (11 criteria, Ōēź2 in 12 months): Impaired control: taking more or longer than intended, unsuccessful efforts to cut down, craving, much time spent. Social impairment: failure to fulfill obligations, continued use despite interpersonal problems, giving up activities. Risky use: use in physically hazardous situations, continued use despite physical/psychological harm. Pharmacological: tolerance (need more for same effect), withdrawal (characteristic syndrome or use to avoid it). Severity: mild (2ŌĆō3), moderate (4ŌĆō5), severe (Ōēź6). Note: tolerance and withdrawal alone do not constitute SUD if in context of medical treatment.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps11`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Brain Structure & Function`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`Which brain structure is primarily responsible for relaying sensory and motor information to the cerebral cortex?`, ch:[`Hippocampus`,`Thalamus ŌĆö acts as a 'relay station' for most sensory information (except olfaction) on its way to the cortex; also integrates and modulates signals`,`Cerebellum`,`Basal ganglia`], ans:1, exp:`Thalamus: paired nuclei; each nucleus relays specific modality. LGN (lateral geniculate nucleus) ŌåÆ visual cortex; MGN (medial geniculate nucleus) ŌåÆ auditory cortex; VPL (ventral posterolateral) ŌåÆ somatosensory cortex; VPM (ventral posteromedial) ŌåÆ face sensation; VA/VL ŌåÆ motor cortex; MD (mediodorsal) ŌåÆ prefrontal cortex. Olfaction bypasses thalamus ŌåÆ direct cortical access (piriform cortex, amygdala). Thalamic gating: modulates what information reaches cortex (relevant for attention, consciousness, sleep). Thalamic infarct: contralateral sensory loss.` },
      { q:`The hippocampus is primarily associated with:`, ch:[`Motor coordination`,`Formation of new declarative memories (episodic and semantic) ŌĆö damage results in anterograde amnesia; also involved in spatial navigation (place cells)`,`Emotional processing of fear`,`Regulation of hunger and satiety`], ans:1, exp:`Hippocampus (medial temporal lobe): pattern completion, pattern separation, and consolidation of new explicit memories. H.M. (Henry Molaison): bilateral hippocampal removal ŌåÆ severe anterograde amnesia; old long-term memories preserved (remote memory intact); procedural learning intact. Place cells (O'Keefe, Nobel 2014): hippocampal neurons encoding spatial location. Grid cells (Moser): entorhinal cortex, providing metric for spatial navigation. HM's amnesia: could not form new episodic or semantic memories; could learn new procedural skills (mirror drawing). Memory consolidation: hippocampus ŌåÆ neocortex over time.` },
      { q:`Broca's area and Wernicke's area are both located in the:`, ch:[`Right hemisphere in most right-handed people`,`Left hemisphere in approximately 95% of right-handed individuals and ~70% of left-handed individuals ŌĆö Broca's area (inferior frontal gyrus) = speech production; Wernicke's area (posterior superior temporal gyrus) = language comprehension`,`Parietal lobe bilaterally`,`Occipital lobe`], ans:1, exp:`Language lateralization: left hemisphere dominant for language in ~97% of right-handers, ~70% of left-handers. Broca's area (left inferior frontal gyrus, BA44/45): speech production, grammar, phonological processing ŌåÆ Broca's aphasia: non-fluent, effortful speech; comprehension relatively intact; frustration. Wernicke's area (left posterior superior temporal gyrus, BA22): language comprehension ŌåÆ Wernicke's aphasia: fluent but meaningless speech (neologisms, word salad), impaired comprehension. Arcuate fasciculus: connects Wernicke's Ōåö Broca's ŌåÆ conduction aphasia (poor repetition).` },
      { q:`The prefrontal cortex (PFC) is primarily associated with which higher cognitive functions?`, ch:[`Visual processing and object recognition`,`Executive functions ŌĆö working memory, planning, decision-making, impulse control, cognitive flexibility, and social cognition`,`Primary motor control of distal limbs`,`Emotional memory consolidation`], ans:1, exp:`PFC (frontal lobe anterior to primary motor cortex): DLPFC (dorsolateral PFC): working memory, cognitive control, planning. VLPFC (ventrolateral): inhibitory control, language processing. OFC (orbitofrontal): reward/punishment valuation, emotional decision-making, social behavior. mPFC (medial): default mode, self-referential thinking, theory of mind. ACC (anterior cingulate): error monitoring, conflict detection, pain affect, attention. PFC damage: disinhibition, poor planning, perseveration, personality change (Phineas Gage). PFC matures last (~mid-20s) ŌĆö explains adolescent risk-taking.` },
      { q:`Which neurotransmitter is primarily produced in the substantia nigra and is deficient in Parkinson's disease?`, ch:[`Serotonin`,`Dopamine ŌĆö produced by neurons in the substantia nigra pars compacta; their degeneration ŌåÆ dopamine deficiency in the striatum ŌåÆ bradykinesia, rigidity, tremor, postural instability`,`GABA`,`Glutamate`], ans:1, exp:`Parkinson's disease: loss of dopaminergic neurons in substantia nigra pars compacta ŌåÆ reduced nigrostriatal dopamine ŌåÆ imbalance in direct (Go) and indirect (No-Go) basal ganglia pathways. Cardinal features: TRAP ŌĆö Tremor (resting, pill-rolling), Rigidity (cogwheel), Akinesia/Bradykinesia, Postural instability. Lewy bodies: ╬▒-synuclein aggregates. Treatment: levodopa (precursor, crosses BBB) + carbidopa (peripheral DOPA decarboxylase inhibitor), dopamine agonists, MAO-B inhibitors. Other DA pathways: mesolimbic (reward, addiction), mesocortical (cognition, emotion), tuberoinfundibular (prolactin regulation).` },
      { q:`The cerebellum's primary functions include:`, ch:[`Initiating voluntary movement`,`Fine-tuning motor coordination, timing, balance, and motor learning ŌĆö receives sensory input and compares intended movement to actual movement; essential for smooth, accurate execution of movements`,`Processing sensory information from the thalamus`,`Regulating circadian rhythms`], ans:1, exp:`Cerebellum: receives: motor cortex commands (cortico-cerebellar), proprioception, vestibular, visual input; compares intended vs. actual movement ŌåÆ sends corrective signals to motor cortex and spinal cord via thalamus. Cerebellar damage: ipsilateral deficits (unlike most brain regions). DASHED: Dysdiadochokinesia (inability to make rapidly alternating movements), Ataxia (gait), Slurred speech (scanning dysarthria), Hypotonia, Eyes (nystagmus), Dysmetria (past-pointing). Cerebellum also involved in: motor learning (classical conditioning of eyeblink response), timing, some cognitive functions (cerebellar cognitive affective syndrome).` },
      { q:`The basal ganglia are primarily involved in:`, ch:[`Sensory processing from thalamus`,`Action selection, habit formation, procedural learning, and modulation of voluntary movement through direct (facilitatory) and indirect (inhibitory) pathways`,`Memory consolidation of episodic events`,`Regulation of autonomic function`], ans:1, exp:`Basal ganglia: caudate + putamen (striatum), globus pallidus, subthalamic nucleus (STN), substantia nigra. Direct pathway: striatum (D1 receptors, activated by dopamine) ŌåÆ GPi/SNr inhibited ŌåÆ thalamus disinhibited ŌåÆ cortex activated = 'Go.' Indirect pathway: striatum (D2 receptors, inhibited by dopamine) ŌåÆ GPe ŌåÆ STN ŌåÆ GPi/SNr ŌåÆ thalamus inhibited ŌåÆ cortex inhibited = 'No Go.' Dopamine (DA) ŌåÆ promotes direct, inhibits indirect ŌåÆ facilitates movement. Parkinson (low DA): impaired direct + excessive indirect ŌåÆ bradykinesia. Huntington (loss of striatal neurons in indirect pathway initially ŌåÆ D2 cells ŌåÆ chorea).` },
      { q:`Which brain structure is part of the limbic system and is critical for forming new spatial and episodic memories?`, ch:[`Putamen`,`Hippocampus`,`Caudate nucleus`,`Thalamus`], ans:1, exp:`Limbic system (Papez circuit and McLean's later expansion): hippocampus ŌåÆ fornix ŌåÆ mammillary bodies ŌåÆ anterior thalamus ŌåÆ cingulate cortex ŌåÆ entorhinal cortex ŌåÆ hippocampus (Papez circuit). Also includes: amygdala (emotion), septal nuclei, hypothalamus. Hippocampus: critical for explicit memory consolidation, spatial navigation (place cells). Entorhinal cortex: major input/output of hippocampus; earliest Alzheimer pathology (tau tangles). Fornix: connects hippocampus to mammillary bodies/septal nuclei; damage ŌåÆ amnesia (diencephalic amnesia). Korsakoff's syndrome: mammillary body degeneration (thiamine deficiency) ŌåÆ anterograde + retrograde amnesia.` },
      { q:`The autonomic nervous system (ANS) regulates involuntary organ function through which two main divisions?`, ch:[`Somatic and enteric`,`Sympathetic (fight-or-flight) and parasympathetic (rest-and-digest) ŌĆö these have generally opposing effects on target organs and maintain homeostasis through their balance`,`Afferent and efferent`,`Motor and sensory`], ans:1, exp:`ANS: involuntary control of heart, smooth muscle, glands. Sympathetic (thoracolumbar T1ŌĆōL2): prepares for action ŌåÆ increased HR, BP, glucose, bronchodilation, pupil dilation, decreased GI motility. Preganglionic: short, myelinated (acetylcholine, nAChR). Postganglionic: long, unmyelinated (norepinephrine, adrenergic receptors except sweat glands: ACh muscarinic). Parasympathetic (craniosacral CN III,VII,IX,X; S2ŌĆōS4): rest/digest ŌåÆ decreased HR, increased GI motility, bronchoconstriction, pupil constriction, glandular secretions. Both pre- and postganglionic: ACh (mAChR at effectors). Enteric nervous system: 'second brain,' ~500 million neurons in gut wall.` },
      { q:`The corpus callosum connects:`, ch:[`The two hemispheres of the cerebellum`,`The left and right cerebral hemispheres, allowing communication between them ŌĆö severing it (for epilepsy treatment) produces split-brain syndrome`,`The cerebral cortex to the brainstem`,`The thalamus to the basal ganglia`], ans:1, exp:`Corpus callosum: largest white matter commissure; ~250 million axons. Connects homotopic and heterotopic cortical areas across hemispheres. Split-brain syndrome (Sperry & Gazzaniga): after callosotomy, each hemisphere operates independently. Right visual field (left hemisphere) can name objects; left visual field (right hemisphere) cannot name but can draw/select with left hand. Shows functional specialization: left = language, analytical; right = visuospatial, holistic. Anterior commissure and hippocampal commissure: smaller connections. Agenesis of corpus callosum: may be asymptomatic if prenatal (other commissures compensate).` },
      { q:`Which neurotransmitter system is primarily implicated in mood regulation and is targeted by SSRIs?`, ch:[`Dopaminergic system`,`Serotonergic system ŌĆö SSRI (selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors) block serotonin reuptake at the presynaptic terminal ŌåÆ increased synaptic serotonin ŌåÆ improved mood in depression`,`GABAergic system`,`Glutamatergic system`], ans:1, exp:`Serotonin (5-hydroxytryptamine, 5-HT): synthesized from tryptophan (ŌåÆ 5-HTP ŌåÆ 5-HT by AADC). Raphe nuclei: primary source in brain. Projections: limbic system (mood), PFC (cognition), cerebellum, spinal cord. Serotonin transporters (SERT, SLC6A4): reuptake ŌåÆ SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline, escitalopram) block SERT ŌåÆ increased synaptic 5-HT. Functions: mood, sleep, appetite, memory, social behavior, thermoregulation. Gut: 95% of body's serotonin. 5-HT receptors (14+ subtypes): ionotropic (5-HT3, LGIC) and metabotropic (all others, GPCRs). MAO-A: metabolizes serotonin ŌåÆ MAOIs (irreversible, interaction with tyramine ŌåÆ hypertensive crisis).` },
      { q:`The hypothalamus regulates which of the following?`, ch:[`Voluntary movement only`,`Hunger, thirst, temperature regulation, circadian rhythms, endocrine function (via pituitary), and autonomic nervous system ŌĆö the 'master regulator' of homeostasis`,`Language and speech`,`Visual processing`], ans:1, exp:`Hypothalamus: small but critical region below thalamus. Functions: (1) Homeostasis: hunger (lateral HA = hunger; VMH = satiety), thirst, temperature (POA: fever; PO cooling/heating responses); (2) Endocrine: parvocellular neurons ŌåÆ releasing hormones (CRH, TRH, GnRH, GHRH, dopamine) ŌåÆ anterior pituitary (portal system); magnocellular neurons ŌåÆ ADH + oxytocin ŌåÆ posterior pituitary; (3) Circadian: SCN (biological clock); (4) ANS regulation; (5) Sexual behavior (INAH3; SDN-POA); (6) Emotional responses (via limbic connections). Damage examples: Prader-Willi (hyperphagia), craniopharyngioma (obesity, hypopituitarism).` },
      { q:`The occipital lobe is primarily responsible for:`, ch:[`Language processing`,`Visual processing ŌĆö contains primary visual cortex (V1, striate cortex) in the calcarine fissure; damage ŌåÆ contralateral visual field deficit (hemianopia)`,`Motor planning`,`Somatosensory processing`], ans:1, exp:`Occipital lobe: primary visual cortex (V1, BA17): processes retinotopic information (upper visual field ŌåÆ lower calcarine bank). Secondary visual cortices (V2, V3, V4, V5/MT): process color, motion, form, depth. Two visual streams: Ventral ('what') stream: V1 ŌåÆ V2 ŌåÆ V4 ŌåÆ inferior temporal cortex; object identification, face recognition. Dorsal ('where/how') stream: V1 ŌåÆ V2 ŌåÆ MT/V5 ŌåÆ posterior parietal cortex; spatial processing, guiding action. Lesions: V1 = cortical blindness (may have blindsight); V4 = achromatopsia; MT = akinetopsia (motion blindness); ITG = prosopagnosia; parietal = spatial neglect.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps12`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Language & Cognition`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`Chomsky's theory of universal grammar proposes that:`, ch:[`Language is entirely learned through reinforcement`,`Humans are born with an innate language acquisition device (LAD) ŌĆö a biological predisposition that facilitates the learning of any human language; underlying grammatical structures are universal`,`Language learning is based on imitation only`,`All languages share identical grammar rules`], ans:1, exp:`Chomsky (transformational generative grammar): Language Acquisition Device (LAD) ŌĆö innate grammatical knowledge that enables children to learn any language rapidly with incomplete input. Evidence: (1) Language universals across diverse languages; (2) Critical period for language acquisition (before puberty, optimal); (3) Children make systematic errors (overgeneralization: 'goed', 'mouses') suggesting rule induction, not rote learning; (4) Children acquire language without explicit instruction. Behaviorist (Skinner) view: language learned through operant conditioning. Chomsky's famous critique of Skinner's 'Verbal Behavior.'` },
      { q:`The linguistic relativity hypothesis (Sapir-Whorf) in its strong form proposes that:`, ch:[`Language influences but does not determine thought`,`Language determines thought ŌĆö the language you speak constrains the concepts you can think about and shapes your perception of reality`,`Thought is independent of language`,`Language and thought develop simultaneously but independently`], ans:1, exp:`Sapir-Whorf hypothesis: Strong (linguistic determinism): language determines thought ŌåÆ no thought without language (discredited ŌĆö evidence for language-independent thought). Weak (linguistic relativity): language influences thought ŌåÆ speakers of different languages have somewhat different cognitive tendencies (partially supported). Examples: Piraha language lacks recursion, numbers, color terms ŌåÆ limited abstract thought? (contested). Russian speakers distinguish light/dark blue with separate words ŌåÆ faster discrimination in blue spectrum. Color categories: Berlin & Kay showed universal basic color terms. Boroditsky's research: directional spatial language influences temporal cognition.` },
      { q:`Cognitive heuristics are:`, ch:[`Systematic, algorithmic problem-solving strategies`,`Mental shortcuts or rules of thumb that simplify decision-making and judgment ŌĆö often useful but can lead to systematic biases (availability, representativeness, anchoring)`,`Unconscious emotional responses to choices`,`Formal logical reasoning strategies`], ans:1, exp:`Heuristics (Tversky & Kahneman): fast, frugal, approximate judgments. Availability heuristic: estimate frequency/probability by ease of recall ŌåÆ overestimate dramatic/vivid events (plane crashes vs. car accidents). Representativeness heuristic: judge probability by how much it resembles prototype ŌåÆ base rate neglect (lawyer-engineer problem). Anchoring/adjustment: start with anchor, adjust insufficiently ŌåÆ anchor biases final estimate. Affect heuristic: emotional response guides judgment. Heuristics vs. algorithms: algorithms guarantee correct answer if applied correctly; heuristics are faster but error-prone. System 1 (fast, intuitive) vs. System 2 (slow, deliberative) thinking ŌĆö Kahneman.` },
      { q:`Working memory, as conceptualized by Baddeley and Hitch, includes which core components?`, ch:[`Episodic memory and semantic memory`,`Phonological loop (verbal/auditory), visuospatial sketchpad (visual/spatial), episodic buffer (integrates information), and central executive (attentional controller)`,`Short-term memory and long-term memory`,`Implicit and explicit memory stores`], ans:1, exp:`Baddeley's working memory model: Central executive: attentional control, dual-task management, inhibition. Phonological loop: verbal working memory (inner voice + phonological store); involved in language, reading. Visuospatial sketchpad: visual and spatial working memory (inner eye + spatial sense). Episodic buffer: binds information from other systems + long-term memory into integrated episodes. Capacity: ~7 ┬▒ 2 items (Miller) ŌåÆ ~4 chunks (Cowan). Duration: ~20ŌĆō30 seconds without rehearsal. Working memory predicts: academic achievement, fluid intelligence, reading comprehension. Neural basis: DLPFC for central executive.` },
      { q:`The availability heuristic leads to biases because:`, ch:[`People underestimate the frequency of common events`,`The ease with which examples come to mind (availability) is used as a proxy for frequency/probability ŌĆö vivid, recent, or emotionally significant events are more available ŌåÆ their frequency is overestimated`,`People rely too heavily on base rates`,`People cannot estimate frequencies at all`], ans:1, exp:`Availability heuristic examples: After media coverage of plane crashes ŌåÆ people overestimate air travel risk. After 9/11 ŌåÆ overestimation of terrorism frequency. More people list 'k' as first letter than third letter of English words, even though more words have k in third position (r-words are more available than third-position examples). After asking about dramatic deaths (shark attacks) ŌåÆ overestimate mortality. Affect heuristic: emotional reactions to a situation substitute for more careful probability assessment. Availability influenced by: recency, vividness, personal relevance, media coverage.` },
      { q:`Metacognition refers to:`, ch:[`Learning through observation`,`Thinking about one's own thinking ŌĆö awareness and regulation of one's cognitive processes, including monitoring comprehension and adjusting learning strategies`,`Transfer of knowledge from one domain to another`,`Unconscious procedural learning`], ans:1, exp:`Metacognition (Flavell): metacognitive knowledge (what you know about cognition), metacognitive monitoring (assessing your own cognitive states), metacognitive control (adjusting strategies). Calibration: accuracy of metacognitive judgments. Dunning-Kruger effect: incompetent individuals overestimate their ability (metacognitive deficit ŌĆö lack the knowledge to recognize their ignorance). Feeling of knowing (FOK): sense that one could recognize the answer even if it can't be recalled. Tip-of-the-tongue (TOT) phenomenon: metacognitive experience of partial retrieval. Educational applications: self-testing, elaborative interrogation, spaced practice all improve metacognitive accuracy.` },
      { q:`The concept of cognitive load theory (Sweller) proposes that:`, ch:[`Complex material is inherently easier to learn when presented all at once`,`Working memory has limited capacity; intrinsic load (complexity of material), extraneous load (poorly designed instruction), and germane load (learning/schema formation) together must not exceed capacity ŌĆö good instructional design reduces extraneous load`,`More information presented = better learning`,`Prior knowledge does not affect learning`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive load theory: intrinsic load: inherent complexity of material (element interactivity). Extraneous load: unnecessary cognitive effort from poor design (split-attention, redundancy). Germane load: load devoted to schema formation and automation. Instructional design: worked examples (reduce extraneous load for novices), goal-free problems, completion problems, minimize split-attention (text + diagram separated). Expertise reversal: supports needed by novices can increase load for experts (worked examples become extraneous for advanced learners). Sweller's implications: match instructional format to learner's prior knowledge.` },
      { q:`Confirmation bias refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency to seek out disconfirming evidence for one's beliefs`,`The tendency to search for, interpret, and recall information in a way that confirms one's pre-existing beliefs, while dismissing or ignoring contradictory information`,`Making decisions based on the most recent information`,`Overconfidence in one's own knowledge`], ans:1, exp:`Confirmation bias (Wason selection task): people preferentially test hypotheses by seeking confirming evidence rather than falsifying evidence. Manifestations: (1) Selective search for information (seek confirming sources); (2) Biased interpretation (ambiguous evidence seen as confirming); (3) Biased recall (remember confirming information better). Clinical relevance: clinicians may fixate on initial diagnosis ŌåÆ miss alternative diagnoses. Wason selection task: only ~10% correctly select the falsifying card. Antidote: consider the opposite, devil's advocate, consider base rates, actively seek disconfirming evidence.` },
      { q:`The Stroop effect demonstrates:`, ch:[`That color naming is slower than word reading in all contexts`,`Interference between automatic processing (word reading) and controlled processing (color naming) when a word's meaning (e.g., RED written in blue ink) conflicts with the required response`,`That attention is unlimited in capacity`,`That visual information is processed before linguistic information`], ans:1, exp:`Stroop effect (Stroop, 1935): naming ink color of color words slower and more error-prone when color and word are incongruent (BLUE written in red ink). Word reading is highly automatic (overlearned) ŌåÆ creates response conflict. Color naming is more controlled ŌåÆ susceptible to interference. Automaticity: highly practiced processes require less attention, are fast, and are difficult to suppress. Practice reduces Stroop interference (color naming becomes more automatic). Clinical applications: Stroop test used to assess selective attention, executive function, and cognitive flexibility in neuropsychology.` },
      { q:`In problem-solving, insight refers to:`, ch:[`Systematic trial-and-error until a solution is found`,`Sudden realization of a problem's solution ŌĆö typically preceded by an impasse, followed by a rapid 'aha!' moment as a novel mental representation emerges`,`Algorithmic application of learned rules`,`Gradual incremental improvement through practice`], ans:1, exp:`Insight (Gestalt psychology): 'aha' or eureka moment. Gestalt: restructuring of the problem representation. Duncker's radiation problem; nine-dot problem. Neural correlates: right hemisphere anterior temporal lobe (EEG gamma burst at insight moment). Incubation: setting aside a problem and returning later facilitates insight (unconscious processing continues; functional fixedness reduced). Functional fixedness: tendency to see objects only in their conventional uses ŌåÆ blocks insight (Duncker's candle problem). Mental set: tendency to use previously successful strategies ŌåÆ can impede solving problems requiring novel approaches.` },
      { q:`Language development in children typically follows which order?`, ch:[`Words ŌåÆ babbling ŌåÆ two-word combinations ŌåÆ full sentences`,`Cooing (0ŌĆō2 months) ŌåÆ babbling (4ŌĆō6 months) ŌåÆ holophrases/first words (~12 months) ŌåÆ two-word combinations (~18ŌĆō24 months) ŌåÆ telegraphic speech ŌåÆ full sentences`,`Full sentences emerge first, then simplified to single words`,`Language develops simultaneously with walking`], ans:1, exp:`Language milestones: 0ŌĆō2 months: cooing (vowel-like sounds). 4ŌĆō6 months: canonical babbling (CV syllables: 'bababa'). 8ŌĆō10 months: variegated babbling (mixture of syllables). ~12 months: first words (holophrases ŌĆö single words expressing whole thoughts). ~18 months: vocabulary explosion (fast mapping). ~18ŌĆō24 months: two-word combinations (telegraphic: 'more milk'). 2ŌĆō3 years: three-word combinations, grammar emerges. 4ŌĆō5 years: near-adult syntax. Critical period: optimal acquisition before puberty (Lenneberg). Evidence: Genie (language-deprived child) ŌĆö never achieved full syntax after puberty.` },
      { q:`Schemas in cognitive psychology are:`, ch:[`Single memories of specific events`,`Mental frameworks or structures that organize knowledge and guide information processing ŌĆö schemas influence what is encoded, how it is interpreted, and what is recalled`,`Innate behavioral patterns`,`Physiological response patterns`], ans:1, exp:`Schemas (Bartlett, 1932; Piaget): organized mental representations. Types: object schemas (what objects are), person schemas (what types of people are like), event/script schemas (typical sequences of events ŌĆö restaurant script), self-schema (beliefs about oneself), role schema (expectations for social roles). Effects on memory: schema-consistent information is better remembered; schema-inconsistent information may be assimilated, distorted, or also remembered if attention-grabbing (von Restorff effect). Bartlett's serial reproduction ('War of the Ghosts'): memory reconstructed ŌåÆ made more consistent with schema (cultural framework).` },
      { q:`Prototype theory of concepts proposes that:`, ch:[`All members of a category share an identical set of defining features`,`Categorization is based on comparison to an idealized, central member (prototype) ŌĆö items are categorized as instances of a concept based on their resemblance to the prototype rather than satisfying strict defining criteria`,`Concepts are based on formal logical definitions`,`Concepts are stored as individual exemplars`], ans:1, exp:`Prototype theory (Rosch): concepts are represented by their most typical/central member (prototype). Typicality gradients: robin is a more typical bird than penguin. Typicality effects: typical members are categorized faster, named more frequently, learned earlier. Basic level categories (chair vs. furniture vs. armchair): most cognitively natural level of categorization ŌĆö balanced between informativeness and distinctiveness. Exemplar theory: alternative ŌĆö categories represented by all remembered instances. Graded membership: family resemblance (Wittgenstein) ŌĆö members share overlapping features without a single defining characteristic.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps13`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Intelligence Theories`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`Spearman's g factor theory proposes that:`, ch:[`Intelligence consists of many independent abilities`,`There is a single general factor (g) underlying all intellectual abilities ŌĆö performance across diverse cognitive tasks is correlated, reflecting this common general intelligence`,`Intelligence is entirely environmentally determined`,`Crystallized intelligence is independent of fluid intelligence`], ans:1, exp:`Spearman (1904): factor analysis of cognitive tests ŌåÆ positive manifold (all correlate positively) ŌåÆ g factor extracted. g reflects: processing efficiency, working memory capacity, abstract reasoning. s factors: specific abilities. g has high heritability (~50ŌĆō80%). g predicts: academic achievement, job performance, health, longevity. Neural correlates: parieto-frontal integration theory (P-FIT) ŌĆö g associated with white matter connectivity between parietal and frontal regions. Debate: g as real entity vs. statistical artifact of factor analysis.` },
      { q:`Howard Gardner's theory of multiple intelligences proposes which intelligences?`, ch:[`Verbal and mathematical only`,`At least 8 relatively independent intelligences: linguistic, logical-mathematical, musical, spatial, bodily-kinesthetic, interpersonal, intrapersonal, naturalistic`,`Fluid and crystallized intelligence only`,`General intelligence with no specific components`], ans:1, exp:`Gardner (1983, 'Frames of Mind'): criteria for intelligence: neuropsychological evidence (localization, dissociation), evolutionary plausibility, susceptibility to coding, unique developmental history, savant/prodigy evidence. Original 8: linguistic (L1), logical-mathematical (L2), musical (M), spatial (S), bodily-kinesthetic (BK), interpersonal (INTer), intrapersonal (INTra), naturalistic. Later proposed: existential. Criticism: some (BK, musical) may not meet traditional definition of intelligence; little psychometric support; high g loading. Educational applications: differentiated instruction (controversial efficacy evidence).` },
      { q:`Fluid intelligence (Gf) and crystallized intelligence (Gc), as described by Cattell and Horn, differ in that:`, ch:[`Gc increases with age while Gf remains stable`,`Gf is the ability to reason and solve novel problems (independent of prior learning); Gc is accumulated knowledge and skills from education and experience ŌĆö Gf declines with aging; Gc remains stable or increases until late old age`,`Both decline equally with age`,`Gf and Gc are identical constructs`], ans:1, exp:`Cattell-Horn Gf-Gc theory: Gf: inductive/deductive reasoning, novel problem-solving, working memory ŌĆö peaks ~late teens/early 20s; declines with age. Gc: vocabulary, knowledge, verbal comprehension ŌĆö increases through adulthood; relatively resistant to normal aging. CHC (Cattell-Horn-Carroll) model: 10 broad abilities + g. Examples: Matrix reasoning (Ravens Progressive Matrices) = Gf. Vocabulary test = Gc. Aging: Gf sensitive to brain aging, medical conditions, dementia. Gc preserved because knowledge/experience compensate.` },
      { q:`The Flynn effect refers to:`, ch:[`The heritability of IQ scores`,`The substantial, progressive rise in average IQ test scores across generations in many countries (approximately 3 IQ points per decade) ŌĆö attributed to environmental factors including nutrition, education, and reduced infectious disease burden`,`The gender gap in IQ`,`Regression to the mean in cognitive testing`], ans:1, exp:`Flynn effect (James Flynn): IQ scores have risen substantially in 20th century (documented in 30+ countries). Magnitude: ~3 IQ points/decade = ~1 standard deviation per 30 years. Implications: (1) IQ tests measure a subset of cognitive abilities that improve with modernity; (2) Environmental factors (nutrition ŌĆö especially iodine, iron; education; reduced lead exposure; less infectious disease; more abstract thinking in modern life) are major determinants. Recent reports: possible plateau or reversal (negative Flynn effect) in some high-income countries. Counters purely genetic determinism ŌĆö genes haven't changed; environment has.` },
      { q:`Emotional intelligence (EI), as conceptualized by Mayer and Salovey, includes which abilities?`, ch:[`Empathy and social skills only`,`Perceiving emotions accurately, using emotions to facilitate thought, understanding emotional information, and managing emotions in self and others`,`IQ applied to social situations`,`Personality traits related to agreeableness`], ans:1, exp:`Mayer-Salovey-Caruso model (1990, 1997): four-branch ability model: (1) Perceiving emotions (in faces, voices, art); (2) Using emotions to facilitate thought (moods affect cognition); (3) Understanding emotional knowledge (how emotions develop, transition); (4) Managing emotions (regulating self and influencing others). Goleman's model: broader (includes motivation, empathy, social skills, self-awareness) ŌĆö criticized as mixing EI with personality traits. EI predicts: relationship quality, leadership, mental health, academic achievement (modest incremental validity over g). MSCEIT: ability-based measure of EI.` },
      { q:`The Flynn effect provides evidence that IQ test scores are heavily influenced by:`, ch:[`Purely genetic factors`,`Environmental factors ŌĆö the rapid increase across generations cannot be explained by genetic changes and points to environmental improvements (nutrition, education, healthcare, reduced toxin exposure)`,`Cultural bias only`,`Measurement error`], ans:1, exp:`This question reinforces the Flynn effect concept from a different angle. Additional context: Heritability ŌēĀ immutability ŌĆö heritability of IQ is high within current environments (~50ŌĆō80%) but this does not prevent large mean-level changes from environmental improvements. Iodine deficiency: reduces IQ by 10ŌĆō15 points; supplementation ŌåÆ Flynn-like gains. Lead exposure: correlates with lower IQ; removing leaded gasoline ŌåÆ contributes to Flynn gains. Schooling: formal education increases cognitive test performance. Flynn effect also shows that IQ tests measure culturally valued cognitive skills rather than fixed biological intelligence.` },
      { q:`Sternberg's triarchic theory of intelligence includes:`, ch:[`Linguistic, musical, and logical intelligences`,`Analytical intelligence (academic problem-solving), creative intelligence (novel situations, generating ideas), and practical intelligence (common sense, adapting to everyday environments)`,`Fluid and crystallized intelligence`,`General intelligence and specific abilities`], ans:1, exp:`Sternberg (1985): triarchic theory. Analytical: measured by IQ tests; decontextualized problems. Creative: coping with novelty, generating original ideas; automatization of skills. Practical: adapting to, shaping, selecting environments; tacit knowledge (implicit, job-relevant knowledge). Teaching to all three: students with practical/creative strengths may underperform on purely analytical tests but succeed in real-world tasks. WICS model (Sternberg): Wisdom + Intelligence + Creativity = successful intelligence. Criticism: limited psychometric support for independence of three components.` },
      { q:`A standardized IQ test produces scores with a mean of 100 and standard deviation of 15. What percentage of the population scores between 85 and 115?`, ch:[`50%`,`68% ŌĆö approximately 68% of scores fall within one standard deviation of the mean in a normal distribution`,`95%`,`99.7%`], ans:1, exp:`Normal distribution: 68-95-99.7 rule. ┬▒1 SD: 68.2% of population. ┬▒2 SD: 95.4%. ┬▒3 SD: 99.7%. IQ 85ŌĆō115: one SD below to one SD above mean (100 ┬▒ 15) ŌåÆ 68%. IQ 70ŌĆō130: ┬▒2 SD ŌåÆ 95.4% ŌåÆ only 4.6% outside this range. IQ < 70: 2.3% below (-2 SD) ŌĆö threshold for intellectual disability (with adaptive deficits). IQ > 130: 2.3% ŌåÆ gifted range. Standard score conversion: z = (X ŌłÆ ╬╝) / Žā.` },
      { q:`The concept of stereotype threat (Steele) is particularly relevant to the measurement of intelligence because:`, ch:[`IQ tests are inherently biased in item content`,`When members of a stereotyped group are reminded of the stereotype that their group performs poorly on intelligence tests, they experience anxiety and cognitive burden that reduce their test performance ŌĆö contributing to observed group differences`,`Intelligence is entirely culturally defined`,`Stereotype threat only affects personality assessments`], ans:1, exp:`Stereotype threat: Steele & Aronson (1995): Black students performed worse on GRE-like test when race was made salient vs. when described as non-diagnostic of ability. Proposed mechanism: cognitive burden from self-monitoring, anxiety, vigilance ŌåÆ reduces working memory ŌåÆ impairs test performance. Effects found across groups: women on math tests, elderly on memory tests, white men on spatial tests when told Asians perform better. Implication: group differences in test performance may partly reflect testing context, not only true ability differences. Reducing threat: de-emphasizing group membership, attributing difficulty to test challenge (not self), affirming non-threatened identity.` },
      { q:`In psychometric testing, reliability refers to:`, ch:[`Measuring what the test claims to measure`,`The consistency and reproducibility of test scores ŌĆö a reliable test yields similar scores across repeated administrations, or high agreement between different raters or test forms`,`The ability of a test to predict future outcomes`,`The norming of scores to a population`], ans:1, exp:`Reliability types: Test-retest: same test, different times (temporal stability). Split-half: correlation between two halves of the same test. Cronbach's alpha: internal consistency (how well items measure the same construct; ╬▒ Ōēź 0.70 acceptable). Inter-rater: agreement between different raters. Alternate forms: correlation between two equivalent test versions. Reliability ŌēĀ validity: a test can be reliable (consistent) but not valid (not measuring what it claims). Validity: construct (measures the theoretical construct), criterion (predicts criterion ŌĆö concurrent, predictive), content (items represent the full domain). Standard error of measurement (SEM) = SD ├Ś ŌłÜ(1 ŌłÆ reliability).` },
      { q:`Intellectual disability (previously mental retardation) in the DSM-5 requires:`, ch:[`IQ score below 70 alone`,`Deficits in intellectual functioning AND adaptive functioning (conceptual, social, practical domains) with onset during the developmental period ŌĆö IQ score is one criterion but severity is based primarily on adaptive functioning`,`IQ score below 50 only`,`Only deficits in academic performance`], ans:1, exp:`Intellectual disability (ID): replaces term 'mental retardation' in DSM-5. Criteria: A (intellectual deficits ŌĆö below 2 SD, ~IQ < 70); B (adaptive functioning deficits in conceptual, social, practical skills); C (onset in developmental period). Severity: Mild (~85%): IQ ~50ŌĆō69; academic difficulties; largely independent as adults. Moderate (~10%): IQ ~35ŌĆō49; supported employment, supervision needed. Severe (~3ŌĆō4%): IQ ~20ŌĆō34; limited communication, needs support. Profound (~1ŌĆō2%): IQ < 20; minimal self-care. Causes: genetic (Down syndrome, Fragile X, phenylketonuria), prenatal (alcohol, infection, hypoxia), perinatal, postnatal (lead poisoning, meningitis).` },
      { q:`Gardner's bodily-kinesthetic intelligence is an example of intelligence because:`, ch:[`It can be easily measured by standard IQ tests`,`It represents a distinct problem-solving ability with neuropsychological evidence (damage to motor areas produces specific deficits), evolutionary plausibility, and a unique developmental trajectory`,`It involves mathematical reasoning`,`It is identical to athletic ability`], ans:1, exp:`Gardner's criteria for a modular intelligence include: potential isolation by brain damage, existence of prodigies/savants, distinct developmental history, an evolutionary history, psychometric evidence of distinctness, susceptibility to symbol systems, core neural operations. Bodily-kinesthetic: use of one's body or parts of it to solve problems or create products. Examples: surgery, dance, athletics, crafts. Neurological support: motor and cerebellar systems, procedural learning. Savant syndrome: some individuals with ID show extraordinary isolated abilities (calendar calculation, perfect pitch, artistic skill) ŌĆö evidence for modular intelligence.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps14`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Basic Statistics for Health Sciences`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The mean, median, and mode are all measures of:`, ch:[`Variability`,`Central tendency ŌĆö the mean is the arithmetic average; the median is the middle value; the mode is the most frequent value`,`Correlation between variables`,`Statistical significance`], ans:1, exp:`Central tendency: Mean (arithmetic average): ╬Żx/n; sensitive to outliers. Median: middle value when ordered; robust to outliers. Mode: most frequent value; applicable to categorical data. When to use: symmetric distributions ŌåÆ mean Ōēł median Ōēł mode (use mean). Skewed distributions ŌåÆ use median (more representative). Categorical data ŌåÆ use mode. Bimodal distribution: two modes ŌåÆ mean/median may not represent either cluster. Trimmed mean: drops extreme values before averaging ŌĆö compromise between mean and median.` },
      { q:`Standard deviation (SD) measures:`, ch:[`The range of scores in a dataset`,`The average amount by which individual data points deviate from the mean ŌĆö a larger SD indicates greater variability or spread in the data`,`The difference between the maximum and minimum values`,`The likelihood that results occurred by chance`], ans:1, exp:`SD = ŌłÜ(variance) = ŌłÜ[╬Ż(x ŌłÆ ╬╝)┬▓/N]. Variance: average squared deviation from mean. SD: in original units, interpretable. Interpretation: 68% of values fall within ┬▒1 SD of mean (normal distribution). CV (coefficient of variation) = SD/mean ├Ś 100%: SD as % of mean; useful for comparing variability across different-scale measurements. SEM (standard error of mean) = SD/ŌłÜn: variability of sample means around population mean; decreases as n increases. CI: mean ┬▒ (z or t) ├Ś SEM.` },
      { q:`A p-value of 0.03 in a hypothesis test means:`, ch:[`There is a 3% chance the research hypothesis is true`,`Assuming the null hypothesis is true, there is a 3% probability of obtaining results at least as extreme as those observed ŌĆö this is below the typical ╬▒ = 0.05 threshold, so we reject the null hypothesis`,`The effect size is small`,`There is 97% confidence the result will replicate`], ans:1, exp:`p-value: probability of observed data (or more extreme) if HŌéĆ is true. p < 0.05 ŌåÆ reject HŌéĆ (statistically significant by conventional threshold). p Ōēź 0.05 ŌåÆ fail to reject HŌéĆ. MISINTERPRETATIONS: p-value is NOT: the probability HŌéĆ is true; the probability of a Type II error; the probability the result will replicate; the effect size. Statistical significance ŌēĀ clinical/practical significance (a small but clinically irrelevant effect can be significant with large n). Effect size (Cohen's d, r, ╬Ę┬▓) quantifies practical significance. APA recommends always reporting effect sizes.` },
      { q:`In a normal distribution, approximately what percentage of data falls within 2 standard deviations of the mean?`, ch:[`68%`,`95%`,`99.7%`,`50%`], ans:1, exp:`Empirical rule (68-95-99.7 rule): ┬▒1 SD: 68.27%. ┬▒2 SD: 95.45%. ┬▒3 SD: 99.73%. Z-scores: z = (x ŌłÆ ╬╝) / Žā. Area under normal curve: z = 1.96 ŌåÆ 95% CI; z = 2.576 ŌåÆ 99% CI. Skewness: asymmetry of distribution. Kurtosis: peakedness (leptokurtic vs. platykurtic). Central Limit Theorem: with sufficiently large n (Ōēź30), sample means are approximately normally distributed regardless of population distribution ŌåÆ basis for parametric tests.` },
      { q:`Pearson's r correlation coefficient measures:`, ch:[`The slope of the regression line`,`The strength and direction of the linear relationship between two continuous variables, ranging from ŌłÆ1 (perfect negative) to +1 (perfect positive), with 0 indicating no linear relationship`,`Whether the correlation is statistically significant`,`The proportion of variance explained by the relationship`], ans:1, exp:`Pearson's r: ranges ŌłÆ1 to +1. Interpretation: |r| < 0.3 (weak), 0.3ŌĆō0.5 (moderate), > 0.5 (strong). r┬▓ = coefficient of determination: proportion of variance in Y explained by X (e.g., r = 0.5 ŌåÆ r┬▓ = 0.25 ŌåÆ X explains 25% of variance in Y). Assumptions: continuous variables, linear relationship, bivariate normality. Spearman's Žü: non-parametric rank correlation; use when variables are ordinal or distribution is non-normal. Causation: correlation ŌēĀ causation (confounders, bidirectionality, coincidence). Restriction of range: truncated sample range ŌåÆ underestimates true correlation.` },
      { q:`Sensitivity of a diagnostic test is defined as:`, ch:[`The probability that a person without the disease tests negative`,`The probability that a person with the disease tests positive (true positive rate) ŌĆö a highly sensitive test rarely misses disease (few false negatives)`,`The probability that a person with a positive test actually has the disease`,`The accuracy of the test across all patients`], ans:1, exp:`Sensitivity = TP / (TP + FN) = P(positive test | disease present). Specificity = TN / (TN + FP) = P(negative test | disease absent). Positive predictive value (PPV) = TP / (TP + FP): depends on prevalence (higher prevalence ŌåÆ higher PPV). Negative predictive value (NPV) = TN / (TN + FN). Likelihood ratio positive: sensitivity / (1 ŌłÆ specificity). ROC curve: sensitivity vs. (1 ŌłÆ specificity) ŌĆö AUC measures overall discriminatory ability. High sensitivity ŌåÆ use for screening (few false negatives). High specificity ŌåÆ use for confirmation (few false positives).` },
      { q:`In a randomized controlled trial, blinding (masking) is used to:`, ch:[`Increase sample size`,`Prevent expectation bias ŌĆö single blind: participants don't know group assignment; double blind: neither participants nor assessors know; triple blind: adds data analysts/statisticians`,`Ensure all participants are similar at baseline`,`Allow participants to choose their preferred treatment`], ans:1, exp:`Blinding: reduces bias from expectations. Types: Single-blind: participant blinded. Double-blind: participant + assessor/clinician blinded. Triple-blind: adds statisticians/data analysts. Placebo control: ensures psychological expectancy effects are equal between groups. Randomization: ensures baseline comparability (controls known and unknown confounders). Allocation concealment: ensures sequence unknown until after assignment ŌĆö prevents selection bias. CONSORT guidelines: reporting standards for RCTs. Open-label: no blinding; acceptable for pragmatic trials or when blinding is impossible (surgical trials).` },
      { q:`The null hypothesis in a clinical trial typically states:`, ch:[`The treatment will be effective`,`There is no difference between groups ŌĆö any observed difference is due to chance; the trial aims to provide evidence to reject or fail to reject this hypothesis`,`The treatment will harm patients`,`The sample is not representative of the population`], ans:1, exp:`Null hypothesis (HŌéĆ): typically: no effect, no difference, no association. Alternative hypothesis (HŌéü): what the researcher expects or hopes to show. Hypothesis testing: calculate test statistic (t, F, Žć┬▓) ŌåÆ p-value ŌåÆ if p < ╬▒, reject HŌéĆ. Type I error: reject HŌéĆ when true (false positive) = ╬▒. Type II error: fail to reject HŌéĆ when false (false negative) = ╬▓. Power = 1 ŌłÆ ╬▓. Sample size: larger n ŌåÆ more power ŌåÆ can detect smaller effects. Effect size: how large is the effect? Clinical significance: is the effect large enough to matter clinically?` },
      { q:`Meta-analysis in medical research is a statistical technique that:`, ch:[`Selects the single best study on a topic`,`Systematically combines data from multiple independent studies to produce an overall estimate of an effect ŌĆö increases statistical power and precision relative to any single study`,`Describes research methods without quantitative synthesis`,`Identifies bias in individual studies`], ans:1, exp:`Meta-analysis: quantitative systematic review. Steps: systematic literature search ŌåÆ quality assessment (PRISMA guidelines) ŌåÆ extract effect sizes ŌåÆ calculate weighted average (weight by study precision/inverse variance) ŌåÆ forest plot. Heterogeneity: I┬▓ statistic ŌĆö variability among studies' effect sizes (I┬▓ > 50% = substantial; use random-effects model). Publication bias: positive results more likely published ŌåÆ funnel plot asymmetry (Egger test). Meta-regression: explores moderators of effect. Cochrane Collaboration: produces high-quality systematic reviews and meta-analyses. Systematic review ŌēĀ meta-analysis: SR can be qualitative; MA has quantitative synthesis.` },
      { q:`An odds ratio (OR) of 2.5 in a case-control study means:`, ch:[`The risk is 2.5 times higher in the exposed group`,`The odds of exposure among cases are 2.5 times the odds of exposure among controls ŌĆö the disease is 2.5 times as likely to have a given exposure in cases vs. controls`,`The absolute risk difference is 2.5%`,`The confidence interval includes the null`], ans:1, exp:`Odds ratio: used in case-control studies (can't calculate risk/RR directly). OR = (a/c)/(b/d) = ad/bc (cross-product ratio). Relative risk (RR) = P(disease|exposed) / P(disease|unexposed): used in cohort studies. When disease is rare: OR Ōēł RR. For common diseases: OR overestimates RR. Number needed to treat (NNT) = 1 / (absolute risk reduction): clinically useful measure. Attributable risk: excess risk in exposed vs. unexposed groups. Forest plot: each study's OR (or RR) with CI; diamond = pooled estimate. OR = 1 ŌåÆ no association; >1 ŌåÆ positive association; <1 ŌåÆ protective.` },
      { q:`A confidence interval (CI) that does not include the null value (1 for ratio measures, 0 for difference measures) indicates:`, ch:[`The result is clinically significant`,`The result is statistically significant at the corresponding ╬▒ level ŌĆö e.g., a 95% CI that does not include 1 for an OR is equivalent to p < 0.05`,`The study had adequate power`,`The effect size is large`], ans:1, exp:`95% CI: range within which the true population parameter lies with 95% confidence. If CI for OR excludes 1 ŌåÆ statistically significant at p < 0.05. If CI for mean difference excludes 0 ŌåÆ statistically significant. Wide CI: imprecise estimate (small n, high variability). Narrow CI: precise estimate (large n, low variability). Note: 95% CI ŌēĀ 95% probability that true value lies in the interval (frequentist interpretation: if we repeated the study many times, 95% of calculated CIs would contain the true value). Bayesian credible interval: more intuitive ŌĆö 95% probability the true value lies in the interval, given the data and prior.` },
      { q:`Incidence and prevalence are related by which concept?`, ch:[`Prevalence = incidence + mortality`,`Prevalence Ōēł incidence ├Ś duration ŌĆö for stable conditions; high incidence + long duration = high prevalence; high incidence + short duration (rapid cure or death) = lower prevalence`,`Incidence always equals prevalence`,`Prevalence is always higher than incidence`], ans:1, exp:`Epidemiological measures: Incidence rate: new cases per population per time unit. Prevalence: all existing cases at a given time. Relationship: Prevalence Ōēł Incidence ├Ś Average Duration (for stable diseases). Examples: AIDS: high prevalence relative to incidence because duration is long (effective treatment extends life). Seasonal flu: high incidence but low prevalence at any point (short duration). Ebola: high case fatality rate ŌåÆ low prevalence despite high incidence during outbreaks. Attack rate: proportion of exposed individuals who develop disease (used in outbreak investigation). Secondary attack rate: probability of infection among susceptible household contacts.` },
      { q:`The chi-square (Žć┬▓) test is used to analyze:`, ch:[`The means of two continuous variables`,`The association between two categorical variables ŌĆö compares observed frequencies with expected frequencies under the null hypothesis of independence`,`The correlation between continuous variables`,`The difference in means between more than two groups`], ans:1, exp:`Chi-square test (Pearson): tests HŌéĆ: no association between categorical variables. Žć┬▓ = ╬Ż(O ŌłÆ E)┬▓ / E. Degrees of freedom: (rows ŌłÆ 1) ├Ś (columns ŌłÆ 1). Assumptions: expected cell counts Ōēź 5 in most cells. Fisher's exact test: for small expected counts (2├Ś2 tables). McNemar's test: for paired categorical data. Contingency tables: 2├Ś2 (OR calculation), 2├Śk. Applications: smoking ├Ś cancer, vaccine ├Ś disease outcome. T-test: compare means of two groups (Student's/Welch's). ANOVA: compare means of Ōēź3 groups. Regression: predict continuous outcome from predictors.` },
    ]
  },
  { id:`ps15`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Social Determinants of Health`, diff:`Easy`, qs:[
      { q:`The social determinants of health (SDOH) refer to:`, ch:[`Genetic factors determining disease susceptibility`,`The non-medical conditions in which people are born, grow, live, work, and age ŌĆö including income, education, housing, food security, social support, and access to healthcare ŌĆö that powerfully shape health outcomes`,`Only behavioral risk factors like smoking and diet`,`The quality of healthcare available in a community`], ans:1, exp:`SDOH (WHO framework): structural determinants (socioeconomic position, policies, power distribution) ŌåÆ intermediate determinants (living conditions, psychosocial factors, health behaviors, healthcare access) ŌåÆ health outcomes. 'Causes of the causes': behavioral risk factors are themselves shaped by social conditions. Social gradient of health: even small differences in SES produce health differences across the full spectrum ŌĆö not just a threshold at poverty. Marmot's Whitehall studies: British civil servants showed progressive health gradient across all grades, not just lowest vs. highest.` },
      { q:`Socioeconomic status (SES) affects health through which pathways?`, ch:[`Genetic selection for social class`,`Multiple pathways: material deprivation (food insecurity, poor housing, environmental toxins), psychosocial stress (chronic stress ŌåÆ HPA/ANS dysregulation), health behaviors (lower SES ŌåÆ more smoking, less exercise), and differential access to healthcare`,`Only through healthcare access`,`Only through behavioral choices`], ans:1, exp:`SES-health pathways: Material: poverty ŌåÆ inadequate nutrition, housing, safety ŌåÆ direct health impacts. Psychosocial: lower SES ŌåÆ more chronic stressors, less control ŌåÆ allostatic load ŌåÆ cardiovascular/immune damage. Behavioral: health-promoting behaviors require resources, knowledge, and opportunity ŌĆö 'choice' is constrained by circumstances. Healthcare access: insurance, transportation, literacy, provider-patient concordance. Social capital: strong community ties ŌåÆ better health. Neighborhood: concentrated poverty ŌåÆ reduced green space, more fast food, less safety for exercise.` },
      { q:`The concept of health disparities refers to:`, ch:[`Random variation in health outcomes between individuals`,`Preventable differences in health and disease burden between population groups (defined by race, ethnicity, SES, geography, gender, sexual orientation, disability) ŌĆö linked to historical inequities and social disadvantage`,`Natural variation in health across the lifespan`,`Differences in health between countries`], ans:1, exp:`Health disparities (health inequities when caused by systemic injustice): Black Americans: higher rates of hypertension, diabetes, maternal mortality, preterm birth vs. white Americans ŌĆö not fully explained by SES or access. Weathering hypothesis (Geronimus): premature biological aging in Black women due to chronic stress of navigating racism. Rural disparities: higher rates of diabetes, cardiovascular disease, opioid use disorder, less access to specialty care. Sexual minority health: higher rates of depression, anxiety, substance use ŌĆö largely due to minority stress (stigma, discrimination, concealment). Disability: frequent encounters with healthcare system barriers.` },
      { q:`Adverse childhood experiences (ACEs) affect adult health by:`, ch:[`Only affecting mental health, not physical health`,`Causing epigenetic changes, HPA axis dysregulation, and altered neural development that increase risk of cardiovascular disease, cancer, substance use disorders, mental illness, and premature mortality in a dose-response fashion`,`Being completely reversible with good adult healthcare`,`Only affecting individuals with genetic vulnerability`], ans:1, exp:`ACE study (Felitti et al., 1998): retrospective study of 17,000 Kaiser Permanente patients. Ten ACE categories: physical/emotional/sexual abuse, physical/emotional neglect, household dysfunction (domestic violence, substance abuse, mental illness, incarceration, divorce). ACE score 1ŌĆō10: dose-response relationship with health outcomes. ACE Ōēź 4: 4ŌĆō12├Ś increased risk of alcoholism, drug abuse, depression, suicide attempt; increased CVD, cancer, liver disease, COPD. Mechanisms: toxic stress ŌåÆ HPA dysregulation ŌåÆ allostatic load ŌåÆ chronic disease. Epigenetic changes: methylation of stress-response genes (NR3C1 ŌĆö glucocorticoid receptor).` },
      { q:`The relationship between education and health is best described as:`, ch:[`Education has no independent effect on health ŌĆö wealth explains everything`,`Education promotes health through multiple pathways: economic (higher income, better jobs), cognitive (health literacy, problem-solving), psychosocial (sense of control, social networks), and behavioral (healthier lifestyle choices)`,`Only postgraduate education affects health`,`Education improves health only in developed countries`], ans:1, exp:`Education-health gradient: each additional year of schooling ŌåÆ 1ŌĆō2 years additional life expectancy. Pathways: (1) Economic: education ŌåÆ higher income, better occupations ŌåÆ material resources; (2) Cognitive: health literacy (ability to obtain, process, act on health information) ŌĆö limited health literacy ŌåÆ poor medication adherence, missed screenings; (3) Psychosocial: mastery, self-efficacy, social connections; (4) Behavioral: more exercise, less smoking, better diet; (5) Marriage selection: educated individuals marry educated partners ŌåÆ shared health benefits. Education interventions: one of most cost-effective population health strategies.` },
      { q:`Food insecurity affects health outcomes primarily through which mechanisms?`, ch:[`Only through reduced caloric intake leading to undernutrition`,`Multiple pathways: nutritional deficiency, psychosocial stress, disrupted development in children, higher risk of diet-related chronic diseases, and trade-offs between food and healthcare expenditure`,`Only affects physical development, not mental health`,`Exclusively affects only the very poor`], ans:1, exp:`Food insecurity: uncertain, insufficient access to adequate food. Paradox: food insecurity associated with obesity ŌĆö 'food insecurity ŌåÆ obesity' cycle. When food is available, energy-dense/nutrient-poor foods (cheaper, longer shelf life) are preferred. Stress eating, cortisol ŌåÆ abdominal fat. In children: cognitive development impairment, school readiness, mental health problems, poor academic performance. Adults: higher rates of hypertension, diabetes, depression, anxiety. Healthcare trade-offs: 'heat or eat' ŌĆö low-income individuals choose between food, heat, medications. Social determinants interact: poverty ŌåÆ food desert access ŌåÆ food insecurity ŌåÆ chronic disease.` },
      { q:`The minority stress model (Meyer) proposes that health disparities in LGBTQ+ populations arise from:`, ch:[`Biological differences in disease susceptibility`,`Excess stress derived from stigma, discrimination, prejudice, expectations of rejection, internalized homophobia/transphobia, and need to conceal identity ŌĆö above and beyond general life stressors`,`Cultural health behaviors only`,`Healthcare access barriers alone`], ans:1, exp:`Minority stress (Meyer, 2003): unique stressors for sexual minority individuals: (1) Distal (external): actual discrimination, violence, victimization; (2) Proximal (internal, based on expectations): expectations of rejection, concealment of identity, internalized homophobia. These chronic stressors ŌåÆ elevated rates of depression, anxiety, substance use disorders, suicidality. Protective factors: family acceptance, community connectedness, social support, positive LGB identity. Minority stress model applies to other stigmatized groups (racial/ethnic minorities). Intersectionality: multiple minority identities ŌåÆ intersecting stressors.` },
      { q:`Environmental health disparities refer to:`, ch:[`The equal distribution of environmental hazards`,`The disproportionate exposure of communities of color and low-income communities to environmental hazards (pollutants, industrial facilities, lack of green space) ŌĆö contributing to higher rates of asthma, cancer, and cardiovascular disease`,`Natural environmental variation without health impact`,`Environmental factors affecting only rural populations`], ans:1, exp:`Environmental justice: Low-income and minority communities are more likely to live near: toxic waste sites, industrial facilities, highways (diesel exhaust), power plants, agricultural pesticide exposure. Health consequences: asthma (indoor/outdoor air pollution), lead poisoning (older housing stock), cardiovascular disease, cancer. Climate change: disproportionately affects vulnerable populations. Food desert: limited access to grocery stores with fresh produce. Heat islands: urban areas lacking green space and tree canopy ŌåÆ excessive heat exposure in heat waves. Environmental health equity: goal of equal protection from environmental hazards.` },
      { q:`Social cohesion in a community is associated with better health outcomes through which mechanism?`, ch:[`Direct effect on genetics`,`Social cohesion (trust, mutual support, civic engagement) ŌåÆ greater collective efficacy, reduced chronic stress, faster disaster recovery, better information sharing, increased political power to improve community conditions`,`Only through reducing crime rates`,`Only in rural communities`], ans:1, exp:`Social cohesion: Putnam's social capital (bonding and bridging). Mechanisms: (1) Collective efficacy: ability of community members to work together ŌåÆ improved neighborhood conditions; (2) Social support: emotional, instrumental, informational ŌåÆ stress buffering; (3) Social control: norms against harmful health behaviors; (4) Political power: engaged communities advocate for health-improving policies. Kawachi et al.: US states with higher social capital ŌåÆ lower mortality from all causes, including CVD. Social isolation (opposite of cohesion): mortality risk equivalent to smoking 15 cigarettes/day. Loneliness epidemic: growing public health concern in many high-income countries.` },
      { q:`Mass incarceration in the United States disproportionately affects which population, and how does it affect health?`, ch:[`Equally affects all demographic groups`,`Disproportionately affects Black and Hispanic men ŌĆö incarceration disrupts families, removes people from social support, exposes to institutional trauma and violence, creates barriers to employment and housing post-release, and spreads infectious diseases (HIV, tuberculosis)`,`Only affects physical health through exposure to violence`,`Has no effect on family health outcomes`], ans:1, exp:`U.S. incarceration: ~2.1 million people incarcerated; racial disparities: Black Americans ~5├Ś more likely to be incarcerated than whites. Health mechanisms: (1) Direct: poor healthcare in jails/prisons, violence exposure, overcrowding ŌåÆ infectious disease. HIV: higher prevalence in prisons, transmitted inside and carried to communities post-release. TB: congregate settings facilitate transmission. (2) Indirect (families): children of incarcerated parents: adverse childhood experience, higher risk of mental health problems, poverty, incarceration themselves. (3) Post-release: felony records ŌåÆ barriers to housing, employment, public benefits ŌåÆ social determinants undermined. (4) Community-level: concentrated in low-income communities ŌåÆ social network disruption.` },
      { q:`The social gradient in health refers to:`, ch:[`A steep threshold effect where only the very poor have poor health`,`A continuous, stepwise relationship between social position (SES) and health ŌĆö each step up the social hierarchy confers progressively better health, so those at every level are healthier than those just below and less healthy than those just above`,`The difference in health between urban and rural populations`,`Cultural differences in health behaviors`], ans:1, exp:`Marmot's Whitehall studies: 10,000 British civil servants. Lowest grade had 3├Ś higher mortality than highest grade. But even the second-highest grade was less healthy than the highest ŌĆö showing a gradient, not just poverty threshold. Explains why improving overall health requires addressing inequality, not just poverty. Mechanisms: sense of control (psychosocial ŌĆö those lower in hierarchy have less autonomy), chronic stress, health behaviors, material conditions. The gradient operates from birth ŌĆö maternal SES affects birth outcomes, then child outcomes, cumulatively.` },
      { q:`Which public health intervention strategy is considered 'upstream' compared to clinical treatment?`, ch:[`Prescribing medication for hypertension`,`Policies that address the root causes of ill health ŌĆö such as increasing minimum wage, improving affordable housing, expanding access to education, or reducing toxic exposures ŌĆö before disease develops`,`Screening programs for early disease detection`,`Providing acute hospital care`], ans:1, exp:`Upstream vs. downstream metaphor (McKinley): downstream: pulling drowning people from the river (treating disease after it occurs ŌĆö clinical medicine). Midstream: teaching people to swim (behavior change interventions). Upstream: preventing them from falling in (structural/policy interventions). Population health approach: Geoffrey Rose: 'the causes of the cases' vs. 'the causes of the rates' ŌĆö population-level risk reduction more effective than treating high-risk individuals alone. Prevention paradox: intervention that gives large population benefit often gives small individual benefit. Primary prevention: prevent disease occurrence. Secondary: early detection (screening). Tertiary: manage existing disease.` },
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps16`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Attitude Formation & Persuasion`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`According to the Elaboration Likelihood Model (ELM), the central route to persuasion involves:`, ch:[`Persuasion based on superficial cues like attractiveness or speaker credibility`,`Careful, thoughtful consideration of the actual content and arguments of a message, leading to more durable attitude change`,`Persuasion that occurs without any cognitive processing`,`Attitude change that always reverts quickly`], ans:1, exp:`The central route involves high elaboration ŌĆö the audience carefully evaluates the logic and evidence of arguments. Attitudes formed this way tend to be stronger, more resistant to counterpersuasion, and more predictive of behavior. The peripheral route relies on heuristic cues (attractiveness, mood, number of arguments) and produces more transient attitude change.` },
      { q:`The peripheral route to persuasion is most likely to be used when an audience:`, ch:[`Is highly motivated and has the cognitive capacity to process the message`,`Has low motivation or limited cognitive resources to evaluate the message carefully`,`Is composed entirely of experts on the topic`,`Has unlimited time to consider the message`], ans:1, exp:`When motivation or ability to process information is low (distraction, low personal relevance, fatigue), people rely on peripheral cues ŌĆö heuristics like "experts are usually right" or "more arguments = stronger position" ŌĆö rather than the substance of the message.` },
      { q:`An attitude is generally described as having three components:`, ch:[`Affective, behavioral, and cognitive (the ABC model)`,`Visual, auditory, and kinesthetic`,`Conscious, preconscious, and unconscious`,`Primary, secondary, and tertiary`], ans:0, exp:`The ABC model of attitudes: Affective (emotional reactions/feelings), Behavioral (actions or behavioral intentions), and Cognitive (beliefs and thoughts about the object). These components are usually consistent but can sometimes conflict, contributing to cognitive dissonance.` },
      { q:`The mere exposure effect refers to the phenomenon whereby:`, ch:[`Repeated exposure to a stimulus decreases liking for it`,`Repeated exposure to a stimulus tends to increase liking/preference for it, even without conscious awareness of the exposure`,`Exposure to a stimulus has no effect on attitudes`,`A single exposure produces maximal liking, with no further effect from repetition`], ans:1, exp:`Zajonc's mere exposure effect: familiarity breeds liking (up to a point ŌĆö excessive repetition can lead to boredom/decreased liking). This occurs even with subliminal exposure, suggesting it doesn't require conscious recognition. Used extensively in advertising.` },
      { q:`The foot-in-the-door technique for gaining compliance involves:`, ch:[`Making a large request first, then following with a smaller request`,`Getting a person to agree to a small request first, increasing the likelihood they will agree to a larger request later`,`Threatening negative consequences for non-compliance`,`Offering an immediate reward for compliance`], ans:1, exp:`Foot-in-the-door: small initial commitment increases later compliance with larger requests, partly explained by self-perception theory (people infer their attitudes from their own behavior ŌĆö "I must be the type of person who helps with this cause"). Contrast with door-in-the-face: starting with a large request that's refused, followed by a smaller "concession" request that seems more reasonable by comparison.` },
      { q:`Source credibility (e.g., expertise and trustworthiness) most strongly affects persuasion via which route?`, ch:[`The central route exclusively`,`The peripheral route, as a heuristic cue`,`Neither route`,`Only when the message has no actual content`], ans:1, exp:`A credible source serves as a peripheral cue ("experts are usually correct"), which can be especially influential when elaboration is low. However, source credibility can also enhance central route processing if it increases perceived message quality.` },
      { q:`The "sleeper effect" in persuasion research describes:`, ch:[`A persuasive message's impact decreasing over time`,`A delayed increase in the persuasive impact of a message from a low-credibility source, as the source and message become dissociated in memory over time`,`Persuasion that only works while the audience is asleep`,`Immediate and permanent attitude change from any message`], ans:1, exp:`Sleeper effect: initially, a message from a low-credibility source has little impact (discounted due to source). Over time, people may remember the message content but forget its (untrustworthy) source, leading to increased persuasive impact later ŌĆö the message and source become "dissociated."` },
      { q:`Cognitive dissonance theory predicts that after making a difficult decision between two similarly attractive options, a person will typically:`, ch:[`Regret the decision and switch back immediately`,`Increase their evaluation of the chosen option and decrease their evaluation of the rejected option (post-decisional dissonance reduction)`,`Feel no change in attitudes toward either option`,`Become indifferent to both options`], ans:1, exp:`Post-decisional dissonance: choosing between similarly attractive alternatives creates dissonance ("why did I give up the good features of the option I rejected?"). To reduce this, people often spread the alternatives apart psychologically ŌĆö inflating the chosen option's value and devaluing the rejected one.` },
      { q:`Implicit attitudes, as measured by tools like the Implicit Association Test (IAT), are characterized by:`, ch:[`Being fully consciously accessible and always consistent with explicit (self-reported) attitudes`,`Being automatic, often unconscious associations that may differ from a person's explicitly stated (conscious) attitudes`,`Having no influence on behavior`,`Being permanently fixed and unchangeable`], ans:1, exp:`Implicit attitudes operate automatically and can diverge from explicit attitudes (which are subject to social desirability and conscious control). Implicit attitudes can predict subtle behaviors (e.g., nonverbal cues) even when explicit attitudes predict more deliberate, controlled behaviors.` },
      { q:`A two-sided persuasive message (presenting both the favored position and acknowledging counterarguments) is generally more effective than a one-sided message when the audience is:`, ch:[`Already in agreement with the message and unlikely to hear counterarguments elsewhere`,`Initially opposed or likely to be exposed to counterarguments, and is relatively well-informed`,`Composed of children with no prior knowledge`,`Completely uninterested in the topic`], ans:1, exp:`Two-sided messages can "inoculate" the audience against counterarguments and enhance perceived credibility, making them more effective for skeptical, informed, or initially opposed audiences. One-sided messages can be effective for audiences already favorable and unlikely to encounter opposing views.` },
      { q:`Reciprocity, as a principle of persuasion (Cialdini), refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency to dislike people who do favors for us`,`The social obligation people feel to return favors, gifts, or concessions, which can be leveraged to gain compliance`,`The avoidance of any social exchange`,`A bias toward agreeing with authority figures only`], ans:1, exp:`Reciprocity norm: receiving something (even a small unsolicited gift) creates a felt obligation to give something back, which marketers and fundraisers exploit (e.g., free address labels included with donation requests).` },
      { q:`Attitudes formed through direct personal experience tend to be:`, ch:[`Weaker and less predictive of behavior than attitudes formed through hearsay`,`Stronger, more accessible, and more predictive of subsequent behavior than attitudes formed indirectly`,`Identical in strength to attitudes formed by mere exposure to advertising`,`Always negative`], ans:1, exp:`Direct experience provides more, and more vivid, information, making the resulting attitude more confidently held, more easily retrieved from memory, and a better predictor of behavior compared to attitudes formed via secondhand information.` },
      { q:`Why might fear appeals (messages emphasizing negative consequences, e.g., anti-smoking ads) sometimes fail to change behavior despite successfully increasing fear?`, ch:[`Fear appeals always increase behavior change proportionally to fear level with no exceptions`,`If the fear is too intense without a clear, feasible action to reduce the threat (efficacy), people may engage in defensive avoidance or denial rather than behavior change`,`Fear has no relationship to persuasion`,`Fear appeals only work on children`], ans:1, exp:`The Extended Parallel Process Model: fear appeals are effective only when paired with a sense of self-efficacy and response efficacy (a believable, feasible way to reduce the threat). Without efficacy, high fear can trigger defensive avoidance, denial, or reactance instead of the intended behavior change.` },
      { q:`Which factor is most associated with resistance to persuasion via "inoculation theory"?`, ch:[`Avoiding any exposure to counterarguments`,`Pre-exposing individuals to weakened versions of counterarguments along with refutations, building "resistance" similar to a vaccine`,`Repeating the same message with no variation`,`Increasing message length only`], ans:1, exp:`Inoculation theory (McGuire): exposing people to a weak version of an opposing argument, along with refutation, helps them develop counterarguments and resist stronger persuasive attacks later ŌĆö analogous to vaccination exposing the immune system to a weakened pathogen.` },
      { q:`A health campaign that uses a well-liked celebrity to promote a vaccine, without providing detailed scientific information, is primarily relying on:`, ch:[`The central route to persuasion`,`The peripheral route to persuasion via a likability/credibility heuristic`,`Inoculation theory`,`Cognitive dissonance reduction`], ans:1, exp:`Using a celebrity endorsement without substantive argument content relies on a peripheral cue (liking/credibility of the source) rather than engaging the audience in careful evaluation of evidence ŌĆö characteristic of the peripheral route.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps17`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Group Dynamics`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Social loafing refers to the tendency for individuals to:`, ch:[`Work harder when part of a group than when working alone`,`Exert less individual effort when working in a group than when working alone, especially when individual contributions cannot be evaluated`,`Always perform identically whether alone or in a group`,`Refuse to participate in any group activity`], ans:1, exp:`Social loafing (Latan├®, Williams, Harkins): occurs when individual effort is "lost in the crowd" ŌĆö accountability decreases as group size increases. Reduced when: individual contributions are identifiable, the task is meaningful/personally relevant, or group cohesion is high.` },
      { q:`Deindividuation refers to:`, ch:[`Increased self-awareness and personal accountability in a crowd`,`The loss of individual identity and self-restraint that can occur in group settings (e.g., crowds, anonymity), potentially leading to impulsive or deviant behavior`,`The process of forming a unique personal identity separate from any group`,`A therapeutic technique for group counseling`], ans:1, exp:`Deindividuation (Zimbardo): anonymity, diffusion of responsibility, and group immersion reduce self-awareness and the influence of personal norms, sometimes resulting in behavior that violates the individual's typical standards (e.g., mob violence, online disinhibition).` },
      { q:`Group polarization describes the phenomenon in which:`, ch:[`Group discussion tends to moderate individuals' initial opinions toward a neutral middle ground`,`Group discussion tends to strengthen the average inclination of group members, pushing the group toward a more extreme position than individuals initially held`,`Groups always reach the opposite conclusion from what individuals initially favored`,`Group discussion has no effect on individual opinions`], ans:1, exp:`Group polarization: discussion among like-minded individuals tends to amplify the initial leaning of the group (risky groups become riskier, cautious groups become more cautious). Mechanisms include exposure to additional persuasive arguments supporting the dominant view and social comparison (wanting to be seen as holding the "correct," often more extreme, position).` },
      { q:`A "social trap" in group dynamics refers to a situation where:`, ch:[`Individuals pursuing their own short-term self-interest create a worse outcome for the group as a whole over the long term (e.g., the tragedy of the commons)`,`Groups always act in the collective best interest automatically`,`There is no conflict between individual and group interests`,`Groups dissolve immediately upon formation`], ans:0, exp:`Social traps (e.g., tragedy of the commons, prisoner's dilemma applied to groups): individually rational, self-interested choices lead to collectively irrational/harmful outcomes (e.g., overfishing a shared resource, pollution, arms races). Resolving social traps often requires regulation, communication, or changing incentive structures.` },
      { q:`In-group bias (or in-group favoritism) refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Treat out-group members more favorably than in-group members`,`Favor members of one's own group over members of an out-group, even when group membership is based on arbitrary or trivial criteria`,`Have no preference between in-group and out-group members`,`Only occur in groups based on race or ethnicity`], ans:1, exp:`Minimal group paradigm studies (Tajfel) showed in-group bias emerges even when groups are formed based on trivial criteria (e.g., coin flip, preference for an artist's paintings) ŌĆö suggesting that mere categorization into groups is sufficient to produce favoritism.` },
      { q:`The Robbers Cave experiment demonstrated that intergroup conflict could be reduced through:`, ch:[`Increasing competition between groups`,`Introducing superordinate goals ŌĆö goals that require cooperation between groups to achieve, which neither group could achieve alone`,`Complete physical separation of the groups permanently`,`Punishing both groups equally`], ans:1, exp:`Sherif's Robbers Cave experiment: competition between two groups of boys created intergroup hostility. Mere contact did not reduce conflict, but introducing superordinate goals (tasks requiring intergroup cooperation, like fixing a shared water supply) significantly reduced hostility and fostered cooperation.` },
      { q:`Group cohesion generally has which effect on group performance and groupthink risk?`, ch:[`Increases performance on all tasks and eliminates risk of groupthink`,`Can improve coordination and satisfaction, but very high cohesion combined with other factors (isolation, directive leadership) increases the risk of groupthink`,`Always decreases group performance`,`Has no relationship to groupthink`], ans:1, exp:`Cohesion is generally beneficial for morale and coordination, but Janis identified high cohesion (combined with insulation from outside opinion, directive leadership, and high stress) as a key antecedent of groupthink, where the desire for consensus overrides realistic appraisal of alternatives.` },
      { q:`Status hierarchies within groups tend to form based on:`, ch:[`Random assignment with no consistent patterns`,`Perceived competence, dominance, and contribution to group goals, often emerging quickly even in newly formed groups`,`Physical height alone in all cultures`,`Alphabetical order of names`], ans:1, exp:`Status hierarchies (pecking orders) tend to emerge rapidly in groups based on perceived expertise, dominance behaviors, and resource control ŌĆö these hierarchies influence communication patterns, influence, and decision-making power within the group.` },
      { q:`Risky shift, an early term related to group polarization, was originally observed when:`, ch:[`Groups consistently made more cautious decisions than individuals`,`Groups made riskier decisions than the average of individual members' initial recommendations`,`Group decisions were identical to individual decisions`,`Groups refused to make any decision`], ans:1, exp:`Early research found groups sometimes shifted toward riskier decisions than individuals alone ŌĆö later understood as one manifestation of the broader phenomenon of group polarization (groups can also shift toward more cautious positions, depending on the initial leaning).` },
      { q:`A leader who focuses primarily on completing tasks and achieving goals, sometimes at the expense of group member relationships, exhibits:`, ch:[`Relationship-oriented (socioemotional) leadership`,`Task-oriented leadership`,`Laissez-faire leadership`,`No leadership style at all`], ans:1, exp:`Task-oriented leaders prioritize structuring activities, setting deadlines, and achieving objectives. Relationship-oriented (socioemotional) leaders prioritize group harmony, morale, and member satisfaction. Effective leadership often requires balancing both, depending on the situation (contingency theories of leadership).` },
      { q:`Why might diverse groups (in terms of perspectives, expertise, or backgrounds) sometimes outperform homogeneous groups on complex problem-solving tasks, despite potentially experiencing more conflict?`, ch:[`Diversity has no effect on group problem-solving`,`A wider range of perspectives and information can reduce groupthink and bring more varied approaches to a problem, though it may require more effort to manage communication and integration`,`Homogeneous groups always outperform diverse groups on every task`,`Diverse groups never experience any conflict`], ans:1, exp:`Diversity can introduce a broader range of information, perspectives, and critical evaluation (counteracting groupthink), which can enhance creative and complex problem-solving ŌĆö though it may also increase process losses (communication difficulties, conflict) that need to be managed.` },
      { q:`The concept of "social identity" (Tajfel & Turner) proposes that:`, ch:[`Self-concept is based solely on individual traits, with no reference to group memberships`,`Part of an individual's self-concept derives from perceived membership in social groups, along with the emotional significance attached to that membership`,`Group memberships have no effect on self-esteem`,`Social identity is fixed at birth and cannot change`], ans:1, exp:`Social identity theory: people categorize themselves and others into groups (social categorization), derive part of their self-esteem from group membership (social identification), and compare their group favorably to other groups (social comparison) ŌĆö contributing to in-group bias and intergroup conflict.` },
      { q:`Brainstorming in groups, despite its popularity, often results in:`, ch:[`More and higher-quality ideas than the same number of individuals working alone (nominal groups)`,`Fewer ideas than the equivalent number of individuals working alone, due to production blocking, evaluation apprehension, and social loafing`,`No difference in idea generation compared to individuals`,`Complete elimination of any creative output`], ans:1, exp:`Research consistently shows that "nominal groups" (individuals brainstorming separately, then pooling ideas) typically generate more and often higher-quality ideas than interactive groups, due to production blocking (one person talking at a time), evaluation apprehension, and social loafing in interactive settings.` },
      { q:`Why might a physician working on a multidisciplinary care team intentionally seek out dissenting opinions before finalizing a treatment plan?`, ch:[`To slow down decision-making unnecessarily with no benefit`,`To reduce the risk of groupthink and ensure that alternative diagnoses, risks, or treatment options are critically considered before committing to a plan`,`Because dissent always means the original plan was wrong`,`Because team members should never disagree with each other`], ans:1, exp:`Actively soliciting dissenting views and alternative perspectives is a recognized strategy for preventing groupthink, helping ensure that critical issues, risks, and alternatives are considered rather than prematurely converging on a single option due to social pressure for consensus.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps18`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Socialization & Institutions`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Socialization refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`Individuals are biologically determined to behave in certain ways with no environmental influence`,`Individuals learn and internalize the norms, values, beliefs, and behaviors appropriate to their society and social roles`,`People become isolated from social groups`,`Genetic mutations are passed between generations`], ans:1, exp:`Socialization is a lifelong process through which individuals learn culturally appropriate attitudes, values, and behaviors via interactions with family, peers, education, media, and other social institutions. It includes both primary socialization (childhood, within the family) and secondary socialization (later life, schools, workplaces).` },
      { q:`Agents of socialization include all of the following EXCEPT:`, ch:[`Family`,`Peer groups`,`Mass media`,`An individual's genetic code`], ans:3, exp:`Agents of socialization are the social institutions and groups (family, peers, schools, media, religion, workplace) through which individuals learn social norms and roles. Genetics is a biological factor, not a socializing agent, though gene-environment interactions can influence developmental outcomes.` },
      { q:`A "total institution," as described by Erving Goffman, is characterized by:`, ch:[`A setting where individuals retain full autonomy and connection to outside society`,`A place where individuals are cut off from wider society and live under the control of an administering authority for an extended period (e.g., prisons, psychiatric hospitals, military barracks)`,`Any institution that provides voluntary, short-term services`,`A type of family structure`], ans:1, exp:`Goffman's "total institutions" involve all aspects of life (sleeping, working, recreation) occurring in the same place under a single authority, with batch treatment of inmates/residents and a sharp break from the outside world ŌĆö examples include prisons, long-term psychiatric hospitals, monasteries, and military boot camps.` },
      { q:`Resocialization refers to the process of:`, ch:[`Learning norms for the first time as an infant`,`Discarding former behavior patterns and accepting new ones as part of a transition in one's life, often associated with entry into a total institution`,`Refusing to adopt any social norms`,`A purely biological maturation process`], ans:1, exp:`Resocialization involves a deliberate, often intense, process of unlearning old norms/values and adopting new ones ŌĆö common in total institutions (e.g., military basic training, religious conversion, recovery programs) where degradation ceremonies may strip individuals of prior identity markers before instilling new ones.` },
      { q:`The "looking-glass self" concept, developed by Charles Cooley, proposes that:`, ch:[`Self-concept develops independently of social interaction`,`A person's self-concept is shaped by how they imagine they appear to others, how they imagine others judge that appearance, and the resulting feelings about themselves`,`People can directly perceive others' thoughts about them with perfect accuracy`,`Self-concept is fixed at birth and never changes`], ans:1, exp:`Cooley's looking-glass self describes a three-step process: (1) we imagine how we appear to others, (2) we imagine their judgment of that appearance, (3) we develop feelings (pride, shame) about ourselves based on these imagined judgments ŌĆö illustrating that self-concept is fundamentally social.` },
      { q:`According to George Herbert Mead's theory of self-development, "role-taking" refers to:`, ch:[`Memorizing scripts for theatrical performance`,`The ability to mentally assume the perspective of another person, understanding how they view a situation`,`Refusing to interact with others`,`A purely biological reflex present from birth`], ans:1, exp:`Mead proposed that the self develops through stages of role-taking: the preparatory stage (imitation), the play stage (taking on roles of "significant others" one at a time), and the game stage (understanding multiple roles simultaneously and the "generalized other" ŌĆö internalized societal expectations).` },
      { q:`The "generalized other," in Mead's framework, refers to:`, ch:[`A specific significant individual, like a parent`,`The internalized attitudes, expectations, and viewpoints of society as a whole, which a person uses to guide their own behavior`,`A stranger encountered briefly`,`An imaginary friend from childhood`], ans:1, exp:`The generalized other represents the internalized sense of societal norms and expectations that develops during the "game stage" of Mead's theory ŌĆö allowing individuals to evaluate their own behavior from the perspective of society broadly, not just specific individuals.` },
      { q:`Anticipatory socialization refers to:`, ch:[`Socialization that occurs only after a role transition has been completed`,`The process of preparing for and adopting the norms, values, and behaviors of a role or status one expects to occupy in the future`,`A type of socialization that only occurs in childhood`,`Refusal to adapt to any future role`], ans:1, exp:`Anticipatory socialization involves practicing/rehearsing for future roles before formally occupying them ŌĆö e.g., a medical student adopting professional behaviors and attire in anticipation of becoming a physician, easing the eventual role transition.` },
      { q:`Social institutions such as the family, education, religion, economy, and government are best understood as:`, ch:[`Random, unrelated social phenomena`,`Established, organized systems of social behavior with a recognized purpose, that work together to meet society's basic needs and maintain social order`,`Temporary arrangements that have no influence on individual behavior`,`Exclusively biological structures`], ans:1, exp:`Social institutions are relatively stable patterns of social behavior organized around particular purposes (reproduction and care in family, transmission of knowledge in education, etc.). Functionalist theory views institutions as interdependent parts contributing to social stability; conflict theory emphasizes how institutions can perpetuate inequality.` },
      { q:`The hidden curriculum in education refers to:`, ch:[`The official, stated academic content of school curricula`,`The implicit lessons about norms, values, and expected behaviors (e.g., punctuality, respect for authority, competition) that schools teach alongside formal academic content`,`Curriculum that is kept secret from teachers`,`A curriculum used only in private schools`], ans:1, exp:`The hidden curriculum encompasses unstated norms and values transmitted through the schooling process ŌĆö such as obedience to authority, time management, and conformity ŌĆö which prepare students for societal roles (e.g., future workplace expectations) beyond explicit academic content.` },
      { q:`From a conflict theory perspective, social institutions like education may serve to:`, ch:[`Equally benefit all social classes with no differential outcomes`,`Reproduce and legitimize existing social inequalities, by providing unequal resources and opportunities that tend to perpetuate the advantages of higher socioeconomic groups`,`Eliminate all social stratification`,`Have no relationship to social class`], ans:1, exp:`Conflict theorists argue that institutions like education can perpetuate inequality through unequal funding, tracking systems, and cultural capital advantages that favor already-advantaged groups, thereby reproducing the existing class structure across generations rather than serving as a pure "equalizer."` },
      { q:`Gender role socialization refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`Biological sex determines behavior with no social influence`,`Individuals learn society's expectations for behaviors, attitudes, and roles considered appropriate for their gender, often beginning in early childhood through family, media, and peer interactions`,`All societies have identical gender roles`,`Gender roles are fixed and never change across history or cultures`], ans:1, exp:`Gender role socialization occurs through differential treatment (e.g., toy choices, language used, expectations communicated by parents/teachers/media) and varies across cultures and historical periods, demonstrating that many gender-associated behaviors are socially constructed rather than purely biologically determined.` },
      { q:`A medical student observing experienced physicians and gradually adopting their communication styles, dress, and professional norms before officially becoming a doctor is undergoing:`, ch:[`Resocialization within a total institution`,`Anticipatory socialization into the medical profession`,`Deviance amplification`,`Cognitive dissonance reduction`], ans:1, exp:`This represents anticipatory socialization ŌĆö the medical student is preparing for and rehearsing the professional role they expect to formally occupy, which can ease the eventual transition into full professional practice (sometimes called "professional socialization").` },
      { q:`Why might entering a "total institution" (e.g., a long-term psychiatric facility) potentially have negative effects on a person's prior social identity?`, ch:[`Because total institutions have no rules or structure`,`Because the loss of personal possessions, privacy, and autonomy, combined with standardized routines and "mortification" processes, can strip away markers of individual identity and impose a new institutional identity`,`Because total institutions always improve self-esteem immediately`,`Because total institutions are identical to one's home environment`], ans:1, exp:`Goffman described "mortification of self" processes in total institutions ŌĆö including loss of name/possessions/privacy, imposition of standardized routines, and surveillance ŌĆö which can erode a person's prior self-concept and replace it with an institutionally defined identity, with potential long-term psychological effects.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps19`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Culture, Norms & Deviance`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Cultural relativism refers to the perspective that:`, ch:[`One's own culture's standards should be used to judge all other cultures`,`A culture's beliefs and practices should be understood and evaluated within the context of that culture itself, rather than by the standards of another culture`,`All cultures are identical`,`Cultural practices have no effect on individual behavior`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural relativism involves understanding practices, beliefs, and values within their own cultural context, avoiding the imposition of one culture's standards onto another. Contrasted with ethnocentrism ŌĆö judging other cultures by the standards of one's own culture (often viewing one's own as superior).` },
      { q:`Ethnocentrism refers to:`, ch:[`Evaluating other cultures using the standards and values of one's own culture, often viewing one's own culture as superior`,`Complete acceptance of all cultural practices without judgment`,`A type of mental disorder`,`The scientific study of different cultures without bias`], ans:0, exp:`Ethnocentrism involves judging other cultures based on the values and standards of one's own culture, often leading to the perception that one's own culture's practices are "normal" or "correct" and others' practices are inferior or strange.` },
      { q:`Mores (as distinct from folkways) refer to:`, ch:[`Norms that, if violated, generally result in mild informal sanctions (e.g., disapproving looks)`,`Norms considered essential to core societal values, whose violation often results in severe sanctions, including legal punishment`,`A type of language dialect`,`Norms that apply only to children`], ans:1, exp:`Mores are norms with strong moral significance attached to fundamental societal values (e.g., prohibitions against murder, incest); violations are typically met with severe condemnation or legal punishment. Folkways are everyday customs/conventions (e.g., table manners, dress norms) whose violation results in milder informal sanctions.` },
      { q:`According to ├ēmile Durkheim, deviance serves which function for society?`, ch:[`Deviance is purely destructive and serves no social function`,`Deviance can clarify and reinforce social norms by defining the boundaries of acceptable behavior, and can sometimes promote social change`,`Deviance always leads to societal collapse`,`Deviance only occurs in societies with no laws`], ans:1, exp:`Durkheim argued deviance is a normal and even functional part of society: reactions to deviance reaffirm shared values/norms (boundary maintenance), can promote social cohesion (uniting people against a perceived violation), and can sometimes act as a catalyst for beneficial social change when norms are challenged.` },
      { q:`Robert Merton's strain theory proposes that deviance arises when:`, ch:[`There is a disjunction between culturally valued goals (e.g., financial success) and the legitimate means available to achieve them`,`Individuals have no goals at all`,`Deviance is purely a result of genetic predisposition`,`Society provides equal access to legitimate means for all`], ans:0, exp:`Strain theory: when culturally approved goals (e.g., wealth, success) are not attainable through legitimate means (education, employment) for some individuals/groups, this strain can lead to deviant adaptations ŌĆö Merton identified modes including conformity, innovation (accepting goals but using illegitimate means), ritualism, retreatism, and rebellion.` },
      { q:`Labeling theory suggests that deviance is:`, ch:[`An inherent quality of certain acts, regardless of social context`,`Not inherent to an act itself, but is created by social definitions and reactions ŌĆö an act becomes "deviant" when it is labeled as such by society`,`Always punished equally regardless of who commits the act`,`Determined solely by an individual's genetic makeup`], ans:1, exp:`Labeling theory (Becker, Lemert) emphasizes that deviance is socially constructed ŌĆö the same act may be labeled deviant in one context but not another, and the application of a "deviant" label (especially by powerful groups/institutions) can shape an individual's self-concept and lead to secondary deviance (further deviant behavior as a result of the label).` },
      { q:`The concept of "secondary deviance" refers to:`, ch:[`The first instance of a deviant act, before any social reaction`,`Subsequent deviant behavior that occurs as a response to being labeled deviant after an initial (primary) deviant act`,`Deviance that is never discovered by others`,`A type of deviance found only in certain professions`], ans:1, exp:`Lemert's distinction: primary deviance is an initial rule-breaking act that may go unnoticed or unlabeled. Secondary deviance occurs when an individual, after being caught and labeled "deviant," begins to internalize this label as part of their identity, potentially leading to a "deviant career" of further rule-breaking.` },
      { q:`Differential association theory (Sutherland) proposes that deviant behavior is learned through:`, ch:[`Spontaneous biological mutation`,`Interaction with others, particularly intimate groups, who transmit definitions favorable or unfavorable toward law violation`,`Watching television exclusively, with no social interaction involved`,`Random chance with no learning process`], ans:1, exp:`Differential association theory: criminal/deviant behavior is learned through social interaction, particularly within intimate personal groups, including techniques for committing deviance and attitudes/rationalizations favorable to violating norms ŌĆö the more frequent, intense, and longer-lasting such associations, the greater the influence.` },
      { q:`The phrase "deviance is relative" emphasizes that:`, ch:[`A behavior considered deviant in one society or time period may be considered acceptable in another society or time period`,`Deviance only applies to relatives of the deviant individual`,`All societies define deviance identically`,`Deviance has a fixed, universal definition across all cultures and eras`], ans:0, exp:`What counts as "deviant" varies across cultures, subcultures, and historical periods (e.g., attitudes toward alcohol consumption, divorce, or certain forms of dress have changed dramatically over time and differ across societies) ŌĆö illustrating the socially constructed nature of deviance.` },
      { q:`Formal social control refers to:`, ch:[`Informal disapproval from family and friends`,`Mechanisms of enforcing norms through codified laws and official agents (e.g., police, courts, regulatory agencies)`,`Religious teachings only`,`A type of mental illness`], ans:1, exp:`Formal social control involves official, codified mechanisms (laws, police, courts, prisons, regulatory bodies) for enforcing societal norms, in contrast to informal social control, which relies on unwritten norms enforced through social interactions (e.g., disapproval, ostracism, gossip).` },
      { q:`A subculture is best defined as:`, ch:[`A group that completely rejects all aspects of mainstream culture and lives in total isolation`,`A group within a larger society that shares some distinctive values, norms, or practices that differ from (but generally do not completely reject) the dominant culture`,`A culture that no longer exists`,`The exact same thing as the dominant culture`], ans:1, exp:`Subcultures share certain distinctive elements (language, values, styles, practices) that differentiate them from the broader/dominant culture, while typically still operating within and sharing many norms of that broader society ŌĆö distinguished from "countercultures," which actively oppose dominant societal values.` },
      { q:`A counterculture differs from a subculture primarily in that a counterculture:`, ch:[`Has no distinctive characteristics at all`,`Actively rejects and opposes one or more central values or norms of the dominant culture`,`Is identical to the dominant culture`,`Only exists among elderly populations`], ans:1, exp:`While subcultures coexist with mainstream culture (sharing many of its norms while having some distinct features), countercultures actively challenge and reject central aspects of the dominant culture's values (e.g., 1960s counterculture movements rejecting mainstream materialism and conformity).` },
      { q:`From a medical perspective, the labeling of certain behaviors (e.g., substance use disorders) as "illnesses" rather than purely "moral failings" or "crimes" reflects which broader sociological process?`, ch:[`Demonization`,`Medicalization of deviance ŌĆö redefining behavior previously seen as immoral or criminal as a medical problem requiring treatment`,`Criminalization`,`No change in how deviance is understood`], ans:1, exp:`Medicalization of deviance describes the historical shift in how certain behaviors (e.g., addiction, certain mental health conditions) have come to be framed as medical conditions deserving treatment rather than purely as moral failings or criminal acts deserving punishment ŌĆö with significant implications for how individuals are treated by society and the healthcare/legal systems.` },
      { q:`Why is understanding cultural relativism important for healthcare providers working with patients from diverse backgrounds?`, ch:[`Because providers should impose their own cultural beliefs about health and illness on all patients`,`Because patients' health beliefs and practices may differ from the provider's own cultural framework, and understanding these differences (without automatically judging them as "wrong") can improve communication, trust, and care`,`Because cultural background has no influence on health beliefs or behaviors`,`Because all patients from a given culture behave identically`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural humility/relativism in healthcare involves recognizing that patients' explanatory models of illness, treatment preferences, and health behaviors are shaped by their cultural context ŌĆö approaching these differences with curiosity and respect (rather than ethnocentric judgment) improves the therapeutic relationship and can lead to better health outcomes, while still maintaining ethical and evidence-based standards of care.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps20`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Gender & Sexuality`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`The distinction between "sex" and "gender" in social science is generally understood as:`, ch:[`Sex and gender are interchangeable terms with identical meanings`,`Sex typically refers to biological characteristics (chromosomes, anatomy, hormones), while gender refers to socially constructed roles, behaviors, and identities associated with being male, female, or other genders`,`Gender is purely biological and sex is purely social`,`Neither term has any meaningful definition`], ans:1, exp:`Sex generally denotes biological attributes (e.g., XX/XY chromosomes, reproductive anatomy), while gender refers to the socially and culturally constructed roles, behaviors, expressions, and identities that a society associates with being a man, woman, or other gender ŌĆö gender identity may or may not align with sex assigned at birth.` },
      { q:`Gender identity refers to:`, ch:[`A person's sexual orientation toward others`,`An individual's internal sense of their own gender, which may or may not correspond to their sex assigned at birth`,`The biological sex determined by chromosomes only`,`A classification system used only in legal documents`], ans:1, exp:`Gender identity is one's deeply felt internal sense of being male, female, both, neither, or another gender. It is distinct from sexual orientation (which describes attraction to others) and from sex assigned at birth (based on anatomy/chromosomes at birth).` },
      { q:`Transgender is a term used to describe individuals whose:`, ch:[`Gender identity differs from the sex they were assigned at birth`,`Sexual orientation is exclusively toward the same sex`,`Biological sex characteristics are ambiguous`,`Gender identity is identical to their sex assigned at birth`], ans:0, exp:`Transgender describes people whose gender identity does not align with their sex assigned at birth. This is distinct from sexual orientation (a transgender person can be heterosexual, homosexual, bisexual, etc.) and from intersex (a term for variations in sex characteristics that don't fit typical binary definitions).` },
      { q:`Intersex refers to individuals who:`, ch:[`Identify with a gender different from their assigned sex`,`Are born with reproductive or sexual anatomy that does not fit typical binary definitions of male or female bodies`,`Are attracted to multiple genders`,`Have undergone gender-affirming surgery`], ans:1, exp:`Intersex is a term for a range of natural variations in sex characteristics (chromosomal, gonadal, or anatomical) that do not fit typical binary notions of male or female bodies ŌĆö it is a description of biological/physical variation, distinct from gender identity or sexual orientation.` },
      { q:`Sexual orientation refers to:`, ch:[`A person's gender identity`,`The pattern of a person's emotional, romantic, and/or sexual attraction to people of the same and/or different genders`,`A purely chosen lifestyle with no biological component`,`The legal classification of a person's marital status`], ans:1, exp:`Sexual orientation describes enduring patterns of attraction (e.g., heterosexual, homosexual, bisexual, asexual) and is conceptually distinct from gender identity (one's internal sense of gender) and from sex/gender expression (outward presentation).` },
      { q:`Gender expression refers to:`, ch:[`The internal, private sense of one's gender`,`The external presentation of gender through behavior, clothing, hairstyle, voice, and other characteristics, which may or may not conform to societal expectations for a given gender`,`A medical diagnosis`,`A synonym for biological sex`], ans:1, exp:`Gender expression is the outward, observable presentation of gender (e.g., through clothing, mannerisms, name, pronouns) and may align with or differ from societal expectations associated with a person's sex assigned at birth or gender identity.` },
      { q:`Research on gender differences in cognitive abilities (e.g., spatial vs. verbal skills) generally shows that:`, ch:[`Differences between genders are vastly larger than the variation within each gender`,`Average differences between genders on most cognitive measures tend to be small relative to the wide variation within each gender, and many differences have narrowed over time, suggesting significant social/environmental influence`,`Cognitive abilities are entirely fixed by genetics with no environmental influence`,`There are no measurable differences of any kind, ever, between any groups`], ans:1, exp:`While some average differences have been reported in certain studies (e.g., spatial rotation tasks), the overlap between distributions for different genders is substantial, and many gap sizes have changed over time and across cultures ŌĆö pointing to significant roles for socialization, education access, stereotype threat, and sociocultural factors alongside any biological contributions.` },
      { q:`Heteronormativity refers to:`, ch:[`The belief that heterosexuality is the only normal or default sexual orientation, and that gender aligns in a binary way with assigned sex ŌĆö often embedded in social institutions and norms`,`A medical condition affecting hormone levels`,`A term describing all forms of sexual orientation equally`,`A type of gender identity`], ans:0, exp:`Heteronormativity describes the often-unstated assumption (embedded in language, institutions, media, and policy) that heterosexuality and a binary alignment between sex and gender are the default or "normal" state, which can marginalize LGBTQ+ individuals and shape disparities in areas including healthcare access and quality.` },
      { q:`Disparities in healthcare access and quality experienced by transgender individuals are most often attributed to:`, ch:[`Inherent biological differences that cannot be addressed by healthcare systems`,`A combination of factors including provider lack of training, discrimination, stigma, insurance coverage gaps, and minority stress`,`A lack of any need for healthcare among transgender populations`,`Equal treatment with no disparities of any kind`], ans:1, exp:`Health disparities affecting transgender individuals stem from systemic and social factors ŌĆö including provider knowledge gaps about transgender health needs, experiences of discrimination within healthcare settings (leading some to avoid care), insurance/coverage barriers for gender-affirming care, and the cumulative effects of minority stress on physical and mental health.` },
      { q:`The "minority stress" model proposes that health disparities experienced by sexual and gender minorities are largely due to:`, ch:[`Genetic predispositions unique to minority groups`,`Chronic, unique stressors related to stigma, prejudice, and discrimination experienced by minority group members, in addition to general life stressors experienced by everyone`,`A complete absence of any stress in minority populations`,`Personal choices unrelated to social context`], ans:1, exp:`Minority stress theory posits that sexual and gender minorities experience excess stress (from stigma, discrimination, internalized stigma, expectation of rejection, and concealment) on top of general life stressors, contributing to documented disparities in mental and physical health outcomes.` },
      { q:`A physician taking a sexual history that asks about specific behaviors (rather than assuming based on a patient's stated identity) reflects which best practice?`, ch:[`Assuming all patients are heterosexual unless stated otherwise`,`Recognizing that sexual identity, attraction, and behavior do not always align, so behavior-based questions are important for accurately assessing risk and providing appropriate care`,`Avoiding any discussion of sexual history`,`Only asking about sexual history for patients who appear to be LGBTQ+`], ans:1, exp:`Identity, attraction, and behavior are related but distinct dimensions ŌĆö a person's stated identity may not predict their sexual behaviors (relevant for STI risk assessment, contraception counseling, etc.), so taking a behavior-based history with all patients (using non-judgmental, open-ended questions) provides more accurate and clinically useful information.` },
      { q:`Gender dysphoria, as defined in the DSM-5, refers to:`, ch:[`A fixed personality trait present in all transgender individuals with no variation`,`Clinically significant distress or impairment related to an incongruence between one's experienced/expressed gender and assigned sex`,`A term synonymous with "transgender" with no additional clinical meaning`,`A diagnosis applied to anyone who does not conform to traditional gender roles`], ans:1, exp:`Gender dysphoria specifically refers to the distress that may result from incongruence between gender identity and sex assigned at birth ŌĆö not all transgender individuals experience clinically significant dysphoria, and the diagnosis exists to facilitate access to appropriate care (e.g., gender-affirming treatment) for those who experience distress.` },
      { q:`Cross-cultural research on gender roles demonstrates that:`, ch:[`Gender roles are identical across all cultures and historical periods, reflecting a universal biological template`,`Gender roles, while shaped by some biological factors, vary considerably across cultures and historical periods, indicating substantial social construction`,`Only Western cultures have any concept of gender roles`,`Gender roles have never changed throughout human history`], ans:1, exp:`Anthropological and sociological research documents wide cross-cultural variation in gender roles, including societies with more than two recognized genders (e.g., some Indigenous cultures' "two-spirit" identities), and roles assigned to genders for tasks like agriculture, caregiving, or leadership vary considerably ŌĆö supporting the social construction of many gender role expectations.` },
      { q:`Why is it considered best practice for healthcare forms and intake processes to include options beyond a binary male/female for gender identity?`, ch:[`Because binary options are always sufficient and inclusive for all patients`,`Because some patients identify outside the male/female binary (e.g., non-binary, genderqueer), and accurately capturing this information can improve communication, ensure appropriate care, and reduce experiences of erasure or discomfort that might otherwise deter patients from seeking care`,`Because non-binary identities do not exist`,`Because it is required only in certain countries with no clinical relevance`], ans:1, exp:`Inclusive intake forms (e.g., separate fields for sex assigned at birth, gender identity, and pronouns, with non-binary options) help ensure accurate documentation relevant to care (e.g., organ inventory for screening purposes) while signaling a welcoming environment, which research links to improved patient comfort, trust, and willingness to seek care.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps21`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Race, Ethnicity & Discrimination`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Race is best understood, from a sociological perspective, as:`, ch:[`A purely biological category with clear, discrete genetic boundaries between groups`,`A socially constructed category, based on perceived physical differences, that has been used to classify groups and that carries significant social, economic, and political consequences despite lacking a clear genetic basis for discrete categories`,`A term identical in meaning to "ethnicity"`,`A category with no social significance whatsoever`], ans:1, exp:`While humans do exhibit genetic variation, this variation does not map onto discrete "racial" categories ŌĆö there is more genetic variation within so-called racial groups than between them. Race is therefore understood as a socially constructed category that nonetheless has profound real-world consequences due to how societies have organized power, resources, and discrimination around it.` },
      { q:`Ethnicity differs from race primarily in that ethnicity is based on:`, ch:[`Perceived physical/biological characteristics only`,`Shared cultural characteristics such as language, ancestry, religion, traditions, or national origin`,`Identical criteria as race with no distinction`,`Legal citizenship status only`], ans:1, exp:`Ethnicity refers to shared cultural heritage, including language, customs, religion, and ancestry/national origin, whereas race has historically been (mis)understood as based on physical/biological traits. An individual can identify with a particular ethnicity while their racial categorization (often externally imposed) may differ.` },
      { q:`Prejudice refers to:`, ch:[`Discriminatory behavior or actions toward a group`,`A preconceived (often negative) attitude or feeling toward an individual or group, typically based on group membership, that may or may not result in observable behavior`,`A type of mental illness`,`A legal classification`], ans:1, exp:`Prejudice is an attitude (cognitive/affective) ŌĆö a preconceived judgment, often negative, toward members of a particular group. Discrimination, by contrast, refers to actual differential (often unfair) treatment or behavior based on group membership; prejudice and discrimination can occur independently of each other.` },
      { q:`Institutional (or systemic) discrimination refers to:`, ch:[`Discrimination perpetrated only by individuals acting alone, with no broader pattern`,`Discriminatory practices and policies embedded within the operations of social institutions (e.g., laws, organizational policies, practices) that produce unequal outcomes for certain groups, regardless of the individual intentions of people within those institutions`,`A term with no practical application`,`Discrimination that has been completely eliminated in modern societies`], ans:1, exp:`Institutional discrimination operates through policies, procedures, and practices embedded in organizations and social structures (e.g., redlining in housing, biased algorithms, unequal school funding formulas) that produce disparate outcomes for certain groups, even without overt individual prejudice by those carrying out the policies.` },
      { q:`Implicit bias refers to:`, ch:[`Conscious, deliberate prejudice that a person openly acknowledges`,`Unconscious attitudes or stereotypes that affect understanding, actions, and decisions, often operating outside of a person's awareness or conscious control`,`A type of formal policy`,`A bias that only affects members of majority groups`], ans:1, exp:`Implicit biases are automatic, unconscious associations (e.g., between race and competence, or gender and occupation) that can influence behavior and decision-making even among individuals who consciously and explicitly reject prejudiced beliefs ŌĆö relevant to healthcare disparities (e.g., differences in pain assessment/treatment across racial groups).` },
      { q:`Health disparities related to race and ethnicity in the United States are best explained by:`, ch:[`Purely genetic differences between racial groups, with no role for social factors`,`A complex interplay of factors including socioeconomic status, access to care, residential segregation, environmental exposures, chronic stress from discrimination, and implicit bias in healthcare delivery`,`Differences in personal motivation to seek healthcare only`,`No measurable disparities exist`], ans:1, exp:`Racial/ethnic health disparities arise from a combination of structural factors (poverty, segregation, unequal access to quality care/insurance, environmental hazards concentrated in certain neighborhoods), the cumulative physiological effects of chronic stress from discrimination ("weathering" hypothesis), and biases within healthcare systems ŌĆö not from inherent biological differences between socially defined racial groups.` },
      { q:`The "weathering hypothesis" proposes that:`, ch:[`Chronic exposure to social, economic, and political marginalization can lead to accelerated biological aging and poorer health outcomes among marginalized groups, particularly affecting outcomes like maternal/infant health`,`Weather conditions directly cause racial health disparities`,`Health outcomes are unrelated to social experiences`,`All racial groups age at identical rates regardless of social context`], ans:0, exp:`Geronimus's weathering hypothesis suggests that the cumulative physiological burden of chronic stress from social and economic adversity (including racism) leads to earlier onset of age-related health conditions and contributes to disparities such as higher rates of adverse birth outcomes among Black women across socioeconomic levels.` },
      { q:`A "model minority" stereotype refers to:`, ch:[`A stereotype suggesting a minority group is uniformly successful, hardworking, and free of struggles, which can mask within-group diversity and obscure disparities or barriers faced by subgroups`,`A scientifically validated description of a group's characteristics`,`A term with entirely positive consequences and no drawbacks`,`A classification used only in legal contexts`], ans:0, exp:`The "model minority" stereotype, often applied to certain Asian American subgroups, can obscure significant economic, educational, and health disparities among different ethnic subgroups within that broader category, and can also be used to dismiss the experiences of other minority groups or to deny the existence of discrimination faced by the "model" group itself.` },
      { q:`Acculturation refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`A person completely abandons their original cultural identity with no other options`,`Individuals or groups from one culture adopt the attitudes, values, customs, beliefs, and behaviors of another culture, which can occur to varying degrees and in various patterns (e.g., assimilation, integration, separation, marginalization)`,`Cultures remain completely static and unchanging`,`Only majority groups undergo cultural change`], ans:1, exp:`Acculturation describes the cultural and psychological changes that occur as a result of contact between different cultural groups, and can take various forms (per Berry's model): assimilation (adopting the new culture, abandoning the old), integration/biculturalism (maintaining aspects of both), separation (maintaining original culture, rejecting the new), or marginalization (rejecting both).` },
      { q:`Research on the "Hispanic/Latino health paradox" refers to the observation that:`, ch:[`Hispanic/Latino populations in the U.S. have uniformly worse health outcomes than other groups across all measures`,`Despite often having lower average socioeconomic status (a known risk factor for poor health), some Hispanic/Latino populations show certain health outcomes (e.g., life expectancy, infant mortality) that are comparable to or better than those of non-Hispanic White populations ŌĆö a finding that has prompted research into protective cultural and social factors`,`Health outcomes are identical across all demographic groups`,`The paradox has been definitively explained by a single genetic factor`], ans:1, exp:`The Hispanic/Latino health paradox refers to the unexpected finding (given socioeconomic disadvantage) of relatively favorable outcomes on certain health measures for some Hispanic/Latino populations ŌĆö proposed explanations include strong social/family support networks, lower smoking rates in some subgroups, and the "healthy immigrant effect" (selection of healthier individuals for immigration), though the paradox does not hold uniformly across all subgroups or health measures.` },
      { q:`Why might using race as a variable in clinical algorithms (e.g., for kidney function estimation) be controversial?`, ch:[`Because race has no relevance to any clinical context whatsoever`,`Because such algorithms may be based on flawed assumptions about biological differences between racial groups, potentially leading to disparities in diagnosis, treatment eligibility, or referral for care`,`Because race-based algorithms always improve outcomes equally for all groups`,`Because using any demographic variable in medicine is illegal`], ans:1, exp:`Some clinical algorithms historically incorporated race-based "corrections" (e.g., for eGFR calculations) based on assumptions that may not reflect actual biological differences, and which could result in systematically different (sometimes delayed) diagnosis or treatment recommendations for Black patients ŌĆö leading many medical organizations to revise or remove race-based adjustments from such tools.` },
      { q:`Microaggressions refer to:`, ch:[`Overt, intentional acts of severe violence based on group membership`,`Brief, everyday verbal, behavioral, or environmental indignities ŌĆö whether intentional or unintentional ŌĆö that communicate hostile, derogatory, or negative messages toward members of marginalized groups`,`Compliments that have no negative effect on the recipient`,`A term that applies only to interactions between strangers`], ans:1, exp:`Microaggressions are subtle (often unintentional) slights or dismissive comments/actions (e.g., "Where are you really from?") that, while individually may seem minor, can have a cumulative negative impact on the well-being of individuals from marginalized groups, including in healthcare settings.` },
      { q:`The term "intersectionality" (Crenshaw) refers to the idea that:`, ch:[`Different forms of social categorization (e.g., race, gender, class, sexual orientation) operate independently and additively with no interaction`,`Individuals can experience overlapping and interdependent systems of disadvantage or discrimination based on multiple aspects of their identity (e.g., race, gender, class) simultaneously, producing unique experiences not captured by considering each category in isolation`,`Only one aspect of identity can be relevant to a person's experience at a time`,`Intersectionality applies only to legal contexts`], ans:1, exp:`Intersectionality emphasizes that systems of oppression/privilege (based on race, gender, class, sexual orientation, disability, etc.) intersect and interact, creating distinct experiences ŌĆö for example, the experiences of a Black woman cannot be fully understood by simply combining the experiences of "Black people" and "women" as separate, additive categories.` },
      { q:`A culturally competent (or culturally humble) healthcare provider would best demonstrate this by:`, ch:[`Assuming all patients of a particular ethnic background hold identical beliefs and practices`,`Approaching each patient as an individual, asking about their specific beliefs, preferences, and circumstances, while being aware of how systemic factors and broad cultural patterns might be relevant, without over-generalizing`,`Avoiding any discussion of cultural background with patients`,`Applying a fixed checklist of "cultural facts" about each ethnic group to every patient from that group`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural humility involves an ongoing process of self-reflection and learning, recognizing the limits of one's knowledge about any individual patient's beliefs (avoiding stereotyping based on group membership), while also being aware of how systemic and structural factors (e.g., discrimination, access barriers) might be relevant to a patient's health and care preferences.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps22`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Aging & Gerontology`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Crystallized intelligence, which tends to remain stable or even increase with age, refers to:`, ch:[`The ability to reason quickly with novel, abstract problems`,`Accumulated knowledge, vocabulary, and skills acquired through education and experience`,`Raw processing speed`,`Short-term memory capacity only`], ans:1, exp:`Crystallized intelligence reflects accumulated facts, knowledge, and verbal skills built up over a lifetime, and tends to remain stable or even improve into older adulthood. In contrast, fluid intelligence ŌĆö the capacity for abstract reasoning and processing novel information quickly ŌĆö tends to decline somewhat with age.` },
      { q:`Fluid intelligence, in contrast to crystallized intelligence, tends to:`, ch:[`Increase steadily throughout the entire lifespan with no decline`,`Peak in early adulthood and gradually decline with advancing age`,`Remain completely unchanged from childhood to old age`,`Be unrelated to any cognitive processes`], ans:1, exp:`Fluid intelligence ŌĆö the ability to solve novel problems, reason abstractly, and process information quickly ŌĆö tends to peak in early adulthood and shows a more gradual decline with age compared to the relative stability of crystallized intelligence.` },
      { q:`Activity theory of aging proposes that:`, ch:[`Successful aging involves disengaging from social roles and activities`,`Successful aging is associated with maintaining social activities, relationships, and roles similar to those of middle age`,`Aging has no relationship to social activity levels`,`All older adults should be institutionalized`], ans:1, exp:`Activity theory suggests that maintaining an active lifestyle and social engagement (replacing lost roles with new ones, if needed) is associated with greater life satisfaction and successful aging, in contrast to disengagement theory.` },
      { q:`Disengagement theory of aging proposes that:`, ch:[`Older adults and society mutually withdraw from each other, which is viewed (in this theory) as a natural and adaptive part of aging`,`Older adults should remain maximally active in all prior social roles`,`Aging involves no changes in social participation`,`Disengagement only occurs due to illness, never naturally`], ans:0, exp:`Disengagement theory (Cumming & Henry) proposed that mutual withdrawal between aging individuals and society is a natural, universal, and even adaptive process ŌĆö this theory has been heavily criticized and largely supplanted by activity theory and continuity theory, which emphasize maintaining engagement.` },
      { q:`Continuity theory of aging suggests that:`, ch:[`People completely change their personalities, habits, and preferences as they age`,`As people age, they tend to maintain consistent patterns of behavior, relationships, and personality, adapting strategies from earlier life to maintain continuity`,`Aging causes a complete loss of identity`,`Continuity theory applies only to physical health, not psychosocial functioning`], ans:1, exp:`Continuity theory proposes that individuals strive to maintain consistency in their habits, relationships, personality, and lifestyle as they age, using familiar strategies to adapt to age-related changes ŌĆö generally viewed as integrating insights from both activity and disengagement perspectives.` },
      { q:`Erik Erikson's final psychosocial stage, "ego integrity vs. despair," occurring in late adulthood, involves:`, ch:[`Forming an initial sense of identity`,`Reflecting on one's life and either achieving a sense of fulfillment/wisdom (integrity) or experiencing regret and feelings of unfulfillment (despair)`,`Establishing intimate relationships for the first time`,`Developing trust in caregivers`], ans:1, exp:`In Erikson's final stage, older adults engage in life review, reflecting on their accomplishments and experiences. Successful resolution leads to a sense of integrity, wisdom, and acceptance; unsuccessful resolution can lead to despair, regret, and fear of death.` },
      { q:`Ageism refers to:`, ch:[`A medical condition associated with advanced age`,`Prejudice or discrimination based on a person's age, often involving stereotypes about older (or younger) individuals`,`A normal and unavoidable part of aging that all individuals experience internally`,`A term used only in legal contexts`], ans:1, exp:`Ageism involves stereotyping, prejudice, and discrimination based on age ŌĆö commonly directed at older adults (e.g., assumptions about cognitive decline, frailty, or irrelevance), but can also affect younger individuals. Ageism in healthcare settings can lead to undertreatment or dismissal of legitimate health concerns.` },
      { q:`Which of the following best describes "normal" age-related changes in memory?`, ch:[`Severe, rapid global memory loss affecting all memory types equally, equivalent to dementia`,`Mild, gradual declines in certain types of memory (e.g., processing speed, working memory, retrieval of names) that do not significantly interfere with daily functioning`,`Complete preservation of all memory functions with absolutely no change`,`Improvement in all types of memory with age`], ans:1, exp:`Normal aging is associated with mild declines in processing speed, working memory, and retrieval (e.g., "tip-of-the-tongue" experiences), but generally does not significantly impair daily functioning ŌĆö distinguishing normal aging from pathological cognitive decline (e.g., dementia), which involves more severe and progressive impairment.` },
      { q:`The "sandwich generation" refers to adults who:`, ch:[`Are caring for both their aging parents and their own children simultaneously`,`Have no family responsibilities`,`Are themselves elderly and require full-time care`,`Work exclusively in food service industries`], ans:0, exp:`The "sandwich generation" describes middle-aged adults who simultaneously provide care/support for their aging parents and their own children ŌĆö a position associated with significant caregiver stress, financial strain, and competing time demands.` },
      { q:`Polypharmacy in older adults refers to:`, ch:[`The use of a single medication for multiple conditions`,`The concurrent use of multiple medications, which increases the risk of drug interactions, adverse effects, and medication non-adherence`,`A condition where older adults refuse all medications`,`A term describing pharmacy locations only`], ans:1, exp:`Polypharmacy (often defined as taking 5 or more medications) is common among older adults managing multiple chronic conditions, and increases risks of drug-drug interactions, adverse drug reactions, falls, cognitive impairment, and complex medication regimens that can reduce adherence.` },
      { q:`Elder abuse can take which of the following forms?`, ch:[`Only physical abuse`,`Physical, emotional/psychological, financial, sexual abuse, and neglect`,`Only financial exploitation`,`Elder abuse does not exist as a recognized phenomenon`], ans:1, exp:`Elder abuse encompasses multiple forms: physical (causing physical pain/injury), emotional/psychological (verbal threats, isolation), financial (exploitation of finances/assets), sexual abuse, and neglect (failure to provide for basic needs) ŌĆö often perpetrated by family members or caregivers, and frequently underreported.` },
      { q:`The concept of "successful aging" (Rowe & Kahn) emphasizes:`, ch:[`Avoidance of disease/disability, maintenance of high cognitive and physical functioning, and continued engagement with life (social/productive activities)`,`Aging is "successful" only if a person remains completely free of any health conditions`,`Successful aging is determined entirely by genetics with no behavioral component`,`Withdrawal from all social activities is the key to successful aging`], ans:0, exp:`Rowe and Kahn's model of successful aging includes three components: low probability of disease/disability, high cognitive/physical functional capacity, and active engagement with life ŌĆö emphasizing that many aspects of aging well are influenced by modifiable behaviors and social factors, not solely by genetics or chance.` },
      { q:`Why might older adults be at increased risk of social isolation, and why is this clinically significant?`, ch:[`Social isolation is irrelevant to health outcomes`,`Factors such as retirement, loss of spouse/friends, mobility limitations, and sensory impairments can increase isolation risk in older adults, and social isolation/loneliness is associated with increased risks of depression, cognitive decline, cardiovascular disease, and mortality`,`Older adults are never socially isolated`,`Social isolation only affects younger populations`], ans:1, exp:`Life transitions common in older age (retirement, bereavement, reduced mobility, hearing/vision loss) can reduce social contact, and research has linked social isolation and loneliness to numerous negative health outcomes (comparable in magnitude to other major risk factors like smoking), making social connectedness an important consideration in geriatric care.` },
      { q:`Advance directives and discussions about end-of-life care preferences are particularly important in geriatric care because:`, ch:[`They have no legal or practical significance`,`They allow individuals to communicate their wishes regarding medical treatment in advance, which can guide care if the person later becomes unable to make or communicate decisions, respecting patient autonomy`,`They are required only for patients without any family members`,`They eliminate the need for any further medical decision-making by family or providers`], ans:1, exp:`Advance directives (living wills, healthcare proxies/durable power of attorney for healthcare) document a person's wishes regarding life-sustaining treatments and designate decision-makers, helping ensure that care aligns with the patient's values and autonomy even if they later lose decision-making capacity.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps23`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Infant Development`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`According to attachment theory (Bowlby and Ainsworth), a "secure attachment" style is characterized by an infant who:`, ch:[`Shows no distress when the caregiver leaves and ignores them upon return`,`Is distressed when the caregiver leaves but is easily comforted and seeks contact upon their return, using the caregiver as a "secure base" for exploration`,`Shows extreme distress and cannot be comforted even after the caregiver returns`,`Shows inconsistent, contradictory behaviors with no clear pattern`], ans:1, exp:`In Ainsworth's "Strange Situation" procedure, securely attached infants (the most common pattern, ~60-65%) explore freely using the caregiver as a secure base, show distress upon separation, and are readily comforted upon reunion ŌĆö associated with caregivers who are consistently responsive to the infant's needs.` },
      { q:`Avoidant (insecure) attachment is characterized by an infant who:`, ch:[`Shows great distress upon separation and clings to the caregiver upon return`,`Shows little distress upon separation and actively avoids or ignores the caregiver upon return`,`Cannot be separated from the caregiver under any circumstances`,`Forms attachment exclusively to objects, never to people`], ans:1, exp:`Avoidant attachment is associated with caregivers who may be unresponsive or rejecting; the infant learns to minimize attachment behaviors, showing little visible distress at separation and avoiding/ignoring the caregiver upon reunion (though physiological stress responses, e.g., elevated cortisol, may still be present).` },
      { q:`Resistant/ambivalent (insecure) attachment is characterized by an infant who:`, ch:[`Shows extreme distress upon separation but has difficulty being comforted upon reunion, sometimes showing anger toward the caregiver while also seeking contact`,`Shows no attachment behaviors at all`,`Is securely attached and explores freely`,`Forms attachments only with strangers`], ans:0, exp:`Resistant/ambivalent attachment is often associated with inconsistent caregiver responsiveness; infants show heightened distress at separation and exhibit ambivalent behaviors upon reunion (seeking contact while also resisting/showing anger), and have difficulty returning to exploration.` },
      { q:`Disorganized attachment is most strongly associated with:`, ch:[`Consistently warm and responsive caregiving`,`Caregiving environments involving fear, abuse, or frightening/unpredictable caregiver behavior, where the caregiver is simultaneously a source of comfort and fear`,`Infants who have never met their caregiver`,`A purely genetic, non-environmental cause`], ans:1, exp:`Disorganized attachment (the least common, most concerning pattern) is associated with caregiving that is frightening, abusive, or grossly inconsistent ŌĆö the infant faces an unsolvable conflict (the caregiver is both the source of comfort and of fear), resulting in contradictory, disoriented behaviors.` },
      { q:`Harlow's experiments with infant rhesus monkeys and surrogate "mothers" demonstrated that infants preferred:`, ch:[`A wire mother that provided food over a soft cloth mother that provided no food`,`A soft, cloth-covered surrogate mother that provided contact comfort, even when a separate wire mother provided food`,`No preference between wire and cloth surrogates`,`Isolation over any surrogate`], ans:1, exp:`Harlow's studies showed that infant monkeys spent significantly more time with a soft cloth "mother" (providing contact comfort) than with a wire "mother" that dispensed food, even going to the wire mother only briefly to feed ŌĆö challenging the then-dominant view that attachment was based primarily on feeding/nourishment.` },
      { q:`Stranger anxiety, the distress infants show in the presence of unfamiliar people, typically emerges around what age?`, ch:[`Birth to 1 month`,`Approximately 6-9 months`,`5 years old`,`Stranger anxiety does not occur in typical development`], ans:1, exp:`Stranger anxiety typically emerges around 6-9 months of age, coinciding with the development of object permanence and the formation of specific attachments ŌĆö infants can now distinguish familiar caregivers from strangers and show wariness toward unfamiliar individuals.` },
      { q:`Separation anxiety in infants typically:`, ch:[`Is absent in all typically developing infants`,`Emerges around the same time as stranger anxiety (approximately 6-9 months), peaks around 14-18 months, and gradually declines as the child develops a sense of object permanence and trust that the caregiver will return`,`Increases continuously throughout childhood with no peak or decline`,`Only occurs in infants with insecure attachment`], ans:1, exp:`Separation anxiety is a normal developmental phenomenon, typically emerging around 6-9 months, often peaking around 14-18 months, and gradually decreasing as children develop better understanding of object permanence (caregivers continue to exist and return even when out of sight) and increased tolerance for separation.` },
      { q:`According to Piaget, "object permanence" ŌĆö the understanding that objects continue to exist even when out of sight ŌĆö typically develops during which stage?`, ch:[`Formal operational stage (12+ years)`,`Sensorimotor stage (birth to ~2 years)`,`Concrete operational stage (7-11 years)`,`Preoperational stage (2-7 years)`], ans:1, exp:`Object permanence is a hallmark achievement of Piaget's sensorimotor stage, typically developing by around 8-12 months ŌĆö before this, infants behave as though objects cease to exist when no longer visible (out of sight, out of mind).` },
      { q:`Temperament, as studied by Thomas and Chess, refers to:`, ch:[`A characteristic learned entirely through parenting style, with no innate component`,`Innate, biologically based individual differences in emotional reactivity, activity level, and self-regulation that appear early in life and tend to be relatively stable`,`A term synonymous with "personality disorder"`,`A characteristic that only emerges in adolescence`], ans:1, exp:`Temperament reflects early-appearing, biologically influenced individual differences (e.g., "easy," "difficult," "slow-to-warm-up" patterns identified by Thomas and Chess) in how infants react emotionally and behaviorally ŌĆö temperament interacts with the caregiving environment ("goodness of fit") to influence later development.` },
      { q:`The concept of "goodness of fit" in temperament research refers to:`, ch:[`The match between a child's temperament and the demands/expectations of their environment (e.g., parenting style), which influences developmental outcomes`,`A measure of physical growth in infants`,`A fixed personality trait unrelated to environment`,`A term used only in adult relationships`], ans:0, exp:`"Goodness of fit" describes how well a child's temperament matches the expectations and demands of their caregiving environment ŌĆö a good fit (e.g., parenting that accommodates a child's temperamental tendencies) is associated with more positive developmental outcomes, even for children with more "difficult" temperaments.` },
      { q:`Failure to thrive (FTT) in infants refers to:`, ch:[`Normal variation in growth with no clinical significance`,`Significant deceleration or failure of expected weight gain/growth, which can result from organic (medical) causes, non-organic (psychosocial/environmental) causes, or both`,`A condition that only affects motor development, never growth`,`A diagnosis applied only to premature infants`], ans:1, exp:`Failure to thrive describes inadequate physical growth in infants/young children, which can result from medical conditions (organic FTT), inadequate caregiving/feeding, neglect, or psychosocial factors (non-organic FTT), or a combination ŌĆö early identification is important given potential impacts on development.` },
      { q:`Reactive attachment disorder (RAD) is associated with:`, ch:[`A history of normal, consistent caregiving with no disruptions`,`A history of grossly inadequate caregiving (e.g., severe neglect, repeated changes in primary caregivers, institutional rearing) resulting in a pattern of inhibited, emotionally withdrawn behavior toward caregivers`,`A purely genetic condition unrelated to caregiving experiences`,`A normal variant of secure attachment`], ans:1, exp:`RAD is associated with a documented history of extremes of insufficient care (severe neglect, frequent changes of primary caregivers, or institutional settings with limited opportunity to form selective attachments), resulting in a pattern of emotionally withdrawn behavior and minimal seeking of comfort from caregivers.` },
      { q:`Why is early attachment quality considered important for later development?`, ch:[`Early attachment has no bearing on any later outcomes`,`Early attachment patterns are thought to form internal working models that can influence later relationships, emotional regulation, and social functioning, although these patterns are not necessarily fixed and can change with new relationship experiences`,`Attachment style is permanently fixed at birth and never changes regardless of experience`,`Attachment is relevant only to infant feeding behaviors`], ans:1, exp:`Bowlby proposed that early attachment experiences shape "internal working models" ŌĆö mental representations of self, others, and relationships ŌĆö that can influence expectations and behaviors in later relationships; however, longitudinal research shows attachment patterns can change in response to significant life experiences (continuity is probabilistic, not deterministic).` },
      { q:`Which statement best reflects current understanding of the relationship between infant temperament and parenting?`, ch:[`Parenting has no influence on a child's developmental outcomes; temperament alone determines outcomes`,`Both temperament (a child's innate characteristics) and parenting/environment interact bidirectionally ŌĆö children's temperaments can influence parenting responses, and parenting can shape how temperamental tendencies are expressed`,`Temperament has no biological basis and is entirely determined by parenting`,`Only parenting matters; temperament is irrelevant`], ans:1, exp:`Modern developmental science emphasizes bidirectional/transactional models: a child's temperament can elicit certain responses from caregivers (e.g., a fussy infant may receive different responses than a calm one), and caregiver responses, in turn, shape how temperamental traits develop and are expressed over time ŌĆö neither factor operates in isolation.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps24`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Adolescent Development`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`According to Piaget, the cognitive stage typically reached during adolescence is the:`, ch:[`Sensorimotor stage`,`Preoperational stage`,`Concrete operational stage`,`Formal operational stage, characterized by abstract reasoning, hypothetical thinking, and systematic problem-solving`], ans:3, exp:`The formal operational stage (beginning around age 11-12) involves the ability to think abstractly, reason about hypothetical situations, engage in systematic deductive reasoning, and consider multiple variables simultaneously ŌĆö capacities not yet present in the concrete operational stage's focus on tangible, concrete objects/events.` },
      { q:`Adolescent egocentrism, as described by David Elkind, includes the concept of the "imaginary audience," which refers to:`, ch:[`A belief that others are constantly watching and evaluating one's appearance and behavior`,`The actual presence of an audience during a performance`,`A type of hallucination`,`A belief that no one is paying attention to oneself`], ans:0, exp:`The "imaginary audience" describes adolescents' heightened self-consciousness and belief that they are the focus of others' attention and evaluation ŌĆö contributing to increased self-consciousness about appearance and behavior in social settings.` },
      { q:`The "personal fable," another aspect of adolescent egocentrism, refers to:`, ch:[`A belief that one's experiences and feelings are unique and that one is invulnerable to risks that affect others (e.g., "it won't happen to me")`,`A type of bedtime story told to children`,`A belief shared identically by all individuals across the lifespan`,`A documented medical condition`], ans:0, exp:`The personal fable involves adolescents' sense of personal uniqueness and invulnerability ŌĆö contributing to risk-taking behaviors (e.g., reckless driving, substance experimentation) based on the belief that negative consequences happen to others, not oneself.` },
      { q:`According to Erikson, the primary psychosocial task of adolescence is:`, ch:[`Trust vs. mistrust`,`Identity vs. role confusion ŌĆö exploring different roles, values, and beliefs to develop a coherent sense of self`,`Generativity vs. stagnation`,`Integrity vs. despair`], ans:1, exp:`Erikson's fifth stage (adolescence) centers on identity formation ŌĆö exploring different roles, beliefs, values, and possible future selves ("identity exploration") to develop a coherent sense of identity. Failure to achieve this can result in role confusion (uncertainty about one's place and identity).` },
      { q:`James Marcia expanded on Erikson's identity stage by describing four "identity statuses." A person in "identity moratorium" is:`, ch:[`Someone who has made commitments without exploring alternatives`,`Someone who is actively exploring different identities/options but has not yet made firm commitments`,`Someone who has neither explored options nor made commitments and shows little interest in doing so`,`Someone who has both explored options and made firm commitments`], ans:1, exp:`Marcia's identity statuses, based on presence/absence of exploration and commitment: Identity achievement (explored + committed), Moratorium (exploring, not yet committed), Foreclosure (committed without exploration, often based on others' expectations), and Diffusion (neither explored nor committed).` },
      { q:`"Identity foreclosure," in Marcia's framework, describes an adolescent who:`, ch:[`Has made commitments to an identity (e.g., career, values) without having explored alternative options, often adopting parental or societal expectations directly`,`Has explored many options and made a confident, independent commitment`,`Has neither explored options nor formed any commitments`,`Refuses to ever form an identity`], ans:0, exp:`Identity foreclosure occurs when an individual commits to roles, values, or goals (e.g., a career path chosen because "that's what my parents wanted") without going through a period of exploration of alternatives ŌĆö this commitment may be relatively rigid and less personally examined.` },
      { q:`Puberty is primarily triggered by:`, ch:[`A decrease in activity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis`,`Increased activity of the hypothalamic-pituitary-gonadal (HPG) axis, leading to increased production of sex hormones (estrogen, testosterone) responsible for secondary sexual characteristics`,`A decrease in growth hormone secretion`,`Changes unrelated to any hormonal processes`], ans:1, exp:`Puberty involves reactivation/maturation of the HPG axis: the hypothalamus increases GnRH secretion, stimulating the pituitary to release LH and FSH, which in turn stimulate the gonads to produce sex hormones (testosterone, estrogen) responsible for the development of secondary sexual characteristics and reproductive maturation.` },
      { q:`The timing of puberty (early vs. late maturation) has been associated with which psychosocial outcomes?`, ch:[`Timing of puberty has no psychosocial implications whatsoever`,`Early maturation in girls has been associated with increased risk for certain psychosocial difficulties (e.g., body image issues, earlier substance use), while effects of early/late maturation can differ between boys and girls`,`Late maturation always has only positive effects for both sexes`,`Early maturation always has only positive effects for both sexes`], ans:1, exp:`Research suggests early-maturing girls may face increased risks (body image concerns, earlier exposure to dating/substance use pressures, mismatch between physical appearance and emotional maturity), while early maturation in boys has sometimes been associated with more positive peer status (though also increased risk-taking) ŌĆö effects are also influenced by social context.` },
      { q:`Adolescent risk-taking behavior (e.g., substance experimentation, reckless driving) has been linked, in neuroscience research, to:`, ch:[`A fully mature prefrontal cortex combined with an underdeveloped limbic/reward system`,`The relatively earlier maturation of limbic/reward-related brain regions compared to the prefrontal cortex (involved in impulse control and judgment), which continues developing into the mid-20s`,`No neurological basis whatsoever; risk-taking is purely a result of upbringing`,`A complete absence of any reward-related brain activity`], ans:1, exp:`Dual-systems models of adolescent brain development propose that limbic/reward-processing regions (e.g., nucleus accumbens) mature earlier and become highly responsive during adolescence, while the prefrontal cortex (responsible for executive function, impulse control, future-oriented thinking) continues maturing into the mid-20s ŌĆö creating a developmental "imbalance" that may contribute to heightened risk-taking, particularly in emotionally charged or peer-present contexts.` },
      { q:`Peer influence during adolescence tends to:`, ch:[`Decrease compared to childhood`,`Increase significantly, with peer relationships becoming increasingly important for identity development, social comparison, and behavior (including both positive and negative influences)`,`Have no impact on behavior at any point`,`Only affect academic performance, with no influence on health behaviors`], ans:1, exp:`Adolescence is marked by increased time spent with peers and heightened sensitivity to peer acceptance/rejection ŌĆö peer relationships play important roles in identity development and social skill-building, but peer influence ("peer pressure") can also contribute to increased risk-taking behaviors.` },
      { q:`Eating disorders such as anorexia nervosa and bulimia nervosa most commonly have an onset during:`, ch:[`Infancy`,`Adolescence and young adulthood`,`Late older adulthood exclusively`,`Eating disorders have no typical age of onset`], ans:1, exp:`Adolescence and young adulthood represent peak periods of onset for many eating disorders, with contributing factors including body image concerns (heightened during puberty), sociocultural pressures regarding appearance, and the broader identity/developmental challenges of this period ŌĆö though eating disorders can occur at other ages as well.` },
      { q:`Conventional moral reasoning, in Kohlberg's stages of moral development, is typically associated with which developmental period?`, ch:[`Early childhood exclusively`,`Adolescence and adulthood, characterized by reasoning based on maintaining social order, approval from others, and conformity to societal rules and laws`,`Old age exclusively`,`Conventional reasoning never develops in any individual`], ans:1, exp:`Kohlberg's conventional level (typically emerging in adolescence) involves moral reasoning based on social approval ("good boy/girl" orientation) and maintaining social order/law (authority and social-order-maintaining orientation) ŌĆö many adults remain at this level, with post-conventional reasoning (based on abstract principles of justice) being less commonly fully achieved.` },
      { q:`Why might confidentiality be a particularly important consideration when providing healthcare to adolescents?`, ch:[`Confidentiality is irrelevant for adolescent patients`,`Adolescents may be more likely to seek care for sensitive issues (e.g., sexual health, substance use, mental health) and to disclose accurate information if they trust that confidentiality will be maintained, within the bounds of safety exceptions (e.g., risk of harm)`,`Adolescents should never have any private conversations with healthcare providers`,`Parents must always be informed of every detail of an adolescent's visit regardless of context`], ans:1, exp:`Many adolescents may avoid seeking care or withhold important information about sensitive topics (sexual activity, substance use, mental health concerns) if they fear information will be shared with parents ŌĆö appropriately balancing confidentiality (within legal/ethical limits, e.g., mandatory reporting for safety concerns) can improve access to and quality of adolescent healthcare.` },
      { q:`Which best describes the relationship between adolescent brain development and the legal/policy debates about age-related restrictions (e.g., driving, alcohol, voting)?`, ch:[`Brain development research has no relevance to such policy debates`,`Research on the protracted development of executive function and impulse control into the mid-20s has informed (and been cited in) debates about age-appropriate restrictions and protections, while also raising questions about how to balance autonomy with protection across different domains`,`Brain development is fully complete by age 10, making all restrictions on adolescents unnecessary`,`All cognitive abilities are identical between a 12-year-old and a 25-year-old`], ans:1, exp:`Findings about ongoing prefrontal cortex development have been influential in legal/policy discussions (e.g., juvenile justice sentencing, graduated driver licensing) ŌĆö though translating neuroscience findings into specific policy thresholds involves additional ethical, legal, and social considerations beyond the biology alone.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps25`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Adult Development & Life Transitions`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`According to Erikson, the psychosocial task of "intimacy vs. isolation" is most associated with which life stage?`, ch:[`Infancy`,`Adolescence`,`Young adulthood`,`Late adulthood`], ans:2, exp:`Erikson's sixth stage, occurring in young adulthood, centers on forming close, committed relationships (intimacy) versus experiencing loneliness and emotional isolation if this task is not successfully navigated ŌĆö building on a foundation of identity established in adolescence.` },
      { q:`"Generativity vs. stagnation," Erikson's seventh psychosocial stage, is typically associated with:`, ch:[`Infancy, focused on developing trust`,`Middle adulthood, involving a focus on contributing to society and guiding future generations (e.g., through parenting, mentorship, work) versus feeling unproductive or self-absorbed`,`Adolescence, focused on identity formation`,`Old age, focused on life review`], ans:1, exp:`Generativity involves a shift toward caring for and contributing to future generations and society (through parenting, mentoring, creative or productive work), while stagnation reflects a sense of unproductiveness, self-absorption, or lack of meaningful contribution.` },
      { q:`The "midlife crisis," a popularly discussed concept associated with middle adulthood, is best characterized in current research as:`, ch:[`A universal, severe psychological crisis experienced by all individuals at a specific age`,`A phenomenon experienced by only a minority of individuals, with research suggesting that significant life dissatisfaction in midlife is not as universal or age-specific as popularly portrayed, and is more strongly linked to specific life events/circumstances than to age itself`,`A condition that occurs only in adolescence`,`A term with no basis in any research literature`], ans:1, exp:`While the concept of a "midlife crisis" is culturally pervasive, research suggests that dramatic, age-linked crises are not universal ŌĆö life satisfaction patterns vary considerably, and difficulties often attributed to "midlife crisis" may instead be linked to specific stressful life events (career changes, health issues, relationship transitions) that can occur at various ages.` },
      { q:`The "empty nest" transition, when adult children leave the parental home, has been found to:`, ch:[`Universally cause severe, long-lasting depression in all parents`,`Have variable effects ŌĆö for many parents, this transition is associated with improved marital satisfaction and increased opportunities for personal pursuits, though some may experience temporary adjustment difficulties`,`Have no documented psychological effects of any kind`,`Only affect fathers, never mothers`], ans:1, exp:`Contrary to the popular notion of "empty nest syndrome" as uniformly distressing, research suggests many parents experience this transition positively ŌĆö with increased time for relationships, career, and personal interests ŌĆö though individual variation exists and difficulties can occur, particularly if parental identity was a primary source of self-definition.` },
      { q:`Which statement best reflects research on relationship satisfaction across the lifespan of long-term marriages?`, ch:[`Marital satisfaction follows a strictly linear decline from the wedding day onward with no recovery`,`Marital satisfaction commonly shows a U-shaped pattern ŌĆö declining somewhat during the child-rearing years and increasing again after children leave home, though individual trajectories vary`,`Marital satisfaction is identical at all points and never changes`,`Marital satisfaction always increases linearly with no decline at any point`], ans:1, exp:`A commonly observed (though not universal) pattern shows relatively high satisfaction early in marriage, a dip during the demanding child-rearing years (associated with role strain, division of labor issues, reduced couple time), and often a rebound in satisfaction during the post-parenting years ŌĆö though individual relationships show considerable variability.` },
      { q:`Bereavement following the death of a spouse has been associated with which health outcomes?`, ch:[`No measurable health effects of any kind`,`Increased risk of mortality (sometimes called the "widowhood effect"), as well as increased risk for depression and other health problems, particularly in the period shortly after the loss`,`Universal improvement in physical health`,`Effects only on physical health, never on mental health`], ans:1, exp:`The "widowhood effect" describes the observed increase in mortality risk for surviving spouses, particularly in the months following the death of a partner ŌĆö attributed to factors including grief-related physiological stress, loss of social/emotional support, and changes in health behaviors (e.g., medication adherence, diet).` },
      { q:`K├╝bler-Ross's stages of grief/dying (denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance) are best understood, according to current perspectives, as:`, ch:[`A rigid, universal sequence that every individual experiences in the same fixed order`,`A framework describing common emotional responses, but not necessarily experienced by everyone, in a fixed order, or completely ŌĆö individuals may experience these (and other) reactions in varying sequences, with overlap, or not at all`,`Stages that apply only to physical illness, never to other types of loss`,`A framework with no continued relevance or use in any context`], ans:1, exp:`While influential, K├╝bler-Ross's stages have been critiqued for being overly prescriptive ŌĆö current understanding emphasizes that grief is highly individual, can involve a wide range of emotional responses (not limited to these five), does not necessarily progress in a fixed linear order, and "acceptance" is not a required or universal endpoint.` },
      { q:`"Filial responsibility" refers to:`, ch:[`The legal and/or felt obligation of adult children to care for their aging parents`,`A type of childhood developmental disorder`,`The responsibility of parents toward infants only`,`A term with no relevance to family relationships`], ans:0, exp:`Filial responsibility describes the social, cultural, and sometimes legal expectation that adult children provide care and support for aging parents ŌĆö norms and expectations around filial responsibility vary considerably across cultures and have implications for caregiving arrangements and related stress.` },
      { q:`Caregiver burden, experienced by individuals caring for chronically ill or disabled family members, is associated with:`, ch:[`No negative effects on the caregiver's own health or well-being`,`Increased risk of physical health problems, depression, anxiety, and social isolation for the caregiver, sometimes referred to as caregiver "burnout"`,`Improvements in caregiver health proportional to the severity of the care recipient's condition`,`Effects only on the care recipient, never the caregiver`], ans:1, exp:`Long-term caregiving (especially for conditions like dementia) is associated with significant physical and psychological strain on caregivers ŌĆö including increased rates of depression, anxiety, sleep disturbance, and physical health declines ŌĆö highlighting the importance of caregiver support resources and respite care.` },
      { q:`Retirement, as a life transition, has been found to have which range of effects on well-being?`, ch:[`Universally negative effects for all individuals`,`Variable effects depending on factors such as whether retirement was voluntary or forced, financial security, health status, and the presence of meaningful activities/social connections to replace work-related roles`,`Universally positive effects for all individuals with no exceptions`,`No effect on well-being for any individual`], ans:1, exp:`Retirement's impact on well-being depends heavily on context ŌĆö voluntary retirement with adequate financial resources, good health, and replacement activities/social ties tends to be associated with positive adjustment, while involuntary retirement (e.g., due to health problems or job loss) or lack of alternative sources of meaning/social connection can be associated with declines in well-being.` },
      { q:`The concept of "socioemotional selectivity theory" (Carstensen) proposes that as people perceive time as more limited (e.g., in older age), they tend to:`, ch:[`Prioritize expanding their social networks to include as many new acquaintances as possible`,`Prioritize emotionally meaningful goals and relationships, narrowing their social networks to focus on close, emotionally rewarding relationships`,`Become completely socially withdrawn with no emotional goals`,`Show no change in social or emotional priorities with age`], ans:1, exp:`Socioemotional selectivity theory proposes that perceived time horizons shape motivational priorities ŌĆö when time is perceived as limited (as often occurs with advancing age, but also in other contexts like terminal illness), individuals tend to prioritize emotionally meaningful goals and close relationships over knowledge-acquisition or expanding social networks.` },
      { q:`Which of the following is an example of a "non-normative" life event/transition (as opposed to a "normative" one)?`, ch:[`Retirement at the typical age for one's cohort`,`An unexpected serious illness or job loss occurring at an atypical time`,`Starting school at the typical age`,`Marriage at a culturally typical age`], ans:1, exp:`Normative life events are those that are expected and occur at culturally/age-typical times (e.g., starting school, retirement at a typical age), while non-normative events are unexpected or occur "off-time" (e.g., a serious illness in young adulthood, an unexpected job loss) ŌĆö non-normative events are often associated with greater stress, partly because they may occur without the social support/preparation typically available for normative transitions.` },
      { q:`A patient in their 50s reports feeling that despite professional success, they feel disconnected from any sense of purpose or contribution beyond their own immediate concerns. In Erikson's framework, this might reflect difficulty with:`, ch:[`Trust vs. mistrust`,`Generativity vs. stagnation`,`Industry vs. inferiority`,`Initiative vs. guilt`], ans:1, exp:`This description aligns with Erikson's stage of generativity vs. stagnation ŌĆö a sense of disconnection from contributing to future generations or broader purposes (despite personal/professional success) reflects the "stagnation" pole of this stage, which is associated with feelings of self-absorption or lack of meaningful contribution.` },
      { q:`Why is understanding normative life-stage transitions (e.g., becoming a parent, retirement, bereavement) clinically useful for healthcare providers?`, ch:[`Because life transitions have no relevance to health or healthcare`,`Because such transitions are often associated with changes in stress levels, mental health risk, health behaviors, and social support, which can affect both the presentation of health concerns and a patient's capacity to manage their health during that period`,`Because providers should assume every patient experiences identical reactions to every transition`,`Because life transitions only matter for pediatric patients`], ans:1, exp:`Major life transitions (parenthood, divorce, retirement, bereavement, caregiving roles) can affect mental health, health behaviors (e.g., diet, exercise, substance use), social support availability, and capacity for self-care/treatment adherence ŌĆö awareness of these transitions can help providers contextualize symptoms, anticipate needs, and provide more holistic, patient-centered care.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps26`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Classical Conditioning`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`In classical conditioning, the unconditioned stimulus (UCS) is defined as:`, ch:[`A stimulus that, after training, comes to elicit a response`,`A stimulus that naturally and automatically triggers a response without any prior learning`,`The response that occurs after conditioning is complete`,`A stimulus that has no effect on behavior`], ans:1, exp:`The UCS naturally and automatically elicits a response (the unconditioned response, UCR) without any learning required ŌĆö e.g., food (UCS) naturally elicits salivation (UCR) in Pavlov's dogs, prior to any conditioning.` },
      { q:`In Pavlov's classic experiments, the bell (initially neutral) became a conditioned stimulus (CS) because it was:`, ch:[`Naturally able to elicit salivation without any pairing`,`Repeatedly paired with the unconditioned stimulus (food), eventually coming to elicit a conditioned response (salivation) on its own`,`Presented only once, with no repetition`,`Never associated with food at any point`], ans:1, exp:`Through repeated pairing with the UCS (food), the previously neutral stimulus (bell) becomes a conditioned stimulus (CS) capable of eliciting the conditioned response (CR, salivation to the bell alone) ŌĆö this is the core process of classical conditioning, acquisition.` },
      { q:`Acquisition, in classical conditioning, refers to:`, ch:[`The initial learning phase in which an association between the CS and UCS is formed`,`The complete disappearance of a learned response`,`The spontaneous return of an extinguished response`,`A response generalizing to similar stimuli`], ans:0, exp:`Acquisition is the initial stage of learning during which the conditioned stimulus (CS) and unconditioned stimulus (UCS) are repeatedly paired, gradually establishing an association such that the CS comes to elicit the conditioned response (CR).` },
      { q:`Extinction, in classical conditioning, occurs when:`, ch:[`The CS is repeatedly presented without the UCS, leading to a gradual decrease in the conditioned response`,`The UCS is presented without the CS, with no effect on the CR`,`The conditioned response increases without any further pairings`,`A new stimulus is introduced that has never been paired with anything`], ans:0, exp:`Extinction occurs when the CS is repeatedly presented alone (without the UCS), gradually weakening the CS-CR association and decreasing the conditioned response ŌĆö though extinction does not necessarily mean the original learning is "erased" (see spontaneous recovery).` },
      { q:`Spontaneous recovery refers to:`, ch:[`The permanent disappearance of a conditioned response after extinction`,`The reappearance of a previously extinguished conditioned response after a rest period, even without further conditioning trials`,`The initial acquisition of a conditioned response`,`A conditioned response that never weakens`], ans:1, exp:`Spontaneous recovery demonstrates that extinction does not fully "erase" the original CS-UCS association ŌĆö after a period of time without exposure to the CS, presenting the CS again can elicit a (typically weaker) conditioned response, suggesting the original learning is suppressed rather than eliminated.` },
      { q:`Stimulus generalization, in classical conditioning, refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency for stimuli similar to the original CS to also elicit the conditioned response`,`The tendency to respond only to the exact original CS and no other stimuli`,`A complete absence of any conditioned response`,`The process of forgetting a learned association entirely`], ans:0, exp:`Stimulus generalization occurs when stimuli similar to the original CS also elicit the CR (e.g., Little Albert's fear of a white rat generalized to other furry white objects). The degree of generalization typically depends on the similarity between the new stimulus and the original CS.` },
      { q:`Stimulus discrimination, in contrast to generalization, refers to:`, ch:[`Responding identically to all stimuli, regardless of similarity to the CS`,`The learned ability to distinguish between the CS and other similar stimuli that have not been paired with the UCS, responding only to the CS`,`The complete elimination of a conditioned response`,`A process that occurs only during extinction`], ans:1, exp:`Stimulus discrimination develops when an organism learns to respond to the specific CS but not to similar stimuli that have not been associated with the UCS ŌĆö achieved through differential reinforcement (pairing only the specific CS with the UCS).` },
      { q:`The "Little Albert" experiment (Watson & Rayner) demonstrated that:`, ch:[`Fear responses cannot be conditioned in humans`,`A previously neutral stimulus (a white rat) could become a conditioned stimulus eliciting a fear response, after being paired with a loud, frightening noise (UCS)`,`Classical conditioning only applies to positive emotional responses`,`Conditioned fear responses cannot generalize to other stimuli`], ans:1, exp:`In this controversial study, a young child ("Little Albert") was conditioned to fear a white rat (initially neutral) by pairing it with a loud, startling noise (UCS, eliciting fear/UCR). Albert's fear subsequently generalized to other similar furry white stimuli (e.g., a rabbit, a Santa Claus mask), demonstrating both conditioning and stimulus generalization of emotional responses.` },
      { q:`Taste aversion learning (e.g., developing a strong dislike for a food after it was followed by nausea, even with a long delay between eating and illness) is notable because it demonstrates:`, ch:[`Classical conditioning always requires immediate temporal contiguity between CS and UCS, with no exceptions`,`Some associations (like taste-illness pairings) can form even with significant delays between the CS (taste) and UCS (illness), and can occur after a single pairing ŌĆö illustrating biological preparedness for certain types of learning`,`Taste aversions cannot be classically conditioned`,`Taste aversion learning is identical across all species and stimulus types with no special features`], ans:1, exp:`Garcia and Koelling's research on taste aversion (the "Garcia effect") showed that animals can form strong taste-illness associations even with delays of hours between consuming a substance and becoming ill, and often after just one pairing ŌĆö challenging the general principle that conditioning requires close temporal contiguity, and suggesting organisms are biologically "prepared" to readily learn certain adaptive associations (e.g., taste-nausea, but not, say, taste-shock).` },
      { q:`Higher-order (second-order) conditioning occurs when:`, ch:[`A previously conditioned CS is paired with a new neutral stimulus, which then also comes to elicit the conditioned response, even without ever being directly paired with the original UCS`,`The UCS is presented without any CS, with no learning occurring`,`Conditioning occurs in only one trial with no repetition`,`A conditioned response is permanently extinguished`], ans:0, exp:`In higher-order conditioning, an established CS (CS1, which elicits the CR due to prior pairing with the UCS) is paired with a new neutral stimulus (CS2). Eventually, CS2 alone can elicit the CR, despite never having been directly paired with the original UCS ŌĆö demonstrating that conditioning can extend beyond direct CS-UCS pairings.` },
      { q:`A patient who experiences nausea specifically when entering the hospital where they previously received chemotherapy (which itself caused nausea), even before receiving treatment on a new visit, is exhibiting:`, ch:[`Operant conditioning via positive reinforcement`,`A classically conditioned response, where the hospital environment (CS) has become associated with chemotherapy-induced nausea (originally a UCR to the chemotherapy drugs, the UCS)`,`A genetic predisposition unrelated to learning`,`Stimulus discrimination preventing any generalized response`], ans:1, exp:`This is a classic example of classically conditioned anticipatory nausea: repeated pairing of the treatment environment/cues (CS) with chemotherapy drugs (UCS, which directly causes nausea/UCR) results in the environment alone eliciting nausea (now a CR) ŌĆö a clinically significant phenomenon in oncology that can sometimes be addressed using behavioral techniques like systematic desensitization.` },
      { q:`Why might exposure therapy for phobias be understood, in part, through the lens of classical conditioning principles?`, ch:[`Because exposure therapy has nothing to do with classical conditioning`,`Because repeated, controlled exposure to a feared stimulus (CS) without the originally associated aversive outcome (UCS) can promote extinction of the conditioned fear response`,`Because exposure therapy works by introducing a new UCS that is more frightening than the original`,`Because phobias cannot be treated using any conditioning-based approach`], ans:1, exp:`Exposure therapy involves repeatedly presenting the feared stimulus (CS, e.g., a spider) in the absence of the originally feared outcome (UCS, e.g., being bitten/harmed), which (similar to extinction in classical conditioning) can weaken the learned fear response over time ŌĆö though cognitive and other factors also contribute to therapeutic outcomes.` },
      { q:`The timing relationship between the CS and UCS that typically produces the strongest conditioning is generally:`, ch:[`The UCS presented well before the CS (backward conditioning), which is generally the most effective`,`The CS presented shortly before the UCS (forward/delay conditioning), which is generally more effective than other temporal arrangements for most types of learning`,`The CS and UCS presented at exactly the same instant always produces the strongest learning in all cases`,`Timing has no effect on the strength of conditioning`], ans:1, exp:`Forward conditioning (CS presented shortly before the UCS, with some overlap or immediately preceding it ŌĆö "delay conditioning") generally produces the strongest and most reliable conditioning for most stimuli, as the CS serves as a predictive signal for the UCS. Backward conditioning (UCS before CS) typically produces weak or no conditioning, with some exceptions.` },
      { q:`A medical student learns to feel anxious upon hearing a pager go off, after repeated experiences of the pager (initially neutral) being followed by stressful emergency situations (which naturally elicit anxiety). According to classical conditioning, the pager sound has become a:`, ch:[`Unconditioned stimulus`,`Conditioned stimulus, eliciting a conditioned anxiety response`,`Unconditioned response`,`A stimulus with no learned association`], ans:1, exp:`The pager sound (initially neutral) has, through repeated pairing with stressful emergencies (UCS, naturally eliciting anxiety/UCR), become a conditioned stimulus capable of eliciting anxiety (now a conditioned response) on its own ŌĆö illustrating how classical conditioning can apply to real-world emotional responses in professional contexts.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps27`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Operant Conditioning`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Operant conditioning, as described by B.F. Skinner, focuses on:`, ch:[`Learning through the association of two stimuli presented together`,`Learning through the consequences (reinforcement or punishment) that follow a behavior, which influence the future frequency of that behavior`,`Learning that occurs only through observation, with no direct experience`,`A type of learning that cannot be studied experimentally`], ans:1, exp:`Operant conditioning describes how the consequences of a behavior (reinforcement increasing the behavior's frequency, or punishment decreasing it) shape future voluntary behavior ŌĆö distinct from classical conditioning's focus on associations between stimuli and involuntary/reflexive responses.` },
      { q:`Positive reinforcement involves:`, ch:[`Removing an unpleasant stimulus to increase a behavior`,`Adding/presenting a desirable stimulus following a behavior, which increases the likelihood of that behavior occurring again`,`Adding an unpleasant stimulus to decrease a behavior`,`Removing a desirable stimulus to decrease a behavior`], ans:1, exp:`Positive reinforcement involves the addition of a pleasant/desirable stimulus (a "reward") contingent on a behavior, increasing the future probability of that behavior ŌĆö e.g., giving a child praise for completing homework increases the likelihood they will do homework again.` },
      { q:`Negative reinforcement involves:`, ch:[`Punishing a behavior by adding an aversive stimulus`,`The removal of an aversive (unpleasant) stimulus following a behavior, which increases the likelihood of that behavior occurring again`,`Decreasing a behavior by withholding a reward`,`A synonym for "bad" or "harmful" reinforcement`], ans:1, exp:`Negative reinforcement strengthens a behavior by removing/avoiding an aversive stimulus ŌĆö e.g., taking aspirin (behavior) relieves a headache (removal of aversive stimulus), increasing the likelihood of taking aspirin for future headaches. Note: "negative" refers to removal/subtraction, not to something "bad" ŌĆö both positive and negative reinforcement increase behavior.` },
      { q:`Positive punishment involves:`, ch:[`Removing a desirable stimulus to decrease a behavior`,`Adding/presenting an aversive stimulus following a behavior, which decreases the likelihood of that behavior occurring again`,`Adding a desirable stimulus to increase a behavior`,`A synonym for negative reinforcement`], ans:1, exp:`Positive punishment involves the addition of an aversive consequence following a behavior, decreasing the future likelihood of that behavior ŌĆö e.g., a burn (aversive stimulus added) after touching a hot stove decreases the likelihood of touching hot stoves again.` },
      { q:`Negative punishment involves:`, ch:[`Adding an aversive stimulus to decrease a behavior`,`The removal of a desirable stimulus following a behavior, which decreases the likelihood of that behavior occurring again`,`Adding a desirable stimulus to increase a behavior`,`A synonym for positive reinforcement`], ans:1, exp:`Negative punishment involves taking away something desirable following a behavior, decreasing future occurrence of that behavior ŌĆö e.g., taking away a teenager's phone privileges (removal of a desirable item) after breaking curfew, to decrease curfew-breaking.` },
      { q:`A fixed-ratio (FR) reinforcement schedule provides reinforcement:`, ch:[`After a variable, unpredictable number of responses`,`After a fixed, predictable number of responses (e.g., every 5th response)`,`After a fixed amount of time has passed, regardless of number of responses`,`Continuously, after every single response`], ans:1, exp:`Fixed-ratio schedules reinforce behavior after a set, predictable number of responses (e.g., a piece-rate factory worker paid per 10 units produced) ŌĆö typically produces high response rates with a brief pause after each reinforcement ("post-reinforcement pause").` },
      { q:`A variable-ratio (VR) reinforcement schedule, exemplified by slot machines, is characterized by:`, ch:[`Reinforcement after a fixed, predictable number of responses`,`Reinforcement after an unpredictable, varying number of responses (averaging around a certain number), which produces high, steady response rates that are highly resistant to extinction`,`Reinforcement provided after a fixed time interval`,`No reinforcement ever being provided`], ans:1, exp:`Variable-ratio schedules (e.g., gambling, where the number of "pulls" needed for a payout varies unpredictably) produce very high, steady rates of responding and are notably resistant to extinction ŌĆö the unpredictability keeps the organism responding in anticipation of reinforcement, contributing to the addictive nature of activities like gambling.` },
      { q:`A fixed-interval (FI) reinforcement schedule provides reinforcement for the first response:`, ch:[`After a fixed amount of time has elapsed, regardless of how many responses occurred during that interval`,`After a fixed number of responses, regardless of time`,`After a variable, unpredictable amount of time`,`Continuously, with reinforcement for every response`], ans:0, exp:`Fixed-interval schedules reinforce the first response after a set time period has elapsed (e.g., checking mail once a day ŌĆö checking more frequently doesn't produce mail faster). This typically produces a "scalloped" response pattern ŌĆö low responding right after reinforcement, increasing as the interval's end approaches.` },
      { q:`A variable-interval (VI) reinforcement schedule produces:`, ch:[`A scalloped response pattern with clear pauses after each reinforcement`,`A relatively steady, moderate response rate, as the unpredictable timing of reinforcement availability encourages consistent checking/responding`,`No responding at all`,`Responses only at the exact moment of reinforcement, with no responding otherwise`], ans:1, exp:`Variable-interval schedules (e.g., checking for a text message at unpredictable times after the message could arrive) produce relatively steady response rates without the pause patterns seen in fixed schedules, since the organism cannot predict exactly when reinforcement will become available.` },
      { q:`Shaping, in operant conditioning, refers to:`, ch:[`Reinforcing only the final, fully correct target behavior, with no reinforcement of any intermediate steps`,`Gradually reinforcing successive approximations of a desired target behavior, until the full target behavior is achieved`,`A process that only applies to punishment, not reinforcement`,`Removing all reinforcement to eliminate a behavior entirely`], ans:1, exp:`Shaping involves reinforcing behaviors that are progressively closer approximations to a desired target behavior (e.g., teaching a pigeon to peck a specific spot by first reinforcing any movement toward that spot, then closer approximations, until only pecks at the exact spot are reinforced) ŌĆö useful for teaching complex behaviors not in the organism's existing repertoire.` },
      { q:`The Premack principle states that:`, ch:[`Reinforcement only works if delivered immediately after the behavior, with no exceptions`,`A more preferred (higher-probability) activity can serve as a reinforcer for a less preferred (lower-probability) activity (e.g., "first finish your vegetables, then you can have dessert")`,`Punishment is always more effective than reinforcement`,`Behaviors cannot be reinforced by other behaviors, only by tangible rewards`], ans:1, exp:`The Premack principle (sometimes called "Grandma's rule") proposes that access to a high-probability/preferred behavior can reinforce a lower-probability/less preferred behavior ŌĆö widely applied in behavior management (e.g., "you can play video games after you finish your homework").` },
      { q:`A drawback of using punishment to decrease behavior, compared to reinforcement-based approaches, includes:`, ch:[`Punishment has no drawbacks and is always the most effective approach`,`Punishment may suppress a behavior temporarily without teaching an alternative desired behavior, can produce fear/avoidance of the punisher, and may not generalize well outside the punishment context`,`Punishment always generalizes perfectly to all contexts with no issues`,`Punishment always increases the behavior it targets`], ans:1, exp:`Critiques of punishment include: it indicates what NOT to do without teaching what TO do instead, can produce unwanted emotional side effects (fear, anxiety, aggression) and avoidance of the punishing agent/situation, may only suppress behavior in the presence of the punisher (poor generalization), and timing/consistency issues can reduce effectiveness ŌĆö reinforcement-based approaches are often recommended as more effective for lasting behavior change.` },
      { q:`Token economies, used in some clinical and educational settings, are an application of:`, ch:[`Classical conditioning principles only`,`Operant conditioning, where tokens (secondary reinforcers) are earned for desired behaviors and can later be exchanged for tangible rewards or privileges (primary/back-up reinforcers)`,`Observational learning exclusively`,`A technique with no theoretical basis`], ans:1, exp:`Token economies use a system of tokens (points, chips, etc.) as conditioned/secondary reinforcers, given immediately for desired behaviors, which can be exchanged later for back-up reinforcers (privileges, items) ŌĆö applying operant conditioning principles, particularly useful when immediate access to the ultimate reinforcer isn't practical.` },
      { q:`Why might a behavior that was reinforced on a variable-ratio schedule be more resistant to extinction than a behavior reinforced on a continuous reinforcement schedule (reinforced every time)?`, ch:[`Variable-ratio schedules provide no reinforcement at all, so there is nothing to extinguish`,`Because with continuous reinforcement, the absence of reinforcement is immediately noticeable (signaling a change), whereas with variable-ratio schedules, the organism is accustomed to unpredictable gaps between reinforcements, making it harder to detect that reinforcement has stopped altogether ŌĆö leading to more persistent responding during extinction`,`Continuous reinforcement always produces more resistance to extinction than any other schedule`,`Resistance to extinction is unrelated to reinforcement schedules`], ans:1, exp:`This phenomenon, sometimes called the "partial reinforcement extinction effect," occurs because behaviors maintained on intermittent (especially variable-ratio) schedules have already been "trained" to persist through periods without reinforcement, making the transition to true extinction less distinguishable from a normal "dry spell" ŌĆö resulting in greater persistence of the behavior even when reinforcement is permanently discontinued.` }
    ]
  },
  {
    id:`ps28`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Cognitive Development ŌĆö Vygotsky`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
      { q:`Lev Vygotsky's sociocultural theory of cognitive development emphasizes the role of:`, ch:[`Innate, universal stages of development that occur regardless of social context`,`Social interaction and cultural context as fundamental drivers of cognitive development`,`Purely biological maturation, with no role for social factors`,`Reinforcement schedules in shaping cognitive abilities`], ans:1, exp:`In contrast to Piaget's emphasis on the child as an independent explorer progressing through universal stages, Vygotsky emphasized that cognitive development is fundamentally shaped by social interactions with more knowledgeable others (parents, teachers, peers) and embedded within a specific cultural context, with language playing a central role.` },
      { q:`The "zone of proximal development" (ZPD), a central concept in Vygotsky's theory, refers to:`, ch:[`Tasks a child can already perform independently without any assistance`,`The range of tasks a child cannot yet perform independently but can accomplish with guidance/assistance from a more skilled person`,`Tasks that are far beyond a child's capability even with maximal assistance`,`A fixed, unchanging set of abilities present from birth`], ans:1, exp:`The ZPD represents the gap between what a learner can do independently and what they can achieve with the support ("scaffolding") of a more knowledgeable other ŌĆö instruction is considered most effective when targeted within this zone, neither too easy (already mastered) nor too difficult (beyond reach even with help).` },
      { q:`"Scaffolding," a concept related to the ZPD, refers to:`, ch:[`Removing all support so a child must learn entirely independently from the start`,`The temporary support and guidance provided by a more knowledgeable other, which is gradually withdrawn as the learner becomes more competent and independent`,`A permanent form of assistance that never changes`,`A physical structure used in construction, with no relevance to learning`], ans:1, exp:`Scaffolding describes the adjustable support (hints, prompts, demonstrations, structured guidance) provided by a teacher, parent, or more skilled peer to help a learner accomplish a task within their ZPD ŌĆö as the learner's competence increases, the support is gradually reduced ("faded"), promoting increasing independence.` },
      { q:`According to Vygotsky, "private speech" ŌĆö children talking to themselves during tasks ŌĆö serves the function of:`, ch:[`Indicating a developmental disorder requiring intervention`,`Helping children regulate their own thinking and behavior, gradually becoming internalized as silent "inner speech" used for self-guidance`,`Having no functional purpose and typically discouraged`,`A behavior that only occurs in adulthood`], ans:1, exp:`Vygotsky viewed private speech (audible self-talk, common in young children, especially during challenging tasks) as a tool for self-regulation and problem-solving, which gradually becomes internalized as silent "inner speech" in older children and adults ŌĆö contrasting with Piaget's view of such speech as merely "egocentric" and a sign of cognitive immaturity.` },
      { q:`Vygotsky's theory places significant emphasis on the role of:`, ch:[`Solitary discovery learning, with minimal input from others`,`Language as a tool for thought, communication, and cultural transmission of knowledge`,`Genetically predetermined developmental milestones that occur independent of culture`,`Reinforcement and punishment as the primary mechanisms of learning`], ans:1, exp:`For Vygotsky, language is central to cognitive development ŌĆö it is the primary means through which culture transmits knowledge, values, and problem-solving strategies to children, and it becomes an internal tool for organizing thought (inner speech) as development proceeds.` },
      { q:`Compared to Piaget's stage theory, which emphasizes universal, biologically driven stages, Vygotsky's theory suggests that cognitive development:`, ch:[`Follows the exact same universal pattern in all cultures with no variation`,`Can vary across cultures, as the specific cognitive skills and tools emphasized depend on what is valued and taught within a particular cultural/social context`,`Is entirely independent of any social or cultural influences`,`Occurs in a fixed sequence that cannot be influenced by education`], ans:1, exp:`Because Vygotsky emphasized the role of culturally-specific tools, language, and social practices in shaping cognition, his theory allows for greater cross-cultural variation in the specific cognitive skills emphasized and the trajectories of development, compared to Piaget's more universal stage-based model.` },
      { q:`A teacher who initially provides a worked example, then gradually has students complete more of a problem independently, removing support as students demonstrate competence, is applying the concept of:`, ch:[`Stimulus generalization`,`Scaffolding within the zone of proximal development`,`Negative reinforcement`,`The personal fable`], ans:1, exp:`This describes a classic application of scaffolding ŌĆö providing initial support tailored to a level just beyond the student's independent capability (within the ZPD), and progressively withdrawing that support as the student's competence grows, fostering eventual independent mastery.` },
      { q:`"Guided participation," a concept related to Vygotsky's ideas, describes:`, ch:[`A child learning entirely alone with no guidance from others`,`The process by which children learn cultural skills and knowledge through active engagement in everyday activities alongside more experienced individuals (e.g., participating in cooking, errands, or work alongside adults)`,`A purely formal, classroom-based instructional method only`,`A concept unrelated to cultural context`], ans:1, exp:`Guided participation (associated with Barbara Rogoff, building on Vygotskian ideas) describes how children in many cultures learn through participation in routine, culturally meaningful activities alongside adults and more experienced peers ŌĆö emphasizing that learning often occurs through informal, everyday social engagement, not just formal instruction.` },
      { q:`In a healthcare setting, a nurse demonstrating a new self-care technique to a patient (e.g., insulin injection), then having the patient practice with supervision and feedback, and gradually allowing the patient to perform the technique independently, reflects which educational concept?`, ch:[`Punishment-based learning`,`Scaffolding, gradually transferring responsibility from the instructor to the learner as competence develops`,`Stimulus discrimination`,`A purely Piagetian, discovery-based approach with no instructor involvement`], ans:1, exp:`This patient education approach mirrors scaffolding: providing structured support and modeling initially, then gradually reducing assistance as the patient (learner) demonstrates increasing competence, ultimately enabling independent performance of the skill.` },
      { q:`Vygotsky's concept of cognitive development being fundamentally a "social" process implies that:`, ch:[`Higher mental functions (e.g., advanced reasoning, problem-solving strategies) initially appear in interactions between people (interpsychological) before being internalized by the individual (intrapsychological)`,`All cognitive functions are present from birth and require no social input`,`Social interactions only matter for emotional development, not cognitive development`,`Children develop higher mental functions in complete isolation before any social contact`], ans:0, exp:`Vygotsky's "general genetic law of cultural development" proposes that higher mental functions first appear on the social plane (between people, e.g., a child and adult collaboratively solving a problem) before being internalized onto the individual psychological plane ŌĆö development thus moves from social/external to individual/internal.` },
      { q:`Which scenario best illustrates a task within a child's "zone of proximal development"?`, ch:[`A task the child can already complete perfectly without any help`,`A task the child cannot complete even with extensive, repeated assistance from an expert`,`A task the child cannot complete alone but can complete successfully with hints and guidance from a parent or teacher`,`A task that has no solution at all`], ans:2, exp:`The ZPD specifically refers to tasks that lie just beyond a learner's current independent ability but are achievable with appropriate support ŌĆö tasks already mastered (no help needed) or far beyond reach (even extensive help insufficient) fall outside the ZPD.` },
      { q:`Why might Vygotsky's emphasis on cultural and social context be particularly relevant when assessing cognitive development or designing educational interventions for children from diverse cultural backgrounds?`, ch:[`Because cognitive assessments and educational approaches developed within one cultural context may not directly translate to children from different cultural/linguistic backgrounds, whose cognitive development has been shaped by different tools, language, and social practices`,`Because cognitive development is identical across all cultures, making cultural context irrelevant`,`Because Vygotsky's theory applies only to children in Russia`,`Because culture has no influence on language development`], ans:0, exp:`Vygotsky's framework highlights that cognitive skills and the "tools of thought" emphasized (language, numerical systems, problem-solving approaches) are culturally embedded ŌĆö assessments or interventions developed in one cultural/linguistic context may inadvertently disadvantage or misjudge children whose development has occurred within a different sociocultural framework, underscoring the importance of culturally responsive approaches in education and assessment.` },
      { q:`A child can solve a simple addition problem alone but cannot yet solve a multi-step word problem alone ŌĆö however, with a teacher asking guiding questions, the child successfully solves the word problem. According to Vygotsky, the word problem represents a task:`, ch:[`Below the child's current independent ability level`,`Within the child's zone of proximal development`,`Entirely beyond the child's capability, even with assistance`,`Unrelated to the child's cognitive development`], ans:1, exp:`Since the child cannot solve the word problem independently but CAN solve it with guided assistance, this task falls within the ZPD ŌĆö representing the "next step" in development that is achievable through scaffolded social interaction, and ideal for targeted instruction.` }
    ]
  },
{
  id:`ps29`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Psychotherapy Approaches`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
    { q:`A therapist helps a client identify and challenge distorted automatic thoughts that contribute to depression. This describes which approach?`, ch:[`Psychoanalysis`,`Cognitive-behavioral therapy`,`Humanistic therapy`,`Systematic desensitization alone`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) focuses on identifying and restructuring maladaptive thoughts and behaviors, helping clients recognize cognitive distortions (e.g., catastrophizing, all-or-nothing thinking) and replace them with more balanced thinking patterns.` },
    { q:`Carl Rogers' client-centered therapy emphasizes which therapist qualities?`, ch:[`Interpretation of unconscious conflicts`,`Unconditional positive regard, empathy, and genuineness`,`Systematic reinforcement schedules`, `Direct behavioral modeling`], ans:1, exp:`Rogers proposed that unconditional positive regard, empathy, and genuineness create a supportive environment that allows clients to achieve self-actualization and personal growth, central to humanistic therapy.` },
    { q:`Exposure therapy is most directly based on which learning principle?`, ch:[`Operant shaping`,`Extinction of a conditioned fear response through repeated exposure without the feared outcome`,`Observational learning`,`Latent learning`], ans:1, exp:`Exposure therapy repeatedly presents the feared stimulus without the aversive outcome, leading to extinction of the conditioned fear response, commonly used for phobias and PTSD.` },
    { q:`A psychodynamic therapist notices that a client reacts to her with the same hostility he felt toward his father. This phenomenon is called:`, ch:[`Resistance`,`Transference`,`Free association`,`Countertransference`], ans:1, exp:`Transference occurs when a client redirects feelings about important figures (often parents) onto the therapist, a key concept used in psychoanalytic therapy to explore unresolved conflicts.` },
    { q:`Group therapy is particularly effective for which of the following reasons?`, ch:[`It eliminates the need for individual insight`,`It provides social support, normalization of experiences, and interpersonal feedback`,`It guarantees faster results than individual therapy in all cases`,`It removes the influence of group dynamics`], ans:1, exp:`Group therapy leverages universality (realizing others share similar struggles), social support, and interpersonal learning through feedback from peers, which can enhance treatment outcomes.` },
    { q:`Dialectical behavior therapy (DBT) was originally developed to treat which condition?`, ch:[`Schizophrenia`,`Borderline personality disorder`,`Specific phobia`,`Generalized anxiety disorder only`], ans:1, exp:`DBT, developed by Marsha Linehan, combines CBT techniques with mindfulness and was originally designed to treat borderline personality disorder, particularly chronic suicidality and emotional dysregulation.` },
    { q:`In behavior therapy, "token economies" operate primarily through which mechanism?`, ch:[`Classical conditioning`,`Operant conditioning using secondary reinforcers exchangeable for rewards`,`Modeling alone`,`Insight-oriented reflection`], ans:1, exp:`Token economies use tokens as conditioned (secondary) reinforcers that can be exchanged for primary reinforcers or privileges, shaping behavior through operant conditioning principles.` },
    { q:`A key limitation of insight-oriented therapies for severe psychotic disorders is:`, ch:[`They are too expensive`,`They require a level of cognitive organization and reality testing that may be impaired during acute psychosis`,`They cannot be delivered in groups`,`They have no theoretical basis`], ans:1, exp:`Insight-oriented therapies require the client to engage in abstract reflection and reality testing, which can be severely impaired during acute psychotic episodes, making supportive and pharmacological approaches more appropriate initially.` },
    { q:`Motivational interviewing is most useful for which clinical goal?`, ch:[`Diagnosing structural brain abnormalities`,`Resolving ambivalence about behavior change, such as substance use`,`Treating acute psychotic symptoms`,`Conducting neuropsychological testing`], ans:1, exp:`Motivational interviewing is a client-centered counseling style that helps resolve ambivalence and strengthens motivation for change, frequently used in substance use treatment.` },
    { q:`Which therapy modality specifically targets the relationship between thoughts, feelings, behaviors, and physiological responses in a structured, time-limited format?`, ch:[`Long-term psychoanalysis`,`Cognitive-behavioral therapy`,`Existential therapy`,`Gestalt therapy`], ans:1, exp:`CBT is structured, time-limited, and focuses on the interplay between cognition, emotion, behavior, and physiology, often using homework assignments and skill-building.` },
    { q:`A therapist using free association and dream analysis to uncover repressed conflicts is practicing:`, ch:[`Behavior therapy`,`Psychoanalysis`,`Cognitive therapy`,`Family systems therapy`], ans:1, exp:`Free association and dream analysis are classic psychoanalytic techniques aimed at accessing unconscious material believed to underlie psychological symptoms.` },
    { q:`Family systems therapy views an individual's symptoms primarily as:`, ch:[`Isolated biochemical abnormalities`,`A reflection of dysfunctional patterns within the family unit`,`Solely the result of genetic factors`,`Unrelated to interpersonal context`], ans:1, exp:`Family systems therapy conceptualizes individual symptoms as embedded within and maintained by family interaction patterns, focusing treatment on the family unit rather than the individual alone.` },
    { q:`Which is an example of systematic desensitization?`, ch:[`Flooding a patient with the most feared stimulus immediately`,`Gradually pairing relaxation with a hierarchy of increasingly feared stimuli`,`Punishing avoidance behavior`,`Ignoring the phobia entirely`], ans:1, exp:`Systematic desensitization pairs relaxation techniques with a graduated hierarchy of feared stimuli, allowing the client to gradually become desensitized to the anxiety-provoking stimulus.` },
    { q:`Biofeedback as a therapeutic technique relies on:`, ch:[`Unconscious conflict resolution`,`Providing real-time physiological information to help patients learn voluntary control over involuntary functions`,`Group social pressure`,`Pharmacological intervention`], ans:1, exp:`Biofeedback provides real-time data on physiological processes (e.g., heart rate, muscle tension) so patients can learn to consciously regulate these typically involuntary responses, useful for conditions like tension headaches.` },
    { q:`Which factor is considered a common factor across effective psychotherapies, regardless of theoretical orientation?`, ch:[`Use of medication`,`The therapeutic alliance between therapist and client`,`Length of training of the therapist`,`Avoidance of discussing emotions`], ans:1, exp:`Research consistently identifies the therapeutic allianceŌĆöthe collaborative, trusting relationship between therapist and clientŌĆöas one of the strongest predictors of positive outcomes across different therapy modalities.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps30`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Pharmacological & Brain Stimulation Treatments`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
    { q:`SSRIs treat depression primarily by:`, ch:[`Blocking dopamine receptors`,`Inhibiting the reuptake of serotonin at the presynaptic terminal, increasing synaptic availability`,`Increasing GABA breakdown`,`Blocking acetylcholine synthesis`], ans:1, exp:`Selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) block the serotonin transporter (SERT), preventing reuptake of serotonin into the presynaptic neuron and increasing its concentration in the synaptic cleft.` },
    { q:`Benzodiazepines exert their anxiolytic effects by:`, ch:[`Blocking NMDA receptors`,`Enhancing GABA-A receptor activity, increasing chloride influx and neuronal inhibition`,`Increasing serotonin synthesis`,`Inhibiting monoamine oxidase`], ans:1, exp:`Benzodiazepines bind to a site on the GABA-A receptor distinct from GABA itself, enhancing the receptor's response to GABA and increasing chloride ion influx, which hyperpolarizes the neuron and reduces excitability.` },
    { q:`Electroconvulsive therapy (ECT) is most strongly indicated for:`, ch:[`Mild generalized anxiety disorder`,`Severe, treatment-resistant depression, especially with psychotic features or active suicidality`,`Specific phobias`,`Adjustment disorder`], ans:1, exp:`ECT is highly effective for severe, treatment-resistant depression, particularly when psychotic features or imminent suicide risk necessitate rapid symptom relief, often working faster than medications.` },
    { q:`Typical (first-generation) antipsychotics primarily act by:`, ch:[`Blocking D2 dopamine receptors`,`Enhancing serotonin reuptake`,`Blocking NMDA glutamate receptors`,`Increasing dopamine synthesis`], ans:0, exp:`Typical antipsychotics block D2 dopamine receptors, particularly in the mesolimbic pathway, reducing positive symptoms of psychosis, but can also cause extrapyramidal side effects via blockade in the nigrostriatal pathway.` },
    { q:`A major risk associated with abrupt discontinuation of benzodiazepines after long-term use is:`, ch:[`Hypertensive crisis from tyramine`,`Withdrawal seizures due to rebound CNS hyperexcitability`,`Serotonin syndrome`,`Tardive dyskinesia`], ans:1, exp:`Long-term benzodiazepine use leads to GABA receptor downregulation; abrupt discontinuation can cause rebound CNS hyperexcitability, including potentially life-threatening withdrawal seizures.` },
    { q:`Lithium is primarily used to treat which condition, and requires monitoring of which parameter?`, ch:[`Schizophrenia; liver enzymes`,`Bipolar disorder; serum drug levels due to narrow therapeutic index`,`Major depression; blood glucose`,`Generalized anxiety; blood pressure`], ans:1, exp:`Lithium is a mood stabilizer used for bipolar disorder with a narrow therapeutic index, requiring regular monitoring of serum levels to avoid toxicity (which can affect kidneys, thyroid, and the CNS).` },
    { q:`Monoamine oxidase inhibitors (MAOIs) require dietary restriction of tyramine-containing foods to avoid:`, ch:[`Serotonin syndrome only`,`A hypertensive crisis caused by excess norepinephrine release`,`Hepatotoxicity`,`Agranulocytosis`], ans:1, exp:`MAOIs prevent the breakdown of tyramine; when tyramine-rich foods (aged cheese, cured meats) are consumed, excess norepinephrine release can precipitate a dangerous hypertensive crisis.` },
    { q:`Repetitive transcranial magnetic stimulation (rTMS) is approved for treatment-resistant depression and works by:`, ch:[`Inducing a generalized seizure`,`Using magnetic pulses to modulate cortical neuronal activity, particularly in the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex`,`Directly altering genetic expression`,`Surgically implanting electrodes`], ans:1, exp:`rTMS uses magnetic fields to induce electrical currents that modulate activity in targeted cortical regions, commonly the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex, without requiring anesthesia or inducing seizures.` },
    { q:`Atypical (second-generation) antipsychotics differ from typical antipsychotics in that they also significantly:`, ch:[`Block serotonin 5-HT2A receptors, reducing extrapyramidal side effects while addressing negative symptoms`,`Have no metabolic side effects`,`Act exclusively on GABA receptors`,`Cannot treat positive symptoms`], ans:0, exp:`Atypical antipsychotics block both D2 and 5-HT2A receptors, which is thought to reduce extrapyramidal side effects compared to typical antipsychotics while also providing some benefit for negative symptoms, though metabolic side effects (weight gain, diabetes risk) are common.` },
    { q:`Stimulant medications like methylphenidate treat ADHD by primarily increasing synaptic levels of:`, ch:[`Serotonin and acetylcholine`,`Dopamine and norepinephrine`,`GABA and glycine`,`Histamine`], ans:1, exp:`Stimulants like methylphenidate block the reuptake of dopamine and norepinephrine, increasing their availability in the prefrontal cortex and improving attention and impulse control in ADHD.` },
    { q:`A serious risk of combining SSRIs with MAOIs is:`, ch:[`Hypoglycemia`,`Serotonin syndrome, characterized by hyperthermia, autonomic instability, and altered mental status`,`Tardive dyskinesia`,`Hepatic failure exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Combining SSRIs with MAOIs can cause excessive serotonergic activity, leading to serotonin syndromeŌĆöa potentially life-threatening condition with hyperthermia, agitation, autonomic instability, and neuromuscular abnormalities.` },
    { q:`Deep brain stimulation (DBS) has been investigated as a treatment for severe, treatment-resistant cases of which condition?`, ch:[`Common cold`,`Obsessive-compulsive disorder and Parkinson's disease`,`Mild seasonal allergies`,`Acute appendicitis`], ans:1, exp:`DBS involves implanting electrodes in specific brain regions to modulate abnormal neural circuit activity and has shown benefit in severe treatment-resistant OCD and motor symptoms of Parkinson's disease.` },
    { q:`A common cognitive side effect associated with ECT is:`, ch:[`Permanent loss of all long-term memories`,`Transient anterograde and retrograde amnesia, typically improving after treatment`,`Immediate cure of all psychiatric symptoms with no side effects`,`Increased IQ`], ans:1, exp:`ECT commonly causes transient memory disturbances, including anterograde and retrograde amnesia around the time of treatment, which generally improve in the weeks following the course of treatment.` },
    { q:`Buspirone is an anxiolytic medication that, unlike benzodiazepines, primarily acts on:`, ch:[`GABA-A receptors directly`,`Serotonin 5-HT1A receptors with minimal sedation or dependence risk`,`Opioid receptors`,`Dopamine D2 receptors exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Buspirone is a partial agonist at serotonin 5-HT1A receptors, providing anxiolytic effects with a lower risk of sedation, dependence, and withdrawal compared to benzodiazepines, though it has a delayed onset of action.` },
    { q:`Why might pharmacological treatment alone be insufficient for many psychiatric conditions?`, ch:[`Medications work instantly and permanently`,`Medications may address symptoms but not underlying psychosocial stressors, behaviors, or cognitive patterns, so combined treatment with psychotherapy is often more effective`,`Medications cure all underlying causes`,`Psychotherapy is never effective`], ans:1, exp:`While medications can effectively target neurochemical aspects of psychiatric symptoms, psychosocial stressors, maladaptive thought patterns, and behavioral factors often require psychotherapy; combined treatment frequently yields superior outcomes to either alone.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps31`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Epidemiology Methods`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
    { q:`Incidence is best defined as:`, ch:[`The total number of existing cases of a disease at a given time`,`The number of new cases of a disease occurring in a population during a specified time period`,`The percentage of a population that has ever had a disease`,`The number of deaths caused by a disease`], ans:1, exp:`Incidence measures the rate of new cases of a disease arising in a population over a specified time period, useful for studying disease etiology and risk.` },
    { q:`Prevalence differs from incidence in that prevalence:`, ch:[`Only counts new cases`,`Reflects the total number of existing cases (new and old) at a given point or period in time`,`Is always lower than incidence`,`Cannot be calculated for chronic diseases`], ans:1, exp:`Prevalence reflects the proportion of a population with a condition at a specific time (point prevalence) or over a period (period prevalence), encompassing both new and pre-existing cases, useful for assessing disease burden.` },
    { q:`A study that follows a group of individuals over time, comparing exposed and unexposed groups for the development of disease, is called a:`, ch:[`Case-control study`,`Cohort study`,`Cross-sectional study`,`Case report`], ans:1, exp:`Cohort studies follow groups (cohorts) over time, comparing those exposed to a risk factor with those unexposed, to determine the incidence of disease outcomesŌĆöuseful for calculating relative risk.` },
    { q:`A case-control study compares individuals with a disease to those without, looking back at:`, ch:[`Future outcomes`,`Past exposures to potential risk factors`,`Current symptoms only`,`Genetic sequences exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Case-control studies are retrospective, comparing exposure histories between people who have the disease (cases) and those who do not (controls), often used for rare diseases and yielding odds ratios.` },
    { q:`Relative risk (RR) is calculated as:`, ch:[`The odds of exposure in cases divided by odds of exposure in controls`,`The incidence of disease in the exposed group divided by the incidence in the unexposed group`,`The total number of cases divided by total population`,`The difference between two means`], ans:1, exp:`Relative risk compares the incidence (risk) of disease in an exposed group to the incidence in an unexposed group, indicating how much more (or less) likely the exposed group is to develop the outcome.` },
    { q:`An odds ratio (OR) of 1 indicates:`, ch:[`The exposure strongly increases risk`,`No association between exposure and outcome`,`The exposure is protective`,`The study is invalid`], ans:1, exp:`An odds ratio of 1 indicates that the odds of the outcome are equal between exposed and unexposed groups, suggesting no association between the exposure and the outcome.` },
    { q:`A cross-sectional study examines exposure and outcome:`, ch:[`At the same point in time, providing a "snapshot" of a population`,`Over decades`,`Only in laboratory animals`,`Only in patients with rare diseases`], ans:0, exp:`Cross-sectional studies assess exposure and disease status simultaneously in a population at one point in time, useful for estimating prevalence but unable to establish temporal (causal) relationships.` },
    { q:`Sensitivity of a diagnostic test refers to:`, ch:[`The proportion of people without the disease who test negative`,`The proportion of people with the disease who correctly test positive`,`The cost of the test`,`The proportion of all tests that are positive`], ans:1, exp:`Sensitivity is the true positive rateŌĆöthe proportion of people who actually have the disease and are correctly identified as positive by the test. High sensitivity is useful for ruling out disease (SnNout).` },
    { q:`Specificity of a diagnostic test refers to:`, ch:[`The proportion of people with the disease who test positive`,`The proportion of people without the disease who correctly test negative`,`The total accuracy of the test`,`The prevalence of the disease`], ans:1, exp:`Specificity is the true negative rateŌĆöthe proportion of people who do not have the disease and are correctly identified as negative. High specificity is useful for ruling in disease (SpPin).` },
    { q:`Confounding occurs when:`, ch:[`A third variable is associated with both the exposure and the outcome, distorting the apparent relationship between them`,`The sample size is too small`,`Researchers fail to randomize`,`A study has perfect internal validity`], ans:0, exp:`A confounding variable is independently associated with both the exposure and the outcome, which can create a spurious association or mask a true association if not controlled for.` },
    { q:`Randomized controlled trials (RCTs) are considered the gold standard for establishing causality primarily because:`, ch:[`They are the cheapest study design`,`Random assignment helps balance both known and unknown confounders between groups`,`They never require informed consent`,`They can be conducted retrospectively`], ans:1, exp:`Randomization helps ensure that confounding variables, both measured and unmeasured, are evenly distributed between treatment and control groups, strengthening causal inference.` },
    { q:`Lead-time bias in cancer screening studies refers to:`, ch:[`Earlier detection of disease appearing to prolong survival, even if it does not actually alter the disease course`,`A bias caused by lead exposure`,`Bias from using old equipment`,`Random measurement error`], ans:0, exp:`Lead-time bias occurs when earlier diagnosis (via screening) appears to extend survival time from diagnosis, even though the actual time of death is unchangedŌĆöcreating an illusion of benefit from screening.` },
    { q:`Recall bias is a particular concern in which study design?`, ch:[`Randomized controlled trials`,`Case-control studies, where participants must remember past exposures`,`Cohort studies with objective biomarkers`,`Meta-analyses`], ans:1, exp:`Case-control studies rely on participants recalling past exposures, and those with a disease (cases) may recall exposures differently (often more thoroughly) than controls, introducing recall bias.` },
    { q:`A "number needed to treat" (NNT) of 10 means:`, ch:[`10 patients must be treated for 1 patient to develop the adverse outcome`,`10 patients must be treated to prevent one additional adverse outcome compared to control`,`The treatment works in 10% of patients only`,`10% of patients will experience side effects`], ans:1, exp:`NNT represents the number of patients who need to receive a treatment to prevent one additional bad outcome, calculated as the inverse of the absolute risk reduction; lower NNT generally indicates a more effective treatment.` },
    { q:`Publication bias refers to the tendency for:`, ch:[`Studies with negative or null results to be less likely to be published than those with positive, significant results`,`All studies to be published regardless of findings`,`Journals to favor negative results`,`Bias only in qualitative research`], ans:0, exp:`Publication bias occurs because studies with statistically significant or positive findings are more likely to be submitted and accepted for publication, which can skew the overall evidence base, particularly in meta-analyses.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps32`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Surveys, Sampling & Bias`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
    { q:`A simple random sample is one in which:`, ch:[`Only volunteers are included`,`Every member of the population has an equal chance of being selected`,`Researchers select participants based on convenience`,`Participants are chosen based on referrals from other participants`], ans:1, exp:`In a simple random sample, every individual in the population has an equal probability of being selected, minimizing selection bias and improving generalizability.` },
    { q:`Stratified sampling involves:`, ch:[`Dividing the population into subgroups (strata) based on shared characteristics, then sampling from each stratum`,`Selecting only the most accessible participants`,`Using only one demographic group`,`Sampling without any structure`], ans:1, exp:`Stratified sampling divides the population into meaningful subgroups (e.g., by age, gender, income) and samples from each, ensuring representation of important subgroups in the final sample.` },
    { q:`Convenience sampling is most likely to result in:`, ch:[`Perfect generalizability`,`Selection bias, since participants are chosen based on ease of access rather than randomness`,`Elimination of all confounders`,`Higher internal validity than RCTs`], ans:1, exp:`Convenience sampling selects participants who are easiest to reach, which often introduces selection bias and limits the generalizability of findings to the broader population.` },
    { q:`Social desirability bias in survey research occurs when:`, ch:[`Respondents answer in a way they believe is more socially acceptable rather than truthfully`,`Researchers manipulate the data after collection`,`Sample sizes are too large`,`Surveys are administered electronically`], ans:0, exp:`Social desirability bias occurs when respondents shade their answers toward what they perceive as more socially acceptable, leading to underreporting of stigmatized behaviors (e.g., drug use) and overreporting of positive behaviors (e.g., voting).` },
    { q:`Response bias due to the way a survey question is worded is called:`, ch:[`Sampling error`,`Wording/framing bias`,`Attrition bias`,`Observer bias`], ans:1, exp:`The way a question is phrasedŌĆöincluding loaded language, leading questions, or framingŌĆöcan systematically influence how respondents answer, known as wording or framing bias.` },
    { q:`Non-response bias occurs when:`, ch:[`Everyone in the sample responds`,`Individuals who do not respond to a survey differ in meaningful ways from those who do, skewing results`,`The sample size is too large`,`The survey is too short`], ans:1, exp:`If non-respondents differ systematically from respondents (e.g., busier people, those less interested in the topic), the results from those who did respond may not represent the full sampled population.` },
    { q:`A Likert scale is commonly used to measure:`, ch:[`Categorical data with no order`,`The degree of agreement or disagreement with a statement along an ordinal scale`,`Exact continuous measurements like blood pressure`,`Binary yes/no responses only`], ans:1, exp:`Likert scales present statements with ordered response options (e.g., "strongly disagree" to "strongly agree"), producing ordinal data that captures degree of attitude or opinion.` },
    { q:`Reliability of a measurement instrument refers to:`, ch:[`Whether the instrument measures what it claims to measure`,`The consistency or reproducibility of results across repeated measurements`,`The cost-effectiveness of the instrument`,`The sample size used to validate it`], ans:1, exp:`Reliability concerns the consistency of a measureŌĆöwhether it produces similar results under consistent conditions, such as test-retest reliability or inter-rater reliability.` },
    { q:`Validity of a measurement instrument refers to:`, ch:[`How consistent the results are over time`,`Whether the instrument actually measures the construct it is intended to measure`,`How quickly the instrument can be administered`,`The number of items in the instrument`], ans:1, exp:`Validity concerns whether an instrument truly measures the underlying construct of interest (e.g., does a depression scale actually capture depression severity, and not something else like general distress).` },
    { q:`Attrition bias in a longitudinal study occurs when:`, ch:[`Participants who drop out differ systematically from those who remain, potentially skewing results`,`The sample is too large`,`Researchers fail to use a control group`,`The study duration is too short`], ans:0, exp:`If participants who drop out of a study (attrition) differ in important ways from those who remain (e.g., sicker patients drop out), the remaining sample may no longer be representative, biasing conclusions.` },
    { q:`A double-blind study design is used primarily to reduce:`, ch:[`Sampling error only`,`Both participant expectancy effects and observer/researcher bias`,`The cost of the study`,`The need for informed consent`], ans:1, exp:`In a double-blind study, neither participants nor researchers know group assignments, reducing both placebo/expectancy effects from participants and unconscious bias from researchers in assessing outcomes.` },
    { q:`Random assignment differs from random sampling in that random assignment:`, ch:[`Determines who is included in the study sample`,`Determines which group (e.g., treatment vs. control) each participant is placed into after recruitment`,`Is the same as stratified sampling`,`Eliminates the need for a sample altogether`], ans:1, exp:`Random sampling concerns how participants are selected from the population (affecting generalizability/external validity), while random assignment concerns how selected participants are allocated to study groups (affecting internal validity by balancing confounders).` },
    { q:`A Type I error in hypothesis testing refers to:`, ch:[`Failing to reject a false null hypothesis`,`Incorrectly rejecting a true null hypothesis (a "false positive")`,`Correctly rejecting the null hypothesis`,`Having too small a sample size`], ans:1, exp:`A Type I error occurs when researchers conclude there is a significant effect (reject the null hypothesis) when in reality no such effect existsŌĆöa false positive, with probability denoted by alpha (often set at 0.05).` },
    { q:`A Type II error in hypothesis testing refers to:`, ch:[`Incorrectly rejecting a true null hypothesis`,`Failing to reject a false null hypothesis (a "false negative")`,`Using the wrong statistical test`,`Having a p-value below 0.05`], ans:1, exp:`A Type II error occurs when researchers fail to detect a true effect (fail to reject a false null hypothesis)ŌĆöa false negative, with probability denoted by beta; statistical power equals 1 minus beta.` },
    { q:`Statistical power refers to:`, ch:[`The probability of making a Type I error`,`The probability of correctly rejecting a false null hypothesis (detecting a true effect)`,`The total sample size only`,`The reliability of a survey instrument`], ans:1, exp:`Statistical power is the probability that a study will detect a true effect if one exists (1 - beta); power increases with larger sample sizes, larger effect sizes, and reduced variability.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps33`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Social Mobility & Stratification`, diff:`Medium`, qs:[
    { q:`Social stratification refers to:`, ch:[`The random distribution of resources in society`,`The hierarchical arrangement of individuals and groups based on factors like wealth, power, and prestige`,`A type of psychological disorder`,`The process of aging within a cohort`], ans:1, exp:`Social stratification describes how society organizes individuals into a hierarchy based on access to resources such as wealth, power, and prestige, creating distinct social classes or strata.` },
    { q:`Intergenerational mobility refers to:`, ch:[`Movement within a single person's lifetime career`,`Changes in social status that occur from one generation to the next, e.g., a child achieving a different social class than their parents`,`Migration between countries`,`Movement between different age groups in a single survey`], ans:1, exp:`Intergenerational mobility examines how social position (e.g., class, income, occupation) changes across generations within families, often used to assess equality of opportunity in a society.` },
    { q:`Intragenerational mobility refers to:`, ch:[`Changes in an individual's own social status during their lifetime`,`Mobility that only occurs between countries`,`A purely biological process`,`Mobility that cannot be measured`], ans:0, exp:`Intragenerational mobility refers to changes in an individual's social status (e.g., income, occupation) that occur within their own lifetime, such as moving from a working-class job to a managerial position.` },
    { q:`A meritocracy is a social system in which:`, ch:[`Social position is determined entirely by inherited wealth`,`Social position is ideally determined by individual ability and effort rather than inherited status`,`Social mobility is impossible`,`All individuals have identical incomes`], ans:1, exp:`In a meritocracy, social position is theoretically based on individual talent, effort, and achievement rather than ascribed characteristics like family background, though critics argue true meritocracy rarely exists due to structural inequalities.` },
    { q:`Cultural capital, as conceptualized by Bourdieu, refers to:`, ch:[`Monetary savings`,`Non-financial assets such as education, knowledge, and tastes that promote social mobility`,`Physical infrastructure`,`Government subsidies`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural capital includes non-financial social assetsŌĆöeducation, language skills, tastes, and cultural knowledgeŌĆöthat can be leveraged to gain social advantages and influence social mobility.` },
    { q:`Social capital refers to:`, ch:[`The networks of relationships and connections that provide individuals with access to resources and opportunities`,`A person's total financial wealth`,`The amount of formal education a person has`,`Government tax revenue`], ans:0, exp:`Social capital encompasses the value derived from social networks and relationships, which can provide access to information, job opportunities, and support, influencing an individual's life chances.` },
    { q:`Structural mobility refers to:`, ch:[`Mobility resulting from an individual's personal effort alone`,`Shifts in the social structure itself, such as economic changes, that move large numbers of people up or down regardless of individual effort`,`A type of downward mobility only`,`Mobility that occurs only in agrarian societies`], ans:1, exp:`Structural mobility occurs when changes in the broader economy or social structure (e.g., the shift from manufacturing to service jobs) shift large numbers of people's social positions, independent of individual merit.` },
    { q:`The "feminization of poverty" refers to:`, ch:[`A decrease in poverty rates among women`,`The disproportionate representation of women, especially single mothers, among the poor`,`A trend that affects only men`,`A historical phenomenon with no modern relevance`], ans:1, exp:`The feminization of poverty describes the trend in which women, particularly single mothers and elderly women, make up a disproportionate share of those living in poverty, often linked to wage gaps and caregiving responsibilities.` },
    { q:`Conflict theory views social stratification primarily as:`, ch:[`A natural and beneficial system that ensures the most qualified people fill important roles`,`A mechanism by which dominant groups maintain power and exploit subordinate groups`,`Irrelevant to understanding society`,`A purely psychological phenomenon`], ans:1, exp:`Conflict theory, rooted in Marxist thought, views stratification as arising from competition over scarce resources, with dominant groups using their power to maintain their advantageous position at the expense of subordinate groups.` },
    { q:`Functionalist theory explains social stratification by arguing that:`, ch:[`It serves no purpose and should be eliminated`,`Unequal rewards motivate individuals to fill important and difficult roles in society`,`It is caused entirely by individual laziness`,`It only exists in industrialized nations`], ans:1, exp:`Functionalists argue that stratification exists because society needs to motivate the most talented individuals to fill the most functionally important and demanding positions by offering greater rewards.` },
    { q:`Davis-Moore thesis is associated with which sociological perspective on stratification?`, ch:[`Symbolic interactionism`,`Functionalism`,`Conflict theory`,`Feminist theory exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`The Davis-Moore thesis is a functionalist explanation proposing that stratification exists because it ensures that the most qualified individuals are motivated to occupy the most important social positions through differential rewards.` },
    { q:`A "glass ceiling" refers to:`, ch:[`A literal architectural feature`,`Invisible structural barriers that prevent women and minorities from advancing to top leadership positions`,`A government policy promoting equal pay`,`A type of educational degree`], ans:1, exp:`The glass ceiling describes invisible, often informal barriersŌĆösuch as bias and lack of mentorshipŌĆöthat prevent qualified women and minorities from rising to senior leadership positions despite their qualifications.` },
    { q:`Income inequality is best measured using which statistical tool?`, ch:[`The Gini coefficient`,`Standard deviation of height`,`The mode of a dataset`,`Chi-square statistic`], ans:0, exp:`The Gini coefficient is a widely used measure of income or wealth inequality within a population, ranging from 0 (perfect equality) to 1 (perfect inequality).` },
    { q:`Status inconsistency occurs when:`, ch:[`An individual's rankings on different dimensions of social stratification (e.g., education, income, occupational prestige) are not aligned`,`A person has the same status across all dimensions`,`A person has no social status at all`,`Status is determined randomly`], ans:0, exp:`Status inconsistency describes a situation where a person ranks differently across various status dimensionsŌĆöfor example, a highly educated individual (high status in education) working in a low-paying job (low status in income).` },
    { q:`Which factor is most strongly associated with reduced intergenerational social mobility in a society?`, ch:[`Universal access to high-quality education`,`Significant disparities in access to education and resources based on family socioeconomic status`,`High rates of voter turnout`,`Low rates of unemployment`], ans:1, exp:`When access to quality education and other resources is heavily dependent on a family's existing socioeconomic status, children from disadvantaged backgrounds face structural barriers to upward mobility, reducing overall intergenerational mobility.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps34`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Attribution Errors & Social Cognition`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`The fundamental attribution error refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Overemphasize situational factors and underemphasize dispositional factors when explaining others' behavior`,`Overemphasize dispositional (personality) factors and underemphasize situational factors when explaining others' behavior`,`Always attribute one's own failures to external factors`,`Avoid making any attributions about behavior`], ans:1, exp:`The fundamental attribution error describes the tendency to overattribute others' behavior to internal traits or dispositions while underestimating the influence of situational factorsŌĆöe.g., assuming someone who is late is lazy rather than considering traffic.` },
    { q:`The actor-observer bias describes the tendency to:`, ch:[`Attribute our own behavior to situational factors but others' behavior to dispositional factors`,`Attribute our own behavior to dispositional factors but others' behavior to situational factors`,`Never make attributions about our own behavior`,`Treat all behaviors identically regardless of actor`], ans:0, exp:`The actor-observer bias reflects our tendency to explain our own behavior in terms of situational constraints (e.g., "I was late because of traffic") while attributing the same behavior in others to their character (e.g., "they're late because they're irresponsible").` },
    { q:`The self-serving bias involves:`, ch:[`Attributing successes to internal factors and failures to external factors`,`Attributing successes to external factors and failures to internal factors`,`Treating success and failure identically`,`Only occurring in clinical populations`], ans:0, exp:`Self-serving bias protects self-esteem by attributing one's successes to internal, stable factors (e.g., skill, effort) while attributing failures to external, situational factors (e.g., bad luck, unfair circumstances).` },
    { q:`The halo effect describes the cognitive bias in which:`, ch:[`A person's negative trait causes us to view all of their other traits negatively`,`A person's positive trait (e.g., physical attractiveness) leads us to assume they have other positive qualities`,`We always judge people accurately`,`We ignore physical appearance entirely`], ans:1, exp:`The halo effect occurs when a single positive trait (often attractiveness or competence in one area) creates a generalized positive impression, leading observers to assume the person also possesses other unrelated positive qualities.` },
    { q:`Confirmation bias in social cognition refers to:`, ch:[`Seeking out and interpreting information in ways that confirm pre-existing beliefs while ignoring contradictory evidence`,`Always changing one's beliefs based on new evidence`,`A bias that only affects scientists`,`Random information processing`], ans:0, exp:`Confirmation bias leads individuals to selectively attend to, interpret, and recall information in ways that support their existing beliefs or hypotheses, while disregarding or discounting disconfirming evidence.` },
    { q:`Just-world hypothesis refers to the belief that:`, ch:[`The world is inherently chaotic and unfair`,`People generally get what they deserve, leading observers to sometimes blame victims for their misfortunes`,`Justice systems are always fair`,`Bad things never happen to good people in reality`], ans:1, exp:`The just-world hypothesis is the belief that the world is fundamentally fair, which can lead people to blame victims of misfortune (e.g., assuming a crime victim "must have done something" to deserve it) to maintain this belief.` },
    { q:`According to social comparison theory, individuals evaluate their own abilities and opinions by:`, ch:[`Never comparing themselves to others`,`Comparing themselves to others, particularly those who are similar (similar others)`,`Only comparing themselves to people who are vastly superior`,`Relying solely on objective external standards`], ans:1, exp:`Social comparison theory proposes that people evaluate their own opinions and abilities by comparing themselves to others, especially those perceived as similar, in the absence of objective standards.` },
    { q:`A schema is best described as:`, ch:[`A random, unorganized collection of memories`,`A cognitive framework or set of expectations that helps organize and interpret information`,`A type of personality disorder`,`A purely physiological brain structure`], ans:1, exp:`Schemas are mental frameworks that help individuals organize, interpret, and predict information based on prior knowledge and experience, but they can also lead to biased information processing when new information is forced to fit existing schemas.` },
    { q:`The "false consensus effect" refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Underestimate how many others share our beliefs and behaviors`,`Overestimate the extent to which others share our own beliefs, attitudes, and behaviors`,`Never consider others' opinions`,`Only occur in collectivist cultures`], ans:1, exp:`The false consensus effect describes the tendency to overestimate how typical or widespread one's own beliefs, opinions, and behaviors are among the general population, often used to validate one's own views.` },
    { q:`Stereotype threat refers to:`, ch:[`The phenomenon where individuals underperform on tasks due to anxiety about confirming a negative stereotype about their group`,`A type of physical threat to one's safety`,`A bias that only affects majority group members`,`The complete absence of stereotypes in a society`], ans:0, exp:`Stereotype threat occurs when individuals are aware of a negative stereotype about their group (e.g., regarding academic performance) and the resulting anxiety can impair their actual performance on related tasks, becoming a self-fulfilling prophecy.` },
    { q:`Implicit bias refers to:`, ch:[`Conscious, deliberate prejudicial attitudes that a person openly endorses`,`Unconscious attitudes or stereotypes that affect understanding, actions, and decisions without conscious awareness`,`A bias that can be completely eliminated through a single training session`,`A bias only present in individuals with explicit prejudiced beliefs`], ans:1, exp:`Implicit biases are unconscious associations or attitudes that influence behavior and judgment outside of conscious awareness, often measured using tools like the Implicit Association Test (IAT), and can exist even in individuals who consciously reject prejudice.` },
    { q:`The "spotlight effect" describes the tendency for people to:`, ch:[`Believe that others are paying less attention to them than they actually are`,`Overestimate the extent to which others notice and evaluate their appearance and behavior`,`Avoid all social situations`,`Have accurate perceptions of how much others notice them`], ans:1, exp:`The spotlight effect refers to the tendency to overestimate how much other people notice our appearance, mistakes, or behaviors, as we are highly focused on ourselves while others are typically less attentive to us than we assume.` },
    { q:`Priming in social cognition refers to:`, ch:[`Exposure to a stimulus influencing the response to a subsequent stimulus, often without conscious awareness`,`A method of permanently changing personality traits`,`Only occurring in laboratory settings with no real-world relevance`,`A type of memory disorder`], ans:0, exp:`Priming occurs when exposure to one stimulus influences a person's response to a later stimulus, often outside conscious awarenessŌĆöe.g., being exposed to words related to "elderly" might cause someone to walk more slowly afterward.` },
    { q:`Cognitive dissonance theory proposes that individuals are motivated to:`, ch:[`Maintain inconsistency between their beliefs and behaviors`,`Reduce psychological discomfort arising from holding contradictory beliefs or from a mismatch between beliefs and behaviors`,`Never change their attitudes once formed`,`Avoid all forms of self-reflection`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive dissonance theory, proposed by Festinger, suggests that holding contradictory cognitions creates psychological discomfort, motivating individuals to reduce this dissonance by changing beliefs, behaviors, or rationalizing the inconsistency.` },
    { q:`In an experiment, smokers who are told smoking causes cancer might rationalize by saying "my grandfather smoked and lived to 90." This best illustrates:`, ch:[`Reduction of cognitive dissonance through rationalization`,`The halo effect`,`Stereotype threat`,`The spotlight effect`], ans:0, exp:`This is an example of reducing cognitive dissonanceŌĆöthe smoker holds two conflicting cognitions (smoking is harmful vs. I smoke) and reduces the resulting discomfort by generating a counterargument that minimizes the perceived risk.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps35`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Persuasion: Framing, Heuristics & Inoculation`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Message framing effects demonstrate that people respond differently to information depending on whether it is presented as:`, ch:[`A gain or a loss, even when the objective outcomes are equivalent`,`Written or spoken`,`Long or short`,`In color or black and white`], ans:0, exp:`Framing effects show that logically equivalent information can lead to different decisions depending on whether it is framed in terms of potential gains (e.g., "90% survival rate") or losses (e.g., "10% mortality rate").` },
    { q:`The availability heuristic leads people to judge the probability of an event based on:`, ch:[`Formal statistical analysis`,`How easily examples of the event come to mind`,`The opinions of experts only`,`Random chance`], ans:1, exp:`The availability heuristic causes people to estimate the likelihood of events based on how readily examples come to mind, which can lead to overestimating the frequency of vivid or memorable events (e.g., plane crashes) relative to their actual statistical likelihood.` },
    { q:`The representativeness heuristic involves judging the probability of an event by:`, ch:[`How much it resembles a typical case or prototype, sometimes ignoring base rate information`,`Calculating exact statistical probabilities`,`Considering only recent events`,`Asking multiple independent experts`], ans:0, exp:`The representativeness heuristic involves assessing likelihood based on similarity to a prototype or stereotype, which can lead to errors such as the base rate fallacy, where statistical base rates are ignored in favor of perceived resemblance.` },
    { q:`Anchoring bias refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Ignore all numerical information presented`,`Rely too heavily on the first piece of information encountered (the "anchor") when making subsequent judgments`,`Always choose the lowest-priced option`,`Make decisions purely based on emotion`], ans:1, exp:`Anchoring bias occurs when an initial piece of information (the anchor) disproportionately influences subsequent judgments and estimates, even when the anchor is arbitrary or irrelevant.` },
    { q:`Inoculation theory proposes that attitudes can be made resistant to persuasion by:`, ch:[`Avoiding any exposure to counterarguments`,`Exposing individuals to weakened versions of counterarguments along with refutations, similar to a vaccine`,`Repeatedly punishing individuals for changing their minds`,`Providing only one-sided information`], ans:1, exp:`Inoculation theory suggests that exposing people to weakened counterarguments, paired with refutations, helps them develop "mental antibodies" that make them more resistant to future persuasion attempts using similar argumentsŌĆöuseful in countering misinformation.` },
    { q:`The "need for cognition" personality trait describes individuals who:`, ch:[`Avoid effortful thinking and rely on heuristics`,`Enjoy and engage in effortful cognitive activities, such as analyzing arguments in depth`,`Cannot process information at all`,`Are always persuaded by peripheral cues`], ans:1, exp:`Individuals high in need for cognition tend to engage more deeply with arguments, processing information via the central route, and are thus more influenced by argument quality than by peripheral cues like source attractiveness.` },
    { q:`According to the Elaboration Likelihood Model, the central route to persuasion is most effective when the audience:`, ch:[`Is highly motivated and able to think carefully about the message content`,`Is distracted and unmotivated`,`Relies on superficial cues like the speaker's appearance`,`Has no interest in the topic`], ans:0, exp:`The central route involves careful, thoughtful consideration of the actual content and arguments of a message, leading to more durable attitude change, and is more likely when the audience has both the motivation and ability to process the message.` },
    { q:`The peripheral route to persuasion relies on cues such as:`, ch:[`The logical strength of arguments`,`Source attractiveness, credibility, or emotional appeals rather than message content`,`Statistical evidence`,`Detailed scientific data`], ans:1, exp:`The peripheral route involves persuasion through superficial cues unrelated to the actual argument qualityŌĆösuch as the attractiveness or credibility of the source, emotional appeals, or the sheer number of arguments presentedŌĆöoften resulting in less durable attitude change.` },
    { q:`Foot-in-the-door technique relies on the principle that:`, ch:[`Agreeing to a small initial request increases the likelihood of agreeing to a larger subsequent request`,`Making a large request first increases compliance with later small requests`,`People never comply with multiple requests`,`Compliance is unrelated to prior behavior`], ans:0, exp:`The foot-in-the-door technique leverages the consistency principleŌĆöafter agreeing to a small request, people are more likely to comply with a larger related request to maintain a self-perception of being helpful or consistent.` },
    { q:`The door-in-the-face technique involves:`, ch:[`Making an extreme initial request that is likely refused, followed by a smaller, more reasonable request`,`Slamming a literal door`,`Only making one request ever`,`Gradually increasing request size over many interactions`], ans:0, exp:`The door-in-the-face technique starts with an unreasonably large request (likely refused), followed by a smaller request, which appears more reasonable by comparison and triggers a sense of reciprocal concession, increasing compliance.` },
    { q:`Vaccine hesitancy campaigns that "pre-bunk" common myths before individuals encounter misinformation are applying which concept?`, ch:[`The availability heuristic`,`Inoculation theory`,`The halo effect`,`Anchoring bias`], ans:1, exp:`Pre-bunking misinformation by exposing people to weakened forms of false claims along with corrections, before they encounter the actual misinformation, applies inoculation theory to build resistance to persuasion by misleading content.` },
    { q:`The "illusory truth effect" refers to the phenomenon where:`, ch:[`Repeated exposure to a statement increases the likelihood that it will be perceived as true, regardless of its actual veracity`,`People always recognize false statements upon first exposure`,`Truth is determined solely by source credibility`,`Statements become less believable with repetition`], ans:0, exp:`The illusory truth effect demonstrates that repeated exposure to a statement, even a false one, increases its perceived truthfulness due to increased processing fluency, which has implications for how misinformation spreads.` },
    { q:`Framing a medical decision as "70% of patients survive this surgery" versus "30% of patients die from this surgery" demonstrates:`, ch:[`A statistical error since the framings are not equivalent`,`Equivalent information presented with different emotional framing, which can influence patient decision-making`,`That patients always choose the surgery regardless of framing`,`A violation of informed consent regulations`], ans:1, exp:`Although mathematically equivalent, framing outcomes in terms of survival (gain frame) versus mortality (loss frame) can significantly influence patient choices, illustrating the powerful effect of framing on medical decision-making.` },
    { q:`The "bandwagon effect" in persuasion refers to:`, ch:[`The tendency to adopt beliefs or behaviors because many other people are doing so`,`A complete resistance to social influence`,`Only occurring in political contexts`,`A type of cognitive dissonance reduction`], ans:0, exp:`The bandwagon effect describes the tendency for individuals to adopt certain beliefs or behaviors because they perceive that many others have already done so, leveraging social proof as a persuasive mechanism.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps36`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Social Identity Theory`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Social identity theory proposes that individuals derive part of their self-concept from:`, ch:[`Their membership in social groups, leading to in-group favoritism and out-group bias`,`Purely individual achievements with no group influence`,`Random assignment processes`,`Genetic factors exclusively`], ans:0, exp:`Social identity theory, developed by Tajfel and Turner, proposes that people categorize themselves and others into groups, and derive self-esteem from their group memberships, which can lead to favoring in-groups and discriminating against out-groups.` },
    { q:`In-group bias refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Favor members of one's own group over members of other groups`,`Treat all groups with equal regard`,`Favor out-groups over in-groups`,`Avoid forming any group identities`], ans:0, exp:`In-group bias is the tendency to give preferential treatment, more positive evaluations, and greater trust to members of one's own group compared to members of out-groups, even when group membership is based on trivial criteria.` },
    { q:`The "minimal group paradigm" experiments demonstrated that:`, ch:[`In-group favoritism requires long-standing rivalries between groups`,`Even arbitrary, trivial group distinctions (e.g., random assignment) can lead to in-group favoritism and discrimination against out-groups`,`Group identity has no effect on behavior`,`People never discriminate based on group membership`], ans:1, exp:`Minimal group studies showed that even when groups were formed based on entirely arbitrary criteria (e.g., a coin flip), participants still favored their own group in resource allocation, demonstrating how readily group identity influences behavior.` },
    { q:`Social categorization, the first stage of social identity theory, involves:`, ch:[`Comparing one's group favorably to other groups`,`Classifying people, including oneself, into groups based on characteristics like race, gender, or nationality`,`Resolving cognitive dissonance`,`Conducting formal psychological assessments`], ans:1, exp:`Social categorization is the cognitive process of sorting people into groups (in-groups and out-groups) based on salient characteristics, which simplifies the social world but can also form the basis for stereotyping.` },
    { q:`Social comparison, in the context of social identity theory, involves:`, ch:[`Comparing one's in-group to relevant out-groups, often in ways that favor the in-group, to enhance self-esteem`,`Comparing one's current self to one's past self only`,`A process unrelated to group membership`,`Comparing physical measurements between individuals`], ans:0, exp:`Social comparison in social identity theory involves comparing one's in-group to relevant out-groups; favorable comparisons enhance the self-esteem derived from group membership, often motivating biased perceptions favoring the in-group.` },
    { q:`Realistic conflict theory proposes that intergroup hostility arises primarily from:`, ch:[`Random chance`,`Competition between groups for limited resources`,`Individual personality traits alone`,`A lack of any group identity`], ans:1, exp:`Realistic conflict theory, exemplified by the Robbers Cave experiment, suggests that intergroup conflict and prejudice arise from real or perceived competition over scarce resources, such as jobs, land, or status.` },
    { q:`In the Robbers Cave experiment, intergroup hostility between two groups of boys was reduced primarily through:`, ch:[`Increased competition between the groups`,`The introduction of superordinate goals that required cooperation between the groups to achieve`,`Physical separation of the groups permanently`,`Punishing one group for the conflict`], ans:1, exp:`Sherif's Robbers Cave experiment found that intergroup conflict, generated through competition, was reduced when the groups were given superordinate goalsŌĆöshared goals requiring cooperation between groupsŌĆöthat could not be achieved by either group alone.` },
    { q:`Self-categorization theory extends social identity theory by emphasizing that:`, ch:[`Individuals never identify with groups`,`The salience of a particular social identity (vs. personal identity) varies depending on context, influencing behavior accordingly`,`Personal identity is always more salient than social identity`,`Group identities are fixed and never change based on context`], ans:1, exp:`Self-categorization theory builds on social identity theory by proposing that the relative salience of personal versus social identities shifts based on context, and when a social identity is salient, individuals are more likely to think and act in terms of group norms.` },
    { q:`Outgroup homogeneity effect refers to the tendency to:`, ch:[`Perceive members of out-groups as more similar to one another than members of one's in-group`,`Perceive in-group members as more similar to each other than out-group members`,`View all groups as equally diverse`,`Only apply to ethnic groups`], ans:0, exp:`The outgroup homogeneity effect describes the tendency to view members of out-groups as "all the same" while perceiving greater diversity and individuality among members of one's own in-group ("they're all alike, but we're diverse").` },
    { q:`Social identity threat occurs when:`, ch:[`An individual's group identity is devalued or threatened, which can affect performance and well-being`,`A person has no social identity`,`Group identity is irrelevant to self-esteem`,`Threats only affect physical safety`], ans:0, exp:`Social identity threat occurs when situational cues signal that one's group identity is devalued, stigmatized, or at risk, which can lead to psychological stress, reduced performance (similar to stereotype threat), and disengagement.` },
    { q:`Acculturation refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`Individuals or groups adopt the cultural traits or social patterns of another group, often through prolonged contact`,`Genetic traits are passed between generations`,`Social stratification is eliminated`,`Group identity becomes irrelevant`], ans:0, exp:`Acculturation describes the process of cultural and psychological change that results from contact between different cultural groups, which can involve assimilation, integration, separation, or marginalization strategies.` },
    { q:`A new immigrant who maintains strong ties to their heritage culture while also actively participating in the new host culture is exhibiting which acculturation strategy?`, ch:[`Assimilation`,`Integration (biculturalism)`,`Separation`,`Marginalization`], ans:1, exp:`Integration (or biculturalism) involves maintaining one's heritage culture identity while also adopting and participating in the host culture, generally associated with the most positive psychological outcomes among acculturation strategies.` },
    { q:`Ethnocentrism refers to:`, ch:[`Evaluating other cultures using the standards and values of one's own culture, often viewing one's own culture as superior`,`A complete absence of cultural values`,`Valuing all cultures equally without bias`,`A type of clinical disorder`], ans:0, exp:`Ethnocentrism is the tendency to judge other cultures by the standards and values of one's own culture, often accompanied by the belief that one's own culture is superior, which can contribute to prejudice and miscommunication.` },
    { q:`Cultural relativism, in contrast to ethnocentrism, involves:`, ch:[`Judging other cultures by the standards of one's own culture`,`Understanding and evaluating a culture's practices within the context of that culture's own values and norms`,`Believing all cultural practices are equally beneficial regardless of context`,`Avoiding any contact with other cultures`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural relativism involves understanding and interpreting a culture's beliefs and practices according to that culture's own standards, rather than judging them against the norms of an outside culture, which is important for culturally competent healthcare.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps37`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Stigma, Deviance & Labeling`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Labeling theory proposes that deviance is:`, ch:[`An inherent quality of certain acts`,`Socially constructed, with behaviors becoming "deviant" when society labels them as such`,`Determined solely by genetics`,`Always punished equally across cultures`], ans:1, exp:`Labeling theory argues that deviance is not an inherent property of an act itself, but is instead a social construct created when society labels certain behaviors or individuals as deviant, which can shape subsequent identity and behavior.` },
    { q:`A "self-fulfilling prophecy" in the context of labeling theory occurs when:`, ch:[`A label has no effect on a person's future behavior`,`Being labeled as deviant leads an individual to internalize that label and behave in ways consistent with it`,`Labels are always accurate representations of behavior`,`Labels are removed immediately after being applied`], ans:1, exp:`When individuals are labeled as deviant (e.g., "criminal" or "troublemaker"), they may internalize this label as part of their self-concept and subsequently engage in behaviors that conform to the label, reinforcing the original categorization.` },
    { q:`Primary deviance refers to:`, ch:[`Initial acts of rule-breaking that have not yet led to a person being labeled as deviant`,`A criminal record that follows a person permanently`,`Deviance committed only by repeat offenders`,`A type of mental illness`], ans:0, exp:`Primary deviance refers to initial, often minor or unnoticed, acts of rule-breaking that do not result in the individual being publicly labeled or identified as deviant, and thus do not significantly affect their self-concept.` },
    { q:`Secondary deviance occurs when:`, ch:[`A person commits a single deviant act and never repeats it`,`A person, after being labeled deviant, begins to accept and act according to that deviant identity, often leading to a deviant career`,`Deviance is completely eliminated`,`A label has no impact on identity`], ans:1, exp:`Secondary deviance occurs when an individual, having been caught and labeled for an initial deviant act, begins to internalize the deviant label as part of their identity, which can lead to a continuation or escalation of deviant behaviorŌĆöa "deviant career."` },
    { q:`Stigma, as conceptualized by Erving Goffman, refers to:`, ch:[`A neutral characteristic with no social consequences`,`An attribute that is deeply discrediting and reduces an individual from a "whole" person to a "tainted, discounted" one in social interactions`,`A purely legal designation`,`A trait that always leads to social rewards`], ans:1, exp:`Goffman described stigma as a deeply discrediting attribute that spoils an individual's social identity, leading others to view and treat the stigmatized person differentlyŌĆöoften through avoidance, discrimination, or reduced status.` },
    { q:`Felt stigma refers to:`, ch:[`The actual experience of being discriminated against`,`The fear or shame of being discriminated against, which can lead to concealment of a condition even without an actual discriminatory act occurring`,`A condition that has no psychological component`,`A type of physical pain`], ans:1, exp:`Felt stigma refers to the internalized fear and shame of potential discrimination, which can lead individuals to conceal a stigmatized condition (e.g., mental illness, HIV status) even in the absence of overt discriminatory experiences (enacted stigma).` },
    { q:`Enacted stigma, in contrast to felt stigma, refers to:`, ch:[`The actual experience of discrimination or unfair treatment due to a stigmatized attribute`,`Internal feelings of shame only`,`A purely hypothetical concept with no real-world examples`,`Stigma that affects only the stigmatized individual's family`], ans:0, exp:`Enacted stigma describes actual instances of discrimination, exclusion, or unfair treatment that an individual experiences as a direct result of possessing a stigmatized characteristic.` },
    { q:`Differential association theory explains deviance as a result of:`, ch:[`Genetic predisposition alone`,`Learning deviant behaviors, values, and attitudes through interactions with others, particularly intimate groups`,`A complete absence of social interaction`,`Random chance events`], ans:1, exp:`Differential association theory, proposed by Edwin Sutherland, suggests that individuals learn deviant behavior through socialization with othersŌĆöparticularly close, intimate groupsŌĆöwho model and reinforce deviant attitudes, techniques, and rationalizations.` },
    { q:`Strain theory (Merton) explains deviance as resulting from:`, ch:[`A disconnect between culturally valued goals (e.g., wealth) and the legitimate means available to achieve them`,`Pure biological predisposition`,`Equal access to resources for all individuals`,`Labels applied randomly by authorities`], ans:0, exp:`Merton's strain theory proposes that deviance arises when there is a gap between socially approved goals (such as financial success) and the legitimate means available to achieve those goals, leading some individuals to pursue goals through illegitimate means (innovation) or reject the goals altogether.` },
    { q:`According to Merton's strain theory, "retreatism" describes individuals who:`, ch:[`Accept both the cultural goals and the legitimate means to achieve them`,`Reject both the cultural goals and the legitimate means, often withdrawing from society (e.g., substance abuse)`,`Use illegitimate means to achieve culturally approved goals`,`Create entirely new goals and new means`], ans:1, exp:`Retreatism, one of Merton's modes of adaptation, describes individuals who reject both the culturally prescribed goals and the legitimate means of achieving them, often withdrawing from mainstream societyŌĆöexemplified by some forms of chronic substance use.` },
    { q:`Medicalization refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`Conditions are removed from medical classification systems`,`Behaviors or conditions previously seen as moral or social issues come to be defined and treated as medical problems`,`Medical care becomes universally accessible`,`Diseases are eradicated through public health campaigns`], ans:1, exp:`Medicalization describes the process by which behaviors or conditions (e.g., addiction, ADHD, alcoholism) that were previously understood in moral, criminal, or social terms come to be defined and treated as medical conditions requiring diagnosis and treatment.` },
    { q:`A potential downside of medicalization is that it may:`, ch:[`Always reduce stigma with no drawbacks`,`Shift responsibility away from social and structural factors, framing societal problems as purely individual medical issues`,`Increase access to social services exclusively`,`Eliminate the need for any treatment`], ans:1, exp:`Critics argue medicalization can individualize and depoliticize problems that have significant social and structural roots (e.g., poverty contributing to mental health issues), potentially diverting attention from systemic interventions toward individual medical treatment.` },
    { q:`Total institutions, as described by Goffman, are characterized by:`, ch:[`Complete integration with the outside community`,`A closed social system where all aspects of life (work, sleep, leisure) occur in the same place under a single authority`,`Voluntary participation with no rules`,`The absence of any social hierarchy`], ans:1, exp:`Total institutions (e.g., prisons, psychiatric hospitals, military barracks) are settings where individuals are cut off from broader society and all aspects of daily life are conducted in the same place under a single authority, often leading to processes like depersonalization.` },
    { q:`Courtesy stigma (or stigma by association) refers to:`, ch:[`Stigma experienced by individuals who are closely associated with a stigmatized person, such as family members`,`A type of stigma that only affects celebrities`,`Stigma that is always positive`,`A legal term with no social science application`], ans:0, exp:`Courtesy stigma describes the stigma experienced by individuals associated with a stigmatized person or groupŌĆöfor example, family members of someone with a mental illness or substance use disorder may also face social discrimination.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps38`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Health Behavior Models`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`The Health Belief Model proposes that health behaviors are influenced by perceived susceptibility, perceived severity, and:`, ch:[`Perceived benefits and barriers to taking action, plus cues to action`,`Genetic predisposition only`,`Random environmental factors`,`The size of one's social network exclusively`], ans:0, exp:`The Health Belief Model identifies key constructsŌĆöperceived susceptibility, perceived severity, perceived benefits, perceived barriers, cues to action, and self-efficacyŌĆöthat together predict whether a person will engage in a health-promoting behavior.` },
    { q:`Self-efficacy, a key construct in several health behavior theories, refers to:`, ch:[`A person's belief in their own ability to successfully perform a behavior and achieve a desired outcome`,`The actual outcome of a behavior`,`A genetic trait that cannot be changed`,`The cost of healthcare`], ans:0, exp:`Self-efficacy, a concept central to Bandura's social cognitive theory, is an individual's confidence in their ability to execute behaviors necessary to produce specific performance attainments, strongly predicting health behavior change and maintenance.` },
    { q:`The Transtheoretical Model (Stages of Change) proposes that behavior change occurs through which sequence of stages?`, ch:[`Precontemplation, contemplation, preparation, action, maintenance`,`Action, maintenance, precontemplation, contemplation`,`A single instantaneous stage`,`Denial, anger, bargaining, depression, acceptance`], ans:0, exp:`The Transtheoretical Model describes behavior change as a process moving through stages: precontemplation (not considering change), contemplation (considering change), preparation (planning to change), action (actively changing), and maintenance (sustaining change).`},
    { q:`In the Transtheoretical Model, a person in the "contemplation" stage is best described as:`, ch:[`Not intending to change behavior in the foreseeable future`,`Intending to change behavior in the near future but not yet taking action`,`Already actively changing their behavior`,`Having maintained the new behavior for over six months`], ans:1, exp:`In the contemplation stage, individuals are aware that a problem exists and are seriously considering changing their behavior in the near future (typically within the next six months), but have not yet taken concrete action.` },
    { q:`The Theory of Planned Behavior adds which construct to the Theory of Reasoned Action?`, ch:[`Perceived behavioral control`,`Genetic risk factors`,`Socioeconomic status`,`Cultural background`], ans:0, exp:`The Theory of Planned Behavior extends the Theory of Reasoned Action by adding perceived behavioral controlŌĆöan individual's perception of how easy or difficult it is to perform a behaviorŌĆöwhich influences both intentions and behavior directly.` },
    { q:`According to the Theory of Reasoned Action, behavioral intention is the primary determinant of behavior, and is itself influenced by:`, ch:[`Attitudes toward the behavior and subjective norms`,`Only genetic factors`,`Random chance`,`Physical environment exclusively`], ans:0, exp:`The Theory of Reasoned Action proposes that behavioral intentionŌĆöthe strongest predictor of actual behaviorŌĆöis shaped by a person's attitude toward the behavior (positive or negative evaluation) and subjective norms (perceived social pressure).` },
    { q:`The "social ecological model" of health behavior emphasizes that behavior is influenced by factors at multiple levels, including:`, ch:[`Individual, interpersonal, organizational, community, and policy levels`,`Only the individual's genetic makeup`,`A single isolated factor`,`Only governmental regulations`], ans:0, exp:`The social ecological model recognizes that health behaviors are shaped by interacting influences across multiple levelsŌĆöindividual (knowledge, attitudes), interpersonal (relationships), organizational, community, and public policyŌĆösuggesting interventions should target multiple levels.` },
    { q:`Health literacy refers to:`, ch:[`The ability to read any text fluently`,`The degree to which individuals can obtain, process, and understand basic health information needed to make appropriate health decisions`,`A formal medical degree`,`Knowledge of a foreign language`], ans:1, exp:`Health literacy encompasses the skills needed to find, understand, and use health information and services to make informed health decisions; low health literacy is associated with poorer health outcomes and increased healthcare costs.` },
    { q:`Locus of control, as it relates to health behavior, describes:`, ch:[`The belief that health outcomes are determined either by one's own actions (internal) or by external factors like fate or chance (external)`,`A type of physical exam finding`,`A measure of blood pressure`,`The location of a hospital`], ans:0, exp:`Locus of control refers to the degree to which individuals believe they have control over events affecting them; an internal locus of control (believing one's actions determine outcomes) is generally associated with healthier behaviors than an external locus.` },
    { q:`The "precaution adoption process model" differs from the Transtheoretical Model primarily in that it includes a distinct stage for:`, ch:[`People who are unaware of the health issue entirely`,`Only people who have already changed their behavior`,`People who have never heard of the health behavior change concept`,`Action and maintenance only`], ans:0, exp:`The precaution adoption process model includes an initial stage of being unaware of the issue, distinguishing it from models like the Transtheoretical Model, which generally assume some baseline awareness of the health issue even in the precontemplation stage.` },
    { q:`Reactance theory predicts that when individuals feel their freedom to choose is threatened (e.g., by a forceful health message), they may:`, ch:[`Always comply immediately`,`Respond by doing the opposite of what is recommended in order to restore their sense of autonomy`,`Become permanently unable to make decisions`,`Have no emotional response`], ans:1, exp:`Psychological reactance occurs when a perceived threat to freedom (e.g., an overly forceful "you must quit smoking now" message) triggers motivation to restore that freedom, sometimes resulting in increased resistance to the recommended behavior.` },
    { q:`Allostatic load refers to:`, ch:[`The cumulative physiological wear and tear on the body resulting from chronic stress and repeated activation of stress response systems`,`A single acute stress response`,`A type of medication dosage`,`A measure of cognitive intelligence`], ans:0, exp:`Allostatic load describes the cumulative biological burden imposed by repeated or chronic stress, reflecting the long-term effects of the body's stress response systems (e.g., HPA axis, sympathetic nervous system) and contributing to disease risk.` },
    { q:`The "health gradient" refers to the observation that:`, ch:[`Health outcomes are unrelated to socioeconomic status`,`Health outcomes improve incrementally at each step up the socioeconomic ladder, not just at the extremes of poverty and wealth`,`Only the poorest individuals experience health disparities`,`Wealthy individuals always have worse health outcomes`], ans:1, exp:`The health gradient describes a graded relationship between socioeconomic status and healthŌĆöhealth improves at each successive level of income, education, or occupational status, not merely a binary difference between "poor" and "non-poor."` },
    { q:`Which best illustrates the concept of "weathering" in health disparities research?`, ch:[`The cumulative biological impact of chronic exposure to social and economic adversity, leading to accelerated aging and earlier onset of chronic disease in marginalized populations`,`The effect of literal weather on mood`,`A measure of vaccination rates`,`A genetic mutation found only in certain populations`], ans:0, exp:`The weathering hypothesis proposes that chronic exposure to social, economic, and political marginalization leads to accelerated biological aging and earlier onset of health problems among members of marginalized groups, contributing to persistent health disparities.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps39`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Addiction Neuroscience`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`The mesolimbic dopamine pathway, central to reward and addiction, primarily projects from the:`, ch:[`Cerebellum to the occipital lobe`,`Ventral tegmental area (VTA) to the nucleus accumbens`,`Hippocampus to the amygdala`,`Thalamus to the primary motor cortex`], ans:1, exp:`The mesolimbic pathway projects from the ventral tegmental area (VTA) to the nucleus accumbens and is central to the brain's reward circuitry, with dopamine release in this pathway reinforcing behaviors, including drug-seeking.` },
    { q:`Most addictive substances, despite differing mechanisms, ultimately increase:`, ch:[`Dopamine release or activity in the nucleus accumbens`,`Serotonin breakdown exclusively`,`GABA receptor downregulation only`,`Acetylcholine synthesis in the cerebellum`], ans:0, exp:`Despite diverse pharmacological mechanisms, most drugs of abuse converge on increasing dopaminergic transmission in the nucleus accumbens, reinforcing the behaviors associated with drug use and contributing to the development of addiction.` },
    { q:`Tolerance, in the context of substance use, refers to:`, ch:[`A decreased response to a drug requiring increased doses to achieve the same effect`,`An increased response to the same dose of a drug over time`,`Immediate cessation of drug effects`,`A type of allergic reaction`], ans:0, exp:`Tolerance occurs when repeated drug exposure leads to neuroadaptations that decrease the drug's effect, requiring progressively higher doses to achieve the same subjective or physiological response.` },
    { q:`Physical dependence is characterized by:`, ch:[`The presence of withdrawal symptoms upon cessation or dose reduction of a substance`,`A purely psychological craving with no physiological component`,`Complete absence of any neuroadaptation`,`Only occurring with illegal substances`], ans:0, exp:`Physical dependence reflects neuroadaptations that occur with repeated drug use, such that abrupt cessation or dose reduction produces a characteristic withdrawal syndrome, reflecting the body's adjustment to the presence of the drug.` },
    { q:`The opponent-process theory of addiction proposes that:`, ch:[`The brain's response to a stimulus is followed by an opposing process that becomes stronger with repeated exposure, contributing to tolerance and withdrawal`,`Drugs have no lasting effects on brain chemistry`,`Addiction is purely a moral failing`,`Withdrawal symptoms are unrelated to the initial drug effect`], ans:0, exp:`Opponent-process theory suggests that an initial drug-induced state (e.g., euphoria) is followed by an opposing compensatory state (e.g., dysphoria); with repeated use, this opponent process strengthens and outlasts the initial effect, contributing to tolerance and withdrawal-driven craving.` },
    { q:`Sensitization, as it relates to addiction, refers to:`, ch:[`A decreased response to a drug over repeated exposures`,`An increased response to a drug (or drug-associated cues) after repeated exposure, which can contribute to craving`,`Complete immunity to a drug's effects`,`A process unrelated to dopamine`], ans:1, exp:`Sensitization describes an enhanced response to a drug or drug-related cues following repeated exposureŌĆöparticularly relevant to incentive-sensitization theory, which proposes that sensitized dopaminergic responses to drug cues drive craving ("wanting") even when the drug's pleasurable effects ("liking") diminish.` },
    { q:`Incentive-sensitization theory distinguishes between "wanting" and "liking" a drug, proposing that with chronic use:`, ch:[`Both wanting and liking increase proportionally`,`"Wanting" (craving) can increase even as "liking" (pleasure) decreases, driving compulsive drug-seeking despite reduced enjoyment`,`Neither wanting nor liking changes with repeated use`,`Liking always exceeds wanting`], ans:1, exp:`Incentive-sensitization theory proposes that the neural systems mediating "wanting" (incentive salience) become sensitized with repeated drug use, leading to intense craving for the drug even as the hedonic "liking" of the drug's effects diminishesŌĆöexplaining compulsive use despite diminishing pleasure.` },
    { q:`The prefrontal cortex's role in addiction is primarily related to:`, ch:[`Executive function, including impulse control and decision-making, which becomes impaired with chronic drug use`,`Basic motor coordination only`,`Visual processing`,`Auditory processing`], ans:0, exp:`Chronic drug use is associated with structural and functional changes in the prefrontal cortex, impairing executive functions such as impulse control, judgment, and decision-making, which contributes to the compulsive nature of addiction.` },
    { q:`Cue-induced craving occurs when:`, ch:[`Environmental stimuli previously associated with drug use (e.g., a specific location) trigger craving through classical conditioning`,`Cravings occur randomly with no identifiable trigger`,`Only physical withdrawal symptoms are present`,`A person has never used the substance before`], ans:0, exp:`Through classical conditioning, environmental stimuli (people, places, paraphernalia) repeatedly paired with drug use become conditioned cues that can trigger craving and relapse even after prolonged abstinence.` },
    { q:`Naltrexone is used in the treatment of opioid and alcohol use disorders primarily by:`, ch:[`Acting as an opioid receptor antagonist, blocking the rewarding effects of opioids and reducing alcohol's reinforcing effects`,`Increasing dopamine release directly`,`Acting as a benzodiazepine agonist`,`Causing an aversive reaction when alcohol is consumed`], ans:0, exp:`Naltrexone is an opioid receptor antagonist that blocks the euphoric and reinforcing effects of opioids and also reduces the rewarding effects of alcohol, helping to reduce cravings and relapse.` },
    { q:`Methadone and buprenorphine are used in opioid use disorder treatment primarily as:`, ch:[`Opioid receptor antagonists that cause immediate withdrawal`,`Opioid agonists/partial agonists that reduce withdrawal symptoms and cravings while reducing the euphoric effects of other opioids`,`Stimulant medications`,`Antipsychotic medications`], ans:1, exp:`Methadone (full agonist) and buprenorphine (partial agonist) act on opioid receptors to reduce withdrawal symptoms and cravings, allowing for stabilization without the intense euphoria associated with short-acting opioids like heroin, as part of medication-assisted treatment.` },
    { q:`The biopsychosocial model of addiction emphasizes that substance use disorders result from the interaction of:`, ch:[`Biological vulnerability, psychological factors, and social/environmental influences`,`Genetics alone`,`Personal choice exclusively, with no biological component`,`Only the pharmacological properties of the drug`], ans:0, exp:`The biopsychosocial model recognizes addiction as a complex interplay between biological factors (genetics, neurochemistry), psychological factors (mental health, coping styles, trauma history), and social factors (peer influence, availability, socioeconomic conditions).` },
    { q:`Behavioral addictions, such as gambling disorder, are thought to share which neurobiological feature with substance addictions?`, ch:[`Activation of similar reward pathways involving the nucleus accumbens and dopamine`,`No overlap in neurobiology whatsoever`,`Activation only of the cerebellum`,`Complete absence of any craving response`], ans:0, exp:`Behavioral addictions like gambling disorder activate similar reward circuitry (involving dopamine release in the nucleus accumbens) as substance addictions, supporting the inclusion of gambling disorder alongside substance use disorders in diagnostic classifications.` },
    { q:`Genetic factors are estimated to account for what proportion of the risk for developing addiction, according to twin studies?`, ch:[`Approximately 0%`,`Approximately 40-60%, varying by substance`,`100%, with no environmental contribution`,`Genetic factors play no role`], ans:1, exp:`Twin and family studies estimate that genetic factors account for roughly 40-60% of the risk for developing substance use disorders, with the remainder attributable to environmental factors and gene-environment interactions, varying somewhat by substance.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps40`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Anxiety Disorders`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Generalized anxiety disorder (GAD) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Excessive, persistent worry about multiple events or activities, occurring more days than not for at least six months`,`A single panic attack with no recurrence`,`Fear restricted to one specific object`,`Hallucinations and delusions`], ans:0, exp:`GAD involves chronic, excessive worry about a variety of topics (work, health, finances) that is difficult to control, occurring more days than not for at least six months, often accompanied by physical symptoms like muscle tension and restlessness.` },
    { q:`Panic disorder is characterized by recurrent, unexpected panic attacks along with:`, ch:[`Persistent concern about having additional attacks or maladaptive behavioral changes related to the attacks`,`Complete absence of physical symptoms`,`Symptoms that occur only in social situations`,`A requirement that attacks always have an identifiable trigger`], ans:0, exp:`Panic disorder requires recurrent unexpected panic attacks plus at least one month of persistent worry about future attacks or significant maladaptive behavioral changes (e.g., avoidance) related to the attacks.` },
    { q:`The amygdala's role in anxiety disorders is primarily related to:`, ch:[`Processing and generating fear responses, often showing hyperactivity in anxiety disorders`,`Long-term memory storage exclusively`,`Motor coordination`,`Visual acuity`], ans:0, exp:`The amygdala plays a central role in processing fear and threat-related stimuli; neuroimaging studies show hyperactivation of the amygdala in response to threatening stimuli in individuals with anxiety disorders.` },
    { q:`Social anxiety disorder (social phobia) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Fear or anxiety about social situations in which the person may be scrutinized or judged by others`,`Fear of open spaces only`,`Fear that occurs exclusively at night`,`A complete inability to recognize emotions in others`], ans:0, exp:`Social anxiety disorder involves marked fear or anxiety about social situations involving possible scrutiny by others (e.g., social interactions, being observed, performing in front of others), often leading to avoidance of these situations.` },
    { q:`Specific phobia involves:`, ch:[`Marked, persistent fear that is excessive or unreasonable, triggered by a specific object or situation`,`A diagnosis that requires fear of multiple unrelated objects`,`Fear that is always proportional to actual danger`,`A condition that always requires medication as first-line treatment`], ans:0, exp:`Specific phobia involves an intense, persistent fear of a specific object or situation (e.g., heights, spiders, flying) that is out of proportion to the actual danger posed, leading to avoidance or significant distress.` },
    { q:`Agoraphobia is characterized by:`, ch:[`Fear of public speaking only`,`Fear or anxiety about situations where escape might be difficult or help unavailable, such as open spaces, crowds, or public transportation`,`Fear of small enclosed spaces exclusively`,`A condition that always co-occurs with schizophrenia`], ans:1, exp:`Agoraphobia involves marked fear or anxiety about two or more situations such as using public transportation, being in open or enclosed spaces, standing in line/crowds, or being outside the home alone, due to fears that escape might be difficult.` },
    { q:`The somatic symptoms of anxiety (e.g., increased heart rate, sweating, trembling) are primarily mediated by activation of the:`, ch:[`Parasympathetic nervous system exclusively`,`Sympathetic nervous system ("fight or flight" response)`,`Enteric nervous system only`,`Somatic motor neurons exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`The physical symptoms of anxietyŌĆöincreased heart rate, rapid breathing, sweating, and muscle tensionŌĆöresult from activation of the sympathetic nervous system, preparing the body for a "fight or flight" response.` },
    { q:`Cognitive theories of anxiety disorders emphasize the role of:`, ch:[`Random neurotransmitter fluctuations only`,`Maladaptive thought patterns, such as catastrophizing and overestimating the likelihood of negative outcomes`,`Complete absence of any cognitive component`,`Only childhood trauma`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive theories propose that anxiety disorders are maintained by maladaptive cognitive patterns, including catastrophic thinking, overestimation of threat probability, and biased attention toward threatening stimuli, which CBT aims to address.` },
    { q:`Separation anxiety disorder is most commonly diagnosed in which population, though it can occur across the lifespan?`, ch:[`Only in elderly adults`,`Children, involving developmentally inappropriate and excessive fear about separation from attachment figures`,`Only in individuals with no family`,`Exclusively in adults with no childhood history of anxiety`], ans:1, exp:`Separation anxiety disorder, while it can be diagnosed in adults, is most commonly recognized in children and involves excessive fear or anxiety concerning separation from major attachment figures, beyond what is developmentally appropriate.` },
    { q:`The GABA neurotransmitter system is implicated in anxiety disorders because GABA functions as the brain's primary:`, ch:[`Excitatory neurotransmitter`,`Inhibitory neurotransmitter, and reduced GABAergic activity is associated with increased anxiety`,`Hormone regulating growth`,`Neurotransmitter involved in vision`], ans:1, exp:`GABA is the brain's primary inhibitory neurotransmitter; reduced GABAergic inhibition is associated with increased neuronal excitability and anxiety, which is why GABA-enhancing drugs like benzodiazepines have anxiolytic effects.` },
    { q:`A patient who experiences intense fear, palpitations, shortness of breath, and a feeling of impending doom that peaks within minutes is most likely experiencing:`, ch:[`A manic episode`,`A panic attack`,`A psychotic break`,`A migraine aura`], ans:1, exp:`A panic attack is characterized by an abrupt surge of intense fear or discomfort that reaches a peak within minutes, accompanied by physical symptoms such as palpitations, sweating, trembling, shortness of breath, and a sense of impending doom.` },
    { q:`The "two-factor theory" of anxiety disorders (Mowrer) proposes that phobias develop through:`, ch:[`Classical conditioning (acquisition of fear) followed by operant conditioning (maintenance through avoidance)`,`Operant conditioning alone, with no role for classical conditioning`,`Purely genetic mechanisms with no learning component`,`Observation alone, with no direct experience necessary`], ans:0, exp:`Mowrer's two-factor theory proposes that phobias are first acquired through classical conditioning (a neutral stimulus becomes associated with fear) and then maintained through operant conditioning, as avoidance of the feared stimulus is negatively reinforced by anxiety reduction.` },
    { q:`Which brain region, when its connectivity with the amygdala is impaired, may contribute to difficulty regulating fear responses in anxiety disorders?`, ch:[`The cerebellum`,`The ventromedial prefrontal cortex`,`The primary visual cortex`,`The pancreas (not a brain region)`], ans:1, exp:`The ventromedial prefrontal cortex is involved in regulating amygdala activity and extinguishing fear responses; impaired connectivity between these regions is associated with difficulty in down-regulating fear and anxiety in anxiety disorders.` },
    { q:`Selective mutism, typically diagnosed in childhood, is characterized by:`, ch:[`A complete and permanent inability to speak in any context due to a physical impairment`,`Consistent failure to speak in specific social situations (e.g., school) despite speaking in other situations (e.g., home), often related to social anxiety`,`A condition unrelated to anxiety`,`A normal developmental stage requiring no clinical attention`], ans:1, exp:`Selective mutism involves a consistent failure to speak in specific social situations where speech is expected (e.g., school), despite speaking normally in other settings (e.g., at home with family), and is classified among anxiety disorders due to its strong association with social anxiety.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps41`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Mood Disorders & Neurobiology`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Major depressive disorder requires at least how many weeks of depressed mood or anhedonia plus other symptoms?`, ch:[`One day`,`Two weeks`,`Six months`,`One year`], ans:1, exp:`A diagnosis of major depressive disorder requires at least a two-week period during which the individual experiences depressed mood or loss of interest/pleasure (anhedonia), along with at least four additional symptoms (e.g., changes in sleep, appetite, energy, concentration).` },
    { q:`The monoamine hypothesis of depression proposes that depression results from:`, ch:[`Excess levels of serotonin, norepinephrine, and/or dopamine`,`Deficiencies in serotonin, norepinephrine, and/or dopamine neurotransmission`,`A complete absence of all neurotransmitters`,`Excess GABA only`], ans:1, exp:`The monoamine hypothesis suggests that depression is associated with decreased availability or activity of monoamine neurotransmittersŌĆöserotonin, norepinephrine, and dopamineŌĆöin the brain, forming the basis for many antidepressant medications.` },
    { q:`Bipolar I disorder requires the presence of at least one:`, ch:[`Manic episode`,`Hypomanic episode only, with no manic episodes ever`,`Major depressive episode only, with no manic or hypomanic episodes`,`Psychotic episode without mood symptoms`], ans:0, exp:`Bipolar I disorder is defined by the occurrence of at least one manic episode, which may be preceded or followed by hypomanic or major depressive episodes, though a major depressive episode is not required for diagnosis.` },
    { q:`Bipolar II disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`At least one manic episode and no depressive episodes`,`At least one hypomanic episode and at least one major depressive episode, with no full manic episodes`,`Only manic episodes with no other mood symptoms`,`Symptoms identical to schizophrenia`], ans:1, exp:`Bipolar II disorder requires at least one hypomanic episode (a less severe form of mania) and at least one major depressive episode, but the individual must never have experienced a full manic episode.` },
    { q:`A manic episode is characterized by a distinct period of abnormally elevated, expansive, or irritable mood lasting at least:`, ch:[`One day`,`One week (or any duration if hospitalization is required)`,`One month`,`Six months`], ans:1, exp:`A manic episode requires a distinct period of abnormally elevated, expansive, or irritable mood and increased goal-directed activity lasting at least one week (or any duration if hospitalization is necessary), accompanied by symptoms like decreased need for sleep, grandiosity, and risky behavior.` },
    { q:`Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) is characterized by:`, ch:[`Severe depressive symptoms lasting only a few days`,`A chronic, lower-grade depressed mood lasting for at least two years in adults`,`Symptoms that resolve completely within one week`,`A condition exclusive to children`], ans:1, exp:`Persistent depressive disorder (dysthymia) involves a chronic depressed mood that occurs for most of the day, more days than not, for at least two years in adults (one year in children/adolescents), often with less severe symptoms than major depression but more persistent.` },
    { q:`The HPA axis (hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis) is implicated in depression through:`, ch:[`Decreased cortisol levels in all depressed patients`,`Dysregulation often involving elevated cortisol levels due to chronic stress and impaired negative feedback`,`No relationship to mood disorders`,`Exclusive effects on the thyroid gland`], ans:1, exp:`Many individuals with depression show HPA axis dysregulation, including elevated cortisol levels and impaired negative feedback inhibition (e.g., abnormal dexamethasone suppression test results), reflecting the link between chronic stress and depression.` },
    { q:`Postpartum depression differs from the "baby blues" in that postpartum depression:`, ch:[`Resolves within a few days without intervention`,`Involves more severe and persistent depressive symptoms that may require treatment, occurring within weeks after childbirth`,`Never involves mood symptoms`,`Only affects fathers`], ans:1, exp:`While "baby blues" are common, mild, and typically resolve within two weeks postpartum, postpartum depression involves more severe, persistent depressive symptoms that significantly impair functioning and often require clinical treatment.` },
    { q:`Seasonal affective disorder (SAD) is a pattern of major depressive episodes that occur:`, ch:[`Randomly throughout the year with no pattern`,`With a regular seasonal pattern, most commonly with onset in fall/winter and remission in spring`,`Only in tropical climates`,`Exclusively during summer months for all patients`], ans:1, exp:`SAD is characterized by a recurrent seasonal pattern of major depressive episodes, most commonly beginning in fall or winter and remitting in spring, thought to be related to changes in light exposure affecting circadian rhythms and neurotransmitter function.` },
    { q:`Anhedonia, a core symptom of major depressive disorder, refers to:`, ch:[`Excessive happiness`,`Markedly diminished interest or pleasure in activities that were previously enjoyable`,`Increased energy levels`,`Improved sleep quality`], ans:1, exp:`Anhedonia is the loss of interest or pleasure in activities that were previously found enjoyable, one of the two core diagnostic criteria for major depressive disorder (along with depressed mood), often linked to dysfunction in dopaminergic reward circuits.` },
    { q:`Neuroimaging studies of depression often show altered activity in which brain region associated with reward processing?`, ch:[`The nucleus accumbens, often showing decreased activity in response to rewarding stimuli`,`The cerebellum exclusively`,`The retina`,`The spinal cord`], ans:0, exp:`Depression is associated with blunted activity in the nucleus accumbens and other reward-related circuitry in response to pleasurable stimuli, consistent with the symptom of anhedonia.` },
    { q:`Rapid cycling in bipolar disorder is defined as the occurrence of at least how many mood episodes within a 12-month period?`, ch:[`One`,`Four`,`Ten`,`Twenty`], ans:1, exp:`Rapid cycling is specified when a patient with bipolar disorder experiences at least four mood episodes (manic, hypomanic, or depressive) within a 12-month period, and is associated with a more severe course and treatment challenges.` },
    { q:`The "kindling hypothesis" in bipolar disorder suggests that:`, ch:[`Each subsequent mood episode requires a greater external trigger than the previous one`,`Initial mood episodes may require significant stressors, but subsequent episodes can occur with progressively less provocation, eventually becoming autonomous`,`Mood episodes have no relationship to prior episodes`,`Medication has no effect on episode frequency`], ans:1, exp:`The kindling hypothesis proposes that initial mood episodes are often triggered by significant life stressors, but with repeated episodes, the brain becomes increasingly sensitized, such that later episodes can occur with less or no external provocationŌĆösimilar to the kindling phenomenon in epilepsy.` },
    { q:`A patient presents with depressed mood, weight gain, increased sleep, and a sensation of heaviness in the limbs ("leaden paralysis"). This symptom pattern is most characteristic of:`, ch:[`Melancholic features`,`Atypical features of depression`,`Catatonic features`,`Psychotic features`], ans:1, exp:`Atypical features of depression include mood reactivity, increased appetite/weight gain, hypersomnia, leaden paralysis (heavy feeling in limbs), and interpersonal rejection sensitivityŌĆöcontrasting with melancholic features, which include early morning awakening, weight loss, and lack of mood reactivity.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps42`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Schizophrenia & Dopamine`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Positive symptoms of schizophrenia include:`, ch:[`Flat affect, social withdrawal, and avolition`,`Hallucinations, delusions, and disorganized speech or behavior`,`Improved cognitive function`,`Increased motivation and goal-directed behavior`], ans:1, exp:`"Positive" symptoms refer to symptoms that represent an excess or distortion of normal functioningŌĆöhallucinations, delusions, disorganized speech, and grossly disorganized or catatonic behaviorŌĆörather than implying they are beneficial.` },
    { q:`Negative symptoms of schizophrenia include:`, ch:[`Hallucinations and delusions`,`Flat affect, alogia, avolition, anhedonia, and social withdrawal`,`Increased speech output`,`Heightened emotional expression`], ans:1, exp:`"Negative" symptoms represent a decrease or loss of normal functionsŌĆöincluding flat or blunted affect, alogia (reduced speech), avolition (lack of motivation), anhedonia, and asocialityŌĆöand are often more resistant to treatment than positive symptoms.` },
    { q:`The dopamine hypothesis of schizophrenia proposes that positive symptoms are related to:`, ch:[`Decreased dopamine activity in the mesolimbic pathway`,`Increased dopamine activity in the mesolimbic pathway`,`Complete absence of dopamine receptors`,`Excess serotonin in the cerebellum exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`The dopamine hypothesis proposes that hyperactivity of dopamine transmission in the mesolimbic pathway contributes to positive symptoms (hallucinations, delusions), while hypoactivity in the mesocortical pathway may contribute to negative and cognitive symptoms.` },
    { q:`Antipsychotic medications that block D2 dopamine receptors are most effective at treating:`, ch:[`Negative symptoms exclusively`,`Positive symptoms, such as hallucinations and delusions`,`Cognitive symptoms exclusively`,`No symptoms of schizophrenia`], ans:1, exp:`D2 receptor antagonism in the mesolimbic pathway is associated with reduction of positive symptoms (hallucinations, delusions), though this mechanism is generally less effective for negative and cognitive symptoms.` },
    { q:`Extrapyramidal symptoms (EPS), a side effect of typical antipsychotics, result from dopamine blockade in which pathway?`, ch:[`The mesolimbic pathway`,`The nigrostriatal pathway`,`The mesocortical pathway`,`The tuberoinfundibular pathway`], ans:1, exp:`Blockade of D2 receptors in the nigrostriatal pathway, which is involved in motor control, produces extrapyramidal symptoms such as parkinsonism, dystonia, akathisia, and with long-term use, tardive dyskinesia.` },
    { q:`Hyperprolactinemia, another antipsychotic side effect, results from dopamine blockade in which pathway?`, ch:[`The mesolimbic pathway`,`The nigrostriatal pathway`,`The tuberoinfundibular pathway`,`The mesocortical pathway`], ans:2, exp:`Dopamine normally inhibits prolactin release via the tuberoinfundibular pathway; D2 receptor blockade in this pathway by antipsychotics removes this inhibition, leading to hyperprolactinemia, which can cause galactorrhea, gynecomastia, and menstrual irregularities.` },
    { q:`A diagnosis of schizophrenia requires symptoms to persist for at least:`, ch:[`One day`,`One week`,`Six months, with at least one month of active-phase symptoms`,`Ten years`], ans:2, exp:`Schizophrenia diagnosis requires continuous signs of disturbance for at least six months, including at least one month of active-phase symptoms (e.g., delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech), along with significant social or occupational dysfunction.` },
    { q:`Schizophreniform disorder differs from schizophrenia primarily in terms of:`, ch:[`The presence of hallucinations`,`Duration of symptomsŌĆöschizophreniform disorder lasts between one and six months`,`The complete absence of delusions`,`Occurring only in children`], ans:1, exp:`Schizophreniform disorder has the same symptom criteria as schizophrenia but with a shorter durationŌĆösymptoms last between one and six months, whereas schizophrenia requires at least six months of disturbance.` },
    { q:`Brief psychotic disorder is characterized by the presence of psychotic symptoms lasting:`, ch:[`More than six months`,`At least one day but less than one month, with eventual full return to premorbid functioning`,`Permanently with no recovery`,`Only during sleep`], ans:1, exp:`Brief psychotic disorder involves the sudden onset of psychotic symptoms (delusions, hallucinations, disorganized speech/behavior) lasting at least one day but less than one month, with eventual full return to premorbid level of functioning.` },
    { q:`The "two-hit hypothesis" of schizophrenia proposes that the disorder results from:`, ch:[`A single genetic mutation with no environmental component`,`An early neurodevelopmental insult (genetic or environmental) combined with a later environmental trigger (e.g., stress) during adolescence/early adulthood`,`Two separate unrelated diseases occurring simultaneously`,`Physical trauma to the head only`], ans:1, exp:`The two-hit hypothesis proposes that schizophrenia arises from an interaction between an early "first hit" (genetic vulnerability or prenatal/perinatal insult affecting brain development) and a "second hit" (environmental stressor during adolescence or early adulthood) that triggers the onset of symptoms.` },
    { q:`Enlarged ventricles and reduced gray matter volume are structural brain findings commonly associated with:`, ch:[`Schizophrenia`,`Normal aging only`,`Specific phobia`,`Generalized anxiety disorder exclusively`], ans:0, exp:`Neuroimaging studies of schizophrenia frequently show enlarged cerebral ventricles and reduced gray matter volume in regions such as the prefrontal cortex and temporal lobes, consistent with neurodevelopmental abnormalities associated with the disorder.` },
    { q:`Schizoaffective disorder is diagnosed when a patient has:`, ch:[`Symptoms of schizophrenia with no mood symptoms ever`,`A major mood episode (depressive or manic) concurrent with schizophrenia symptoms, plus a period of psychotic symptoms without mood symptoms`,`Only mood symptoms with no psychotic features`,`A diagnosis that is identical to bipolar disorder`], ans:1, exp:`Schizoaffective disorder requires an uninterrupted period of illness during which there is a major mood episode concurrent with schizophrenia's active-phase symptoms, plus a period of at least two weeks of delusions or hallucinations in the absence of a major mood episode.` },
    { q:`The "social drift" hypothesis explains the association between schizophrenia and lower socioeconomic status by proposing that:`, ch:[`Poverty directly causes schizophrenia in all cases through toxin exposure`,`Individuals with schizophrenia tend to drift downward in socioeconomic status due to the disorder's impact on functioning, rather than poverty causing the disorder`,`Schizophrenia only affects wealthy individuals`,`Socioeconomic status has no relationship to schizophrenia`], ans:1, exp:`The social drift hypothesis suggests that the cognitive and functional impairments associated with schizophrenia lead affected individuals to "drift" into lower socioeconomic strata over time, offering an alternative (or complementary) explanation to social causation theories for the observed association between schizophrenia and lower SES.` },
    { q:`Glutamate dysfunction, particularly involving NMDA receptor hypofunction, has been implicated in schizophrenia based partly on observations that:`, ch:[`NMDA receptor antagonists like ketamine and PCP can induce psychotic-like symptoms in healthy individuals`,`Glutamate has no role in cognition`,`NMDA receptors are found only in the peripheral nervous system`,`Glutamate antagonists cure schizophrenia completely`], ans:0, exp:`The NMDA receptor hypofunction hypothesis is supported by observations that NMDA receptor antagonists (e.g., ketamine, phencyclidine) can induce both positive and negative symptoms resembling schizophrenia in healthy individuals, suggesting glutamatergic dysfunction may play a role beyond the dopamine hypothesis alone.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps43`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Personality Disorders`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Personality disorders are grouped into Cluster A, B, and C. Cluster A disorders are characterized by:`, ch:[`Odd or eccentric behavior`,`Dramatic, emotional, or erratic behavior`,`Anxious or fearful behavior`,`No distinguishing features`], ans:0, exp:`Cluster A personality disordersŌĆöparanoid, schizoid, and schizotypalŌĆöare characterized by odd, eccentric thinking or behavior, often involving social detachment or unusual beliefs.` },
    { q:`Cluster B personality disorders are characterized by:`, ch:[`Odd or eccentric behavior`,`Dramatic, emotional, or erratic behavior`,`Anxious or fearful behavior`,`Complete absence of emotion`], ans:1, exp:`Cluster B personality disordersŌĆöantisocial, borderline, histrionic, and narcissisticŌĆöare characterized by dramatic, emotional, erratic behavior and significant difficulties with interpersonal relationships and impulse control.` },
    { q:`Cluster C personality disorders are characterized by:`, ch:[`Dramatic, erratic behavior`,`Odd, eccentric behavior`,`Anxious or fearful behavior`,`Grandiosity and lack of empathy exclusively`], ans:2, exp:`Cluster C personality disordersŌĆöavoidant, dependent, and obsessive-compulsiveŌĆöare characterized by anxious, fearful thinking and behavior, often involving excessive worry about rejection, abandonment, or loss of control.` },
    { q:`Borderline personality disorder is characterized by a pervasive pattern of:`, ch:[`Stable relationships and a consistent self-image`,`Instability in interpersonal relationships, self-image, and affect, along with marked impulsivity`,`Complete emotional detachment from others`,`Grandiosity with no fear of abandonment`], ans:1, exp:`Borderline personality disorder involves pervasive instability in interpersonal relationships (alternating idealization and devaluation), self-image, and emotions, along with marked impulsivity, intense fear of abandonment, and recurrent suicidal/self-harm behaviors.` },
    { q:`Antisocial personality disorder requires evidence of conduct disorder before what age?`, ch:[`Age 5`,`Age 15`,`Age 25`,`Age 40`], ans:1, exp:`A diagnosis of antisocial personality disorder requires evidence of conduct disorder with onset before age 15, reflecting a long-standing pattern of disregard for and violation of the rights of others, and the diagnosis itself can only be made at age 18 or older.` },
    { q:`Narcissistic personality disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`A pervasive pattern of grandiosity, need for admiration, and lack of empathy`,`Excessive submissiveness and need to be taken care of`,`Social detachment and restricted emotional expression`,`Preoccupation with orderliness and control`], ans:0, exp:`Narcissistic personality disorder involves a pervasive pattern of grandiosity (in fantasy or behavior), an excessive need for admiration, and a lack of empathy for others, often accompanied by a sense of entitlement.` },
    { q:`Histrionic personality disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`Excessive emotionality and attention-seeking behavior`,`Restricted range of emotional expression`,`Avoidance of social situations due to fear of criticism`,`Suspiciousness and distrust of others`], ans:0, exp:`Histrionic personality disorder involves a pervasive pattern of excessive emotionality and attention-seeking behavior, including discomfort when not the center of attention, and often theatrical or seductive behavior.` },
    { q:`Schizotypal personality disorder is distinguished from schizoid personality disorder primarily by the presence of:`, ch:[`Cognitive and perceptual distortions and eccentric behavior, in addition to social detachment`,`A complete absence of any odd beliefs`,`Full-blown psychosis meeting criteria for schizophrenia`,`Excessive emotional expressiveness`], ans:0, exp:`While both schizoid and schizotypal personality disorders involve social detachment, schizotypal personality disorder also includes cognitive and perceptual distortions (e.g., magical thinking, ideas of reference) and eccentric behavior or appearance.` },
    { q:`Avoidant personality disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`Social inhibition, feelings of inadequacy, and hypersensitivity to negative evaluation`,`A grandiose sense of self-importance`,`Disregard for the rights of others`,`Excessive need to be cared for, leading to submissive behavior`], ans:0, exp:`Avoidant personality disorder involves pervasive social inhibition, feelings of inadequacy, and hypersensitivity to criticism or rejection, leading individuals to avoid occupational and social activities involving interpersonal contact despite a desire for relationships.` },
    { q:`Dependent personality disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`An excessive need to be taken care of, leading to submissive and clinging behavior and fears of separation`,`A pervasive distrust and suspiciousness of others`,`Preoccupation with rules, order, and control at the expense of flexibility`,`A lack of remorse for harming others`], ans:0, exp:`Dependent personality disorder involves an excessive, pervasive need to be taken care of, leading to submissive and clinging behaviors and significant fears of separation, with difficulty making everyday decisions without excessive reassurance from others.` },
    { q:`Obsessive-compulsive personality disorder (OCPD) differs from obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) in that OCPD:`, ch:[`Involves true obsessions and compulsions that the person finds distressing and ego-dystonic`,`Is a pervasive personality pattern of preoccupation with orderliness, perfectionism, and control that is generally ego-syntonic (consistent with self-image)`,`Always co-occurs with psychosis`,`Is the same disorder with a different name`], ans:1, exp:`OCPD is a personality disorder characterized by a pervasive pattern of preoccupation with orderliness, perfectionism, and control, which individuals typically view as appropriate (ego-syntonic), unlike OCD, where obsessions and compulsions are typically distressing and recognized as excessive (ego-dystonic).` },
    { q:`Paranoid personality disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`A pervasive pattern of distrust and suspiciousness such that others' motives are interpreted as malevolent`,`Excessive emotionality and need for attention`,`Complete indifference to social relationships`,`A pattern of submissive and clinging behavior`], ans:0, exp:`Paranoid personality disorder involves a pervasive, unwarranted distrust and suspiciousness of others, with individuals frequently interpreting others' motives as malevolent, even without sufficient evidence.` },
    { q:`Splitting, a defense mechanism commonly associated with borderline personality disorder, refers to:`, ch:[`The inability to view oneself or others in a balanced way, instead categorizing them as either entirely good or entirely bad`,`Physically separating from social situations`,`A type of memory loss`,`A surgical procedure`], ans:0, exp:`Splitting is a primitive defense mechanism in which a person views themselves or others in extreme, polarized termsŌĆöas either "all good" or "all bad"ŌĆöwithout the capacity to integrate both positive and negative qualities into a cohesive view, common in borderline personality disorder.` },
    { q:`Personality disorders are generally considered to be:`, ch:[`Acute conditions that resolve within days`,`Long-standing, pervasive patterns of inner experience and behavior that deviate markedly from cultural expectations and are stable over time`,`Always caused by a single traumatic event in adulthood`,`Curable with antibiotics`], ans:1, exp:`Personality disorders are characterized by enduring patterns of inner experience and behavior that deviate markedly from cultural expectations, are pervasive and inflexible, have an onset in adolescence or early adulthood, and remain stable over time, leading to distress or impairment.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps44`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Neurodevelopmental Disorders`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Autism spectrum disorder is characterized by persistent deficits in:`, ch:[`Social communication and interaction, plus restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities`,`Only motor coordination, with no social impairments`,`Memory consolidation exclusively`,`Language acquisition only, with normal social skills`], ans:0, exp:`Autism spectrum disorder is defined by persistent deficits in social communication and social interaction across multiple contexts, combined with restricted, repetitive patterns of behavior, interests, or activities (e.g., stereotyped movements, insistence on sameness).` },
    { q:`ADHD (attention-deficit/hyperactivity disorder) symptoms must be present before what age for diagnosis?`, ch:[`Age 4`,`Age 12`,`Age 18`,`Age 25`], ans:1, exp:`According to DSM-5 criteria, several symptoms of inattention or hyperactivity-impulsivity must have been present before age 12, and symptoms must occur in two or more settings (e.g., home and school).` },
    { q:`Intellectual disability (intellectual developmental disorder) requires deficits in both:`, ch:[`Intellectual functioning (e.g., reasoning, problem-solving) and adaptive functioning (e.g., daily living skills), with onset during the developmental period`,`Only physical growth, with normal cognitive abilities`,`Vision and hearing only`,`Memory only, with no other deficits`], ans:0, exp:`Intellectual disability requires deficits in both intellectual functions (such as reasoning, problem-solving, abstract thinking, typically assessed via IQ testing) and adaptive functioning (conceptual, social, and practical skills needed for independence), with onset during the developmental period.` },
    { q:`Specific learning disorder, such as dyslexia, is diagnosed when:`, ch:[`A person has below-average intelligence overall`,`Academic skills (e.g., reading) are substantially below what would be expected for age, despite adequate intelligence and educational opportunity`,`A person has never attended school`,`Academic skills are above grade level`], ans:1, exp:`Specific learning disorders involve significant difficulties in specific academic skills (reading, writing, or mathematics) that are substantially below age-expected levels, not attributable to intellectual disability, sensory impairments, or lack of educational opportunity.` },
    { q:`Tourette's disorder is characterized by:`, ch:[`Multiple motor tics and at least one vocal tic, present for more than one year`,`A single tic that resolves within a week`,`Tics that are always voluntary and easily suppressed indefinitely`,`A condition exclusively affecting adults`], ans:0, exp:`Tourette's disorder requires the presence of both multiple motor tics and at least one vocal tic (not necessarily concurrently), persisting for more than one year, with onset before age 18.` },
    { q:`The "broader autism phenotype" refers to:`, ch:[`A formal diagnostic category in the DSM-5`,`Subclinical traits related to autism (e.g., social or communication difficulties) observed in relatives of individuals with autism, suggesting a genetic component`,`A condition that only occurs in identical twins`,`A type of treatment for autism`], ans:1, exp:`The broader autism phenotype describes milder, subclinical autism-related traits (e.g., social communication difficulties, restricted interests) observed at higher rates in first-degree relatives of individuals with autism, supporting genetic contributions to the condition.` },
    { q:`Fetal alcohol spectrum disorders result from:`, ch:[`Maternal alcohol consumption during pregnancy, which can cause a range of physical, cognitive, and behavioral effects in the child`,`Paternal alcohol consumption only, with no effect from maternal exposure`,`Alcohol consumption by the child after birth`,`A purely genetic condition unrelated to alcohol exposure`], ans:0, exp:`Fetal alcohol spectrum disorders encompass a range of effectsŌĆöincluding characteristic facial features, growth deficiencies, and cognitive/behavioral impairmentsŌĆöresulting from prenatal exposure to alcohol, which crosses the placenta and can disrupt fetal brain development.` },
    { q:`Communication disorders, such as language disorder, are characterized by persistent difficulties with:`, ch:[`Acquisition and use of language across modalities (spoken, written, sign), due to deficits in vocabulary, sentence structure, or discourse`,`Motor coordination only`,`Social relationships exclusively, with normal language`,`Visual processing only`], ans:0, exp:`Communication disorders involve persistent difficulties in the acquisition and use of language, including reduced vocabulary, limited sentence structure, and impairments in discourse, which significantly impact functional communication.` },
    { q:`Comorbidity between ADHD and learning disorders is:`, ch:[`Essentially zero, as the two conditions are mutually exclusive`,`Common, with many individuals meeting criteria for both conditions, requiring comprehensive assessment`,`Only seen in adults, never in children`,`A sign of misdiagnosis in all cases`], ans:1, exp:`ADHD and specific learning disorders frequently co-occur, and comprehensive evaluation is important because each condition can affect treatment planning and academic accommodations differently, and untreated comorbidities can compound functional impairment.` },
    { q:`Stereotypic movement disorder involves:`, ch:[`Repetitive, seemingly driven, and purposeless motor behavior (e.g., hand-flapping, body rocking) that interferes with social, academic, or other activities`,`A single voluntary movement performed once`,`A condition that always requires surgical intervention`,`Movements that occur exclusively during sleep`], ans:0, exp:`Stereotypic movement disorder involves repetitive, seemingly driven motor behaviors (e.g., hand-flapping, head-banging, body rocking) that are not better explained by another condition and that interfere with normal activities or may result in self-injury.` },
    { q:`Early intensive behavioral intervention (e.g., applied behavior analysis) for autism spectrum disorder is based primarily on principles of:`, ch:[`Psychoanalysis`,`Operant conditioning, using reinforcement to shape desired behaviors and reduce problematic ones`,`Humanistic therapy`,`Pharmacological intervention exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Applied behavior analysis (ABA) uses operant conditioning principlesŌĆöreinforcement, shaping, and promptingŌĆöto teach new skills and reduce challenging behaviors in individuals with autism spectrum disorder, and is among the most well-studied interventions.` },
    { q:`The increased prevalence of autism spectrum disorder diagnoses over recent decades is thought to be substantially attributable to:`, ch:[`Vaccines, which have been definitively proven to cause autism`,`Broadened diagnostic criteria, increased awareness, and improved screening, rather than a single environmental cause`,`A complete absence of any genetic component`,`Decreased availability of healthcare`], ans:1, exp:`Research attributes much of the increase in autism diagnoses to broadened diagnostic criteria (including the spectrum concept), increased awareness among clinicians and parents, and improved screening; the discredited vaccine-autism link has been thoroughly disproven by extensive research.` },
    { q:`Rett syndrome, a neurodevelopmental disorder, is most strongly associated with mutations in which gene?`, ch:[`MECP2`,`BRCA1`,`CFTR`,`HBB`], ans:0, exp:`Rett syndrome is caused by mutations in the MECP2 gene, located on the X chromosome, and predominantly affects females, characterized by normal early development followed by regression in motor and language skills along with characteristic hand-wringing movements.` },
    { q:`In evaluating a child with possible neurodevelopmental disorder, why is a comprehensive developmental history important?`, ch:[`It is not important; a single test is always sufficient`,`Because neurodevelopmental disorders involve onset during the developmental period, and understanding the trajectory of skill acquisition helps differentiate between disorders and identify regression`,`Because all neurodevelopmental disorders have identical presentations`,`Because medication history is the only relevant factor`], ans:1, exp:`A comprehensive developmental history helps establish the timing of symptom onset (a key diagnostic criterion for many neurodevelopmental disorders), identify any regression in previously acquired skills (which may suggest specific conditions like Rett syndrome), and differentiate between overlapping presentations.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps45`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Memory Consolidation & Amnesia`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Memory consolidation refers to the process by which:`, ch:[`Memories are immediately forgotten`,`Newly formed, labile memories are stabilized into more permanent, long-term storage over time`,`Short-term memory capacity is permanently reduced`,`Sensory memory is converted directly into procedural memory only`], ans:1, exp:`Consolidation is the process by which initially fragile, newly encoded memories become stabilized in long-term storage, involving molecular changes at the synaptic level and systems-level reorganization involving the hippocampus and cortex.` },
    { q:`The hippocampus plays a critical role in:`, ch:[`The formation of new declarative (explicit) memories`,`Procedural memory exclusively, with no role in declarative memory`,`Visual acuity`,`Regulating heart rate directly`], ans:0, exp:`The hippocampus is essential for forming new declarative memories (facts and events); damage to the hippocampus typically results in anterograde amnesiaŌĆöan inability to form new long-term declarative memoriesŌĆöwhile older memories may remain intact.` },
    { q:`Anterograde amnesia refers to:`, ch:[`The inability to recall memories formed before the onset of amnesia`,`The inability to form new memories after the onset of the causative event or condition`,`A complete loss of procedural memory only`,`Enhanced memory formation`], ans:1, exp:`Anterograde amnesia is the inability to form new explicit/declarative memories following the onset of brain damage or a causative event, while memories formed prior to the event may be relatively preserved.` },
    { q:`Retrograde amnesia refers to:`, ch:[`The inability to form any new memories`,`The inability to recall memories that were formed before the onset of amnesia`,`A type of memory enhancement`,`Loss of motor skills only`], ans:1, exp:`Retrograde amnesia involves the loss of memories that were formed before the onset of the amnesia-inducing event, with memories closer in time to the event often being more vulnerable than more remote memories (Ribot's law).` },
    { q:`The famous case of patient H.M., who underwent bilateral medial temporal lobe resection (including the hippocampus), demonstrated that:`, ch:[`The hippocampus is not necessary for any type of memory`,`Damage to the hippocampus can cause severe anterograde amnesia for declarative memories while sparing procedural memory and short-term memory`,`Procedural memory is stored exclusively in the hippocampus`,`Memory is localized to a single, undifferentiated brain region`], ans:1, exp:`H.M.'s case demonstrated a dissociation between memory systems: he developed profound anterograde amnesia for declarative (episodic and semantic) memories after hippocampal removal, but retained intact procedural memory (e.g., learning new motor skills) and normal short-term/working memory.` },
    { q:`Procedural memory, which remains intact in many amnesia patients, refers to memory for:`, ch:[`Facts and personal experiences`,`Skills and habits, such as riding a bicycle or playing an instrument`,`Specific dates of historical events`,`Vocabulary definitions only`], ans:1, exp:`Procedural memory is a form of implicit (non-declarative) memory involving skills and habits (e.g., motor skills, learned behaviors), which is typically mediated by the basal ganglia and cerebellum and can remain intact even when declarative memory is severely impaired.` },
    { q:`Long-term potentiation (LTP) is considered a cellular mechanism underlying:`, ch:[`Memory and learning, involving strengthening of synaptic connections with repeated stimulation`,`Muscle atrophy`,`Cell death exclusively`,`Random neuronal firing with no functional significance`], ans:0, exp:`LTP refers to a long-lasting strengthening of synaptic connections following repeated or high-frequency stimulation, particularly well studied in the hippocampus, and is considered a key cellular mechanism underlying learning and memory formation.` },
    { q:`Korsakoff syndrome, often associated with chronic alcohol use, results from a deficiency of which vitamin and primarily affects which structures?`, ch:[`Vitamin C; the cerebellum`,`Thiamine (B1); the mammillary bodies and thalamus`,`Vitamin D; the spinal cord`,`Folate; the occipital lobe`], ans:1, exp:`Korsakoff syndrome results from thiamine (vitamin B1) deficiency, often due to chronic alcohol use, causing damage to the mammillary bodies and thalamus, leading to severe anterograde amnesia and confabulation (filling memory gaps with fabricated information).` },
    { q:`Confabulation, seen in conditions like Korsakoff syndrome, refers to:`, ch:[`Deliberate lying to deceive others`,`The unintentional production of fabricated or distorted memories without the intent to deceive`,`Complete absence of speech`,`Enhanced accuracy of memory recall`], ans:1, exp:`Confabulation involves the unintentional creation of false memories or fabricated information, often to fill gaps in memory, without conscious awareness that the information is incorrectŌĆödistinct from deliberate lying.` },
    { q:`Reconsolidation refers to the phenomenon in which:`, ch:[`Memories, once retrieved, become temporarily labile and must be re-stabilized, during which time they can be modified`,`Memories cannot be changed once formed`,`All memories are permanently erased upon retrieval`,`Only procedural memories can be reconsolidated`], ans:0, exp:`Reconsolidation theory proposes that retrieving a consolidated memory returns it to a labile state, requiring it to be re-stabilized (reconsolidated); during this window, the memory can potentially be modified, weakened, or strengthenedŌĆörelevant to therapies targeting traumatic memories.` },
    { q:`The serial position effect, in which items at the beginning and end of a list are remembered better than middle items, reflects the operation of:`, ch:[`Only short-term memory`,`Both long-term memory (primacy effect) and short-term memory (recency effect)`,`Only procedural memory`,`A random artifact with no theoretical basis`], ans:1, exp:`The primacy effect (better recall of early items) reflects transfer to long-term memory through rehearsal, while the recency effect (better recall of final items) reflects retrieval from short-term/working memory, which is still active immediately after presentation.` },
    { q:`Working memory, as conceptualized by Baddeley, includes which key component responsible for manipulating and processing information from multiple sources?`, ch:[`The phonological loop`,`The central executive`,`The visuospatial sketchpad`,`The episodic buffer only`], ans:1, exp:`Baddeley's model of working memory includes the central executive, which directs attention and coordinates information from the phonological loop (verbal information) and visuospatial sketchpad (visual/spatial information), as well as the episodic buffer, which integrates information into a unified representation.` },
    { q:`Encoding specificity principle proposes that memory retrieval is most effective when:`, ch:[`Retrieval occurs in a completely different context than encoding`,`The conditions at retrieval match the conditions present during encoding (e.g., context, mood)`,`No cues are present at retrieval`,`Memories are encoded without any context`], ans:1, exp:`The encoding specificity principle states that memory retrieval is enhanced when the cues present at retrieval match those present during encodingŌĆöexplaining phenomena like context-dependent and state-dependent memory.` },
    { q:`Damage to the prefrontal cortex is most likely to impair which aspect of memory?`, ch:[`Source memory and the ability to organize and strategically retrieve information`,`Basic sensory perception`,`Reflexive motor responses`,`Heart rate regulation`], ans:0, exp:`The prefrontal cortex plays a key role in working memory, source monitoring (remembering where/how information was acquired), and strategic retrieval and organization of memories; damage can lead to difficulties with source memory and memory organization despite relatively intact basic recognition memory.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps46`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Signal Detection Theory`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`In signal detection theory, a "hit" refers to:`, ch:[`Correctly identifying that a signal is present when it is actually present`,`Incorrectly identifying a signal as present when it is absent`,`Correctly identifying that a signal is absent when it is absent`,`Failing to detect a signal that is present`], ans:0, exp:`A hit occurs when a signal is present and the observer correctly detects/responds that it is presentŌĆöone of the four possible outcomes in signal detection theory along with misses, false alarms, and correct rejections.` },
    { q:`A "false alarm" in signal detection theory occurs when:`, ch:[`A signal is present and correctly detected`,`No signal is present, but the observer reports detecting one`,`A signal is present but not detected`,`No signal is present and none is reported`], ans:1, exp:`A false alarm occurs when the observer reports detecting a signal when no signal is actually presentŌĆöanalogous to a "false positive" in diagnostic testing.` },
    { q:`A "miss" in signal detection theory occurs when:`, ch:[`A signal is present but the observer fails to detect it`,`No signal is present and the observer correctly reports its absence`,`A signal is present and correctly detected`,`The observer always responds correctly`], ans:0, exp:`A miss occurs when a signal is actually present but the observer fails to detect or report itŌĆöanalogous to a "false negative" in diagnostic testing, which has important implications for screening tests in medicine.` },
    { q:`A "correct rejection" in signal detection theory refers to:`, ch:[`Correctly identifying the absence of a signal when no signal is present`,`Incorrectly identifying a signal as present`,`Failing to identify a present signal`,`A type of memory error unrelated to detection`], ans:0, exp:`A correct rejection occurs when no signal is present and the observer correctly reports its absenceŌĆöanalogous to a "true negative" in diagnostic testing.` },
    { q:`In signal detection theory, "sensitivity" (d') reflects:`, ch:[`The observer's response bias only`,`The observer's ability to distinguish between the presence and absence of a signal, independent of response bias`,`The total number of trials conducted`,`The speed of the observer's responses`], ans:1, exp:`Sensitivity (d') is a measure of how well an observer can discriminate between signal and noise (or signal-present and signal-absent trials), reflecting the separation between the signal and noise distributions, independent of the observer's response criterion or bias.` },
    { q:`Response bias (criterion) in signal detection theory reflects:`, ch:[`The observer's underlying perceptual ability`,`The observer's general tendency to favor one type of response (e.g., "yes, signal present") over another, regardless of actual sensitivity`,`A fixed property that cannot be influenced by instructions or incentives`,`The exact same concept as sensitivity`], ans:1, exp:`Response bias (or criterion) reflects an observer's general tendency to respond "yes" or "no" regardless of the actual stimulus, which can be influenced by the costs and benefits associated with different types of errors (e.g., a radiologist might adopt a more liberal criterion if missing a tumor is considered far worse than a false alarm).` },
    { q:`If the consequences of a "miss" (e.g., missing a malignant tumor on imaging) are considered far more severe than a "false alarm" (e.g., a false-positive biopsy), a rational observer would likely:`, ch:[`Adopt a more conservative criterion, increasing both hits and false alarms`,`Adopt a more liberal criterion, increasing the hit rate at the cost of more false alarms`,`Have no change in their response criterion`,`Stop performing the task altogether`], ans:1, exp:`When the cost of a miss is high relative to the cost of a false alarm, observers tend to shift toward a more liberal response criterion (more readily reporting "signal present"), which increases the hit rate but also increases the false alarm rate.` },
    { q:`A receiver operating characteristic (ROC) curve plots:`, ch:[`Hit rate against false alarm rate across different response criteria`,`Reaction time against accuracy`,`Memory capacity against age`,`Sample size against statistical power`], ans:0, exp:`An ROC curve plots the hit rate (true positive rate) against the false alarm rate (false positive rate) across a range of decision criteria, providing a way to evaluate a detection system's sensitivity independent of any single threshold, with greater area under the curve indicating better discrimination.` },
    { q:`Signal detection theory is particularly useful in medicine for evaluating:`, ch:[`The cost of healthcare facilities`,`Diagnostic test performance, balancing sensitivity and specificity based on the clinical context and consequences of errors`,`Patient satisfaction surveys exclusively`,`Hospital staffing schedules`], ans:1, exp:`Signal detection theory provides a framework for understanding the trade-offs between sensitivity and specificity in diagnostic testing, helping clinicians choose appropriate cutoff values based on the relative costs of false positives versus false negatives in a given clinical context.` },
    { q:`If an observer becomes more cautious and requires stronger evidence before reporting "signal present," this would result in:`, ch:[`An increase in both hits and false alarms`,`A decrease in both hits and false alarms (fewer "yes" responses overall)`,`No change in hit or false alarm rates`,`An increase in hits but a decrease in misses, with no effect on false alarms`], ans:1, exp:`A more conservative (cautious) criterion means the observer requires stronger evidence before responding "yes," which decreases both the hit rate (more misses) and the false alarm rate (fewer false "yes" responses on noise trials)ŌĆöthis represents a shift in bias, not sensitivity.` },
    { q:`A radiologist who, due to fatigue, becomes equally likely to miss a true tumor and falsely flag a normal scan as abnormal would show:`, ch:[`Increased sensitivity (d') with unchanged bias`,`Decreased sensitivity (d'), reflecting reduced ability to discriminate signal from noise`,`A change in bias only, with no effect on sensitivity`,`No measurable change in performance`], ans:1, exp:`If errors increase in both directions (more misses and more false alarms) without a clear shift toward one type of error over the other, this reflects a decrease in sensitivity (d')ŌĆöa reduced ability to discriminate between signal and noiseŌĆörather than simply a shift in response criterion.` },
    { q:`Why might two radiologists with identical perceptual sensitivity (d') produce different numbers of false positives on the same set of mammograms?`, ch:[`This is impossible if sensitivity is identical`,`They may have different response criteria (biases), e.g., one is more cautious about missing cancer and thus more willing to call a scan abnormal`,`Sensitivity and bias are the same concept`,`False positives are entirely random and unrelated to any cognitive factor`], ans:1, exp:`Even with identical underlying perceptual sensitivity, two observers can adopt different response criteria based on their individual risk tolerance, training, or institutional guidelinesŌĆöone radiologist might set a more liberal threshold (more false positives but fewer missed cancers) than another.` },
    { q:`In the context of signal detection theory, "noise" refers to:`, ch:[`Literal auditory sound only`,`Any background variability or random fluctuations that can be mistaken for a signal`,`A type of memory disorder`,`The absence of any stimulus whatsoever`], ans:1, exp:`In signal detection theory, "noise" refers to the inherent variability or random fluctuations in the sensory or decision-making system (or environment) that can sometimes be mistaken for a true signal, contributing to false alarms.` },
    { q:`A pregnancy test with very high sensitivity but lower specificity would be expected to have:`, ch:[`A low false negative rate but a relatively higher false positive rate`,`A high false negative rate and a low false positive rate`,`No false results of any kind`,`Equal numbers of all four outcome types by definition`], ans:0, exp:`High sensitivity means the test correctly identifies most true positives (low false negative/miss rate), but lower specificity means it may also incorrectly flag some true negatives as positive (higher false positive/false alarm rate)ŌĆöa common trade-off in screening tests designed to minimize missed diagnoses.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps47`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Language Disorders & Aphasia`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Broca's area, located in the frontal lobe, is primarily associated with:`, ch:[`Language comprehension`,`Speech production, with damage causing non-fluent (expressive) aphasia`,`Visual processing`,`Auditory processing of music exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Broca's area, located in the inferior frontal gyrus (typically left hemisphere), is critical for speech production; damage results in Broca's (expressive/non-fluent) aphasia, characterized by slow, effortful, and grammatically simplified speech with relatively preserved comprehension.` },
    { q:`Wernicke's area, located in the temporal lobe, is primarily associated with:`, ch:[`Language comprehension, with damage causing fluent aphasia with impaired comprehension`,`Motor control of the legs`,`Speech production with preserved comprehension`,`Visual acuity`], ans:0, exp:`Wernicke's area, located in the posterior superior temporal gyrus (typically left hemisphere), is critical for language comprehension; damage results in Wernicke's (receptive/fluent) aphasia, characterized by fluent but often nonsensical speech and severely impaired comprehension.` },
    { q:`A patient with Broca's aphasia typically presents with:`, ch:[`Fluent, grammatically correct speech with poor comprehension`,`Non-fluent, effortful, telegraphic speech with relatively preserved comprehension and awareness of their deficit`,`Complete loss of all motor function`,`Normal speech with no deficits`], ans:1, exp:`Broca's aphasia is characterized by non-fluent, halting, effortful speech often lacking grammatical structure (telegraphic speech), while comprehension is relatively preserved; patients are often aware of and frustrated by their language difficulties.` },
    { q:`A patient with Wernicke's aphasia typically presents with:`, ch:[`Fluent but often meaningless or nonsensical speech (word salad), with impaired comprehension and often unawareness of their deficit`,`Complete muteness`,`Normal comprehension and normal speech`,`Preserved ability to read but not speak, with all other functions normal`], ans:0, exp:`Wernicke's aphasia is characterized by fluent speech that is often grammatically correct but semantically empty or nonsensical (sometimes called "word salad"), with significantly impaired comprehension; patients often lack awareness of their language deficits (anosognosia).` },
    { q:`The arcuate fasciculus connects Broca's area and Wernicke's area; damage to this pathway results in:`, ch:[`Conduction aphasia, characterized by poor repetition with relatively preserved fluency and comprehension`,`Complete loss of vision`,`Global aphasia with no preserved language function`,`Normal language function with no deficits`], ans:0, exp:`Conduction aphasia results from damage to the arcuate fasciculus, the white matter tract connecting Broca's and Wernicke's areas; patients have relatively fluent speech and good comprehension but show a disproportionate difficulty with repetition.` },
    { q:`Global aphasia results from damage to:`, ch:[`A small, isolated region with no functional significance`,`Both Broca's and Wernicke's areas (or a large perisylvian region), causing severe impairment in both language production and comprehension`,`Only the cerebellum`,`Only the primary visual cortex`], ans:1, exp:`Global aphasia results from extensive damage affecting both anterior (Broca's) and posterior (Wernicke's) language areas, typically due to a large stroke in the territory of the middle cerebral artery, causing severe impairments in both language production and comprehension.` },
    { q:`Anomic aphasia is primarily characterized by:`, ch:[`Difficulty with word-finding (naming objects), with relatively preserved fluency and comprehension`,`Complete inability to understand any spoken language`,`Total loss of motor speech production`,`Hallucinations`], ans:0, exp:`Anomic aphasia is characterized predominantly by difficulty retrieving names of objects or words (anomia), often manifesting as frequent pauses and circumlocution, while fluency, repetition, and comprehension remain relatively intactŌĆöit is often the mildest form of aphasia.` },
    { q:`Aphasia is best defined as:`, ch:[`A motor speech disorder affecting only articulation, with intact language knowledge`,`An acquired language disorder affecting the production and/or comprehension of language, typically resulting from brain damage`,`A developmental disorder present from birth only`,`A hearing impairment`], ans:1, exp:`Aphasia refers to an acquired impairment of languageŌĆöaffecting speaking, understanding, reading, and/or writingŌĆöresulting from damage to language-related brain areas, most commonly due to stroke, but also from trauma, tumors, or neurodegenerative disease.` },
    { q:`Dysarthria differs from aphasia in that dysarthria involves:`, ch:[`Impaired language comprehension and formulation`,`A motor speech disorder caused by weakness or incoordination of the muscles used for speech, with intact language knowledge`,`The same underlying mechanism as aphasia`,`A purely psychological condition`], ans:1, exp:`Dysarthria is a motor speech disorder resulting from muscle weakness or poor coordination affecting articulation, resonance, or respiration for speech, while the underlying language system (vocabulary, grammar, comprehension) remains intactŌĆödistinguishing it from aphasia, which is a language disorder.` },
    { q:`Apraxia of speech is characterized by:`, ch:[`Difficulty planning and coordinating the precise movements needed for speech, despite no muscle weakness`,`Loss of vocabulary knowledge`,`Impaired auditory comprehension only`,`A visual field defect`], ans:0, exp:`Apraxia of speech involves difficulty planning and sequencing the motor movements required for speech production, despite intact muscle strength and language knowledgeŌĆöpatients may know what they want to say but struggle to coordinate the articulatory movements to produce it.` },
    { q:`In most right-handed individuals, language functions are predominantly localized to:`, ch:[`The right hemisphere`,`The left hemisphere`,`The cerebellum exclusively`,`Equally distributed with no lateralization`], ans:1, exp:`In approximately 95-99% of right-handed individuals (and a majority of left-handed individuals as well), language functions are predominantly lateralized to the left hemisphere, including Broca's and Wernicke's areas.` },
    { q:`A patient who can understand spoken language and produce fluent speech, but cannot repeat phrases verbatim, most likely has damage to:`, ch:[`The arcuate fasciculus (conduction aphasia)`,`The primary visual cortex`,`The cerebellum exclusively`,`The spinal cord`], ans:0, exp:`Difficulty with repetition despite preserved fluency and comprehension is the hallmark of conduction aphasia, resulting from disruption of the arcuate fasciculus, which connects Wernicke's area (comprehension) to Broca's area (production).` },
    { q:`Aphasia assessments typically evaluate which key domains?`, ch:[`Fluency, comprehension, repetition, and naming`,`Only visual acuity`,`Only motor strength in the limbs`,`Only memory for numbers`], ans:0, exp:`Standard aphasia assessments evaluate multiple domainsŌĆöfluency of spontaneous speech, auditory comprehension, repetition ability, and namingŌĆöas the pattern of impairment across these domains helps localize the lesion and classify the type of aphasia.` },
    { q:`Why is early speech-language therapy important following a stroke causing aphasia?`, ch:[`It has no effect on outcomes and is not recommended`,`Neuroplasticity is often greatest in the early period after injury, and early intervention may improve functional language recovery`,`It guarantees complete recovery within 24 hours`,`It is only useful for motor recovery, not language`], ans:1, exp:`The brain exhibits the greatest capacity for neuroplastic reorganization in the early period following a stroke, and early, intensive speech-language therapy is associated with better functional outcomes in language recovery, though some recovery can continue over months to years.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps48`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Research Ethics`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Informed consent requires that research participants be provided with information about:`, ch:[`Only the benefits of the study, not the risks`,`The purpose, procedures, risks, benefits, and their right to withdraw at any time without penalty`,`Nothing, as long as they sign a form`,`Only the financial compensation offered`], ans:1, exp:`Informed consent requires that participants receive comprehensive information about the study's purpose, procedures, potential risks and benefits, confidentiality protections, and their right to withdraw at any time without penalty, allowing them to make a voluntary, informed decision about participation.` },
    { q:`The Belmont Report established three core ethical principles for research involving human subjects: respect for persons, beneficence, and:`, ch:[`Justice`,`Profitability`,`Efficiency`,`Confidentiality alone`], ans:0, exp:`The Belmont Report (1979) outlined three foundational principles: respect for persons (autonomy and protection of those with diminished autonomy), beneficence (maximizing benefits and minimizing harms), and justice (fair distribution of research burdens and benefits).` },
    { q:`The Tuskegee syphilis study is widely cited as a major ethical violation because researchers:`, ch:[`Provided excessive treatment to participants`,`Withheld effective treatment (penicillin) from African American men with syphilis without their informed consent, even after treatment became available`,`Used only animal subjects`,`Obtained proper informed consent from all participants`], ans:1, exp:`The Tuskegee study followed African American men with untreated syphilis for decades without informed consent, and researchers withheld penicillin even after it became the standard effective treatment, representing a profound violation of beneficence, justice, and informed consent.` },
    { q:`An Institutional Review Board (IRB) is responsible for:`, ch:[`Approving and monitoring research involving human subjects to ensure ethical standards are met`,`Providing funding for research studies`,`Conducting the actual research procedures`,`Marketing research findings to the public`], ans:0, exp:`IRBs review proposed research involving human participants to ensure that ethical principles are upheld, including appropriate risk-benefit ratios, adequate informed consent procedures, and protections for vulnerable populations, both before and during the study.` },
    { q:`Beneficence in research ethics requires that researchers:`, ch:[`Maximize possible benefits and minimize possible harms to participants`,`Ignore potential risks to participants`,`Only consider benefits to the researchers themselves`,`Avoid all research involving any risk whatsoever`], ans:0, exp:`Beneficence obligates researchers to design studies that maximize potential benefits (to participants and society) while minimizing potential harms, and to continuously assess whether the risk-benefit ratio remains favorable throughout the study.` },
    { q:`The principle of justice in research ethics is concerned with:`, ch:[`Ensuring that the benefits and burdens of research are fairly distributed across different groups in society`,`Maximizing profit for pharmaceutical companies`,`Ensuring all studies are conducted in courtrooms`,`Excluding all vulnerable populations from any research`], ans:0, exp:`Justice requires that the selection of research subjects be fair, ensuring that no group bears a disproportionate burden of research risks while another group reaps most of the benefitsŌĆöhistorically relevant to concerns about exploitation of vulnerable or marginalized populations.` },
    { q:`Deception in research is generally considered ethically acceptable only when:`, ch:[`It is never acceptable under any circumstances`,`The research could not practicably be conducted without it, the deception does not involve significant risk, and participants are debriefed afterward`,`Participants are never informed of the deception`,`It is used to maximize financial gain for researchers`], ans:1, exp:`Deception may be ethically permissible in limited circumstances when it is necessary for the validity of the research, involves minimal risk, and is followed by debriefing, in which participants are informed of the true nature of the study and given the opportunity to ask questions or withdraw their data.` },
    { q:`Vulnerable populations in research, such as children, prisoners, and pregnant women, require:`, ch:[`No special protections, as standard consent procedures are sufficient`,`Additional safeguards to ensure their participation is voluntary and that they are not subject to coercion or undue influence`,`Complete exclusion from all research`,`Lower compensation than other participants`], ans:1, exp:`Vulnerable populations may have diminished autonomy or be at increased risk of coercion (e.g., prisoners may feel pressured to participate for perceived benefits), so additional ethical safeguards are required to ensure voluntary, informed participation and appropriate risk-benefit considerations.` },
    { q:`Confidentiality in research refers to:`, ch:[`Publishing all participant data publicly`,`Protecting the privacy of participants' data and identities, limiting access to identifiable information`,`A guarantee that no one will ever know a study was conducted`,`The same concept as anonymity in all cases`], ans:1, exp:`Confidentiality involves protecting participants' identifiable information from unauthorized disclosure, typically by limiting access, using coded identifiers, and securely storing dataŌĆödistinct from anonymity, where no identifying information is collected or retained at all.` },
    { q:`The Nuremberg Code, developed after World War II, established as its first principle:`, ch:[`The voluntary consent of the human subject is absolutely essential`,`Research can proceed without any consent if scientifically justified`,`Only government researchers can conduct human research`,`Children are ideal research subjects`], ans:0, exp:`The Nuremberg Code, developed in response to unethical experiments conducted by Nazi physicians during WWII, established voluntary informed consent as the first and most fundamental principle for ethical research involving human subjects.` },
    { q:`A researcher discovers during a study that a participant has a previously undiagnosed serious medical condition unrelated to the study. The most appropriate ethical action is to:`, ch:[`Ignore the finding entirely, as it is outside the scope of the study`,`Inform the participant of the finding (per the consent agreement) and refer them for appropriate follow-up care`,`Publish the finding without the participant's knowledge`,`Use the finding to disqualify the participant without explanation`], ans:1, exp:`Researchers generally have an ethical obligation to disclose clinically significant incidental findings to participants (as outlined in the consent process) and facilitate appropriate referral for follow-up care, balancing respect for persons and beneficence.` },
    { q:`Equipoise in clinical research refers to:`, ch:[`A state of genuine uncertainty among experts regarding which of two treatments is more beneficial, justifying a randomized trial comparing them`,`A guarantee that both treatments are equally ineffective`,`A requirement that all trials use a placebo`,`A statistical method for analyzing data`], ans:0, exp:`Equipoise refers to genuine uncertainty within the expert medical community about whether a new treatment is better, worse, or equivalent to the standard treatment, which is considered an ethical prerequisite for conducting a randomized controlled trial comparing the two.` },
    { q:`Placebo-controlled trials raise ethical concerns particularly when:`, ch:[`An effective standard treatment already exists and withholding it could cause harm to participants in the placebo group`,`No effective treatment currently exists for the condition`,`Participants are fully informed and consent to the possibility of receiving a placebo`,`The condition being studied is not serious`], ans:0, exp:`Using a placebo control is more ethically concerning when an effective standard treatment already exists, as withholding that treatment from the placebo group could result in preventable harmŌĆöin such cases, active-controlled trials (comparing new treatment to standard treatment) are often preferred.` },
    { q:`Why is ongoing IRB monitoring (not just initial approval) important for long-term research studies?`, ch:[`It is not important once a study begins`,`New information (e.g., adverse events, emerging risks) may arise during the study that requires re-evaluation of the risk-benefit balance and potential modification of the protocol or consent process`,`IRBs only review studies after they are completed`,`Ongoing monitoring is solely for financial auditing purposes`], ans:1, exp:`Ongoing IRB oversight ensures that as new information emerges during a studyŌĆösuch as unexpected adverse events or new safety dataŌĆöthe risk-benefit ratio can be reassessed, and protocols, consent forms, or even the continuation of the study can be modified accordingly to protect participants.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps49`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Healthcare Inequality`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Health disparities are best defined as:`, ch:[`Random variations in health outcomes with no identifiable pattern`,`Preventable differences in health outcomes that are closely linked with social, economic, and environmental disadvantage`,`Differences in health outcomes due solely to individual genetic variation`,`A term with no relevance to public health`], ans:1, exp:`Health disparities refer to systematic, plausibly avoidable differences in health outcomes (e.g., disease rates, life expectancy) that adversely affect groups who have historically experienced social or economic disadvantage, often along lines of race, ethnicity, socioeconomic status, or geography.` },
    { q:`Social determinants of health include factors such as:`, ch:[`Only an individual's genetic makeup`,`Conditions in which people are born, grow, live, work, and age, including income, education, housing, and access to healthcare`,`Only hospital quality ratings`,`Only personal lifestyle choices, with no role for social or economic context`], ans:1, exp:`Social determinants of health encompass the broad range of social, economic, and environmental conditions that influence health outcomes, including income, education, employment, housing, neighborhood environment, social support, and access to healthcare and healthy food.` },
    { q:`Implicit bias among healthcare providers has been shown to potentially contribute to disparities by:`, ch:[`Having no measurable effect on clinical decision-making`,`Influencing clinical decisions and patient-provider communication in ways that may disadvantage certain racial or ethnic groups, even without conscious intent`,`Only affecting providers who explicitly endorse prejudiced views`,`Improving care equally for all patient groups`], ans:1, exp:`Research suggests that implicit biasesŌĆöunconscious attitudes that providers may holdŌĆöcan subtly influence clinical decision-making, communication style, and pain management recommendations, potentially contributing to disparities in care quality even among providers who consciously reject prejudice.` },
    { q:`Geographic disparities in healthcare access, such as those experienced in rural areas, are often related to:`, ch:[`An oversupply of healthcare providers in rural areas`,`Provider shortages, longer travel distances to care, and limited availability of specialty services`,`Universal access to identical services regardless of location`,`A complete absence of any health needs in rural populations`], ans:1, exp:`Rural areas often face shortages of healthcare providers (especially specialists), longer travel distances and times to reach care facilities, and limited availability of specialized services, contributing to disparities in access and health outcomes compared to urban areas.` },
    { q:`Health insurance status is strongly associated with:`, ch:[`No difference in healthcare utilization or outcomes`,`Access to preventive care, timely diagnosis, and overall health outcomes, with uninsured individuals often facing delayed care and worse outcomes`,`Only the cost of care, with no impact on health outcomes`,`Improved outcomes only for insured individuals with chronic diseases, but not acute conditions`], ans:1, exp:`Lack of health insurance is associated with delayed or forgone care, reduced use of preventive services, later-stage diagnosis of conditions like cancer, and worse overall health outcomes, representing a major contributor to health disparities in systems where insurance is not universal.` },
    { q:`Language barriers between patients and healthcare providers can contribute to disparities by:`, ch:[`Having no impact on the quality of care provided`,`Leading to miscommunication, reduced patient understanding of diagnoses and treatment plans, and lower satisfaction with care`,`Improving diagnostic accuracy`,`Only affecting billing processes`], ans:1, exp:`Language barriers can result in miscommunication about symptoms, diagnoses, and treatment instructions, reduced adherence to treatment plans, lower patient satisfaction, and increased risk of medical errorsŌĆöprofessional interpreter services help mitigate these effects.` },
    { q:`The term "medical mistrust" among certain populations, particularly some racial and ethnic minority groups, often stems from:`, ch:[`A complete absence of any historical basis`,`Historical and ongoing experiences of discrimination and unethical treatment within the healthcare system (e.g., the Tuskegee study)`,`Excessive trust in alternative medicine only`,`Government propaganda with no factual basis`], ans:1, exp:`Medical mistrust among some populations is rooted in documented historical injustices (such as the Tuskegee syphilis study) as well as ongoing experiences of discrimination and disparities in care, and can affect willingness to seek care, participate in research, or follow medical recommendations.` },
    { q:`Implicit in the concept of "cultural competence" in healthcare is the idea that providers should:`, ch:[`Treat all patients identically regardless of their cultural background`,`Develop awareness, knowledge, and skills to provide effective care to patients from diverse cultural backgrounds, respecting their values and beliefs`,`Avoid discussing cultural factors with patients`,`Require all patients to adopt the provider's cultural perspective`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural competence involves healthcare providers developing the awareness, knowledge, and communication skills necessary to provide respectful and effective care to patients from diverse cultural, linguistic, and religious backgrounds, recognizing how cultural factors may influence health beliefs and behaviors.` },
    { q:`Food deserts, areas with limited access to affordable and nutritious food, are associated with:`, ch:[`Lower rates of diet-related chronic diseases`,`Higher rates of obesity, diabetes, and other diet-related chronic conditions due to limited access to healthy food options`,`No relationship to health outcomes`,`Increased availability of fresh produce`], ans:1, exp:`Food desertsŌĆöareas where residents have limited access to supermarkets offering affordable, nutritious food, often relying instead on convenience stores or fast foodŌĆöare associated with higher rates of obesity, type 2 diabetes, and cardiovascular disease.` },
    { q:`The Affordable Care Act (ACA) aimed to reduce health disparities partly by:`, ch:[`Eliminating all health insurance options`,`Expanding access to health insurance coverage through Medicaid expansion and health insurance marketplaces`,`Reducing funding for preventive services`,`Restricting coverage to only the wealthiest individuals`], ans:1, exp:`The ACA expanded health insurance coverage through Medicaid expansion (in states that adopted it) and the creation of health insurance marketplaces with subsidies, aiming to reduce the number of uninsured individuals and improve access to preventive and other healthcare services.` },
    { q:`Disparities in maternal mortality rates between Black and white women in the United States are an example of:`, ch:[`A purely genetic phenomenon with no social component`,`A persistent health disparity influenced by factors including access to quality care, implicit bias, and the cumulative effects of structural racism`,`A disparity that has been completely eliminated`,`An issue unrelated to social determinants of health`], ans:1, exp:`Significant racial disparities in maternal mortality persist even after controlling for socioeconomic status and education, suggesting contributions from factors such as implicit bias in clinical care, differential access to quality care, and the cumulative physiological effects of chronic stress related to structural racism.` },
    { q:`Telehealth has been proposed as one strategy to address healthcare disparities by:`, ch:[`Eliminating the need for any healthcare providers`,`Increasing access to care for individuals in rural or underserved areas who face transportation or provider shortage barriers`,`Only benefiting individuals with no internet access`,`Increasing costs for all patients uniformly`], ans:1, exp:`Telehealth can help address geographic and transportation barriers to care, particularly benefiting patients in rural or underserved areas with limited access to specialists, though disparities in internet/technology access (the "digital divide") can limit its benefits for some populations.` },
    { q:`A community health worker (CHW) program that employs trusted local residents to help connect community members with healthcare and social services is an example of an intervention targeting:`, ch:[`Only biological determinants of health`,`Social determinants of health, by addressing barriers related to access, trust, and navigation of complex systems`,`Genetic engineering`,`Pharmaceutical development`], ans:1, exp:`Community health worker programs leverage trusted relationships within communities to help individuals navigate healthcare systems, access social services, and address social determinants of health (e.g., housing, transportation, food security), which can improve health outcomes and reduce disparities.` },
    { q:`Why might addressing only individual-level behaviors (e.g., "eat healthier") be insufficient to reduce health disparities at a population level?`, ch:[`Individual behaviors have no impact on health whatsoever`,`Structural and social factors (e.g., food access, income, neighborhood safety, healthcare access) constrain individual choices, so addressing only individual behavior without addressing these broader determinants is unlikely to substantially reduce population-level disparities`,`All individuals have identical access to resources regardless of social context`,`Disparities are entirely due to individual choice with no structural component`], ans:1, exp:`Individual health behaviors are shaped by the broader social and structural context in which people live (e.g., availability of healthy food, safe places to exercise, healthcare access); interventions focused solely on individual behavior change without addressing these structural constraints are less likely to produce meaningful reductions in population-level health disparities.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps50`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Globalization & Cross-Cultural Medicine`, diff:`Hard`, qs:[
    { q:`Globalization's effect on the spread of infectious disease is best illustrated by:`, ch:[`Decreased international travel reducing disease spread`,`Increased international travel and trade facilitating the rapid spread of pathogens across borders`,`Complete isolation of all countries from each other`,`No change in disease transmission patterns over time`], ans:1, exp:`Globalization has dramatically increased the speed and scale of international travel and trade, allowing infectious diseases to spread across borders and continents far more rapidly than in the past, as demonstrated by recent pandemics.` },
    { q:`The "epidemiological transition" refers to the shift in a population's leading causes of death and illness from:`, ch:[`Chronic diseases to infectious diseases as countries develop`,`Infectious diseases and malnutrition to chronic, non-communicable diseases as countries develop economically`,`A pattern that does not occur in any country`,`Genetic diseases to environmental diseases only`], ans:1, exp:`The epidemiological transition describes a pattern observed as countries undergo economic development: leading causes of morbidity and mortality shift from infectious diseases and malnutrition toward chronic, non-communicable diseases (e.g., cardiovascular disease, cancer, diabetes) associated with aging populations and lifestyle changes.` },
    { q:`Medical tourism refers to:`, ch:[`Tourists visiting hospitals as part of sightseeing`,`The practice of traveling to another country to receive medical treatment, often to access lower-cost or more readily available care`,`A type of vaccination requirement for international travel`,`A disease that only affects tourists`], ans:1, exp:`Medical tourism involves individuals traveling internationally to obtain medical, dental, or surgical care, often motivated by lower costs, shorter wait times, or access to procedures not available or legal in their home country, raising questions about continuity of care and quality assurance.` },
    { q:`Brain drain in global health refers to:`, ch:[`A neurological condition`,`The emigration of highly trained healthcare professionals from low-resource countries to higher-income countries, depleting the healthcare workforce in their home countries`,`A type of medical equipment shortage`,`The loss of medical knowledge over time`], ans:1, exp:`Brain drain describes the migration of skilled healthcare workers (physicians, nurses) from low- and middle-income countries to higher-income countries seeking better pay and working conditions, which can exacerbate healthcare workforce shortages in the countries of origin.` },
    { q:`Culture-bound syndromes refer to:`, ch:[`Diseases that occur in all cultures with identical presentations`,`Patterns of symptoms or behaviors recognized as illnesses within specific cultural contexts, which may not map directly onto standard biomedical diagnostic categories`,`A category that no longer exists in modern medicine`,`Diseases caused exclusively by genetic mutations`], ans:1, exp:`Culture-bound syndromes are recurrent, locality-specific patterns of aberrant behavior or troubling experience that may be recognized as afflictions within particular cultural groups, illustrating how cultural context shapes the expression and interpretation of psychological and physical distress.` },
    { q:`When working with patients from different cultural backgrounds, the explanatory model of illness refers to:`, ch:[`The biomedical diagnosis only`,`The patient's own beliefs about the cause, course, and treatment of their illness, which may differ from the biomedical model`,`A model used only by researchers, never by clinicians`,`A model that is identical across all cultures`], ans:1, exp:`The explanatory model of illness, a concept developed by Arthur Kleinman, refers to a patient's personal and cultural understanding of their illnessŌĆöincluding perceived causes, expected course, and appropriate treatmentsŌĆöwhich clinicians should explore to provide culturally sensitive and effective care.` },
    { q:`The World Health Organization's role in global health includes:`, ch:[`Setting international health standards, coordinating responses to global health emergencies, and providing technical support to countries`,`Providing direct medical care to all individuals worldwide`,`Replacing national healthcare systems`,`Having no involvement in pandemic response`], ans:0, exp:`The WHO, a specialized agency of the United Nations, plays a key role in setting international health standards and guidelines, coordinating responses to global health emergencies (e.g., declaring public health emergencies of international concern), and providing technical assistance to member countries.` },
    { q:`Health disparities between high-income and low-income countries are most starkly illustrated by differences in:`, ch:[`Average shoe size`,`Maternal and infant mortality rates, life expectancy, and access to basic healthcare services`,`Television ownership rates`,`Internet usage exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`Stark disparities exist between high-income and low-income countries in key health indicators such as maternal mortality, infant and child mortality, life expectancy, and access to basic healthcare and sanitation, reflecting broader disparities in resources and infrastructure.` },
    { q:`Traditional or alternative medicine practices in many cultures often coexist with biomedical healthcare. Effective cross-cultural care typically involves:`, ch:[`Dismissing all traditional practices as invalid`,`Acknowledging and, where appropriate, integrating patients' use of traditional practices while ensuring safety and avoiding harmful interactions with biomedical treatments`,`Refusing to treat any patient who uses traditional medicine`,`Requiring patients to choose only one system with no discussion`], ans:1, exp:`Culturally competent care involves openly discussing patients' use of traditional or alternative practices, respecting their cultural significance, while also assessing for potential interactions or contraindications with prescribed biomedical treatments, fostering trust and improved adherence.` },
    { q:`The concept of "global burden of disease" is used to:`, ch:[`Measure only the financial cost of healthcare systems`,`Quantify and compare the impact of different diseases, injuries, and risk factors across populations using metrics like disability-adjusted life years (DALYs)`,`Rank countries by population size only`,`Measure only mortality, with no consideration of disability`], ans:1, exp:`The global burden of disease framework uses metrics such as disability-adjusted life years (DALYs)ŌĆöwhich combine years of life lost due to premature death and years lived with disabilityŌĆöto compare the health impact of various diseases and risk factors across different populations and over time.` },
    { q:`Vaccine hesitancy as a global health challenge is influenced by:`, ch:[`Only a single, universal factor with no cultural variation`,`A complex interplay of factors including misinformation, historical mistrust of medical institutions, religious beliefs, and access barriers, which vary across cultural and social contexts`,`Complete absence of any psychological or social component`,`Factors that are identical across all countries and communities`], ans:1, exp:`Vaccine hesitancy arises from a complex combination of factors, including misinformation and disinformation, historical experiences with medical institutions, religious or philosophical beliefs, perceived risk versus benefit, and practical access barriers, which vary significantly across different cultural and social contexts and require tailored public health responses.` },
    { q:`The "social gradient" in health is observed:`, ch:[`Only within a single country and not across countries`,`Both within and across countries, with health outcomes generally improving as socioeconomic status increases`,`Only in the wealthiest nations`,`As a phenomenon with no consistent pattern`], ans:1, exp:`The social gradient in healthŌĆöwhere health outcomes improve incrementally with increasing socioeconomic statusŌĆöhas been documented both within countries (across different social classes) and across countries (comparing nations with different overall levels of economic development), highlighting the pervasive influence of social determinants on health globally.` },
    { q:`When treating an immigrant patient who has limited English proficiency and comes from a culture with different beliefs about disclosure of terminal diagnoses, the most appropriate approach is to:`, ch:[`Withhold information from the patient entirely without discussion`,`Use a professional interpreter and explore the patient's preferences regarding information-sharing and decision-making, which may involve family members, while respecting patient autonomy`,`Insist on the same disclosure practices regardless of patient preference`,`Avoid treating the patient until they learn English`], ans:1, exp:`Culturally sensitive care involves using professional interpreters (not family members, to avoid errors and privacy issues) and openly discussing the patient's preferences regarding how much information they want to receive and who should be involved in decision-making, balancing respect for autonomy with cultural humility regarding differing norms around disclosure.` },
    { q:`A key challenge in conducting global health research and interventions is ensuring:`, ch:[`That interventions developed in high-income countries are applied identically without adaptation`,`That interventions are culturally appropriate, sustainable, and developed in partnership with local communities and health systems`,`That local healthcare workers are excluded from program design`,`That research findings are never shared with the host country`], ans:1, exp:`Effective global health interventions require cultural appropriateness, sustainability within local health system capacity, and meaningful partnership with local communities and health workers, rather than simply transplanting models developed in different contexts without adaptationŌĆöan approach sometimes criticized as "parachute research" when done poorly.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps51`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Advanced Statistics ŌĆö Correlation, Regression & Effect Size`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`A correlation coefficient (r) of -0.85 indicates:`, ch:[`A weak positive relationship`,`A strong negative relationship between two variables`,`No relationship between two variables`,`That one variable causes the other`], ans:1, exp:`A correlation coefficient close to -1 indicates a strong negative (inverse) linear relationshipŌĆöas one variable increases, the other tends to decrease. Correlation values range from -1 to +1, with magnitude indicating strength and sign indicating direction; correlation does not imply causation.` },
    { q:`The coefficient of determination (r┬▓) represents:`, ch:[`The strength of a causal relationship`,`The proportion of variance in one variable that is explained by (or shared with) the other variable`,`The sample size required for significance`,`The probability of a Type I error`], ans:1, exp:`R-squared represents the proportion of variance in the dependent variable that can be statistically explained by the independent variable(s); for example, an r of 0.7 yields an r┬▓ of 0.49, meaning 49% of the variance is shared between the variables.` },
    { q:`In linear regression, the slope coefficient represents:`, ch:[`The predicted value of Y when X equals zero`,`The average change in the dependent variable (Y) for each one-unit increase in the independent variable (X)`,`The correlation coefficient`,`The total variance explained by the model`], ans:1, exp:`The slope (regression coefficient) quantifies the expected change in the dependent variable for each one-unit increase in the independent variable, while the y-intercept represents the predicted value of Y when X equals zero.` },
    { q:`Cohen's d is a measure of:`, ch:[`Statistical significance (p-value)`,`Effect size, expressing the standardized difference between two means`,`Sample size`,`Correlation strength only`], ans:1, exp:`Cohen's d expresses the difference between two group means in terms of standard deviation units, providing a standardized measure of effect size that is independent of sample size, with conventional benchmarks of 0.2 (small), 0.5 (medium), and 0.8 (large).` },
    { q:`A statistically significant result (p < 0.05) with a very small effect size most likely indicates:`, ch:[`A clinically meaningful and important finding regardless of sample size`,`That the result, while unlikely due to chance, may have limited practical or clinical significance, possibly due to a very large sample size`,`That the study has no value`,`That the null hypothesis is definitely true`], ans:1, exp:`With sufficiently large sample sizes, even very small, practically unimportant differences can become statistically significant; effect size measures (like Cohen's d) help assess whether a statistically significant finding is also practically or clinically meaningful.` },
    { q:`A confidence interval of 95% for a mean difference means:`, ch:[`There is a 95% probability that the true population parameter falls within this specific interval`,`If the study were repeated many times, approximately 95% of the calculated confidence intervals would contain the true population parameter`,`95% of individual data points fall within this range`,`The result is statistically significant regardless of whether the interval includes zero`], ans:1, exp:`The frequentist interpretation of a 95% confidence interval is that, over many repeated samples, approximately 95% of such intervals constructed in the same way would contain the true population parameterŌĆöit does not mean there is a 95% probability the true value lies in this particular interval.` },
    { q:`Multiple regression analysis allows researchers to:`, ch:[`Examine the relationship between one independent variable and one dependent variable only`,`Examine the relationship between multiple independent variables and a single dependent variable, controlling for the effects of other variables in the model`,`Establish causation definitively`,`Eliminate the need for random sampling`], ans:1, exp:`Multiple regression extends simple regression by including multiple predictor (independent) variables, allowing researchers to assess the unique contribution of each predictor to the outcome while statistically controlling for (holding constant) the other predictors in the model.` },
    { q:`A meta-analysis combines results from multiple studies to:`, ch:[`Always confirm the findings of the largest individual study`,`Produce a more precise estimate of an effect by pooling data, increasing statistical power`,`Eliminate the need for individual studies`,`Guarantee the absence of bias`], ans:1, exp:`Meta-analyses statistically combine results from multiple independent studies addressing similar research questions, increasing overall statistical power and providing a more precise pooled estimate of the effect, though they remain susceptible to issues like publication bias and heterogeneity among included studies.` },
    { q:`Heterogeneity in a meta-analysis refers to:`, ch:[`The degree of variability in effect sizes across the included studies, which may be due to differences in populations, methods, or interventions`,`The total number of participants across all studies`,`A measure of publication bias only`,`The p-value of the pooled estimate`], ans:0, exp:`Heterogeneity refers to the variation in study outcomes (effect sizes) across studies included in a meta-analysis; high heterogeneity may indicate that the studies are not measuring the same underlying effect, possibly due to differences in populations, interventions, or methodologies, and can be assessed using statistics like I┬▓.` },
    { q:`A regression to the mean phenomenon explains why:`, ch:[`Extreme scores on a measure tend to be followed by scores closer to the average on a subsequent measurement, even without any intervention`,`All measurements become more extreme over time`,`Mean values are always inaccurate`,`Sample sizes must always be increased`], ans:0, exp:`Regression to the mean describes the statistical tendency for extreme initial measurements (e.g., very high blood pressure readings) to be followed by measurements closer to the average on retesting, due to natural variabilityŌĆöimportant to consider when evaluating apparent treatment effects in studies without control groups.` },
    { q:`A scatterplot showing a curvilinear (e.g., U-shaped) relationship between two variables would likely show what value when a standard Pearson correlation coefficient is calculated?`, ch:[`A coefficient close to 1 or -1, accurately reflecting the strong relationship`,`A coefficient close to 0, even though a strong (non-linear) relationship exists, because Pearson's r only captures linear relationships`,`An undefined value`,`Always exactly 0.5`], ans:1, exp:`Pearson's correlation coefficient specifically measures the strength of a linear relationship; a strong curvilinear (e.g., U-shaped or inverted U-shaped) relationship can yield a Pearson r close to zero despite a clear and meaningful underlying relationship between the variables, illustrating the importance of visualizing data.` },
    { q:`In a study, two variables are found to be correlated, but a third variable influences both, creating an apparent but non-causal relationship. This third variable is called a:`, ch:[`Dependent variable`,`Confounding variable`,`Independent variable`,`Control variable that has been properly accounted for`], ans:1, exp:`A confounding variable is associated with both the independent and dependent variables and can create a spurious correlation between them; failing to account for confounders can lead to incorrect causal inferences from correlational data.` },
    { q:`A z-score of +2.0 for an individual's test score indicates that the individual's score is:`, ch:[`Exactly at the mean of the distribution`,`Two standard deviations above the mean`,`Two raw points above the mean`,`In the bottom 2% of the distribution`], ans:1, exp:`A z-score expresses how many standard deviations a value is from the mean; a z-score of +2.0 indicates the score is two standard deviations above the mean, which in a normal distribution corresponds to approximately the 97.7th percentile.` },
    { q:`When comparing means across more than two groups, why is conducting multiple separate t-tests problematic compared to using ANOVA?`, ch:[`T-tests are always less powerful than ANOVA regardless of context`,`Conducting multiple t-tests increases the overall probability of a Type I error (false positive) across the family of comparisons`,`ANOVA cannot be used with more than two groups`,`T-tests require larger sample sizes than ANOVA in all cases`], ans:1, exp:`Each individual statistical test carries a risk of a Type I error (commonly set at 5%); performing multiple pairwise t-tests inflates the overall (family-wise) error rate across all comparisons, whereas ANOVA tests for an overall difference among group means in a single test, controlling the overall Type I error rate (with post-hoc tests used for pairwise comparisons if the overall test is significant).` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps52`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Experimental Design & Replication Crisis`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`The "replication crisis" in psychology refers to:`, ch:[`The observation that a substantial proportion of published findings, particularly in social psychology, fail to be replicated in subsequent independent studies`,`A crisis caused by too many replication studies being conducted`,`A problem unique to physics, with no relevance to psychology`,`The complete abandonment of the scientific method`], ans:0, exp:`The replication crisis refers to widespread concern, supported by large-scale replication projects, that many published findings in psychology (and other fields) do not replicate when independent researchers attempt to reproduce the original studies, raising questions about the reliability of the published literature.` },
    { q:`P-hacking refers to the practice of:`, ch:[`Conducting a single pre-registered analysis as planned`,`Manipulating data analysis (e.g., trying multiple statistical tests, selectively reporting outcomes) until a statistically significant result (p < 0.05) is obtained`,`Always reporting non-significant results`,`A method approved by all journals as best practice`], ans:1, exp:`P-hacking involves exploiting flexibility in data analysisŌĆösuch as trying different statistical tests, excluding outliers selectively, or analyzing multiple outcome measuresŌĆöuntil a statistically significant result is found, which inflates the false positive rate and contributes to non-replicable findings.` },
    { q:`Pre-registration of a study involves:`, ch:[`Publishing the results before conducting the study`,`Publicly documenting the study's hypotheses, methods, and analysis plan before data collection begins, to reduce the potential for p-hacking and HARKing`,`Registering only successful studies after the fact`,`A process that has no impact on research credibility`], ans:1, exp:`Pre-registration involves specifying hypotheses, methods, and planned analyses in a publicly accessible registry before data collection, which helps distinguish confirmatory (hypothesis-testing) research from exploratory research and reduces opportunities for p-hacking and selective reporting.` },
    { q:`HARKing refers to the practice of:`, ch:[`Hypothesizing After the Results are KnownŌĆöpresenting a post-hoc explanation as if it were an a priori hypothesis`,`Conducting research with no hypotheses at all`,`A statistical technique for handling missing data`,`A method for increasing sample size`], ans:0, exp:`HARKing ("Hypothesizing After the Results are Known") involves presenting a hypothesis that was developed after seeing the data as though it had been formulated before the study, which can mislead readers about the exploratory versus confirmatory nature of the findings and inflate the apparent support for the hypothesis.` },
    { q:`The "file drawer problem" refers to:`, ch:[`A problem with physical storage of paper records`,`The tendency for studies with non-significant or null results to remain unpublished, skewing the published literature toward positive findings`,`A method for organizing pre-registrations`,`A statistical correction applied automatically by journals`], ans:1, exp:`The file drawer problem describes how studies finding null or non-significant results are less likely to be submitted or accepted for publication and often remain in researchers' "file drawers," leading the published literature to overrepresent positive findingsŌĆöa major contributor to publication bias.` },
    { q:`A direct (exact) replication attempts to:`, ch:[`Test a completely different hypothesis using different methods`,`Reproduce the original study's methods as closely as possible to determine whether the original finding can be obtained again`,`Avoid using any of the original study's procedures`,`Only replicate studies that already failed`], ans:1, exp:`Direct (exact) replications aim to closely reproduce the original study's procedures, materials, and population to assess whether the original finding can be reproduced, providing the most direct test of the reliability of the original result.` },
    { q:`A conceptual replication differs from a direct replication in that it:`, ch:[`Uses identical methods and measures as the original study`,`Tests the same underlying hypothesis or theoretical question using different methods, operationalizations, or populations`,`Cannot provide any useful information about a finding's robustness`,`Always produces the same result as a direct replication`], ans:1, exp:`Conceptual replications test the same underlying theoretical hypothesis but using different operationalizations, measures, methods, or populations, which can demonstrate whether a finding generalizes across different contexts, though differing results can be harder to interpret (failure to replicate vs. genuine boundary condition).` },
    { q:`Researcher degrees of freedom refers to:`, ch:[`The formal statistical degrees of freedom in an ANOVA`,`The numerous decisions researchers can make during data collection and analysis (e.g., when to stop collecting data, which variables to include) that can be exploited, intentionally or not, to obtain significant results`,`A measure of how many co-authors a paper has`,`A concept that has been fully eliminated by modern statistical software`], ans:1, exp:`"Researcher degrees of freedom" refers to the flexibility researchers have in numerous methodological and analytical decisions throughout a study; without pre-registration, this flexibility can be consciously or unconsciously exploited to increase the likelihood of finding statistically significant (but potentially spurious) results.` },
    { q:`Open science practices, such as data sharing and pre-registration, aim to address the replication crisis by:`, ch:[`Making research less transparent`,`Increasing transparency, allowing other researchers to verify analyses, attempt replications, and detect questionable research practices`,`Eliminating the need for peer review`,`Guaranteeing that all studies will replicate successfully`], ans:1, exp:`Open science practicesŌĆöincluding pre-registration, open data and materials, and registered reportsŌĆöincrease transparency and accountability in the research process, making it easier for the scientific community to verify findings, attempt replications, and identify questionable research practices.` },
    { q:`A "registered report" is a publication format in which:`, ch:[`Journals agree to publish a study based on the quality of its introduction and methods (peer-reviewed before data collection), regardless of whether the results are significant`,`Only studies with significant results are accepted`,`Researchers must pay extra fees for guaranteed publication`,`The study design cannot be peer-reviewed`], ans:0, exp:`In the registered report format, the study's rationale, hypotheses, and methods undergo peer review and receive in-principle acceptance before data collection begins; publication is then guaranteed regardless of the outcome (significant or null), which directly addresses publication bias.` },
    { q:`Why might a large-scale replication project find a smaller effect size than the original study, even when the effect is genuinely real?`, ch:[`Replication is methodologically impossible`,`The original published effect size may have been inflated due to publication bias (only significant, often larger, effects get published) and small original sample sizes`,`Effect sizes always increase with replication`,`Larger samples always produce larger effect sizes`], ans:1, exp:`Due to publication bias favoring significant results, and the tendency for studies with smaller sample sizes to require larger observed effects to reach significance, originally published effect sizes are often inflated estimates ("winner's curse"); larger, well-powered replication studies tend to produce more accurate (often smaller) effect size estimates.` },
    { q:`The Open Science Collaboration's large-scale replication project of 100 psychology studies (2015) found that:`, ch:[`100% of studies replicated successfully with identical effect sizes`,`A substantial proportion of studies (less than half) showed a statistically significant effect in the replication, and average effect sizes were generally smaller than the original studies`,`No studies replicated at all`,`Replication success had no relationship to original effect size or sample size`], ans:1, exp:`The 2015 Open Science Collaboration project found that less than half of the 100 replicated studies produced statistically significant results matching the original direction, and average effect sizes in replications were roughly half the magnitude of the original studies, fueling widespread discussion of the replication crisis.` },
    { q:`Why is statistical power particularly important in the context of the replication crisis?`, ch:[`Power is irrelevant to replication`,`Underpowered original studies (small sample sizes) are more likely to produce inflated or spurious significant effects that fail to replicate in adequately powered follow-up studies`,`High power guarantees a study's hypothesis is correct`,`Power only matters for studies with null results`], ans:1, exp:`Underpowered studies have a higher likelihood that any statistically significant result obtained is either an inflated estimate of a true effect or a false positive; adequately powered replication studies (with larger samples) provide a more reliable test of whether an effect is real and of what magnitude.` },
    { q:`A key recommendation arising from the replication crisis is to shift emphasis from:`, ch:[`Replication studies toward only novel findings`,`Solely valuing novel, surprising findings toward also valuing rigorous, well-powered, and replicable research, including direct replications`,`Quantitative methods toward purely qualitative methods`,`Peer review toward no review at all`], ans:1, exp:`In response to the replication crisis, the field has increasingly emphasized the value of rigorous methodology, adequate statistical power, transparency, and replication studies (which were previously undervalued and difficult to publish), alongsideŌĆönot instead ofŌĆönovel discoveries.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps53`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Behavioral Genetics & Heritability`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Heritability is best defined as:`, ch:[`The proportion of variance in a trait within a population that can be attributed to genetic differences among individuals`,`The probability that an individual will inherit a specific trait from a parent`,`A fixed value that is identical for all traits and populations`,`The percentage of an individual's traits that are genetic`], ans:0, exp:`Heritability is a population-level statistic representing the proportion of phenotypic variance in a trait that is attributable to genetic variance within that specific population under specific environmental conditionsŌĆöit does not indicate the degree to which an individual's traits are genetically determined.` },
    { q:`Twin studies estimate heritability by comparing trait similarity between:`, ch:[`Only fraternal (dizygotic) twins`,`Monozygotic (identical) twins, who share ~100% of their genes, and dizygotic (fraternal) twins, who share ~50% of their genes on average`,`Only siblings raised in different households`,`Only adopted children and their biological parents`], ans:1, exp:`Twin studies compare the concordance (similarity) of traits between monozygotic twins (who share virtually all their genes) and dizygotic twins (who share on average 50% of their segregating genes, like regular siblings); greater similarity in monozygotic twins compared to dizygotic twins suggests a genetic contribution to the trait.` },
    { q:`A heritability estimate of 0.5 for a trait means:`, ch:[`50% of an individual's expression of the trait is due to genetics, and 50% is due to environment`,`50% of the variance in the trait across the population studied is attributable to genetic differences among individuals, with the remainder attributable to environmental factors and error`,`The trait is inherited from only one parent`,`The trait will appear in exactly half of all offspring`], ans:1, exp:`Heritability estimates apply to population-level variance, not individual-level causation; a heritability of 0.5 means that, within the studied population and environment, about half of the observed variation in the trait can be statistically attributed to genetic differences among individuals.` },
    { q:`Shared environment, in behavioral genetics, refers to:`, ch:[`Environmental influences that make siblings raised together more similar to each other (e.g., socioeconomic status of the household)`,`Environmental influences that make siblings raised together different from each other`,`A purely genetic concept`,`Environmental factors that are identical across all families regardless of context`], ans:0, exp:`Shared environment refers to environmental factors experienced in common by siblings raised in the same household (e.g., parental income, neighborhood, parenting style), which tend to make siblings more similar to one another, independent of shared genetics.` },
    { q:`Non-shared (unique) environment refers to:`, ch:[`Environmental influences shared by all family members equally`,`Environmental experiences unique to each individual that contribute to differences between siblings, even those raised in the same household (e.g., different peer groups, individual experiences)`,`A factor with no measurable impact on behavior`,`The same as genetic influence`], ans:1, exp:`Non-shared environment encompasses individual-specific experiences (e.g., different friend groups, illnesses, or teachers) that contribute to differences between siblings raised in the same family, and behavioral genetic studies often find that non-shared environmental influences account for a substantial portion of variance in personality and behavior.` },
    { q:`Gene-environment interaction (G x E) refers to:`, ch:[`The idea that genes and environment never interact`,`The phenomenon where the effect of a genetic variant on a trait depends on the environmental context, or vice versa`,`A purely theoretical concept with no empirical support`,`The same concept as heritability`], ans:1, exp:`Gene-environment interaction occurs when the effect of a genotype on a phenotype depends on the environment (or the effect of an environmental exposure depends on genotype)ŌĆöfor example, a genetic variant associated with depression risk may only manifest in individuals exposed to significant early life stress.` },
    { q:`Gene-environment correlation refers to:`, ch:[`The phenomenon where genetic predispositions influence the types of environments individuals are exposed to or seek out`,`A statistical artifact with no real biological basis`,`The complete independence of genes and environment`,`A concept that applies only to physical traits, not behavior`], ans:0, exp:`Gene-environment correlation describes how genetic predispositions can influence the environments individuals experienceŌĆöfor example, a child with a genetic predisposition toward sociability (evocative correlation) may elicit more social interaction from others, or a musically talented child (passive correlation) may be raised by musically inclined parents who also provide a musically rich environment.` },
    { q:`Adoption studies are valuable in behavioral genetics because they allow researchers to:`, ch:[`Eliminate the need for any genetic data`,`Disentangle genetic and environmental influences by comparing adopted children to both their biological relatives (genetic influence) and adoptive relatives (environmental influence)`,`Study only identical twins`,`Prove that environment has no effect on any trait`], ans:1, exp:`Adoption studies compare similarities between adopted individuals and their biological relatives (with whom they share genes but not environment) versus their adoptive relatives (with whom they share environment but not genes), helping to separate genetic from environmental contributions to trait variance.` },
    { q:`The "missing heritability" problem refers to the observation that:`, ch:[`Twin and family studies estimate heritability values higher than what can be explained by specific genetic variants identified through genome-wide association studies (GWAS)`,`Heritability estimates are always zero for behavioral traits`,`GWAS studies have identified all genetic contributions to complex traits`,`Heritability can only be measured in plants`], ans:0, exp:`Missing heritability refers to the gap between heritability estimates from twin/family studies (often relatively high for traits like height or intelligence) and the much smaller proportion of variance explained by individual genetic variants identified through GWAS, possibly due to factors like rare variants, gene-gene interactions, and epigenetic effects not fully captured by current methods.` },
    { q:`Polygenic traits, such as height and many psychiatric conditions, are influenced by:`, ch:[`A single gene with complete penetrance`,`Many genes, each contributing a small effect, combined with environmental factors`,`No genetic factors whatsoever`,`Only mitochondrial DNA`], ans:1, exp:`Polygenic traits result from the combined small effects of many different genetic variants across the genome, interacting with environmental factors, in contrast to monogenic (Mendelian) traits, which are determined primarily by a single gene.` },
    { q:`A polygenic risk score is calculated by:`, ch:[`Measuring a single gene's expression level`,`Aggregating the effects of many genetic variants, each weighted by their estimated effect size from GWAS, to estimate an individual's genetic predisposition to a trait or disease`,`Counting the total number of chromosomes`,`Measuring environmental exposures only`], ans:1, exp:`Polygenic risk scores combine information across many genetic variants (typically identified through genome-wide association studies), each weighted according to its estimated effect on the trait, to provide an aggregate estimate of an individual's genetic predisposition, though such scores currently explain only a portion of the variance for most complex traits.` },
    { q:`Why does heritability NOT indicate that a trait is unchangeable or that intervention is futile?`, ch:[`Heritability estimates are always zero, so this question is moot`,`Heritability is a population-level statistic specific to a given environment; even highly heritable traits can be modified by environmental interventions (e.g., the heritability of phenylketonuria-related intellectual disability is high, but dietary intervention prevents the outcome)`,`Heritability always equals 100% for behavioral traits`,`Environmental interventions are impossible by definition`], ans:1, exp:`A classic example is phenylketonuria (PKU): the genetic component is essentially fully penetrant (heritability near 100% in untreated populations), yet a simple dietary intervention (avoiding phenylalanine) can completely prevent the associated intellectual disabilityŌĆödemonstrating that high heritability does not preclude effective environmental intervention.` },
    { q:`Epigenetics refers to:`, ch:[`Changes in the DNA sequence itself`,`Heritable changes in gene expression that do not involve changes to the underlying DNA sequence, often influenced by environmental factors`,`A type of chromosomal abnormality`,`A concept unrelated to gene-environment interactions`], ans:1, exp:`Epigenetic mechanisms (such as DNA methylation and histone modification) regulate gene expression without altering the DNA sequence itself, can be influenced by environmental factors (e.g., stress, diet, toxins), and in some cases can be transmitted across generations, providing a potential mechanism for gene-environment interactions.` },
    { q:`Studies of the heritability of intelligence (IQ) generally find that heritability estimates:`, ch:[`Are constant across the entire lifespan and identical across all socioeconomic groups`,`Tend to increase with age and may vary depending on socioeconomic context (e.g., lower heritability and greater environmental influence in more deprived environments)`,`Are always zero in adults`,`Cannot be studied using twin designs`], ans:1, exp:`Research suggests that the heritability of IQ tends to increase from childhood to adulthood (as individuals increasingly select and shape their own environments), and some studies suggest that in environments characterized by significant deprivation, environmental factors may account for a larger proportion of variance in cognitive ability (the Scarr-Rowe hypothesis), illustrating that heritability estimates are context-dependent.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps54`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Prefrontal-Amygdala Circuits & Decision-Making`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`The prefrontal cortex's top-down regulation of the amygdala is primarily involved in:`, ch:[`Generating fear responses`,`Modulating and often inhibiting amygdala-driven emotional responses, allowing for more regulated behavior`,`Processing visual information exclusively`,`Controlling reflexive spinal responses`], ans:1, exp:`The prefrontal cortex, particularly the ventromedial and dorsolateral regions, exerts top-down regulatory control over the amygdala, helping to modulate and contextualize emotional responses (e.g., during fear extinction or emotion regulation strategies like cognitive reappraisal).` },
    { q:`Damage to the ventromedial prefrontal cortex (as in the famous case of Phineas Gage) is most associated with:`, ch:[`Complete loss of all cognitive function`,`Impaired decision-making and emotional regulation, with relatively preserved general intelligence`,`Loss of motor function in the legs`,`Improved social judgment`], ans:1, exp:`Damage to the ventromedial prefrontal cortex, as famously demonstrated in Phineas Gage and studied extensively by Antonio Damasio, is associated with significant impairments in decision-making, emotional regulation, and social behavior, despite relatively intact general intelligence and memory.` },
    { q:`The somatic marker hypothesis (Damasio) proposes that:`, ch:[`Decision-making relies solely on logical, unemotional reasoning`,`Emotional processes, including bodily ("somatic") signals associated with past experiences, guide and bias decision-making, particularly under uncertainty`,`The body has no role in cognitive processes`,`Emotions only interfere with decision-making and serve no adaptive function`], ans:1, exp:`The somatic marker hypothesis proposes that emotional signals (somatic markers), linked to the body's physiological responses based on past experiences, are integrated into decision-making processesŌĆöparticularly when reasoning under uncertaintyŌĆöhelping to guide choices toward advantageous outcomes by flagging certain options as "good" or "bad" before conscious deliberation.` },
    { q:`The Iowa Gambling Task is commonly used to assess:`, ch:[`Visual acuity`,`Decision-making under conditions of uncertainty and risk, particularly sensitive to ventromedial prefrontal cortex function`,`Memory for word lists`,`Motor reaction time exclusively`], ans:1, exp:`The Iowa Gambling Task involves choosing cards from decks with different long-term reward/punishment profiles; patients with ventromedial prefrontal cortex damage often continue to choose disadvantageously even when healthy individuals learn to avoid risky decks, reflecting impaired integration of emotional learning into decision-making.` },
    { q:`Dual-process theories of decision-making (e.g., System 1 and System 2) propose that judgments arise from:`, ch:[`A single unified cognitive process`,`The interaction between a fast, automatic, intuitive process and a slower, more effortful, deliberate process`,`Random neural firing with no systematic basis`,`Only conscious, deliberate reasoning, with no automatic processes`], ans:1, exp:`Dual-process theories distinguish between System 1 (fast, automatic, intuitive, often emotion-driven, associated with heuristics) and System 2 (slow, effortful, deliberate, analytical) processes; many cognitive biases arise from over-reliance on System 1 processing in situations requiring more careful System 2 analysis.` },
    { q:`Delay discounting refers to the phenomenon where:`, ch:[`The subjective value of a reward decreases as the delay until its receipt increases`,`All rewards are valued identically regardless of timing`,`Future rewards are always valued more than immediate rewards`,`Delay has no effect on decision-making`], ans:0, exp:`Delay discounting describes how the subjective value of a future reward decreases as the time delay to receiving it increases; steep discounting (strongly preferring smaller immediate rewards over larger delayed rewards) is associated with impulsivity and conditions like substance use disorders and ADHD.` },
    { q:`The amygdala's role in fear conditioning involves:`, ch:[`Storing the conditioned fear association and coordinating the physiological fear response`,`Processing language exclusively`,`Generating voluntary motor movements`,`Regulating blood glucose levels directly`], ans:0, exp:`The amygdala, particularly the lateral and central nuclei, is critical for the acquisition and expression of conditioned fear responses, integrating sensory information about the conditioned stimulus with the unconditioned stimulus and coordinating downstream autonomic and behavioral fear responses.` },
    { q:`Extinction of a conditioned fear response involves:`, ch:[`Erasing the original fear memory completely`,`The formation of a new inhibitory memory (mediated partly by the ventromedial prefrontal cortex) that competes with and suppresses the original fear memory, rather than erasing it`,`A process that occurs instantaneously with no neural basis`,`Strengthening the original fear association`], ans:1, exp:`Fear extinction does not erase the original conditioned fear memory but instead involves new learningŌĆöformation of an inhibitory memory trace, involving the ventromedial prefrontal cortex's modulation of the amygdalaŌĆöthat competes with and suppresses (but does not eliminate) the expression of the original fear response, which is why fear can sometimes "return" (renewal, reinstatement, spontaneous recovery).` },
    { q:`The dual-systems model of adolescent risk-taking proposes that heightened risk-taking during adolescence results from:`, ch:[`A simultaneous, equal maturation of both reward-related and cognitive control systems`,`The reward/socioemotional system (e.g., limbic regions including the amygdala and ventral striatum) maturing earlier than the cognitive control system (prefrontal cortex), creating an imbalance`,`Complete absence of any reward system activity in adolescents`,`Adolescents having fully mature prefrontal cortices, identical to adults`], ans:1, exp:`The dual-systems (or maturational imbalance) model proposes that limbic/reward-related brain regions mature relatively early (around puberty), while the prefrontal cortexŌĆöresponsible for cognitive control and impulse regulationŌĆöcontinues developing into the mid-20s, creating a temporary imbalance that may contribute to increased risk-taking and sensation-seeking during adolescence, particularly in emotionally charged contexts.` },
    { q:`Anterior cingulate cortex (ACC) activity is often associated with:`, ch:[`Conflict monitoring and error detection during decision-making`,`Processing visual color information exclusively`,`Generating reflexive spinal reflexes`,`Regulating digestion directly`], ans:0, exp:`The anterior cingulate cortex plays a key role in conflict monitoring (detecting situations where competing responses are activated) and error detection, signaling the need for increased cognitive control, often working in concert with the dorsolateral prefrontal cortex.` },
    { q:`In the context of addiction, the imbalance between an overactive reward system (involving the ventral striatum/nucleus accumbens) and a weakened prefrontal regulatory system contributes to:`, ch:[`Enhanced ability to resist drug-related cues`,`Difficulty inhibiting drug-seeking behavior despite negative consequences, reflecting impaired top-down control over bottom-up reward-driven impulses`,`Complete absence of craving`,`Improved long-term decision-making`], ans:1, exp:`Chronic drug use is associated with both sensitization of reward circuitry (increasing the salience of drug-related cues) and impairment of prefrontal regulatory control, creating an imbalance that makes it difficult to inhibit drug-seeking behavior even when an individual consciously wants to quit and is aware of negative consequences.` },
    { q:`Cognitive reappraisal, an emotion regulation strategy, involves:`, ch:[`Suppressing all outward expression of emotion while the internal emotional experience remains unchanged`,`Reinterpreting the meaning of an emotionally evocative stimulus or situation in order to change one's emotional response to it`,`Avoiding all emotionally evocative situations permanently`,`A strategy with no neural correlates`], ans:1, exp:`Cognitive reappraisal involves changing the way one thinks about a situation to alter its emotional impact (e.g., reinterpreting a stressful exam as a challenge rather than a threat); it is associated with increased prefrontal cortex activity and decreased amygdala activity, and is generally associated with better psychological outcomes than suppression.` },
    { q:`Emotional suppression, in contrast to cognitive reappraisal, is associated with:`, ch:[`Reduced physiological arousal and improved well-being`,`Reduced outward emotional expression but often persistent or even increased internal physiological arousal, and is generally associated with poorer long-term psychological outcomes`,`Complete elimination of the emotional experience`,`Identical neural and physiological effects as reappraisal`], ans:1, exp:`Emotional suppression (inhibiting the outward expression of emotion) often fails to reduce, and may even increase, internal physiological arousal and subjective distress, and is associated with poorer interpersonal functioning and well-being compared to cognitive reappraisal, which addresses the emotional response earlier in the generative process.` },
    { q:`The concept of "hot" versus "cool" cognitive systems, applied to phenomena like delay of gratification (e.g., the "marshmallow test"), proposes that:`, ch:[`Both systems are identical in function`,`The "hot" system (emotional, reflexive, amygdala-related) drives impulsive responses to emotionally salient stimuli, while the "cool" system (cognitive, reflective, prefrontal-related) supports strategic, self-regulatory behavior`,`Only the "cool" system is present in children`,`The "hot" system is located exclusively in the cerebellum`], ans:1, exp:`The hot/cool systems framework, proposed by Metcalfe and Mischel, describes how emotionally salient ("hot") stimuli can trigger impulsive, automatic responses, while the "cool," cognitive system supports more reflective, strategic behavior (e.g., delaying gratification); the relative balance and developmental maturation of these systems influences self-regulatory capacity.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps55`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Obedience, Power & Situational Forces`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Milgram's obedience experiments demonstrated that:`, ch:[`Most participants refused to administer any shocks under any circumstances`,`A majority of participants were willing to administer what they believed were dangerous or potentially lethal electric shocks to another person when instructed to do so by an authority figure`,`Obedience to authority is unrelated to situational factors`,`Only individuals with severe psychological disorders would obey such instructions`], ans:1, exp:`Milgram's classic studies found that approximately 65% of participants administered the maximum shock level when instructed by an experimenter (an authority figure), demonstrating the powerful influence of situational factors and perceived legitimate authority on obedience, even when actions conflicted with personal moral beliefs.` },
    { q:`Milgram found that obedience rates decreased significantly when:`, ch:[`The authority figure was in the same room giving direct, immediate orders`,`The "victim" (learner) was in closer physical proximity to the participant, or when the authority figure's legitimacy was reduced`,`Participants were given more time to consider their actions privately with no other changes`,`The study was conducted at a prestigious university only`], ans:1, exp:`Variations of Milgram's experiment found that obedience decreased when the victim was in closer proximity (e.g., in the same room, requiring physical contact) and when the perceived legitimacy or proximity of the authority figure was reduced (e.g., orders given by phone rather than in person), highlighting the role of situational variables in obedience.` },
    { q:`The Stanford Prison Experiment (Zimbardo) is often cited as evidence that:`, ch:[`Individual personality traits are the sole determinant of behavior in institutional settings, with no role for situational context`,`Situational and contextual factors (e.g., assigned roles, perceived power dynamics) can powerfully shape behavior, sometimes leading ordinary individuals to engage in abusive behavior`,`All participants behaved identically regardless of assigned role`,`The study had no ethical concerns`], ans:1, exp:`The Stanford Prison Experiment, despite significant methodological and ethical criticisms (including researcher influence on participant behavior), is frequently cited as illustrating how situational factorsŌĆösuch as assigned roles (guard vs. prisoner) and institutional power structuresŌĆöcan lead ordinary individuals to engage in behaviors inconsistent with their typical personality, though the study's conclusions have been substantially debated and critiqued in recent reanalyses.` },
    { q:`The concept of "diffusion of responsibility" helps explain:`, ch:[`Why individuals are more likely to help in an emergency when more bystanders are present`,`The bystander effect, in which individuals are less likely to help a victim when other bystanders are present, because responsibility is perceived as shared among the group`,`A phenomenon that only occurs in laboratory settings`,`Why obedience to authority decreases in group settings`], ans:1, exp:`Diffusion of responsibility is a key mechanism underlying the bystander effect: when multiple bystanders are present, each individual feels less personal responsibility to act, believing that someone else will intervene, which paradoxically reduces the likelihood that any individual will help.` },
    { q:`Pluralistic ignorance, relevant to bystander situations, refers to:`, ch:[`A situation in which individuals privately reject a norm but assume that others accept it, leading everyone to act according to a perceived (but inaccurate) group consensus`,`A complete absence of any social influence`,`A phenomenon that only affects isolated individuals`,`Accurate perception of group consensus by all members`], ans:0, exp:`Pluralistic ignorance occurs when individuals look to others' (apparently calm) reactions to interpret an ambiguous situation, and because everyone is similarly looking to others for cues while masking their own concern, the group collectively misjudges the situation as non-emergency, delaying helping behavior.` },
    { q:`Conformity, as demonstrated in Asch's line judgment experiments, refers to:`, ch:[`Changing one's behavior or beliefs to match those of a group, even when the group's judgment appears to be incorrect`,`A complete refusal to be influenced by others under any circumstances`,`A phenomenon limited to judgments about visual perception only`,`Behavior that occurs only when an individual is alone`], ans:0, exp:`Asch's experiments demonstrated that individuals would often conform to an obviously incorrect group judgment about line lengths, even when the correct answer was visually unambiguous, illustrating the powerful influence of normative social pressure on individual behavior and judgment.` },
    { q:`Normative social influence refers to conformity that occurs because of:`, ch:[`A genuine belief that the group's judgment is more accurate`,`A desire to be liked, accepted, or avoid social rejection by the group, even if one privately disagrees`,`A complete absence of social pressure`,`Random chance`], ans:1, exp:`Normative social influence involves conforming to group behavior or opinions in order to be liked, accepted, or to avoid social disapproval or rejection, even when the individual privately holds a different viewŌĆödistinct from informational social influence, where conformity reflects genuine belief that the group has accurate information.` },
    { q:`Informational social influence refers to conformity that occurs because:`, ch:[`Individuals genuinely believe the group possesses more accurate information, particularly in ambiguous situations`,`Individuals want to avoid social rejection regardless of accuracy concerns`,`Conformity never occurs in ambiguous situations`,`Group members are always incorrect`], ans:0, exp:`Informational social influence occurs when individuals conform because they look to others for guidance on how to interpret an ambiguous situation, genuinely believing that the group's interpretation is more likely to be correct than their own, especially when they are uncertain.` },
    { q:`Groupthink refers to a phenomenon in which:`, ch:[`Group members critically evaluate all options and actively seek dissenting opinions`,`The desire for group harmony and consensus leads to dysfunctional decision-making, including the suppression of dissenting viewpoints and failure to critically evaluate alternatives`,`Groups always make better decisions than individuals`,`A phenomenon that only occurs in groups of two people`], ans:1, exp:`Groupthink occurs when a cohesive group's desire for unanimity and harmony overrides realistic appraisal of alternative courses of action, leading to poor decision-making, illusions of invulnerability, self-censorship of doubts, and pressure on dissenters to conformŌĆöoften cited in analyses of major historical policy failures.` },
    { q:`Deindividuation refers to the phenomenon in which:`, ch:[`Individuals become more self-aware and accountable in group settings`,`Individuals lose their sense of individual identity and personal accountability within a group, particularly when anonymous, which can lead to behavior they would not normally engage in alone`,`Group settings always reduce aggressive behavior`,`A process that requires complete isolation from any group`], ans:1, exp:`Deindividuation describes a psychological state in which a person experiences a loss of self-awareness and individual accountability when part of a group, often facilitated by anonymity (e.g., crowds, online environments), which can lower inhibitions and increase the likelihood of impulsive or norm-violating behavior.` },
    { q:`The "agentic state," as described by Milgram, refers to a psychological state in which an individual:`, ch:[`Acts as an autonomous agent, taking full personal responsibility for their actions`,`Sees themselves as an instrument carrying out another person's (an authority figure's) wishes, and thus does not feel personally responsible for the consequences of their actions`,`Refuses to follow any instructions from authority figures`,`Experiences complete loss of consciousness`], ans:1, exp:`In the agentic state, an individual perceives themselves as an agent for executing the wishes of an authority figure, effectively transferring responsibility for their actions to that authority, which Milgram proposed as a key psychological mechanism enabling destructive obedience.` },
    { q:`Critiques of the Stanford Prison Experiment in recent years have focused on:`, ch:[`The complete absence of any participants`,`Evidence that the researchers actively coached "guards" to behave more aggressively, raising questions about whether the results reflect spontaneous situational effects or demand characteristics`,`The fact that the study was conducted with no ethical oversight whatsoever, which was considered acceptable at the time`,`The study having a sample size in the millions`], ans:1, exp:`Recent reanalyses, including released audio recordings, have suggested that researchers actively encouraged or coached participants playing "guards" to act more aggressively, raising significant concerns about demand characteristics and challenging the original interpretation that the abusive behavior emerged purely spontaneously from the assigned roles.` },
    { q:`Why is understanding situational influences on behavior (e.g., obedience, conformity, deindividuation) important in medical ethics and professional conduct?`, ch:[`It is not relevant to medical practice`,`Recognizing how situational and institutional pressures can influence even well-intentioned individuals to act unethically helps inform the design of safeguards, reporting systems, and training to prevent ethical violations in healthcare settings`,`It proves that individuals have no responsibility for their actions in any context`,`It only applies to historical psychological experiments with no modern relevance`], ans:1, exp:`Understanding how situational pressures (hierarchy, conformity, diffusion of responsibility) can lead even ethical individuals toward problematic behavior informs the design of institutional safeguardsŌĆösuch as clear reporting channels, a culture that encourages speaking up, and training that addresses these dynamicsŌĆöimportant for preventing issues like medical errors going unreported or unethical research practices.` },
    { q:`A new resident, uncomfortable questioning a senior attending's clearly incorrect order, ultimately follows the order without speaking up. This scenario illustrates the relevance of which combination of concepts?`, ch:[`Obedience to authority and normative social influence (fear of social disapproval for challenging a superior)`,`Only classical conditioning`,`Only the bystander effect, with no role for authority`,`A purely individual personality flaw with no situational component`], ans:0, exp:`This scenario illustrates how obedience to perceived legitimate authority (the attending physician) combines with normative social influence (fear of social repercussions or appearing disrespectful/incompetent for challenging a superior) to inhibit speaking up, even when the resident may recognize a problemŌĆöa dynamic relevant to patient safety culture and the importance of structured communication tools.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps56`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Critical Theory & Social Constructionism`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Social constructionism proposes that:`, ch:[`All categories and concepts (e.g., race, gender, mental illness) are entirely biological with no social influence`,`Many categories and concepts that appear "natural" or fixed are, at least in part, products of social processes, historical context, and shared meanings rather than objective, immutable facts`,`Social factors have no influence on how concepts are understood or categorized`,`Only physical objects can be socially constructed`], ans:1, exp:`Social constructionism examines how concepts, categories, and meanings (including categories like race, gender, illness, and normalcy) are shaped by social processes, historical context, language, and power relations, rather than being purely objective or biologically predeterminedŌĆöwithout necessarily denying any biological basis, but emphasizing the social dimensions of how these categories are defined and understood.` },
    { q:`Critical theory, as applied to medicine and society, often examines:`, ch:[`How power structures, ideology, and social institutions shape health, illness, and access to care, often with the goal of identifying and addressing inequities`,`Only the biochemical mechanisms of disease`,`A purely apolitical analysis of healthcare systems`,`Individual genetic variation exclusively`], ans:0, exp:`Critical theory approaches in medicine examine how power dynamics, social structures, ideology, and institutional practices shape health outcomes, the distribution of illness, and access to healthcare resources, often with an explicit aim of identifying and challenging structural inequities.` },
    { q:`The concept of "medicalization" can be analyzed through a critical lens by asking:`, ch:[`Whether a condition has a name`,`Whose interests are served by defining a particular human experience as a medical condition, and what are the social consequences of doing so (e.g., shifting focus from social causes to individual treatment)`,`Only whether a medication exists for the condition`,`Nothing, as medicalization is a purely neutral, apolitical process`], ans:1, exp:`A critical analysis of medicalization examines questions of power and interestŌĆöwho benefits from defining a condition medically (e.g., pharmaceutical industry, healthcare providers), and how this framing might individualize and depoliticize problems with significant social or structural roots, potentially diverting attention from addressing those root causes.` },
    { q:`Intersectionality, a concept developed by Kimberl├® Crenshaw, refers to:`, ch:[`The idea that different forms of social categorization (e.g., race, gender, class) operate independently with no interaction`,`The interconnected nature of social categorizations such as race, class, and gender, which combine to create overlapping and interdependent systems of discrimination or disadvantage`,`A purely mathematical concept used in epidemiology`,`A term that applies only to traffic engineering`], ans:1, exp:`Intersectionality describes how various aspects of a person's social identity (e.g., race, gender, socioeconomic status, sexual orientation) intersect and interact, creating unique experiences of discrimination, privilege, or disadvantage that cannot be fully understood by examining each category in isolation.` },
    { q:`The "social model of disability" contrasts with the "medical model of disability" by emphasizing that:`, ch:[`Disability is solely an individual medical problem requiring cure`,`Disability results significantly from societal barriers (e.g., physical, attitudinal, institutional) that disable people with impairments, rather than the impairment itself being the primary "problem"`,`Society has no role in shaping the experience of disability`,`Only medical interventions can address disability`], ans:1, exp:`The social model of disability shifts focus from an individual's impairment as the primary "problem" (medical model) to the ways in which societal structures, environments, and attitudes create barriers that disable people with impairmentsŌĆösuggesting that removing these barriers, rather than solely "fixing" the individual, is central to addressing disability.` },
    { q:`Foucault's concept of "biopower" refers to:`, ch:[`A type of renewable energy`,`The ways in which modern states and institutions exercise power over populations through the regulation and management of bodies, health, and life processes (e.g., public health policies, medical surveillance)`,`A concept with no relevance to healthcare`,`Individual physical strength`], ans:1, exp:`Foucault's concept of biopower describes how modern power operates through the management and regulation of populations' bodies and biological processesŌĆöthrough institutions like medicine, public health, and statisticsŌĆöshaping norms around health, sexuality, and behavior in ways that extend beyond direct coercion.` },
    { q:`The "medical gaze," a concept from Foucault, describes:`, ch:[`A literal visual examination technique`,`The way medical perception and language can reduce patients to their disease or body parts, separating the illness from the lived experience of the person`,`A type of eye examination equipment`,`A purely positive and neutral aspect of clinical practice with no critique implied`], ans:1, exp:`The "medical gaze" describes how clinical perception and discourse can fragment and objectify patients, focusing on the disease, organ, or pathology rather than the whole person and their subjective experienceŌĆöa concept used to critique potential dehumanizing aspects of biomedical practice while also informing efforts toward more patient-centered care.` },
    { q:`Structural violence refers to:`, ch:[`Direct, interpersonal physical violence only`,`Social structures and institutions (e.g., poverty, discrimination, unequal access to resources) that systematically harm or disadvantage certain groups, even without direct interpersonal violence`,`A concept with no application to health outcomes`,`Violence that occurs only during war`], ans:1, exp:`Structural violence refers to the ways social structures and institutionsŌĆösuch as systemic poverty, racism, and unequal access to education, housing, and healthcareŌĆöcause harm to populations by preventing them from meeting basic needs, even in the absence of direct, interpersonal violence, and is increasingly recognized as a key driver of health disparities.` },
    { q:`The "sick role," a concept from Talcott Parsons, describes:`, ch:[`A set of social expectations and exemptions (e.g., exemption from normal social responsibilities) granted to individuals who are recognized as ill, in exchange for seeking competent help and wanting to get well`,`A formal medical diagnosis`,`A role that applies only to chronic illness`,`A concept with no relevance to sociology`], ans:0, exp:`Parsons' sick role concept describes a set of social norms: a sick person is exempted from normal social obligations and is not held responsible for their condition, but in turn is expected to view the sick state as undesirable, seek competent medical help, and cooperate with treatment to get wellŌĆöillustrating illness as a socially defined role, not just a biological state.` },
    { q:`Critiques of the "sick role" concept include the observation that it:`, ch:[`Applies equally well to all conditions, including chronic and stigmatized illnesses`,`May not adequately account for chronic illness (where "getting well" may not be a realistic expectation) or stigmatized conditions (where individuals may be blamed despite the sick role's premise of non-responsibility)`,`Has no critiques and is universally accepted`,`Was developed without any sociological basis`], ans:1, exp:`Critics note that the sick role model, developed with acute illness in mind, does not map well onto chronic illness (where full recovery may be impossible, challenging the "wanting to get well" expectation) or onto stigmatized conditions (e.g., addiction, certain mental illnesses, HIV) where individuals may still be blamed for their condition despite the sick role's assumption of non-responsibility.` },
    { q:`Symbolic interactionism, a sociological perspective, emphasizes:`, ch:[`Large-scale social structures as the primary unit of analysis, ignoring individual interactions`,`How individuals create and interpret meaning through everyday social interactions, and how shared symbols and meanings (e.g., the meaning of "illness" or "health") shape behavior and self-concept`,`Only biological determinants of behavior`,`A perspective with no application to healthcare settings`], ans:1, exp:`Symbolic interactionism focuses on the micro-level processes through which individuals construct and negotiate meaning through social interaction, examining how shared symbols, labels, and meanings (e.g., what it means to be "sick," "disabled," or a "patient") are created and influence behavior and identity.` },
    { q:`A critical theory perspective on the "obesity epidemic" might examine:`, ch:[`Only the individual caloric intake of affected persons, with no broader context`,`How food industry practices, food deserts, marketing, socioeconomic factors, and weight-based stigma interact with individual behavior, questioning whether framing obesity purely as an individual failing obscures these broader structural factors`,`A purely genetic explanation with no social factors`,`Nothing, as critical theory has no relevance to this topic`], ans:1, exp:`A critical perspective would examine how structural factorsŌĆöfood industry marketing and lobbying, food deserts, socioeconomic constraints on food choices, and pervasive weight stigmaŌĆöinteract with and shape individual behaviors related to diet and weight, questioning narratives that frame obesity solely as a matter of individual willpower or choice.` },
    { q:`The concept of "epistemic injustice" refers to:`, ch:[`A type of physical injury`,`A wrong done to someone specifically in their capacity as a knowerŌĆöfor example, when a patient's testimony about their own symptoms is given less credibility due to bias against their social group`,`A legal term unrelated to communication`,`A concept that applies only to academic publishing`], ans:1, exp:`Epistemic injustice occurs when an individual is wronged in their capacity as a knower or communicator of knowledgeŌĆöfor example, "testimonial injustice" occurs when a listener gives a speaker's testimony less credibility due to identity-based prejudice (e.g., a patient's pain reports being dismissed due to bias), which has documented impacts on healthcare quality and trust.` },
    { q:`Why might a critical theory perspective be valuable for a clinician, even one who primarily focuses on individual patient care?`, ch:[`It has no practical value for individual clinical encounters`,`It can help clinicians recognize how broader social structures, power dynamics, and biases may be influencing a patient's health, their interactions with the healthcare system, and the clinician's own perceptions and decisions, fostering more equitable and effective care`,`It requires abandoning all biomedical knowledge`,`It is relevant only to sociologists, never to practicing physicians`], ans:1, exp:`A critical theory lens can help clinicians recognize how social determinants, structural inequities, and their own potential biases may shape a patient's health status, their experiences within the healthcare system, and the clinical encounter itselfŌĆöfostering greater awareness, more effective communication, and more equitable care, complementing rather than replacing biomedical expertise.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps57`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Health Communication & Medical Decision-Making`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Shared decision-making in clinical encounters involves:`, ch:[`The physician making all decisions without input from the patient`,`A collaborative process in which clinicians and patients work together to make healthcare decisions, incorporating clinical evidence and the patient's values and preferences`,`The patient making all decisions without any clinical guidance`,`A process used only for end-of-life care decisions`], ans:1, exp:`Shared decision-making involves a collaborative process where clinicians provide evidence-based information about options, risks, and benefits, while patients share their values, preferences, and circumstances, leading to a decision that reflects both clinical evidence and patient-centered considerations.` },
    { q:`Numeracy, in the context of health communication, refers to:`, ch:[`The ability to read text fluently`,`The ability to understand and use numerical information, such as risk statistics and probabilities, to make health decisions`,`A measure of a patient's age`,`A type of medical imaging technique`], ans:1, exp:`Health numeracy refers to the ability to comprehend and apply numerical conceptsŌĆösuch as percentages, probabilities, and risk ratiosŌĆöwhich is essential for understanding information about treatment risks, benefits, and screening test results; low numeracy is associated with difficulty making informed health decisions.` },
    { q:`Presenting risk information using natural frequencies (e.g., "10 out of 100 people") rather than percentages (e.g., "10%") tends to:`, ch:[`Make the information more confusing for most people`,`Improve comprehension of risk information for many individuals, including those with lower numeracy`,`Have no effect on understanding`,`Only be useful for healthcare professionals`], ans:1, exp:`Research suggests that presenting probabilistic information as natural frequencies (e.g., "10 out of 100 people") rather than percentages or single-event probabilities can improve comprehension and reduce errors in risk perception, particularly for individuals with lower numeracy skills.` },
    { q:`The "teach-back" method in patient education involves:`, ch:[`The clinician repeatedly lecturing the patient without checking understanding`,`Asking the patient to explain, in their own words, the information or instructions just provided, to confirm understanding and identify areas needing clarification`,`Having the patient teach the clinician about their condition`,`A method used only for pediatric patients`], ans:1, exp:`The teach-back method involves asking patients to restate, in their own words, key information or instructions (e.g., medication regimens) they have just received, allowing clinicians to assess and reinforce understanding and to identify and correct any misunderstandingsŌĆöan evidence-based strategy for improving health literacy outcomes.` },
    { q:`Decisional conflict refers to:`, ch:[`A patient's certainty about a healthcare decision`,`A state of uncertainty about which course of action to take when choice involves risk, loss, regret, or challenge to personal values`,`A disagreement between two physicians about a diagnosis`,`A legal dispute over medical malpractice`], ans:1, exp:`Decisional conflict describes the personal uncertainty a patient may experience when facing a healthcare decision involving competing options with different risks and benefits, particularly when values are challengedŌĆödecision aids are often used to help reduce decisional conflict by clarifying values and providing balanced information.` },
    { q:`Patient decision aids are tools designed to:`, ch:[`Replace the need for any conversation between clinician and patient`,`Provide balanced, evidence-based information about treatment options, risks, and benefits, and help patients clarify their values to support shared decision-making`,`Persuade patients toward a single predetermined choice`,`Be used only by clinicians, never by patients`], ans:1, exp:`Patient decision aids present balanced information about the options, outcomes, and uncertainties of different healthcare choices, often including exercises to help patients clarify their personal values, supporting more informed and values-congruent decision-making in partnership with their clinician.` },
    { q:`The concept of "patient activation" refers to:`, ch:[`A patient's level of physical activity`,`A patient's knowledge, skills, and confidence for managing their own health and healthcare`,`The activation of a medical device`,`A measure of how quickly a patient responds to treatment`], ans:1, exp:`Patient activation describes the extent to which individuals understand their role in the care process and have the knowledge, skills, and confidence to manage their health and healthcare; higher patient activation is associated with better health outcomes and more effective engagement with the healthcare system.` },
    { q:`When discussing prognosis with a seriously ill patient, research suggests that most patients:`, ch:[`Never want any information about their prognosis under any circumstances`,`Vary in their preferences for prognostic information, and clinicians should explore individual preferences for the type, amount, and timing of information shared`,`All want exactly the same amount of detail delivered the same way`,`Should never be asked about their preferences`], ans:1, exp:`Patient preferences for prognostic information vary considerablyŌĆösome want detailed statistical information, others prefer general information or want family members to receive detailsŌĆöso eliciting individual preferences (e.g., through open-ended questions about how much information the patient wants) is an important component of patient-centered communication.` },
    { q:`Motivational interviewing techniques, such as "rolling with resistance," involve:`, ch:[`Directly confronting and arguing against a patient's resistance to change`,`Avoiding direct confrontation of resistance, instead exploring the patient's own perspective and ambivalence in a non-judgmental way`,`Ignoring the patient's stated concerns entirely`,`Telling the patient they must change immediately or face consequences`], ans:1, exp:`"Rolling with resistance" involves avoiding direct argumentation when a patient expresses ambivalence or resistance to change, instead exploring the patient's perspective with curiosity and reflecting their concerns back to them, which tends to be more effective than confrontation in fostering eventual behavior change.` },
    { q:`The "ask-tell-ask" technique in clinical communication involves:`, ch:[`Asking the patient what they already know or want to know, providing information, then asking them to summarize or ask further questions`,`Asking the same question three times in a row`,`A technique used only for obtaining informed consent for surgery`,`Telling the patient information three times without any questions`], ans:0, exp:`The ask-tell-ask technique structures information delivery by first assessing the patient's current understanding and informational needs/preferences ("ask"), providing relevant information tailored to that assessment ("tell"), and then checking understanding and addressing further questions ("ask")ŌĆöpromoting effective, patient-centered communication.` },
    { q:`Discussing a "do not resuscitate" (DNR) order with a patient and family requires sensitivity to which of the following considerations?`, ch:[`Only the legal requirements, with no consideration of patient/family emotions or values`,`The patient's values, goals of care, cultural and religious beliefs, and emotional responses, in addition to providing clear medical information about prognosis and likely outcomes of resuscitation`,`Telling the family the decision has already been made by the medical team with no input needed`,`Avoiding the topic entirely to prevent distress`], ans:1, exp:`Conversations about DNR orders and goals of care require integrating clear, honest medical information (e.g., realistic likelihood of survival and quality of life after resuscitation) with deep attention to the patient's and family's values, cultural and religious beliefs, and emotional responses, often requiring multiple conversations over time.` },
    { q:`A patient declines a recommended treatment after being fully informed of the risks and benefits, and the clinician determines the patient has decision-making capacity. The appropriate response is to:`, ch:[`Override the patient's decision and proceed with treatment regardless`,`Respect the patient's autonomous decision, while continuing to provide support, address any modifiable concerns, and ensure the door remains open for future discussion`,`Refuse to provide any further care to the patient`,`Report the patient to legal authorities`], ans:1, exp:`Respecting patient autonomy is a core ethical principle; when a patient with decision-making capacity makes an informed decision to decline treatment, clinicians should respect this choice while continuing to provide support, explore any concerns that might be addressed, and remain available for future discussions as circumstances or the patient's perspective may change.` },
    { q:`Health communication campaigns that use fear appeals (e.g., graphic warning images on cigarette packages) are most effective when they:`, ch:[`Induce overwhelming fear with no accompanying information about how to address the threat, leading to avoidance`,`Induce a moderate level of fear combined with clear, actionable information about how to reduce the threat (high "response efficacy" and "self-efficacy")`,`Provide no information about the consequences of the behavior`,`Are used in isolation with no other components`], ans:1, exp:`According to the Extended Parallel Process Model, fear appeals are most effective when they induce a moderate level of perceived threat (severity and susceptibility) combined with high perceived efficacyŌĆöboth response efficacy (the recommended action will work) and self-efficacy (the individual can perform the action); without sufficient efficacy information, high fear can lead to defensive avoidance or denial rather than behavior change.` },
    { q:`Why might using overly technical medical jargon during a patient encounter undermine shared decision-making, even if the clinician provides comprehensive information?`, ch:[`Jargon always improves patient understanding regardless of health literacy`,`Patients may not understand the information well enough to meaningfully weigh options against their own values and preferences, undermining their ability to participate as an informed partner in the decision`,`Jargon has no effect on patient comprehension or decision-making`,`Patients prefer technical language over plain language universally`], ans:1, exp:`Effective shared decision-making requires that patients genuinely understand their options, risks, and benefits well enough to relate this information to their own values and life circumstances; the use of technical jargon, even if comprehensive, can create a barrier to genuine comprehension, undermining the patient's ability to be an informed and equal partner in the decision-making process, particularly for patients with lower health literacy.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps58`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Evolutionary Psychology & Sexual Selection`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Evolutionary psychology proposes that many human psychological traits and behaviors:`, ch:[`Are entirely learned with no evolutionary basis`,`May have evolved because they conferred reproductive or survival advantages to ancestral humans, even if they are not always adaptive in modern environments`,`Are identical across all species with no human-specific adaptations`,`Cannot be studied scientifically`], ans:1, exp:`Evolutionary psychology examines how psychological mechanisms may have been shaped by natural and sexual selection because they enhanced survival or reproductive success in ancestral environments, while acknowledging that these mechanisms may produce behaviors that are mismatched with modern environments (evolutionary mismatch).` },
    { q:`Sexual selection, as distinguished from natural selection, refers to selection pressures arising from:`, ch:[`Survival advantages only, with no role for reproduction`,`Competition for mates and mate choice, which can favor traits that enhance reproductive success even if they impose survival costs`,`Random genetic drift exclusively`,`Environmental factors unrelated to reproduction`], ans:1, exp:`Sexual selection refers to selection pressures specifically related to competition for mates (intrasexual selection, e.g., male-male competition) and mate choice (intersexual selection, e.g., female choice of mates), which can favor traitsŌĆölike elaborate ornamentationŌĆöthat may even reduce survival but enhance reproductive success.` },
    { q:`Parental investment theory proposes that the sex that invests more in offspring (often, but not always, females in mammals due to gestation and lactation) will:`, ch:[`Be less selective about mating partners`,`Be more selective ("choosier") about mating partners, while the sex investing less may compete more intensely for mating opportunities`,`Have no preferences regarding mating partners`,`Always have identical reproductive strategies as the other sex`], ans:1, exp:`Parental investment theory (Trivers) proposes that the sex with greater obligatory investment in offspring (e.g., gestation, lactation in mammals) tends to be more selective in mate choice, since poor mate choice carries higher costs, while the sex with lower obligatory investment may compete more intensely for access to mates.` },
    { q:`The concept of "inclusive fitness" extends traditional notions of fitness by including:`, ch:[`Only an individual's own direct reproductive success`,`An individual's own reproductive success plus the effects of their behavior on the reproductive success of genetic relatives, weighted by the degree of relatedness`,`A measure unrelated to genetics`,`Only behaviors that benefit unrelated individuals`], ans:1, exp:`Inclusive fitness, central to Hamilton's theory of kin selection, accounts for both an individual's direct reproductive success and the indirect fitness effects of helping genetic relatives reproduce, weighted by the coefficient of relatednessŌĆöhelping to explain altruistic behaviors directed toward kin.` },
    { q:`Hamilton's rule predicts that an altruistic behavior will be favored by natural selection when:`, ch:[`The cost to the actor exceeds the benefit to the recipient, regardless of relatedness`,`The benefit to the recipient, multiplied by the genetic relatedness between actor and recipient, exceeds the cost to the actor (rB > C)`,`Relatedness is always zero`,`The behavior provides no benefit to anyone`], ans:1, exp:`Hamilton's rule (rB > C) states that an altruistic gene will spread if the benefit to the recipient (B), weighted by the genetic relatedness (r) between the altruist and recipient, exceeds the cost to the altruist (C)ŌĆöproviding a framework for understanding kin-directed altruism.` },
    { q:`Reciprocal altruism, as a complement to kin selection, helps explain altruistic behavior between:`, ch:[`Genetically related individuals only`,`Unrelated individuals, based on the expectation of future reciprocation ("you scratch my back, I'll scratch yours")`,`Individuals of different species only`,`No real organisms; it is a purely theoretical construct with no observed examples`], ans:1, exp:`Reciprocal altruism (Trivers) proposes that altruistic acts toward unrelated individuals can evolve if there is a reasonable likelihood of future reciprocation, effectively functioning as a delayed exchange of benefitsŌĆörequires mechanisms to detect and punish "cheaters" who fail to reciprocate.` },
    { q:`The "evolutionary mismatch" hypothesis proposes that many modern health problems arise because:`, ch:[`Human bodies and behaviors evolved in response to ancestral environments that differ substantially from modern environments, creating a mismatch (e.g., preferences for high-calorie foods that were adaptive in times of scarcity but contribute to obesity in food-abundant modern environments)`,`Evolution has stopped entirely for humans`,`Modern environments are identical to ancestral environments`,`All modern diseases have purely genetic causes unrelated to environment`], ans:0, exp:`Evolutionary mismatch describes how traits that were adaptive in ancestral environments (e.g., a preference for calorie-dense foods, which was advantageous when food was scarce) can become maladaptive in modern environments characterized by abundant food and reduced physical activity demands, contributing to conditions like obesity and metabolic disease.` },
    { q:`Postpartum depression, from an evolutionary perspective, has been hypothesized by some researchers to potentially relate to:`, ch:[`A complete absence of any evolutionary explanation, as it serves no possible function`,`Signals related to insufficient social support or resources for raising offspring, though this remains a hypothesis among several proposed explanations and does not negate the importance of clinical treatment`,`A condition that has no biological component whatsoever`,`A behavior that is universally beneficial with no negative consequences`], ans:1, exp:`Some evolutionary hypotheses propose that postpartum depression symptoms might, in some contexts, relate to assessment of available social support or resources for offspring care, though such hypotheses remain speculative and are actively debated; importantly, evolutionary hypotheses about origins do not diminish the clinical importance of recognizing and treating postpartum depression as a serious condition requiring support and treatment.` },
    { q:`Critics of evolutionary psychology often raise concerns about:`, ch:[`The field having too much empirical support and no room for debate`,`The risk of generating "just-so stories"ŌĆöplausible-sounding evolutionary narratives that are difficult to test empirically and may be used to justify existing social arrangements or stereotypes`,`The complete absence of any theoretical framework`,`Evolutionary psychology being universally accepted with no methodological critiques`], ans:1, exp:`A common critique of evolutionary psychology is the risk of constructing "just-so stories"ŌĆöpost-hoc evolutionary explanations for behaviors that sound plausible but are difficult to rigorously test, and which critics argue can sometimes be used to naturalize or justify existing social inequalities or stereotypes (e.g., regarding gender roles) without sufficient empirical support.` },
    { q:`The "good genes" hypothesis in mate selection proposes that certain preferred traits in potential mates (e.g., symmetry, certain physical characteristics) may serve as:`, ch:[`Random preferences with no adaptive significance`,`Honest signals of genetic quality or health, which mate choice may have evolved to favor because offspring with such mates may have higher fitness`,`Traits that are entirely culturally determined with no biological basis`,`Indicators that are unrelated to any aspect of fitness`], ans:1, exp:`The "good genes" hypothesis suggests that certain physical traits favored in mate choice may function as honest, hard-to-fake signals of underlying genetic quality, immune function, or developmental stability (e.g., symmetry), such that choosing mates with these traits could confer fitness benefits to offspring.` },
    { q:`Alloparenting, observed in humans and some other species, refers to:`, ch:[`Parental care provided exclusively by biological parents`,`Caregiving provided to offspring by individuals other than the biological parents (e.g., grandparents, older siblings, other community members)`,`A complete absence of any parental care`,`A behavior observed only in solitary species`], ans:1, exp:`Alloparenting refers to caregiving behaviors directed toward offspring by individuals other than the genetic parents, which is relatively common in humans (sometimes referred to as "cooperative breeding") and has been proposed to have played an important role in human evolutionary history, potentially related to the relatively long period of human childhood dependency.` },
    { q:`The "grandmother hypothesis" proposes that menopause and extended post-reproductive lifespan in human females may have evolved because:`, ch:[`Older females provide no benefit to their kin after menopause`,`Grandmothers who survive past reproductive age can increase the survival and reproductive success of their grandchildren through caregiving and resource provision, providing an inclusive fitness benefit`,`Menopause has no evolutionary explanation and is purely a byproduct of modern medicine`,`Reproductive cessation occurs in all mammalian species at the same age`], ans:1, exp:`The grandmother hypothesis proposes that the relatively long post-reproductive lifespan observed in human females may have been favored by selection because grandmothers who help care for grandchildren and provide resources can increase their grandchildren's survival and their own daughters' reproductive output, providing an inclusive fitness benefit that offsets the cessation of direct reproduction.` },
    { q:`When applying evolutionary perspectives to understanding human behavior, it is important to recognize that:`, ch:[`An evolutionary explanation for a behavior automatically makes that behavior morally justified or unchangeable (the naturalistic fallacy)`,`Evolutionary explanations describe potential historical origins or functions of traits, but this does not imply that resulting behaviors are morally desirable, inevitable, or unchangeable in modern contexts`,`Evolutionary psychology eliminates the need to consider cultural or environmental factors`,`All human behaviors have a single, universally agreed-upon evolutionary explanation`], ans:1, exp:`A critical consideration when applying evolutionary perspectives is avoiding the naturalistic fallacyŌĆöthe assumption that because a trait or behavior may have an evolutionary origin or historical function, it is therefore morally good, justified, or impossible to change; evolutionary explanations are about origins and mechanisms, not moral prescriptions, and behaviors remain subject to cultural, environmental, and individual influences.` },
    { q:`Cross-species comparative studies of mating systems (e.g., monogamy, polygyny) in relation to sexual dimorphism (size differences between sexes) suggest that:`, ch:[`Greater sexual dimorphism is generally associated with more polygynous mating systems, where male-male competition for mates is more intense`,`Sexual dimorphism has no relationship to mating systems in any species`,`All species show identical levels of sexual dimorphism regardless of mating system`,`Monogamous species always show the greatest sexual dimorphism`], ans:0, exp:`Comparative studies across species suggest that greater sexual dimorphism (e.g., males being substantially larger than females) is often associated with more polygynous mating systems, where intense male-male competition for mating access favors larger body size or other competitive traits in malesŌĆörelevant to discussions of human sexual dimorphism and mating system evolution, though human patterns are complex and debated.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps59`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Cross-Cultural Psychology & WEIRD Bias`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`The acronym "WEIRD" in psychological research refers to samples that are:`, ch:[`Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, and Democratic`,`Wealthy, Educated, Independent, Religious, and Dominant`,`Western, Elderly, Isolated, Rural, and Disadvantaged`,`A term with no specific meaning in psychology`], ans:0, exp:`WEIRD stands for Western, Educated, Industrialized, Rich, and Democratic, describing the demographic profile of the populations from which a large proportion of psychological research samples are drawnŌĆöpopulations that may not be representative of humanity as a whole.` },
    { q:`A major critique highlighted by the WEIRD samples issue is that:`, ch:[`Findings from WEIRD populations always generalize perfectly to all human populations`,`Many foundational findings in psychology, often assumed to reflect universal human cognition and behavior, may not generalize to non-WEIRD populations, which represent the majority of the world's population`,`Non-WEIRD populations have been studied more extensively than WEIRD populations`,`This issue has no implications for the validity of psychological theories`], ans:1, exp:`Research has shown that on many psychological dimensions (e.g., visual perception, fairness judgments, self-concept), WEIRD populations are often outliers compared to the broader range of human variation, raising concerns about the generalizability of psychological theories developed primarily from WEIRD samples.` },
    { q:`Individualism versus collectivism, a key dimension in cross-cultural psychology, refers to:`, ch:[`The degree to which a culture emphasizes individual autonomy and personal goals versus group harmony and collective goals`,`A measure of a country's gross domestic product`,`A dimension that applies only to political systems, not psychology`,`A fixed, unchanging characteristic of a culture with no within-culture variation`], ans:0, exp:`Individualism-collectivism describes a cultural dimension where individualistic cultures tend to emphasize personal autonomy, individual achievement, and self-expression, while collectivistic cultures tend to emphasize group harmony, interdependence, and fulfilling social roles and obligationsŌĆöthough significant variation exists within any culture.` },
    { q:`The independent versus interdependent self-construal distinction proposes that individuals in individualistic cultures tend to define themselves in terms of:`, ch:[`Their relationships and roles within social groups`,`Unique internal attributes, traits, and preferences that are relatively stable across contexts`,`Only their physical characteristics`,`A concept that does not vary across cultures`], ans:1, exp:`In individualistic cultures, the "independent" self-construal emphasizes defining oneself through unique internal attributes, abilities, and preferences that remain relatively consistent across social contexts, while the "interdependent" self-construal (more common in collectivistic cultures) emphasizes defining oneself in relation to social roles, relationships, and group memberships.` },
    { q:`Cross-cultural research on the fundamental attribution error has found that:`, ch:[`The tendency to attribute behavior to dispositional factors over situational factors is identical across all cultures with no variation`,`Individuals from more collectivistic cultures may be relatively more likely (compared to individuals from individualistic cultures) to consider situational factors when explaining others' behavior`,`Collectivistic cultures show no attribution biases of any kind`,`Attribution processes are entirely genetically determined with no cultural influence`], ans:1, exp:`Cross-cultural research suggests that the fundamental attribution error, while present across cultures, may be somewhat less pronounced in more collectivistic cultures, where individuals may be more attuned to situational and contextual factors when explaining behavior, compared to the stronger dispositional bias often observed in individualistic cultures.` },
    { q:`The use of standardized psychological assessments developed in one cultural context, when applied to a different cultural context without adaptation, raises concerns about:`, ch:[`No concerns, as psychological constructs are universal and assessments require no adaptation`,`ValidityŌĆöwhether the assessment accurately measures the same construct across different cultural groups, given potential differences in language, norms, and the relevance of specific items`,`Only concerns about translation costs`,`Concerns that apply only to assessments of physical health, not psychological constructs`], ans:1, exp:`Applying psychological assessments across cultures without careful adaptation raises concerns about both linguistic translation accuracy and conceptual/construct validityŌĆöwhether the underlying construct being measured (e.g., "depression," "intelligence") has the same meaning, expression, and relevance across different cultural contexts, requiring careful cross-cultural validation.` },
    { q:`Cultural variation in the expression and interpretation of emotional distress (e.g., somatic symptoms being more prominent in some cultural contexts than verbal expressions of sadness) has implications for:`, ch:[`Nothing; emotional expression is identical across all cultures`,`Clinical assessment and diagnosis, as relying solely on diagnostic criteria developed in one cultural context (e.g., emphasizing verbally reported sadness) may lead to underdiagnosis or misdiagnosis in other cultural contexts`,`Only research methodology, with no clinical relevance`,`The complete invalidity of any diagnostic criteria across all cultures`], ans:1, exp:`Recognizing cultural variation in symptom expressionŌĆöfor example, some cultural groups may be more likely to present psychological distress through somatic complaints (e.g., headaches, fatigue) rather than directly reporting sadnessŌĆöis important for accurate clinical assessment, as diagnostic criteria developed primarily in one cultural context may not capture presentations common in other contexts, potentially leading to underdiagnosis or misdiagnosis.` },
    { q:`The concept of "cultural idioms of distress" refers to:`, ch:[`A formal medical diagnosis recognized in all diagnostic manuals identically`,`Culturally specific ways of expressing and communicating suffering, which may not directly correspond to standard diagnostic categories but are meaningful within a particular cultural context`,`A concept with no relevance to clinical practice`,`Idioms used only in literature, unrelated to psychology`], ans:1, exp:`Cultural idioms of distress are ways that members of a cultural group communicate and experience suffering (e.g., specific terms or concepts for certain forms of distress) that may not map directly onto standard psychiatric diagnostic categories, and understanding these idioms is important for culturally sensitive assessment and care.` },
    { q:`When comparing cognitive task performance across cultural groups, researchers must consider that observed differences may reflect:`, ch:[`Only innate cognitive ability differences between groups, with no other possible explanations`,`Differences in familiarity with the testing format, language, educational background, or the cultural relevance of the task content, in addition to (or instead of) any underlying cognitive differences`,`Nothing, as cognitive tasks are entirely culture-free by design`,`A single, universally agreed-upon explanation that applies to all observed differences`], ans:1, exp:`Cross-cultural comparisons of cognitive task performance must carefully consider potential confounds such as differential familiarity with testing procedures and formats, language barriers, educational background, and whether the task content itself is culturally relevant or meaningful, as these factors can produce performance differences that do not reflect genuine differences in underlying cognitive abilities.` },
    { q:`Acculturative stress refers to:`, ch:[`Stress experienced by individuals undergoing the process of adapting to a new cultural environment, which can affect mental health`,`A type of stress that only affects individuals who never leave their country of origin`,`A condition unrelated to immigration or cultural transition`,`Stress that has no impact on health outcomes`], ans:0, exp:`Acculturative stress refers to the psychological stress that can result from the process of adapting to a new cultural environment, including challenges related to language barriers, discrimination, loss of social support networks, and navigating differing cultural normsŌĆöand is associated with increased risk for mental health difficulties among immigrant populations.` },
    { q:`The "ecological fallacy" in cross-cultural research occurs when:`, ch:[`Researchers correctly apply group-level findings only to group-level conclusions`,`Conclusions about individuals are drawn based on data aggregated at the group (e.g., national or cultural) level, which may not accurately reflect individual-level relationships`,`Research is conducted only in ecological (outdoor) settings`,`A concept that has no relevance to psychological research`], ans:1, exp:`The ecological fallacy occurs when researchers infer characteristics or relationships about individuals based solely on data aggregated at a group level (e.g., assuming that because a country scores high on a collectivism index, every individual within that country is highly collectivistic), which can lead to incorrect conclusions about individual-level psychology, given substantial within-group variation.` },
    { q:`Why is it important for global mental health initiatives to avoid simply exporting Western diagnostic categories and treatment models without adaptation?`, ch:[`Because Western models are always completely ineffective everywhere`,`Because the expression of distress, help-seeking behaviors, and culturally appropriate treatment approaches can vary significantly, and interventions developed without local input may be less acceptable, accessible, or effective`,`Because no mental health interventions of any kind are needed in non-Western contexts`,`Because Western diagnostic categories have never been validated anywhere`], ans:1, exp:`Effective global mental health interventions require sensitivity to how mental distress is understood, expressed, and addressed within local cultural frameworks; uncritically exporting diagnostic categories and treatments developed in Western contexts without considering local explanatory models, stigma, help-seeking patterns, and available resources can result in interventions that are poorly accepted, inaccessible, or ineffective.` },
    { q:`A researcher conducting a study comparing "happiness" across multiple countries must consider that:`, ch:[`The concept of happiness is identical and universally understood in exactly the same way across all cultures and languages`,`Both the conceptualization of well-being/happiness and the willingness to report high or low levels (response styles) may vary across cultures, complicating direct cross-national comparisons`,`Happiness cannot be measured in any culture`,`Only one culture's definition of happiness is "correct"`], ans:1, exp:`Cross-national comparisons of subjective well-being must account for potential cultural variation in how happiness/well-being is conceptualized (e.g., individual achievement-focused vs. social harmony-focused conceptions) as well as cultural differences in response styles (e.g., some cultures may show a tendency toward more moderate responses on rating scales), which can complicate straightforward comparisons of average scores across countries.` },
    { q:`Etic versus emic approaches in cross-cultural research refer to:`, ch:[`Etic approaches study behavior from within a culture using culture-specific concepts, while emic approaches apply universal categories across cultures`,`Etic approaches apply universal categories and measures across cultures (an "outsider" perspective), while emic approaches study behavior from within a specific cultural context using culture-specific concepts (an "insider" perspective)`,`These terms are interchangeable with no meaningful distinction`,`A distinction relevant only to linguistics, not psychology`], ans:1, exp:`The etic approach involves studying psychological phenomena using concepts and measures intended to apply universally across cultures (an outsider's perspective, useful for cross-cultural comparison), while the emic approach involves studying phenomena from within a specific cultural context, using culturally specific concepts and meanings (an insider's perspective)ŌĆöboth approaches offer valuable but different insights, and combining them can enrich cross-cultural understanding.` },
  ]
},
{
  id:`ps60`, cat:`Psych/Soc`, title:`Poverty, Trauma & ACEs ŌĆö Biological + Sociological Integration`, diff:`Expert`, qs:[
    { q:`Adverse Childhood Experiences (ACEs) refer to:`, ch:[`Only positive experiences during childhood that promote resilience`,`Potentially traumatic events occurring during childhood, such as abuse, neglect, and household dysfunction (e.g., parental substance use, domestic violence)`,`Experiences that have no lasting impact on adult health`,`A category that includes only physical injuries`], ans:1, exp:`ACEs encompass a range of potentially traumatic experiences during childhood, including various forms of abuse (physical, emotional, sexual), neglect, and household dysfunction (e.g., witnessing domestic violence, parental incarceration, substance abuse, mental illness), which research has linked to long-term health outcomes.` },
    { q:`The landmark ACE study (Felitti & Anda) found that higher ACE scores were associated with:`, ch:[`Decreased risk of chronic diseases in adulthood`,`Increased risk of numerous adverse health outcomes in adulthood, including cardiovascular disease, depression, substance use disorders, and reduced life expectancy, in a dose-response relationship`,`No relationship to adult health outcomes`,`Effects only on physical, but not mental, health`], ans:1, exp:`The original ACE study found a strong, graded dose-response relationship between the number of ACEs experienced and numerous negative health outcomes in adulthoodŌĆöincluding heart disease, cancer, chronic lung disease, depression, substance use disorders, and premature mortalityŌĆösuggesting cumulative biological and behavioral effects of childhood adversity.` },
    { q:`The biological mechanism most commonly proposed to link early life adversity to later health problems involves:`, ch:[`Direct physical injury to organs at the time of the adverse event only`,`Toxic stressŌĆöprolonged activation of the body's stress response systems (e.g., HPA axis, sympathetic nervous system) during critical developmental periods, leading to lasting changes in brain architecture and physiological systems`,`A mechanism entirely unrelated to the nervous or endocrine systems`,`Effects that are limited strictly to the immune system with no neurological component`], ans:1, exp:`The "toxic stress" framework proposes that prolonged or repeated activation of stress response systems (cortisol, sympathetic nervous system) during sensitive developmental windows, particularly in the absence of buffering relationships with caregivers, can lead to lasting alterations in brain development (e.g., affecting the prefrontal cortex, amygdala, hippocampus), immune function, and other physiological systems, increasing vulnerability to a range of health problems across the lifespan.` },
    { q:`The distinction between "positive stress," "tolerable stress," and "toxic stress" in childhood development emphasizes that:`, ch:[`All forms of childhood stress are equally harmful regardless of context`,`The presence of supportive, responsive relationships with caregivers can buffer the physiological effects of stress, transforming what might otherwise be "toxic" stress into "tolerable" stress`,`Children should be shielded from all forms of stress`,`Stress has no measurable physiological effects in children`], ans:1, exp:`This framework highlights that the presence of stable, supportive adult relationships can buffer a child's stress response, helping potentially toxic experiences become "tolerable"ŌĆöthe brief activation of stress response systems with effective coping support ("positive stress," e.g., first day of school) is a normal and even adaptive part of development, while toxic stress occurs when strong, frequent, or prolonged adversity occurs without adequate buffering support.` },
    { q:`Poverty during childhood has been associated with structural and functional differences in brain regions including:`, ch:[`No brain regions; poverty has no measurable neurological correlates`,`The hippocampus, amygdala, and prefrontal cortexŌĆöregions involved in memory, emotional regulation, and executive function`,`Only the cerebellum, with no effects on cognitive or emotional regions`,`Brain regions involved exclusively in basic sensory processing`], ans:1, exp:`Neuroimaging research has found associations between childhood poverty and differences in brain structure and function in regions including the hippocampus (memory), amygdala (emotional processing), and prefrontal cortex (executive function, emotional regulation), potentially mediated by factors such as chronic stress, nutrition, cognitive stimulation, and parental stress.` },
    { q:`The "weathering hypothesis," applied to racial health disparities, proposes that chronic exposure to social and economic adversity related to systemic racism leads to:`, ch:[`No measurable biological effects`,`Accelerated biological aging (e.g., as measured by markers like telomere length or allostatic load), contributing to earlier onset of age-related health conditions`,`Effects that are entirely reversible with no lasting consequences`,`Improved health outcomes due to resilience`], ans:1, exp:`The weathering hypothesis proposes that the cumulative biological burden ("allostatic load") resulting from chronic exposure to social and economic adversityŌĆöincluding experiences of discriminationŌĆöleads to accelerated biological aging, which can manifest in markers such as shortened telomeres and contribute to earlier onset of chronic conditions and disparities in life expectancy.` },
    { q:`Resilience, in the context of childhood adversity, is best understood as:`, ch:[`A fixed, innate trait that some children have and others completely lack`,`A dynamic process involving the interaction of individual characteristics, relationships (especially with supportive caregivers), and broader environmental/community resources that can help mitigate the impact of adversity`,`A guarantee that adverse experiences will have no impact whatsoever`,`A concept that cannot be influenced by interventions`], ans:1, exp:`Resilience is increasingly understood not as a fixed individual trait but as a dynamic process resulting from the interplay between individual factors, relationships (particularly at least one stable, supportive relationship with a caregiver or other adult), and broader community and systemic resourcesŌĆömeaning resilience can potentially be fostered through targeted interventions and policies.` },
    { q:`Epigenetic research on early life adversity (e.g., studies of maternal care in animal models) has demonstrated that:`, ch:[`Early environmental experiences can lead to lasting changes in gene expression (e.g., via DNA methylation) that affect stress reactivity, without altering the underlying DNA sequence`,`Early experiences have no lasting biological effects of any kind`,`Only direct genetic mutations can affect stress-related gene expression`,`Epigenetic changes are always immediately and completely reversed`], ans:0, exp:`Animal studies have demonstrated that variations in early maternal care can lead to lasting epigenetic modifications (such as DNA methylation patterns affecting glucocorticoid receptor gene expression) that influence offspring's HPA axis reactivity and stress response throughout life, providing a potential biological mechanism linking early environment to lifelong stress regulation, with some evidence suggesting parallel processes may occur in humans.` },
    { q:`Trauma-informed care in healthcare settings involves:`, ch:[`Ignoring any history of trauma to avoid making patients uncomfortable`,`Recognizing the widespread impact of trauma, understanding potential paths for recovery, and integrating this knowledge into policies and practices to avoid re-traumatization`,`Requiring all patients to disclose detailed trauma histories regardless of relevance`,`A approach used only in mental health settings, with no relevance to general medical care`], ans:1, exp:`Trauma-informed care involves recognizing the high prevalence and potential impact of trauma (including ACEs) on patients' health and behavior, and adapting healthcare practices, environments, and interactions to avoid re-traumatization, promote a sense of safety and trust, and support recovery, while not requiring (but being prepared for) disclosure of trauma histories.` },
    { q:`The intergenerational transmission of trauma can occur through which combination of mechanisms?`, ch:[`Only through direct genetic mutation, with no other pathways`,`A combination of potential mechanisms including epigenetic changes, parenting behaviors and attachment patterns shaped by parents' own trauma histories, and ongoing socioeconomic and environmental conditions`,`Trauma cannot be transmitted across generations through any mechanism`,`Only through verbal disclosure of traumatic events`], ans:1, exp:`Intergenerational transmission of trauma is thought to involve multiple, potentially interacting pathways, including epigenetic modifications, the influence of a parent's own trauma history on their caregiving behaviors and the parent-child attachment relationship, and the perpetuation of socioeconomic disadvantage and environmental stressors across generations.` },
    { q:`Why is it important for clinicians to consider a "two-generation approach" when addressing the health of children in families experiencing poverty and adversity?`, ch:[`Because children's health is entirely independent of their caregivers' well-being`,`Because addressing the well-being (including mental health, economic stability, and parenting capacity) of caregivers can directly impact the health and developmental outcomes of children, recognizing the interconnected nature of family health`,`Because two-generation approaches are required by law in all clinical settings`,`Because only the child's individual biology matters for health outcomes`], ans:1, exp:`A two-generation approach recognizes that the health and well-being of caregivers (e.g., parental mental health, economic stability, access to resources) significantly influences the home environment and caregiving capacity, which in turn affects child development and healthŌĆöaddressing only the child in isolation may be insufficient if the broader family context of adversity is not also addressed.` },
    { q:`Public policy interventions aimed at reducing the impact of childhood poverty on long-term health (e.g., income support programs, early childhood education) can be understood through which framework?`, ch:[`A framework that views health purely as a result of individual genetic factors, unaffected by policy`,`A framework recognizing that social determinants of healthŌĆöshaped significantly by public policyŌĆöinfluence the biological and developmental pathways linking early adversity to later health outcomes, meaning "upstream" policy interventions can have "downstream" health effects`,`A framework with no connection between economic policy and health outcomes`,`A framework that applies only to adult health, not childhood`], ans:1, exp:`This reflects a social determinants of health framework, recognizing that "upstream" factors (policies affecting income, housing, early education, healthcare access) shape the social and physical environments that influence "downstream" biological and developmental processes (stress physiology, brain development) linking early childhood adversity to lifelong health trajectoriesŌĆösuggesting that policy-level interventions can be a powerful lever for improving population health.` },
    { q:`A pediatrician implementing universal ACEs screening in their practice should be prepared to:`, ch:[`Screen for ACEs but have no plan for what to do with positive results`,`Have a thoughtful approach to how results are used, including connecting families with appropriate resources and support, while being mindful of the potential for screening itself to cause distress if not handled sensitively`,`Use ACEs scores as the sole basis for reporting all families to child protective services`,`Avoid any discussion of the screening results with families`], ans:1, exp:`Implementing ACEs screening responsibly requires more than identifying riskŌĆöit requires having clear protocols and connections to resources (e.g., mental health services, social work, parenting support) for families who screen positive, training in trauma-informed communication to discuss results sensitively, and awareness that screening processes themselves should be implemented thoughtfully to avoid causing additional harm or stigma.` },
    { q:`Integrating biological and sociological perspectives on poverty and trauma (e.g., understanding both the neurobiological effects of toxic stress and the structural drivers of poverty) is important because:`, ch:[`Only one perspective (either biological or sociological) can be correct, and the other must be discarded`,`A comprehensive understanding requires recognizing that biological processes (e.g., stress physiology, brain development) and social/structural factors (e.g., poverty, discrimination, access to resources) interact dynamically, and effective interventions may need to address both individual-level biological/psychological needs and broader structural conditions`,`Biological and sociological factors operate in completely separate, non-interacting domains`,`This integration has no practical implications for clinical practice or policy`], ans:1, exp:`A biopsychosocial and structural understanding recognizes that the biological effects of early adversity (e.g., altered stress physiology, brain development) do not occur in a vacuumŌĆöthey are shaped by and interact with social and structural conditions like poverty, discrimination, and access to resources; effective approaches to improving health and reducing disparities likely require interventions at multiple levels, from individual clinical care and trauma-informed practices to broader social policy changes addressing structural determinants.` },
  ]
},
];
